[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ Hello, I am the 14th World Champion Vladimir Kramnik and I would like to introduce you to my course on Sicilian Defense. With this ends my repertoire on 1. e4, which aims to provide you with complete knowledge of all the opening systems that Black can use: with the first course we dealt with 1... e5, while with the second course we looked at all the other replies except 1... c5, which we will deal with now.The Sicilian is a very important opening, at every level and with every time control. I am sure that many of you have the Sicilian in your repertoire, so I will try to give you detailed overviews.The Sicilian has always been a problem, with White, and I know it still is! Against all other openings, White always has a safe option, but not with the Sicilian. You can never be sure that you will maintain complete control of the situation by playing it.I have played the Sicilian for half my career, probably more, having a lot of fun and getting good results. Then, advancing with age, when a player loses some of his calculating skills and optimism, I switched to 1... e5. It is normal for a player to switch to more classical openings as he ages. There are exceptions, for example, Garry Kasparov, who played the Sicilian for his entire career - with incredible results.It is therefore an opening that cannot be refuted, that is for sure, but it is equally so that it is not bulletproof. It is usually easier for White to arrive at a playable position than it is if Black plays 1... e5. There are still many unresolved questions in this opening, as there are in chess for that matter.The structure of the course will be similar to the previous two. I will present the material so that you have, first of all, a general understanding because this opening is very popular and there are so many games in the database that it is easy to get lost: move order, which lines are playable, which are doing well, and which are almost refuted. It is difficult and time-consuming to try to figure out what the current state of the theory is, but I can do it for you in a limited amount of time, giving you options for different time controls, and that also suit different playing styles.I will not go into details as other courses do, which you can study once you find the system you want to add to your repertoire; it would really take too much time. We will start with the sidelines and then move on to the main lines, the most dangerous ones.In general, I believe that the lines we are going to see in the first lesson are not dangerous for Black, but it is good to know exactly how to equalize, or even how to take the advantage. }
1. -- *

