1. e4 c5 { Let's start our investigations with the romantic move  2.b4 } 2. b4
{ I do not think that ...c5 is such a serious mistake that it is possible to punish Black for playing it! If you start with this pawn sacrifice, Black will just be better, actually in more than one way. }
2... cxb4 3. a3
{ This does not work for White and I do not recommend it at all. If you want to play like this, maybe it's better to do it after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  d6  3.b4  , when White is not better but neither is it worse. We will look at it later.   After the immediate  3.d4  then  3...d5  is perfectly fine for Black. }
3... d5 { The most logical continuation. } 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Nf3
{ Of course not  5.axb4  , when you're going to lose the rook after  5...Qe5+  6.Be2  Qxa1 }
5... e6 { 5...e5  is also a good and principled move. } 6. Bb2 Nf6 7. Be2 Nc6
{ White has some sort of compensation, perhaps he can even equalize, but it is clear that it is only Black who can be better. }
