1. e4 c5 2. d4
{ Playing immediately for the center, but even here White cannot expect an advantage from the opening. }
2... cxd4 3. c3
{ The most played move and the main idea behind 2. d4. Again, I don't think ....c5 is so bad as to allow White to play aggressively, even sacrificing material. And I also don't think there are good prospects for White, even with the faster time controls. }
3... dxc3
{ If I were lucky enough to be Black in this line, I would take the pawn right away.  3...Nf6  , attacking the e4-pawn, is the least Black can do, but it is enough.  4.e5  White has no choice but to advance the e-pawn.  4...Nd5  with a transposition to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nc3 }
4. Nxc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 e6
{ White has a very slight development lead, but he gave away a central pawn to get it, and it is clear that it is only Black who can fight for the advantage. Probably, objectively, Black is already better. }
