1. e4 c5
{ Now let's see what happens when White decides not to give away a pawn for free in the first few moves. }
2. b3
{ I played it twice, and against strong Grandmasters, winning both games. This led to an increase in the popularity of this line, but not for long.It is not the refutation of the Sicilian of course, but it has some points. Nowadays, however, it would be risky to have it in one's reportoire for too long, because obviously, b3 cannot really lead to an advantage.   I will now explain what the idea is and how I came up with it. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  3.b3  Nc6  4.Bb2  Black can simply play  4...e5  .  A very logical move, creating a barrier for the white bishop. But after playing b3 on the second move, I still have the option of playing f4 in many variations. For example after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.b3  d6  3.Bb2  , the move  3...e5  already not so good, White has the initiative because the knight is not in f3 and can push the f-pawn.  4.Nc3  Nc6  5.Bc4  Nf6  6.Nge2  followed by castling and f4. And White probably has a nice plus in this position. }
2... Nc6 3. Bb2 d6 { One of the options available to Black. } 4. f4
{ My main idea.  4.Bb5  is also possible.  4...Bd7  5.f4  Nf6  6.Qe2  e6  7.Nf3  Be7  is a complicated position, but perfectly playable for White. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3
{ And after  5...g6  White can continue with Bb5 and Nf3, and maybe castle on the queenside. }
