1. e4 c5 2. g3
{ Not really fighting for an advantage, but trying to reach a king's indian with a tempo up. Some people use this slow system to avoid main variations theory. }
2... d5
{ A good way to equalize, and that is probably why g3 went out of fashion.   2...Nc6  is of course also possible, with  3.Bg2  g6  and a fine position for Black. }
3. exd5
{ 3.d3  isn't very good.  3...dxe4  4.dxe4  Qxd1+  5.Kxd1  Nc6  and Black equalizes, since White still has to solve some issues with his king.   If  3...Nc6  4.Nd2  e5  5.Bg2  White is in a King's Indian a tempo up, but since the knight is already on d2 there is no real chance to get an advantage for White. }
3... Qxd5 4. Nf3 Bg4 5. Bg2 Qe6+
{ A very important check, otherwise White, if he can castle, can aim to have an advantage. }
6. Kf1 { 6.Qe2  leads to nothing for White after  6...Qxe2+  7.Kxe2  Nc6 } 6...
Nc6 7. h3 Bh5
{ Keeping the bishop on the board. Even  7...Bxf3  is pretty ok for Black.  8.Bxf3  Qd7  9.d3  e6  And the position is more or less equal, the black knight has an excellent outpost on d4 and White cannot play c3 without weakening the d3 pawn. }
8. d3 Qd7 { Intending to continue with ...e6, ...Be7 and ...Nf6. } 9. g4 Bg6
10. Nh4 e6
{ White will have the bishop pair, but his king is not in a good position. He will have to spend time to bring the h1 rook into play, while Black's position is very solid.   I would probably prefer to play with Black; even if White could complete the development of the kingside, the weakness of the dark squares would still be a problem. And Black's game, on the other hand, is very simple. }
