1. e4 c5 2. d3 { The same King's Indian setup idea. } 2... Nc6 3. g3 d5
{ Still very good, even if with this move order White has some playable options. }
4. exd5
{ 4.Nd2  is probably White's best continuation, but after  4...Nf6  5.Bg2  e5  Black is just fine. }
4... Qxd5 5. Nf3 { This line actually leads to a forced draw, if Black wants. }
5... Nd4 6. Bg2 Bh3 7. Bxh3 Nxf3+ 8. Kf1 Nd2+ { The rook on h1 is hanging. } 9.
Ke2
{ If White wants to play to win he can try this move, but it is probably not recommended.  9.Kg1  leads to a perpetual, after  9...Nf3+  10.Kf1 }
9... Qh5+
{ If  9...Nxb1  White should not capture in b1 immediately, but should first stop the check on h5. }
10. Kxd2 Qxh3 11. b3
{ Followed by ...Qd7. With this strange king in the center of the board, White will be no better off, but he will still be able to equalize, slowly completing this artificial long castling - Bb2, Qf3, Nc3 Rhe1 and Kc1. }
