1. e4 c5 2. Be2
{ An unusual attempt, also played by some strong grandmasters such as Nigel Short in a game against Sergey Karjakin. The idea, as will be soon evident, is to continue with f4. It doesn't give White any advantage, obviously. }
2... Nc6 3. f4 g6 { Played by Karjakin. } 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O d6
{ If you don't know the theory, play it this way and you definitely won't have any big problems. }
6. c3 Nf6 7. d3 O-O 8. Kh1
{ White must move the king to make room for the bishop, because if White starts with  8.Be3  then probably  8...Ng4  will come. }
8... b5 { Black starts his usual play on the queenside. } 9. a3
{ I show you this variation, which is far from forced, just to give you an idea of how the game can continue. }
9... a5 10. Be3 Bb7 11. Nbd2 b4 12. d4 cxd4 13. cxd4 e6
{ The position is perfectly fine for Black. } *

