1. e4 c5 2. Be2
{ An unusual attempt, also played by some strong grandmasters such as Nigel Short in a game against Sergey Karjakin. The idea, as will be soon evident, is to continue with f4. It doesn't give White any advantage, obviously. }
2... Nc6 3. f4 d5 4. d3
{ This is White's idea. Now, if Black continues with  4...dxe4  , after  5.dxe4  Qxd1+  White can take with the bishop  6.Bxd1  and can claim a certain plus, even if after  6...b6  followed by ...Bb7 it's not clear if White is really better. }
4... e6 5. Nf3 Bd6
{ White should probably try to play e5 right away, because if he continues with  6.O-O  Nge7  7.c3  than  7...f6  8.Be3  O-O  9.Kh1  b6  and Black has a solid position, controlling the center. Perhaps even with a slight advantage. }
6. e5 Bc7 7. c3
{ The position now reminds the French Defense, but Black has a very good version of it, because White has played d3, and will have to probably lose a tempo to play d4. Also, usually, the f-pawn does not stand on f4 in this type of position. }
7... Nge7 8. O-O O-O 9. Na3 f6
{ Even if it's probably equal, I would rather prefer Black here. His position is easier to play. }
10. d4 cxd4 11. cxd4 Bd7
{ A key maneuver that every French player knows very well. } 12. Kh1 Be8
{ All black pieces are good, there is pressure against the d4-pawn, and Black has no problems at all. }
