1. e4 c5 2. Ne2
{ A very strange move. Its only purpose, as I understand it, is to avoid the Najdorf. Nothing else can be avoided.  For instance, if  2...Nc6  White can play  3.d4  immediately or  3.Nbc3  , transposing into the main Sicilian but avoiding the Najdorf. The same goes after  2...e6  3.d4  . }
2... d6 3. Nbc3
{ One can also play  4.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  ,  but then it would not make sense to play 2. Ne2 instead of 2. Nf3. }
3... Nf6
{ In case of  3...Nc6  White can play  4.d4  avoiding the Najdorf after  4...cxd4  5.Nxd4  . }
4. g3 { White's idea. } 4... g6
{ If you play with e6-systems, then  4...e6  is perfectly playable. After  5.Bg2  Be7  6.d4  cxd4  7.Nxd4  O-O  8.O-O  Nc6  Black has a very, very good version of the g3-system. }
5. Bg2 Bg7 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4
{ It may be a little scary for those who do not play the Dragon because we have already entered the Sicilian Dragon. But there is no need to worry: the g3 system is really harmless against it. }
7... O-O
{ You don't even need to know much with Black, just play normal moves. } 8. O-O
Nc6 9. Nde2
{ Via a different move order we are getting to my old game with Black against Vassily Ivanchuk. If White plays  9.Be3  we have  9...Ng4  .  And if White would play @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/2np1np1/8/3NP3/2N3P1/PPP2PBP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nb3  then  9...Bg4  is good, for example,  10.f3  Be6  or  10...Bd7  , both moves are perfectly fine. }
9... Rb8 { Just trying to get ...b5 at some point. } 10. a4 a6
{ And again, Black is doing perfectly fine here. } *

