1. e4 c5 2. Ne2
{ A very strange move. Its only purpose, as I understand it, is to avoid the Najdorf. Nothing else can be avoided. For instance, if  2...Nc6  White can play  3.d4  immediately or  3.Nbc3  , transposing into the main Sicilian but avoiding the Najdorf. The same goes after  2...e6  3.d4  . }
2... d6 3. Nbc3
{ One can also play  4.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  ,  but then it would not make sense to play 2. Ne2 instead of 2. Nf3. }
3... Nf6
{ In case of  3...Nc6  White can play  4.d4  avoiding the Najdorf after  4...cxd4  5.Nxd4  . }
4. g3 { White's idea. } 4... g6
{ If you play with e6-systems, then  4...e6  is perfectly playable. After  5.Bg2  Be7  6.d4  cxd4  7.Nxd4  O-O  8.O-O  Nc6  Black has a very, very good version of the g3-system. }
5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O Nc6 7. d3 O-O
{ And as I already mentioned, these positions are ok for Black. I will just give you an example of how the game can develop. }
8. h3 Rb8 { Black's usual plan, without any fear of f4/g4. } 9. f4 Nd7
{ 9...Ne8  is equally good.  Black has very good statistics in this position, and not because his position is better, just because it's easier to play.  The only thing that you should avoid is  9...b5  , a typical blunder because  10.e5  comes.  10...dxe5  11.Bxc6  and Black loses a piece. }
10. g4 b5 11. Ng3 b4 12. Nce2 a5
{ Black has a clear plan on the queenside, while I really don't know how White can create anything on the opposite front. }
