1. e4 c5 2. f4
{ A move that brings me good memories, which I played throughout my childhood.  I didn't have many books in my provincial town, so I didn't know the theory and I thought that  2.f4  might be an interesting option. I played it until I reached 2400, so up to a more than decent level.  Usually, when White wants to play with f4, he starts with  2.Nc3  and after  2...Nc6  continues with  3.f4  . We will analyze this line in the next chapter.   My idea, however, was to maintain some flexibility and decide according to Black's reply. For example, after  2.f4  g6  3.Nf3  Bg7  White can try  4.c3  followed by d4, instead of  4.Nc3  . }
2... d5
{ A very strong move. Definitely the critical continuation, and the one that made me abandon this line. If Black plays  2...e6  , there is probably nothing better for White than to play with Nc3. }
3. exd5
{ In the Soviet Junior Championship I once tried  3.Bb5+  Bd7  4.Bxd7  Qxd7  5.d3  Pretending that in case of ...d4 the endgame is slightly better for White.  5...Nc6  6.Nf3  e6  7.O-O  Bd6  8.Qe2  Nge7  With an equal position. Black has no problems at all.   In the same tournament I played  3.Nc3  First of all,  3...d4  4.Nce2  Nc6  5.Nf3  is perfectly fine for Black. White wants to continue with Ng3 but Black can play ...h5.   The main problem is  3...dxe4  4.Nxe4  Nf6  is strong. If you take on f6, after  5.Nxf6+  exf6  White's pawn on f4 is really badly placed and the computer already gives quite a considerable advantage to Black.   If  5.Nxc5  ,  5...e5  is a strong continuation that gives Black the initiative.  So Black's @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2p5/4NP2/8/PPPP2PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  seems to be the refutation of this system. Probably White has to play  5.d3  and try to equalize. }
3... Qxd5 4. Nc3 Qd8 5. Nf3
{ Here White has quite a considerable advantage in development, and good chances to take the lead. }
*

