{  } 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3
{ The so-called closed Sicilian. It is a system used because of its simplicity. White's moves are logical, on the other hand, however, Black's moves are also simple to play. There are a couple of interesting lines that can be tried with White, which we will analyze in this lesson, but I think that all in all Black does not have any serious problems to solve after 2. Nc3.As for how Black responds, it depends on what system a player uses against the main Sicilian, because White can achieve it if he wants with a transposition after Nf3 and d4. That is why I will show you 2... d6, 2... Nc6 and 2... e6. }
2... e6
{ Let us assume that Black usually plays the Paulsen, so he will start with ...e6 and if White plays  3.Nf3  , we can easily transpose into the main line of the Paulsen.  Now there are two main lines for White,  3.g3  and  3.f4  . }
3. f4 Nc6 4. Nf3 d5
{ This is a very important position, which can be reached via different move orders.  Modern computers want to play  4...Nh6  , with the idea of completing the development with ...Be7 and ...f5. And that is probably a good idea, even though my classical chess education opposes these unconventional moves. }
5. Bb5 { White's main idea. } 5... Ne7
{ When I played 2. f4 myself, this position was considered better for White. Today this is no longer the case: Black will continue with ...a6 with a beautiful position. }
6. exd5
{ This is the continuation for which it was believed that this line could lead to White's advantage. }
6... exd5 7. Qe2
{ This is the idea behind  6. exd5, White blocks Black's development. For instance after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2nppp/2n5/1Bpp4/5P2/2N2N2/PPPPQ1PP/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@7...g6  White can play  8.Qe5  and Black is forced to play  8...Rg8  . }
7... Bg4 { And Black is ok. } *

