{  } 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3
{ The so-called closed Sicilian. It is a system used because of its simplicity. White's moves are logical, on the other hand, however, Black's moves are also simple to play. There are a couple of interesting lines that can be tried with White, which we will analyze in this lesson, but I think that all in all Black does not have any serious problems to solve after 2. Nc3.As for how Black responds, it depends on what system a player uses against the main Sicilian, because White can achieve it if he wants with a transposition after Nf3 and d4. That is why I will show you 2... d6, 2... Nc6 and 2... e6. }
2... Nc6
{ And now let's assume that Black usually plays the Sveshnikov, or the Rauzer, in which case it makes sense to play 2... Nc6 on move 2. }
3. Nge2
{ This move leads to a game like the one discussed in the previous lesson. }
3... Nf6 4. g3
{ Of course White can always play  4.d4  if he wants to transpose into the main line. }
4... d5
{ With this move, White gains some chances because the position becomes rather complicated.  The alternatives for Black are  4...g6  5.Bg2  Bg7  or  4...e6  where the best option for White is to transpose to a Scheveningen with the bishop in fianchetto.  5.Bg2  Be7  6.d4  cxd4  7.Nxd4  O-O  8.O-O  d6  9.Be3  Bd7 }
5. exd5 Nd4
{ According to the engine, after  5...Nxd5  6.Bg2  Nxc3  7.bxc3  g6  Black equalizes; White continues with Rb1, d4, Nf4 and takes the initiative. Black is probably fine anyway, but I prefer White's position. }
6. Bg2 Bg4 7. O-O
{ A very complicated position, which requires further analysis. After  7.h3  Bf3  8.Bxf3  Nxf3+  9.Kf1  Nd4  and Black is going to take back the pawn on d5, with a good position. }
7... Nf3+
{ 7...Nxd5  is also possible, thanks to the pin on e2.  8.f3  Bf5  9.d3  A very strange position, plenty of potential for both sides. I only mention that the first choice of the engine here is ... h5. }
8. Bxf3
{ If  8.Kh1  actually  8...h5  ,  intending ...h4, is quite dangerous. } 8...
Bxf3 9. d4
{ Apparently, it does not look good for White who seems on the verge of being mated. But in reality, it is not so simple. }
9... c4 10. Qe1 Nxd5 11. Nf4
{ And it is probably White who is fighting for an advantage, but objectively it should be equal. Very sharp, but equal. }
*

