{  } 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3
{ The so-called closed Sicilian. It is a system used because of its simplicity. White's moves are logical, on the other hand, however, Black's moves are also simple to play. There are a couple of interesting lines that can be tried with White, which we will analyze in this lesson, but I think that all in all Black does not have any serious problems to solve after 2. Nc3.As for how Black responds, it depends on what system a player uses against the main Sicilian, because White can achieve it if he wants with a transposition after Nf3 and d4. That is why I will show you 2... d6, 2... Nc6 and 2... e6. }
2... Nc6
{ And now let's assume that Black usually plays the Sveshnikov, or the Rauzer, in which case it makes sense to play 2... Nc6 on move 2. }
3. Bb5
{ A very tricky move. It can be a useful weapon in your arsenal, as it has been in that of strong players - Alexander Grischuk used it in classical chess, for example. If your opponent doesn't know what to do, you can really end up in a better position. }
3... Nd4
{ The only move to equalize.  3...e6  4.Bxc6  bxc6  5.f4  Strategically, it is a very dangerous position for Black. }
4. Bc4 e6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. O-O
{ 6.e5  isn't good for White, as after  6...d5  , a very strong move,  7.exf6  dxc4  Black is slightly better. }
6... a6
{ An important move, after which I think Black's position is good. The idea is to play  7... d5 against both7.a4  and  7.e5 }
7. d3 b5 8. Bb3
{ And Black can equalize with precise play, but no more than that. This variation can become part of your white repertoire. }
8... Nxb3
{ 8...Nxf3+  can be played too, after  9.Qxf3  Bb7  White has a development advantage, but Black has the constant threat of ...c4, cutting off the bishop. }
9. axb3 Bb7
{ And if Black can complete the development, he solves every problem. So White must hurry if he does not want to end up in a worse position. }
10. e5 Nd5
{ Even the ambitious ... Ng4, according to engines, is ok for Black. } 11. Ng5
{ If  11.Ne4  Be7  Black is perfectly ok. Next, he wants to castle, and the light-squared bishop on b7 is a powerful piece. }
11... Nxc3 12. bxc3 Qc7
{ Black obviously has several ways to continue, but this seems logical. } 13.
Re1 h6 14. Qh5 g6 15. Qh3 Bg7 16. Nf3 a5
{ With ... a4 next.   For now, is difficult to castle for Black, but his king is pretty safe in the center. His position is certainly no worse. }
*

