{ The so-called closed Sicilian. It is a system used because of its simplicity. White's moves are logical, on the other hand, however, Black's moves are also simple to play. There are a couple of interesting lines that can be tried with White, which we will analyze in this lesson, but I think that all in all Black does not have any serious problems to solve after 2. Nc3.As for how Black responds, it depends on what system a player uses against the main Sicilian, because White can achieve it if he wants with a transposition after Nf3 and d4. That is why I will show you 2... d6, 2... Nc6 and 2... e6. }
2... Nc6
{ And now let's assume that Black usually plays the Sveshnikov, or the Rauzer, in which case it makes sense to play 2... Nc6 on move 2. }
3. f4 { A very popular line at the amateur and semi-professional level. } 3...
g6
{ Black can also play  3...e6  4.Nf3  d5  5.Bb5  Nge7  with a perfectly fine position. }
4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bb5
{ 5.Bc4  is also possible, but we will analyze it via the 2. Nc3 d6 move order. }
5... Nd4
{ An important move to remember. We already know that White wants to take on c6 with a strategically nice position. }
6. O-O { If  6.Bc4  Black can just play  6...e6  followed by ...Be7. } 6...
Nxb5 7. Nxb5 a6 { This is also a plausible alternative to  7...d5  . } 8. Nc3
b5 9. d3 d6 10. Qe1
{ White intends to continue with his usual plan, Qh4-f5, and a direct attack on the kingside. }
10... Bb7
{ The only thing Black must keep in mind is that he must not hurry with castling, so as not to end up under the opponent's attack. }
11. a3
{ If  11.Qh4  then  11...e6  ,  trying to exchange queens which is of course very favorable for Black. }
11... Qd7 12. Bd2 { White is waiting for Black to castle. } 12... Nh6
{ White has a development advantage, equalized by Black's bishop pair. } *

