{  } 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3
{ The so-called closed Sicilian. It is a system used because of its simplicity. White's moves are logical, on the other hand, however, Black's moves are also simple to play. There are a couple of interesting lines that can be tried with White, which we will analyze in this lesson, but I think that all in all Black does not have any serious problems to solve after 2. Nc3.As for how Black responds, it depends on what system a player uses against the main Sicilian, because White can achieve it if he wants with a transposition after Nf3 and d4. That is why I will show you 2... d6, 2... Nc6 and 2... e6. }
2... Nc6
{ And now let's assume that Black usually plays the Sveshnikov, or the Rauzer, in which case it makes sense to play 2... Nc6 on move 2. }
3. g3
{ A very important system, played by some great players such as tenth World Champion Boris Spassky and English top player Michael Adams. I also tried to include it in my repertoire, but I was not happy with the kind of positions White gets. }
3... e6 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. Nge2 { If  5.d3  then  5...d5 } 5... Be7
{ 5...d5  is also possible. After  6.exd5  exd5  7.d4  White gets a better version of the line we analyzed in the previous lesson, in which he was forced to take back d4 with the queen.  7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  Bg4  9.f3  Bd7  10.O-O  Be7  11.Be3  Modern engines assert that this position is completely equal, even though Black has a weakness on d5. }
6. O-O O-O 7. d3 { 7.d4  cxd4  8.Nxd4  d6  transposes. } 7... Rb8
{ This system with e6 and d6 was very popular when I was a kid, mainly because of Kasparov, and I remember winning numerous games simply by following this plan: let White advance with his pawns on the kingside and launch an offensive on the opposite side.   7...d5  is a valid alternative, after  8.exd5  exd5  9.Bg5  d4  10.Bxf6  Bxf6  11.Ne4  Be7  12.Nf4  it looks a bit dangerous but after  12...Bf5  Black is very solid and the position is just equal. }
8. f4 d6 9. h3 Nd7 { Of course not  9...b5  10.e5 } 10. g4 b5 11. Ng3 b4 12.
Nce2 Bh4
{ Or  12...h6  .  Next Black will continue with ...a5, ...Ba6, ...a4. } *

