{  } 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3
{ The so-called closed Sicilian. It is a system used because of its simplicity. White's moves are logical, on the other hand, however, Black's moves are also simple to play. There are a couple of interesting lines that can be tried with White, which we will analyze in this lesson, but I think that all in all Black does not have any serious problems to solve after 2. Nc3.As for how Black responds, it depends on what system a player uses against the main Sicilian, because White can achieve it if he wants with a transposition after Nf3 and d4. That is why I will show you 2... d6, 2... Nc6 and 2... e6. }
2... Nc6
{ And now let's assume that Black usually plays the Sveshnikov, or the Rauzer, in which case it makes sense to play 2... Nc6 on move 2. }
3. g3
{ A very important system, played by some great players such as tenth World Champion Boris Spassky and English top player Michael Adams. I also tried to include it in my repertoire, but I was not happy with the kind of positions White gets. }
3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6
{ This is an importan tabiya; you can also reach this position via 2. Nc3 d6 }
6. f4 e6 { Easier for Black to play than ...Nf6. } 7. Nf3 Nge7 8. O-O O-O 9.
Be3
{ Pretending to play d4 sometime, although it is not at all clear whether it is possible. }
9... Nd4 { The main line. } 10. e5 Bd7
{ A strong move that works tactically and that you definitely need to remember. It's not the only one for Black, but it's the best. }
11. Ne4
{ If  11.Nxd4  cxd4  12.Bxd4  Bc6  suddenly White cannot keep his extra pawn, Black just wants to exchange the light-squared bishop on g2 and play ...Nc6, taking back the e5-pawn. }
11... Nef5 12. Bf2 Nxf3+ 13. Qxf3 Bc6
{ And the position is, once again, equal. } *

