{  } 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3
{ The so-called closed Sicilian. It is a system used because of its simplicity. White's moves are logical, on the other hand, however, Black's moves are also simple to play. There are a couple of interesting lines that can be tried with White, which we will analyze in this lesson, but I think that all in all Black does not have any serious problems to solve after 2. Nc3.As for how Black responds, it depends on what system a player uses against the main Sicilian, because White can achieve it if he wants with a transposition after Nf3 and d4. That is why I will show you 2... d6, 2... Nc6 and 2... e6. }
2... Nc6
{ And now let's assume that Black usually plays the Sveshnikov, or the Rauzer, in which case it makes sense to play 2... Nc6 on move 2. }
3. g3
{ A very important system, played by some great players such as tenth World Champion Boris Spassky and English top player Michael Adams. I also tried to include it in my repertoire, but I was not happy with the kind of positions White gets. }
3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6
{ This is an importan tabiya; you can also reach this position via 2. Nc3 d6 }
6. Be3
{ I do not like this system, but that does not mean it is not playable; one of the main problems is that Black has several setups available, and all of them are good. With the exception of  6...e6  , as White has  7.Qd2  and after  7...Nge7  he can immediately play  8.Bh6  - White's main idea when he put the bishop on e3. }
6... Rb8
{ Usually Black waits to bring the knight into play; by doing so, he prevents Bh6 and prepares support for the pawn advance on the queenside. }
7. Qd2 b5 8. Nge2
{ If  8.a3  then  8...a5  is possible, but Black can also continue with  8...Nf6  9.Bh6  O-O  without being concerned about White castling on the other side of the board; that would be too risky.  10.Bxg7  Kxg7  11.f4  and now  11...e5  is a typical resource, once the dark-squared bishops have been exchanged. }
8... Nd4
{ Once again,  8...Nf6  is perfectly fine for Black after  9.Bh6  O-O  10.Bxg7  Kxg7  11.O-O  e5  12.f4  Nd4 }
9. O-O h5
{ Black can keep the king in the center for the time being, and begin to bother the opponent on the kingside. There is a typical trick, which is the tactical justification of Black's last move,  10.h3  Bxh3  Something you need to remember!  11.Bxd4  cxd4  12.Bxh3  dxc3  13.bxc3  b4  and probably Black is already better. }
10. Nd1
{ It is not easy to react after ...h5. If Black plays  10.h4  it will no longer be possible for him to play f4, because Black will take his knight to g4. If instead  10.f4  , after  11...h4  the threats along the h-file could become quite serious. }
10... Nxe2+ 11. Qxe2 h4 12. c3 b4 { 12...Nf6  is also possible. } 13. f4 hxg3
14. hxg3 Nh6 15. Bf3 Qd7 { And Black's position is really comfortable. } *

[Event "?"]
