[White "Lesson 27: 2.Nc3 "]
[Black "2.Nc3 d6 3.f4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

{  } 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3
{ The so-called closed Sicilian. It is a system used because of its simplicity. White's moves are logical, on the other hand, however, Black's moves are also simple to play. There are a couple of interesting lines that can be tried with White, which we will analyze in this lesson, but I think that all in all Black does not have any serious problems to solve after 2. Nc3.As for how Black responds, it depends on what system a player uses against the main Sicilian, because White can achieve it if he wants with a transposition after Nf3 and d4. That is why I will show you 2... d6, 2... Nc6 and 2... e6. }
2... d6
{ If, for example, Black plays  2...Nc6  then White can continue with  3.Nf3  , transposing to the main Sicilian, and Black can't get the Najdorf anymore. }
3. f4
{ A popular move in the 1990s, when it was used as an antidote to Najdorf. Nowadays, with the engines getting stronger and stronger, White has lost the optimism needed to play this position.   Both  3.g3  Nc6  4.Bg2  g6  and  3.Nge2  Nf6  4.g3  g6  or  4...e6  transpose to the lines previously analyzed. }
3... Nc6
{ 3...g6  4.d4  cxd4  5.Qxd4  Nf6  6.e5  Nc6  7.Bb5  Nh5  The position is very complicated, and even if the engines claim it to be equal, it requires further analysis.   4.Nf3  Bg7  5.Bc4  Now  5.d4  leads to a good version of the Dragon after  5...cxd4  6.Nxd4  Nc6  7.Be3  Nf6   If  5.Bb5+  then simply  5...Bd7  . }
4. Nf3 g6 5. Bb5 Bd7
{ Not  5...Bg7  6.Bxc6+  bxc6  7.d3  As you already know, this position is strategically dangerous for Black. }
6. O-O Bg7 7. d3 Nf6 8. Bxc6
{ An old Soviet Junior Championship game of mine, played in 1989 against Rublevsky, saw  8.Qe1  Nd4  9.Bxd7+  Nxd7  10.Qf2  And even though later I managed to win, the position is equal. }
8... Bxc6 9. Qe1 { White's typical plan on the kingside. } 9... b5
{ If Black does not know what to do, he may end up under a dangerous attack; for example, after  9...O-O  10.Qh4  e6  f5  , even though the computer thinks the position is still ok after  10...Qd7  11.f5   9...Qd7  is also good. As we have already mentioned, the important thing in these positions is not to castle quickly. }
10. Qh4 a5
{ As long as you do not castle, White's attack is unsuccessful.   The bishop pair, especially the light-squared one which can become very dangerous, secures a good position for Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
