[White "Lesson 27: 2.Nc3 "]
[Black "2.Nc3 d6 3.f4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

{  } 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3
{ The so-called closed Sicilian. It is a system used because of its simplicity. White's moves are logical, on the other hand, however, Black's moves are also simple to play. There are a couple of interesting lines that can be tried with White, which we will analyze in this lesson, but I think that all in all Black does not have any serious problems to solve after 2. Nc3.As for how Black responds, it depends on what system a player uses against the main Sicilian, because White can achieve it if he wants with a transposition after Nf3 and d4. That is why I will show you 2... d6, 2... Nc6 and 2... e6. }
2... d6
{ If, for example, Black plays  2...Nc6  then White can continue with  3.Nf3  , transposing to the main Sicilian, and Black can't get the Najdorf anymore. }
3. f4
{ A popular move in the 1990s, when it was used as an antidote to Najdorf. Nowadays, with the engines getting stronger and stronger, White has lost the optimism needed to play this position.   Both  3.g3  Nc6  4.Bg2  g6  and  3.Nge2  Nf6  4.g3  g6  or  4...e6  transpose to the lines previously analyzed. }
3... Nc6
{ 3...g6  4.d4  cxd4  5.Qxd4  Nf6  6.e5  Nc6  7.Bb5  Nh5  The position is very complicated, and even if the engines claim it to be equal, it requires further analysis.   4.Nf3  Bg7  5.Bc4  Now  5.d4  leads to a good version of the Dragon after  5...cxd4  6.Nxd4  Nc6  7.Be3  Nf6   If  5.Bb5+  then simply  5...Bd7  . }
4. Nf3 g6 5. Bc4 Bg7 6. O-O e6
{ My recommendation.  6...Nf6  is dubious. After  7.d3  O-O  8.Qe1  Intending, as usual, f5-Qh4 and Bh6.  8...Bg4  And this unusual bishop move is enough to equalize.   8.f5  looks dangerous but, as usual, the engines find ways to refute the attack.  8...gxf5  9.Qe1  Be6 }
7. d3
{ White can even play  7.f5  , a pure positional sacrifice.  7...exf5  8.d4  Nge7  9.Qe1  h6  10.Bd2  with a slight advantage for Black. }
7... Nge7 8. Qe1
{ 8.a3  O-O  9.Ba2  Rb8  with Black's typical play on the queenside. } 8... O-O
9. Bb3
{ With the idea that if Black plays  9...d5  , White replies with  10.e5  Even  10.f5  is an interesting idea.   If  9.Qh4  , Black quickly starts his play in the center with  9...d5  10.Bb3  Nd4  and an equal position. }
9... a6 10. Qh4 b5 { Simply ignoring White's play on the kingside. } 11. f5
gxf5 12. Bh6 f6 { White has some initiative, but nothing more than that. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 28: Alapin 2.c3"]
[Black "The Alapin 2.c3 - 2...d6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ The Alapin Sicilian is a solid and logical opening choice for White. They aim to occupy the center with d2-d4.  GM Sveshnikov was the main proponent of the Alapin and he played it all his life.  He made a great attribution to the development of its opening theory. At the top of his career, in the 90s, it was not so easy to neutralize this opening - the engines weren't as strong yet.  Nowadays, the Alapin is not considered to be so dangerous anymore but nonetheless, it's a very decent weapon for White. Most importantly, Black can't get away by playing on general principles - they need to know their opening theory because the play can get sharp surprisingly quickly. }
2... d6 { 2...d6 is not very logical. } 3. d4 { White occupies the center. }
3... Nf6 4. Bd3
{ Allowing White to develop his knight to c3 only makes matters worse for Black: }
4... cxd4 5. cxd4 g6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. h3 O-O 8. Nf3
{ White solidly controls the center. } *

