[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 28: Alapin 2.c3"]
[Black "The Alapin 2.c3 - 2...d5 #28"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ The Alapin Sicilian is a solid and logical opening choice for White. They aim to occupy the center with d2-d4.  GM Sveshnikov was the main proponent of the Alapin and he played it all his life.  He made a great attribution to the development of its opening theory. At the top of his career, in the 90s, it was not so easy to neutralize this opening - the engines weren't as strong yet.  Nowadays, the Alapin is not considered to be so dangerous anymore but nonetheless, it's a very decent weapon for White. Most importantly, Black can't get away by playing on general principles - they need to know their opening theory because the play can get sharp surprisingly quickly. }
2... d5 { This move is very solid and perfectly playable for Black. } 3. exd5
Qxd5
{ White doesn't have the option of playing Nc3 now, unlike in the Scandinavian Defense. }
4. Nf3 { 4.d4  Nf6  5.Nf3  transposes to the text move. } 4... Nf6 5. d4
{ 5.Na3  is not a logical move. White certainly needs to play d2-d4 whereas the knight can remain flexible for now. }
5... e6 { This is Black's main line. It's very solid. } 6. Na3
{ This is White's main move. He wants to recapture on d4 with a piece, using Nb5 @@StartBracket@@threatening Nc7+@@EndBracket@@ to gain a tempo. }
6... a6 { The most solid move. } 7. Nc4 Nbd7 8. a4
{ 8.a4 is a logical move, preventing ...b5 followed by ...Bb7. } 8... cxd4 9.
Qxd4 Bc5 10. Qxd5 exd5 11. Ne3 Ba7
{ The a7-bishop is strong and Black gets his knight to c5; Black has enough activity to compensate for his slight positional weakness - the d5-pawn. White would like to exchange the dark-squared bishops with Be3 but because the knight is on e3 now, it will take too much time. Therefore 8.Be2 is the main move. }
