{ This position can be considered as an improved Alekhine's Defense: the d5-knight is stable and Black controls the d4-square. }
4. Bc4
{ Since White ran out of ideas in the fight for an opening advantage after  4.d4  , White players started to exploit the move order  4.Bc4  . }
4... Nb6 5. Bb3 c4 6. Bc2 Nc6 7. Nf3 d5
{ This move forces White to capture on d6.   Against  7...d6  , White gains the additional option of  8.Qe2  and although I'm not sure if it's dangerous, this is simply unnecessary. }
8. exd6 Qxd6 9. O-O g6 { This is by far the main move in the position. } 10.
Na3
{ Attacking the c4-pawn is White's only way of fighting for the advantage. }
10... Bg7
{ 10...Bf5  is an interesting alternative for Black, who is looking to unbalance the game by castling queenside again.  11.Bxf5  gxf5  12.b3  O-O-O   If Black plans to castle queenside, he must sacrifice the c-pawn and shouldn't hand White the a-file by including  12...cxb3?!  13.axb3  when  13...O-O-O  loses to  14.Nb5  .  13.Nxc4  Nxc4  14.bxc4  Qd3  Achieving d2-d4 will not be easy for White, certainly not without giving up his c4-pawn, and as a result, the c1-bishop remains passive.  15.Re1  Rg8∞  .  If White has any advantage at all, it's at least not obvious. I can surely recommend the motivated student looking into this variation a bit deeper. }
