[White "Lesson 28: Alapin 2.c3"]
[Black "The Alapin 2.c3 - 2...Nf6 #25"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ The Alapin Sicilian is a solid and logical opening choice for White. They aim to occupy the center with d2-d4.  GM Sveshnikov was the main proponent of the Alapin and he played it all his life.  He made a great attribution to the development of its opening theory. At the top of his career, in the 90s, it was not so easy to neutralize this opening - the engines weren't as strong yet.  Nowadays, the Alapin is not considered to be so dangerous anymore but nonetheless, it's a very decent weapon for White. Most importantly, Black can't get away by playing on general principles - they need to know their opening theory because the play can get sharp surprisingly quickly. }
2... Nf6
{ This is currently the most popular move. It's very straightforward, attacking the e4-pawn and limiting White's options. White struggles to get anything at all after 2...Nf6. }
3. e5 Nd5
{ This position can be considered as an improved Alekhine's Defense: the d5-knight is stable and Black controls the d4-square. }
4. Bc4
{ Since White ran out of ideas in the fight for an opening advantage after  4.d4  , White players started to exploit the move order  4.Bc4  . }
4... Nb6 5. Bb3 c4 6. Bc2 Nc6 7. Nf3 d5
{ This move forces White to capture on d6.   Against  7...d6  , White gains the additional option of  8.Qe2  and although I'm not sure if it's dangerous, this is simply unnecessary. }
8. exd6 Qxd6 9. O-O g6 { This is by far the main move in the position. } 10.
Na3
{ Attacking the c4-pawn is White's only way of fighting for the advantage. }
10... Bg7
{ 10...Bf5  is an interesting alternative for Black, who is looking to unbalance the game by castling queenside again.  11.Bxf5  gxf5  12.b3  O-O-O   If Black plans to castle queenside, he must sacrifice the c-pawn and shouldn't hand White the a-file by including  12...cxb3?!  13.axb3  when  13...O-O-O  loses to  14.Nb5  .  13.Nxc4  Nxc4  14.bxc4  Qd3  Achieving d2-d4 will not be easy for White, certainly not without giving up his c4-pawn, and as a result, the c1-bishop remains passive.  15.Re1  Rg8∞  .  If White has any advantage at all, it's at least not obvious. I can surely recommend the motivated student looking into this variation a bit deeper. }
11. b3 Be6 12. Re1
{ This is White's best try. Generally speaking, Re1 is a more useful move than Qe2.   12.Ng5  is pointless after  12...Bd5=  . }
12... O-O 13. bxc4 Nxc4 14. Rxe6
{ This was the point of 12.Re1. A forcing variation ensues. } 14... Qxe6 15.
Bb3 N6a5 16. Nxc4 Nxc4 17. d3
{ White is an exchange down but will win the c4-knight in exchange for the d3-pawn. }
17... Rfd8
{ Black equalized but White has the better prospects, in the practical sense. }
18. Qf1 Qf5
{ Other moves lose by force. For example,  18...Qd7  19.dxc4!  Bxc3  20.Bh6  Bxa1  22.Qxa1  f6  22.c5+  Kh8  23.Ne5+-  wins for White. Suddenly all of White's pieces are involved in the attack. }
19. dxc4 Bxc3 20. Bh6 Bxa1 21. Qxa1 Qf6 22. Qe1 a5
{ An important move. White's would undoubtedly have an advantage if he could have kept his bishop on the a2-g8 diagonal. }
23. h4 a4 24. Bc2
{ After  24...Rd7  , the engines confidently defend Black's position but from a practical viewpoint, White is playing for two results - he has the bishop pair and Black's king could be a target. }
