{ This was the point of 12.Re1. A forcing variation ensues. } 14... Qxe6 15.
Bb3 N6a5 16. Nxc4 Nxc4 17. d3
{ White is an exchange down but will win the c4-knight in exchange for the d3-pawn. }
17... Rfd8
{ Black equalized but White has the better prospects, in the practical sense. }
18. Qc2
{ White gets out of the pin on the d-file while keeping the d3-pawn protected. The other try is 18.Qf1. }
18... b5 19. dxc4 bxc4 20. Ba4 Rd3 21. Bd2 Rad8 22. Be1
{ The position remains more difficult to play for Black, even after the best moves 22...R8d5 or 22...h5. The position is very unbalanced and you can certainly outplay your opponent in a practical game.  This is the current state of the Alapin Variation 1.e4 c5 2.c3. Black needs exact knowledge to equalize. 2...d5 is very solid but there may still be room for improvement for White. 2...Nf6 is more challenging, White is running out of ideas to fight for the theoretical opening advantage.  As we can see in the variation at hand, there is still a game to be played, where White can put pressure on his opponent. }
