1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ The Alapin Sicilian is a solid and logical opening choice for White. They aim to occupy the center with d2-d4.  GM Sveshnikov was the main proponent of the Alapin and he played it all his life.  He made a great attribution to the development of its opening theory. At the top of his career, in the 90s, it was not so easy to neutralize this opening - the engines weren't as strong yet.  Nowadays, the Alapin is not considered to be so dangerous anymore but nonetheless, it's a very decent weapon for White. Most importantly, Black can't get away by playing on general principles - they need to know their opening theory because the play can get sharp surprisingly quickly. }
2... Nf6
{ This is currently the most popular move. It's very straightforward, attacking the e4-pawn and limiting White's options. White struggles to get anything at all after 2...Nf6. }
3. e5 Nd5
{ This position can be considered as an improved Alekhine's Defense: the d5-knight is stable and Black controls the d4-square. }
4. Bc4
{ Since White ran out of ideas in the fight for an opening advantage after  4.d4  , White players started to exploit the move order  4.Bc4  . }
4... Nb6 5. Bb3 c4 6. Bc2 Nc6 7. Nf3 d5
{ This move forces White to capture on d6.   Against  7...d6  , White gains the additional option of  8.Qe2  and although I'm not sure if it's dangerous, this is simply unnecessary. }
8. exd6 Qxd6 9. O-O Bg4
{ This move deserves serious consideration. Black pins the f3-knight and threatens to weaken White's structure, or at least, considerably simplify the game, with ...Ne5. }
10. h3 Bh5 11. Re1 O-O-O
{ Black plays aggressively and is looking for a double-edged game. } 12. a4
{ Against  12.b3  Qf6=  is the best move. } 12... Na5
{ Theory suggests Black holds here. This could be an interesting surprise weapon for Black if you are looking to unbalance the game. That said, 9...g6 is by far the main move as it is incredibly solid for Black. }
