1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ The most dangerous move that White can try. This move prepares d4 to fight for the center. }
2... a6
{ The O'Kelly Variation, which is not that bad, actually. Now White has two main options available. }
3. d4
{ I was taught that White should not play like this against the O'Kelly, but now I consider that this move is playable and White is even slightly better after }
3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ This is the idea behind the move 2...a6. White would like to play 6.Nb5 here, but the pawn on a6 covers that square. Therefore, White should play }
6. Nde2 Bc5 7. Ng3 d6 8. Bc4
{ I don't think this line is enough for Black to equalize. White will bring the bishop back to b3 and, although the knight is slightly awkward on g3, Black has to prove that his position is fine to keep the balance. }
