[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 29: 2.Nf3 Sidelines"]
[Black "2...d6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ The most dangerous move that White can try. This move prepares d4 to fight for the center. }
2... d6
{ When Black plays 2... d6, the most common system players want to reach is the Najdorf. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ The Evergreen Dragon system. It's not so popular among the elite, but, if Black knows it well, it can be a very serious weapon at lower levels at all time controls, but especially in rapid ones.   The most challenging setup that White has against the Dragon is }
6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
{ Objectively, Black is experiencing some problems. The play will become very sharp, and detailed knowledge is very important to keep control of the game, especially if it's played with Black. The reason is that White's play is simple: O-O-O and pushing the h-pawn to h5.   In these lines, if Black makes an inaccurate move, he will get mated. Nevertheless, the Dragon is still not refuted, but it's a very risky opening to play. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 30: 2.Nf3 e6 3rd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "3rd Move Sidelines: 3.Be2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ In this chapter we will take a look at what to do in case White decides to delay or postpone playing the early d4 break.   If you want to play the Paulsen system, ...e6 is obligatory, but if you prefer the Taimanov, you can start with ...Nc6. It all depends which of the white sidelines you prefer to face. ...e6 offers the most amount of sidelines to White, but we shouldn't be worried about any of them - 3. c3 perhaps being the most critical among them. }
3. Be2 { A rather unambitious move, but it has a point. } 3... Nc6
{ Our normal move. } 4. O-O
{ White is hesitating whether he wants to play d4 or c3-d4, etc. } 4... Nf6
{ In my opinion, the most logical waiting move. } 5. Nc3 d6
{ Quite a good version of a normal sicilian, since White hasn't challenged the center. }
6. d4 { The only logical move. } 6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 Be7
{ We find ourselves in the Scheveningen system, named after the Seaside district in South Holland where it was first discovered that ...e6 and ...d6 is a solid way to approach the Sicilian - back when opening novelties were prevalent. }
8. Be3 O-O
{ There is a lot of theory starting here, and castling is the precise move order.  8...a6  9.a4  O-O  10.f4  Qc7  11.Kh1  Re8  Kasparov played this position many times, but it's not so clear whether Black will finally equalize. }
9. a4
{ This is White's attempt to stop Queenside counterplay before it starts, but the tempo saved on ...a6 is important for Black. }
9... Nxd4 { This is a typical way to handle this position. } 10. Qxd4 b6
{ Very solid, developing the queenside next. } *

