1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ In this chapter we will take a look at what to do in case White decides to delay or postpone playing the early d4 break.   If you want to play the Paulsen system, ...e6 is obligatory, but if you prefer the Taimanov, you can start with ...Nc6. It all depends which of the white sidelines you prefer to face. ...e6 offers the most amount of sidelines to White, but we shouldn't be worried about any of them - 3. c3 perhaps being the most critical among them. }
3. Be2 { A rather unambitious move, but it has a point. } 3... Nc6
{ Our normal move. } 4. O-O
{ White is hesitating whether he wants to play d4 or c3-d4, etc. } 4... Nf6
{ In my opinion, the most logical waiting move. } 5. Nc3 d6
{ Quite a good version of a normal sicilian, since White hasn't challenged the center. }
6. d4 { The only logical move. } 6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 Be7
{ We find ourselves in the Scheveningen system, named after the Seaside district in South Holland where it was first discovered that ...e6 and ...d6 is a solid way to approach the Sicilian - back when opening novelties were prevalent. }
8. Be3 O-O
{ There is a lot of theory starting here, and castling is the precise move order.  8...a6  9.a4  O-O  10.f4  Qc7  11.Kh1  Re8  Kasparov played this position many times, but it's not so clear whether Black will finally equalize. }
9. f4
{ A different kind of system, but it's important to know how to meet this advance. }
9... e5 { White has a hard time playing for an advantage after this move. } 10.
fxe5 dxe5 11. Nf5
{ In this line, White tries to claim an advantage of the bishop pair. } 11...
Bxf5 12. Rxf5
{ 12.exf5  Qa5  is nothing for White - in fact Black is better with the passed e-pawn. }
12... g6
{ The start of an important sequence to remember, after which White has nothing... }
13. Rf1 Qxd1 14. Raxd1 Nd4
{ The key move - locking down the center so we can finish our development. }
15. Bd3
{ Basically forced, otherwise we will win back the bishop pair with no problems whatsoever. If White gets greedy, he will be punished after  15.Bxd4  exd4  16.Rxd4  Bc5  . }
15... Rac8 { 15...Kg7  is also fine, after which it's Black has equalized. } *

