1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ In this chapter we will take a look at what to do in case White decides to delay or postpone playing the early d4 break.   If you want to play the Paulsen system, ...e6 is obligatory, but if you prefer the Taimanov, you can start with ...Nc6. It all depends which of the white sidelines you prefer to face. ...e6 offers the most amount of sidelines to White, but we shouldn't be worried about any of them - 3. c3 perhaps being the most critical among them. }
3. g3
{ This is quite a serious choice for White, and was played by Carlsen against Anand in the World Championship 2014. }
3... d5 { The most solid and principled approach. } 4. exd5 exd5 5. d4
{ This is probably the only testing move, immediately challenging Black's full center in Grunfeld style. }
5... Nf6 { Calm development, supporting the center. } 6. Bg2 Be7 7. Nc3 O-O 8.
O-O Nc6
{ All of these moves are very likely to be seen on the board, after which White has some claim to a slight plus since Black will inevitably be left with an isolated d-pawn, but this shouldn't be enough to worry Black too much. }
9. dxc5
{ The principled approach. If  9.Re1  h6  is a typical move, stopping a minor piece from arriving on g5, and following up with active play in the center. Black has enough activity to compensate. }
9... Bxc5 10. Bg5 Be6
{ White is not in time to put any meaningful pressure on Black's position, and Black can follow up with d4 next with an equal game. }
