1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ In this chapter we will take a look at what to do in case White decides to delay or postpone playing the early d4 break.   If you want to play the Paulsen system, ...e6 is obligatory, but if you prefer the Taimanov, you can start with ...Nc6. It all depends which of the white sidelines you prefer to face. ...e6 offers the most amount of sidelines to White, but we shouldn't be worried about any of them - 3. c3 perhaps being the most critical among them. }
3. g3
{ This is quite a serious choice for White, and was played by Carlsen against Anand in the World Championship 2014. }
3... Nc6 { This is another reliable weapon against the g3 system. } 4. d4
{ This is a tricky way to proceed for White to catch your opponent in an interesting version of the maroczy bind with g3 instead of f3. }
4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 d5
{ A very important move, but enough to equalize.  5...Nf6  should be avoided.  6.Bg2  Be7  7.c4  O-O  8.Nc3  In this position, if White manages to castle, play b3 and consolidate the central space. }
6. Bg2
{ Here White tries to pressurize the center with the bishop instead of the knight. }
6... dxe4
{ Here we need to take, which leads to an acceptable endgame position. } 7.
Nxc6 { The only critical try. } 7... Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 bxc6 9. Bxe4 Bb7
{ The position should be equal since Black has enough dynamics to compensate for the structural liability. }
