1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ In this chapter we will take a look at what to do in case White decides to delay or postpone playing the early d4 break.   If you want to play the Paulsen system, ...e6 is obligatory, but if you prefer the Taimanov, you can start with ...Nc6. It all depends which of the white sidelines you prefer to face. ...e6 offers the most amount of sidelines to White, but we shouldn't be worried about any of them - 3. c3 perhaps being the most critical among them. }
3. Nc3
{ The only idea of this move is to avoid the mainlines of the Paulsen system from Black. }
3... a6
{ After  3...Nc6  White has nothing better than  4.d4  cxd4  and if you're a Paulsen player, you shouldn't be bothered at all by this. }
4. g3
{ This is an independent try against the early ...a6, after which the aforementioned setups with ...g6, ...Bg7 and ...Nc6 aren't playable, but Black still has a solid way forward. }
4... b5 { The logical justification of the ...a6 move. } 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. d3 d6 7.
O-O Nf6
{ Continuing normally, since the structure has been determined with d3 already. }
8. Nh4 { Making way for the f4 advance. } 8... Nc6 9. f4 Be7
{ This position is a slightly improved version of the closed Sicilian, with vague notions of a kingside attack. But Black will always have sufficient counterplay. }
