3. b3
{ This is quite a serious sideline which I've done some work on in the past in order to have it as a weapon in Rapid chess, so you should take note of how to meet the pressure on the a1-h8 diagonal. }
3... Nc6
{ Note that  3...a6  Bb2  Nc6  would transpose.   3...b6  4.Bb2  Bb7  5.Nc3  Nc6  6.d4  cxd4  7.Nxd4  Nf6  8.f3  and here it's not easy for Black to equalize since the bishop on b2 is quite threatening, and Black has taken no action to neutralize it.   3...d5  looks logical, but I'm not sure it equalizes after  4.exd5  exd5  5.Bb5+  Nc6   5...Bd7  6.Bxd7+  Qxd7  7.O-O  Nf6  8.d4  Be7  9.Bb2  This position benefits white due to the strong dark-squared bishop and Black's isolated pawn.  6.O-O  Bd6  7.Bb2  Nf6  8.Qe2+  Be6  Ng5  here, if Black manages to finish development, they will be fine, but it's not without some risk. }
4. Bb2 a6
{ Prepares ...d5 without allowing White the Bb5 pin.  4...Nf6  5.e5  Nd5  This is a different way to play leading to some strange positions which need to be carefully analyzed before testing them, but Black should be ok.   4...d5  Bb5  leads to some problems for Black as they will lose all control of the central dark squares. }
5. c4 { Stopping Black's idea of ...d5. } 5... Qc7
{ And from here, Black's play will revolve around preventing White from conveniently playing d4. }
6. g3 Nf6 7. e5
{ This is possible, to attempt to sacrifice the pawn and play for compensation, but White will never be better after }
7... Ng4 8. Bg2 Ngxe5
{ Black is doing just fine since d4 will remain impossible for some time to come. }
