[Black "3rd Move Sidelines: 3.c4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ In this chapter we will take a look at what to do in case White decides to delay or postpone playing the early d4 break.   If you want to play the Paulsen system, ...e6 is obligatory, but if you prefer the Taimanov, you can start with ...Nc6. It all depends which of the white sidelines you prefer to face. ...e6 offers the most amount of sidelines to White, but we shouldn't be worried about any of them - 3. c3 perhaps being the most critical among them. }
3. c4
{ This was mostly considered to be completely harmless, and still is - but it can lead to some complex positions we need to be aware of. }
3... Nc6 4. Nc3
{ This is one alternative to the immediate d4, so Black should do what they can to neutralize this break in the future. }
4... Nf6 5. Be2
{ White now wants to play d4 and castle, so Black's reply is basically forced. }
5... d5
{ Clearly the best move, opening the position and avoiding being cramped by Maroczy type positions if White is able to acheive d4, after which the white queen will have influence over the d5 square. }
6. cxd5
{ Taking with the c-pawn is not so critical, as White cannot break with d4 next. }
6... exd5 7. e5 Nd7 8. Nxd5 Ndxe5
{ Winning back the pawn with a basically equal position with nothing much to play for for either side. }
*

