[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 30: 2.Nf3 e6 3rd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "3rd Move Sidelines: 3.c4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ In this chapter we will take a look at what to do in case White decides to delay or postpone playing the early d4 break.   If you want to play the Paulsen system, ...e6 is obligatory, but if you prefer the Taimanov, you can start with ...Nc6. It all depends which of the white sidelines you prefer to face. ...e6 offers the most amount of sidelines to White, but we shouldn't be worried about any of them - 3. c3 perhaps being the most critical among them. }
3. c4
{ This was mostly considered to be completely harmless, and still is - but it can lead to some complex positions we need to be aware of. }
3... Nc6 4. Nc3
{ This is one alternative to the immediate d4, so Black should do what they can to neutralize this break in the future. }
4... Nf6 5. Be2
{ White now wants to play d4 and castle, so Black's reply is basically forced. }
5... d5
{ Clearly the best move, opening the position and avoiding being cramped by Maroczy type positions if White is able to acheive d4, after which the white queen will have influence over the d5 square. }
6. exd5
{ The mainline, preparing d4 when this time the e-pawn will not be loose. }
6... exd5 7. d4
{ This is White's concept, but Black can equalize in multiple ways. } 7... cxd4
{ This is the start of my recommended route to equality - more concrete and simple.  7...Be6  is another way that keeps more tension in the position, putting pressure on c4.  8.O-O  dxc4  9.Be3  Nxd4  10.Nxd4  cxd4  11.Bxd4  Qa5  Alexander Grischuk used this against me in 2011 Candidates which was enough to equalize. }
8. Nxd4 dxc4 9. Nxc6
{ White attempts to ruin our structure, but it's not enough. } 9... Qxd1+
{ Making sure to throw in this intermezzo to mess up White's coordination. }
10. Nxd1 bxc6 11. Bxc4 Bc5
{ Another reliable option is  11...Bb4+  12.Bd2  Bxd2+  13.Kxd2  and there's such reduced material that it's hard to imagine White having anything here. }
12. Be3 Bb6
{ Black doesn't take, and help White re-develop his knight, but rather maintains the tension, which equalizes. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 30: 2.Nf3 e6 3rd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "3rd Move Sidelines: 3.c4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ In this chapter we will take a look at what to do in case White decides to delay or postpone playing the early d4 break.   If you want to play the Paulsen system, ...e6 is obligatory, but if you prefer the Taimanov, you can start with ...Nc6. It all depends which of the white sidelines you prefer to face. ...e6 offers the most amount of sidelines to White, but we shouldn't be worried about any of them - 3. c3 perhaps being the most critical among them. }
3. c4
{ This was mostly considered to be completely harmless, and still is - but it can lead to some complex positions we need to be aware of. }
3... Nc6 4. d4 cxd4 { We always need to take on d4. } 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Bb4
{ A strong move, fighting for control of e4. } 7. Nxc6 bxc6
{ 7...dxc6  should be avoided because it's quite unpleasant for Black after  8.Qxd8  Kxd8  9.e5  Ne4   9...Nd7  10.Bf4  Bxc3+  11.bxc3  is a clear advantage for White with more space and active prospects.  10.a3  is a very important resource when after  10...Ba5  White has  11.b4  Nxc3  12.bxa5  when the knight is in no man's land. }
8. Bd3
{ This looks relatively harmless but is quite popular so best to be accurate.  8.e5  Ne4  of course gives Black good pressure and an advantage. }
8... e5
{ We play this to solidify White's light-squared bishop as a bad piece, and to grab some central space. }
9. O-O O-O 10. h3 Bc5
{ Rerouting the bishop to the most active diagonal now that there's no pin.  10...d6  going for a quick ...d5 is not so great after  11.Na4  d5  12.exd5  cxd5  13.a3  Be7  14.cxd5  and here I won against Garry Kasparov in a nice rapid game in a similar structure. White has a small plus with the queenside majority, and Black's e-pawn as a liability. }
11. Na4 Bd4
{ Black shouldn't have any problems here, following up with the normal moves, ...a5, ...h6, ...d6 and completing development. Having secured a piece on d4 is a big achievement for Black. }
*

