6. Bb5+ { Developing with tempo, but luckily it also helps us develop. } 6...
Bd7 7. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 8. O-O Be7 9. dxc5 Nxc5
{ This position should be a draw but as discussed, the IQP gives White a slight plus. }
10. Be3 O-O
{ Standard moves will follow, leading to a very small edge for White. } 11. Re1
Re8 12. Qc2 Qd7 13. Nbd2 b5
{ A typical plan for Black is to push the b- and a-pawns up the board and eventually go for ...b4, undermining White's control of d4. }
14. h3 a5 15. Nb3 Ne6 16. Nbd4 b4
{ May be an equalizing move. Whatever slight pull White had is disappearing. }
