[Black "3rd Move Sidelines: 3.c3 (Alternative: 3...Nf6 / 6...b6 #2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ In this chapter we will take a look at what to do in case White decides to delay or postpone playing the early d4 break.   If you want to play the Paulsen system, ...e6 is obligatory, but if you prefer the Taimanov, you can start with ...Nc6. It all depends which of the white sidelines you prefer to face. ...e6 offers the most amount of sidelines to White, but we shouldn't be worried about any of them - 3. c3 perhaps being the most critical among them. }
3. c3
{ Perhaps the most critical of White's sidelines against 2...e6. But as we will see, it's not enough to stop us from playing it! As White, you can choose this to avoid entering many theoretical discussions you'll find in other lines, but you can still hope for some kind of opening advantage. }
3... Nf6
{ This is a playable alternative to  3...d5  but the move ...e6 having been committed means Black will have a harder time equalizing compared to version of this line with ...Nc6 but without ...e6. }
4. e5 Nd5 5. d4 { White's logical follow-up - taking the full center. } 5...
cxd4 6. cxd4 b6
{ This system is very risky. Just for reference, the mainline goes as follows: }
7. Nc3 { Not White's only option but indeed quite dangerous. } 7... Nxc3 8.
bxc3 Qc7 { Putting pressure on c3 and provoking Bd2. } 9. Bd2 Bb7 10. Bd3 d6
{ Sooner or later this is necessary, to contest White's space advantage. } 11.
O-O Nd7
{ This type of position needs to be concretely analyzed before playing. For instance, White has dangerous threats against the vulnerable f7-point. }
12. Re1 { This is the mainline, lining up against Black's king. } 12... dxe5
{ 12...h6  is too slow and after  13.Bf4  White is better.   12...Be7  13.Ng5  dxe5  14.Qh5  Bxg5   14...g6  15.Qh6  is too dangerous to allow.  15.Bxg5  Black  again has some issues with the king stuck in the center and it might be defensible but very risky. }
13. Nxe5
{ This is the mainline, but again,  13.Ng5  must be checked to be sure Black isn't getting wiped off the board. }
13... Nxe5
{ The main move, as this knight is too dangerous to be left unchecked.  13...Bd6  f4  creates a nice central bind with good attacking prospects for White. }
14. Rxe5 Bd6 15. Rh5 g6
{ Here Black would be completely without problems if it weren't for White's next move. }
16. Bb5+ Ke7 { 16...Bc6  17.Qf3  is lights out for Black. } 17. Rh3 h5 18. c4
a6
{ Engines believe this is holdable for Black, but we have to jump through many hoops to get here, and it's still not so pleasant with our king in the center in the middlegame. }
