1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ In this chapter we will take a look at what to do in case White decides to delay or postpone playing the early d4 break.   If you want to play the Paulsen system, ...e6 is obligatory, but if you prefer the Taimanov, you can start with ...Nc6. It all depends which of the white sidelines you prefer to face. ...e6 offers the most amount of sidelines to White, but we shouldn't be worried about any of them - 3. c3 perhaps being the most critical among them. }
3. c3
{ Perhaps the most critical of White's sidelines against 2...e6. But as we will see, it's not enough to stop us from playing it! As White, you can choose this to avoid entering many theoretical discussions you'll find in other lines, but you can still hope for some kind of opening advantage. }
3... Nf6
{ This is a playable alternative to  3...d5  but the move ...e6 having been committed means Black will have a harder time equalizing compared to version of this line with ...Nc6 but without ...e6. }
4. e5 Nd5 5. d4 { White's logical follow-up - taking the full center. } 5...
cxd4 6. cxd4 d6
{ This is my main recommendation in these 3...Nf6 alternative variations. It's a bit more solid and popular. We need to counter in the center immediately. }
7. Bc4 Be7 8. O-O O-O
{ As you can see, Black is in no danger of getting crushed as in some lines of the ... b6 system, but White still maintains some chances for an advantage. }
9. Qe2 Nc6
{ The main move, leaving the c8-bishop passive for the moment in favor of pressurizing the center. }
10. Rd1 { White's main move, not yet offering central simplifications. } 10...
Qc7
{ Stepping off the dangerous d-file.  10...Na5  might also equalize, but it's a bit more obscure.  11.Bd3   11.Bxd5  exd5  12.Nc3  Be6  13.Bf4  Here even though the computer gives equality, I believe it's more comfortable for White because of Black's bad e6-bishop.  11...Nb4  is the idea, insisting on winning the bishop pair in exchange for some time.  12.Nc3  Nxd3  13.Rxd3  It's still not straightforward to equalize since White has some dangerous ideas on the kingside now that the rook is active.  13...b6  14.b4  Nc6  15.a3  d5  16.Bf4  This is a very dangerous position with an attack looming. }
11. Bd2 Rd8
{ Black is very close to equalizing, but no guarantees. There is a lot of tension in the position and it is Black whose position is more precarious. That's why I prefer 3...d5 ultimately. }
