1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The move employed by Najdorf or Dragon players. Sometimes Rauzer players play this order instead of  2...Nc6  but, in general, White's sidelines against  2...Nc6  are far more challenging than the ones we'll see here. Therefore, I think it's safer to start with  2...d6  . }
3. b4
{ The craziest line in this chapter. Better thanthe 2.b4 line, but still not good. Maybe White can't even equalize here. }
3... cxb4 4. d4 Nf6 5. Bd3 e5
{ The most testing.  5...g6  is another approach. White will try to get some compensation with a timely a3, but Black should be fine. }
6. O-O exd4 7. Nxd4 Nc6 { 7...Be7  may be more principled. } 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9.
Qe1 Be7 { Black will castle next with a perfectly equal position. } *

