1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The move employed by Najdorf or Dragon players. Sometimes Rauzer players play this order instead of  2...Nc6  but, in general, White's sidelines against  2...Nc6  are far more challenging than the ones we'll see here. Therefore, I think it's safer to start with  2...d6  . }
3. g3 { Another sideline that shouldn't be worrying. } 3... Nf6 4. Nc3 g6
{ 4...e5  is another way of playing. } 5. Bg2 Bg7
{ Steering the game into a Dragon, where g3-systems are rather harmless. } 6.
d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 O-O 8. O-O Nc6
{ White needs to decide what to do with his knight. } 9. Nb3
{ After  9.Nxc6  bxc6  10.e5  dxe5  11.Qxd8  Rxd8  12.Bxc6  Rb8  White gets a better pawn structure, but Black is extremely active. Following ...Bf5 only Black can fight for an advantage. }
9... Bg4 10. f3 Be6
{ Keeping an eye on the d5-square, but the bishop can retreat to d7 too. } 11.
Nd5 b5 { Black is very comfortable. } *

