1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The move employed by Najdorf or Dragon players. Sometimes Rauzer players play this order instead of  2...Nc6  but, in general, White's sidelines against  2...Nc6  are far more challenging than the ones we'll see here. Therefore, I think it's safer to start with  2...d6  . }
3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 { This makes more sense. } 4... cxd4 5. Qxd4
{ 5.Nxd4  transposes back to standard Open Sicilian lines. } 5... Nc6
{ Black shouldn't be afraid of  6.Bb5  . } 6. Bb5 Bd7 7. Bxc6
{ 7.Qd3  g6  is a fantastic Dragon. } 7... Bxc6
{ If  7...bxc6  White has the annoying  8.e5  . } 8. Bg5 e6 9. O-O-O Be7
{ White can't fight for the advantage and can even become worse. } 10. Rhe1 O-O
11. Kb1 h6
{ Kasparov's idea, which buried this line. White can't get the desirable Qd2-Nd4 setup.   Instead,  11...Qc7  12.Qd2  Rfd8  13.Nd4  leads to a typical position with opposite-side castling.  13...Rab8  14.f3  b5  15.g4  b4  16.Nce2  a5  17.Ng3  Both sides are busy with their attacks, but Black's prospects seem better. }
12. Bxf6 { This leads by force to a better endgame for Black. } 12... Bxf6 13.
Qxd6 Qb6 { Forcing the white queen back. } 14. Qd2 Rad8 15. Qe3
{ Now Black gets the pawn back. } 15... Bxc3 16. Qxb6 Rxd1+ 17. Rxd1 axb6 18.
bxc3 Bxe4 { Black's bishop is superior to White's knight. } *

