1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The move employed by Najdorf or Dragon players. Sometimes Rauzer players play this order instead of  2...Nc6  but, in general, White's sidelines against  2...Nc6  are far more challenging than the ones we'll see here. Therefore, I think it's safer to start with  2...d6  . }
3. d4 Nf6 { A way to sidestep the Qxd4 systems with c4 and the 5.f3 line. } 4.
dxc5
{ The only move with independent value.  4.Nc3  cxd4  5.Nxd4  leads to normal Open Sicilians.   4.Bb5+  Bd7  5.Bxd7+  Qxd7  is harmless. }
4... Nxe4 { The point. } 5. cxd6 Nc6 { The most accurate. } 6. Be3 e5
{ This is the most precise. White can still pose some problems after  6...Nxd6  7.Nc3  g6  8.Nb5  . }
7. Bd3 Nxd6 8. Nc3 Be7 9. Qe2
{ This position deserves some analysis. If Black is fine here, then @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/2p5/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  might be a good order to deprive White of some options. However, as shown throughout this chapter, those systems were not particularly dangerous, to begin with.It's probably a matter of taste, but anyway  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/2p5/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...cxd4  is by far the most popular move. }
