1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The move employed by Najdorf or Dragon players. Sometimes Rauzer players play this order instead of  2...Nc6  but, in general, White's sidelines against  2...Nc6  are far more challenging than the ones we'll see here. Therefore, I think it's safer to start with  2...d6  . }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ A popular way to skip tons of theory and get a playable position, but Black shouldn't be worried. }
4... Nc6 5. Bb5
{ More challenging than  5.Qe3  g6  6.Be2  Bg7  7.O-O  Nf6  8.h3  O-O  9.Rd1  Be6=  . Black is always comfortable in Dragon setups when White hasn't castled queenside. Also, White has lost some tempi here with his queen. }
5... a6
{ Very principled and interesting. This was seen in Rapport-Firouzja, Candidates 2022. }
6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. c4
{ White's usual plan in this system is to set up a Maroczy bind. } 7... e5 8.
Qd3 Ne7 { Black will eventually try to break in the center with ...f5. } 9. c5
{ Otherwise, Black gets very comfortable. } 9... Ng6 10. cxd6
{ The endgame after ...Qxd6 is pretty equal. } *

