[Black "5.f3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The move employed by Najdorf or Dragon players. Sometimes Rauzer players play this order instead of  2...Nc6  but, in general, White's sidelines against  2...Nc6  are far more challenging than the ones we'll see here. Therefore, I think it's safer to start with  2...d6  . }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ White still has one way of steering the game away from Sicilian main systems. }
5. f3
{ The idea is to protect the e4-pawn to set up a Maroczy bind with c4 and Nc3. However, it is too slow, and allows Black to equalize directly. }
5... e5
{ I recommend this direct equalizer, which is the biggest problem of White's system.  5...Nc6  keeps the game alive, but allows White to transpose back into standard lines after  6.Nc3  e5  7.Nb3  . Also, Black has to work to equalize after  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2np1n2/8/3NP3/5P2/PPP3PP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.c4  . }
6. Bb5+ Nbd7 7. Nf5 { This aggressive approach doesn't work well. } 7... d5 8.
exd5 a6 { White should already be thinking about equalizing. } 9. Ba4
{ This is simply too risky.  9.Be2  Nb6  10.Ne3  is a modest but sensible continuation, and probably White's best. }
9... b5 10. Bb3 { Trying to hold onto the pawn doesn't end well for White. }
10... Nc5 11. Ne3 Bd6 { Followed by ...O-O and ...e4 with huge compensation. }
*

