{ By far, the main move.  4.h3  Nc6  5.Bd3  transposes and  5.Qc2  e5  looks like a good Ruy Lopez for Black. }
4... g6
{ The simplest and most logical, stopping d4. Me and other strong players have gone for  4...Bd7  in the past. }
5. O-O Bg7 6. Bb5+
{ Played by Anand or Adams in the 90s. this may be White's only try to get d4. If now  6...Nbd7  7.Re1  a6  8.Bf1  White gets d4.   After  6.Re1  O-O  7.Bf1  e5  or  7...Nc6  Black is threatening to put an end to d4 ideas.  8.h3  e5  and White can say goodbye to d2-d4, so it's now or never for  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/2np1np1/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQRBK1 w - - 6 8@@EndFEN@@  8.d4  but  8...cxd4  9.cxd4  Bg4  10.d5  Ne5  11.Nbd2  Qa5  and White's center is shaky. }
6... Nc6 { The sharp, ambitious option. } 7. d4 O-O 8. d5 a6
{ 9...Na5  9.Re1  e6  10.Bf1  Re8  leads to a strange position. The knight looks out of place but can't be captured. Black has fine development. }
9. Bd3 Na5 10. Bg5 { 10.a4  e6  Black has to break in the center. } 10... h6
11. Bh4 b5 12. Nbd2 e6
{ Again, breaking in the center is the way to go. This position is equal and unclear. }
