[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 31: 2.Nf3 d6 3rd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "3.c3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The move employed by Najdorf or Dragon players. Sometimes Rauzer players play this order instead of  2...Nc6  but, in general, White's sidelines against  2...Nc6  are far more challenging than the ones we'll see here. Therefore, I think it's safer to start with  2...d6  . }
3. c3
{ A logical attempt, though not really dangerous. Black has more than one way to reach a good position. }
3... Nf6
{ The most logical reply, intending to stop d4. Notice Black is not threatening  4.--  ...Nxe4  due to  5.Qa4+  . }
4. Be2
{ By far, the main move.  4.h3  Nc6  5.Bd3  transposes and  5.Qc2  e5  looks like a good Ruy Lopez for Black. }
4... g6
{ The simplest and most logical, stopping d4. Me and other strong players have gone for  4...Bd7  in the past. }
5. O-O Bg7 6. Bb5+
{ Played by Anand or Adams in the 90s. this may be White's only try to get d4. If now  6...Nbd7  7.Re1  a6  8.Bf1  White gets d4.   After  6.Re1  O-O  7.Bf1  e5  or  7...Nc6  Black is threatening to put an end to d4 ideas.  8.h3  e5  and White can say goodbye to d2-d4, so it's now or never for  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/2np1np1/2p5/4P3/2P2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQRBK1 w - - 6 8@@EndFEN@@  8.d4  but  8...cxd4  9.cxd4  Bg4  10.d5  Ne5  11.Nbd2  Qa5  and White's center is shaky. }
6... Bd7 { This is more solid. } 7. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 8. Re1
{ 8.Qe2  is also met by  8...Ne5  . } 8... Ne5 9. d4
{ After  9.Nxe5  dxe5  White gets nothing. } 9... Nxf3+ 10. Qxf3 Nd7 11. Rd1
{ White has the center but, with some pieces off the board, he shouldn't expect much. }
