1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The move employed by Najdorf or Dragon players. Sometimes Rauzer players play this order instead of  2...Nc6  but, in general, White's sidelines against  2...Nc6  are far more challenging than the ones we'll see here. Therefore, I think it's safer to start with  2...d6  . }
3. Bb5+
{ The only serious attempt for an edge, other than  3.d4  . From the point of view of White players, the Moscow Variation entails fewer risks and is less theoretically demanding than the main lines of the Open Sicilian. }
3... Bd7
{ This move is perfectly fine, though not as popular nowadays, which is probably a matter of fashion. It reduces White's combating options and Black is safe in these lines as long as he is well prepared and knows some critical positions.I don't have a clear explanation as to why people stopped playing this way. White has more reasons than Black to be concerned about getting move-ordered. I think it's a good weapon for club players with the Black pieces, and I can't find a way for White to get an advantage against this system. }
4. Bxd7+ Qxd7 { White has very few tries to get some edge. } 5. c4
{ The only challenging plan and by far the most popular among top players. If White succeeds in creating a Maroczy bind, he should be slightly better, although Black's position is solid. However, White's plan is not so easy to execute. }
5... Nc6 { This used to be popular. } 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 g6 8. Nc3 Bg7 9. Nde2
{ This move allows White to get a better version of the lines with @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  , and casts some doubts over the order starting with  @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  . }
9... Nf6 { Now  9...Nh6  doesn't work so well because ...Ng4 is pointless. }
10. f3 O-O 11. O-O a6 12. a4
{ I played this against Gelfand already in 1994, when the Moscow Variation was starting to become popular at the top level. Nowadays, all top players have used it at some point. }
12... Qd8 { Gelfand's plan. } 13. Kh1 Qa5 14. Rb1 Rfc8
{ This seemingly balanced position contains some venom. If Black's counterplay @@StartBracket@@usually connected to some break on b5 or d5@@EndBracket@@ runs out of steam, he might very well get outplayed. Definitely, not the smoothest path to equality, which makes the @@StartFEN@@rn2kbnr/pp1qpppp/3p4/2p5/2P1P3/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  order a more sensible choice. }
