[Black "3.Bb5+ Nd7 4.c4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The move employed by Najdorf or Dragon players. Sometimes Rauzer players play this order instead of  2...Nc6  but, in general, White's sidelines against  2...Nc6  are far more challenging than the ones we'll see here. Therefore, I think it's safer to start with  2...d6  . }
3. Bb5+
{ The only serious attempt for an edge, other than  3.d4  . From the point of view of White players, the Moscow Variation entails fewer risks and is less theoretically demanding than the main lines of the Open Sicilian. }
3... Nd7
{ The most popular nowadays, perhaps due to the fact that Najdorf players prefer complicated play. According to the modern state of theory, this system is also in good shape. }
4. c4 { Not dangerous if Black knows how to develop. } 4... Nf6 5. Nc3
{ A move like  5...e5  is possible, but  5...g6  is a better plan. } 5... g6
{ This is Black's best setup with the knight on d7. } 6. O-O Bg7 7. d4 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 O-O { White's bishop belongs on e2 and is completely misplaced on b5. } 9.
Ba4
{ This runs into some annoying tactics.   9.Bxd7  is probably White's best chance, which says a lot.  9...Bxd7  10.Qd3  White has got nothing tangible out of the opening.  10...a6  11.a4  Ng4  12.Nf3  Rc8=  Black should be okay here. White is missing his light-squared bishop. }
9... Qb6
{ A nice alternative is  9...Nb6  10.Bb3  Nfd7  , but the text is stronger. }
10. Nde2 Nc5
{ Putting some pressure on c4 with  10...Qc7  11.Bb3  Nb6  is fine too. } 11.
Bc2 Be6 { 11...Qa6  is nice too. } 12. b3 { This fails tactically. } 12...
Nfxe4 { A recurring resource. Black simply wins a pawn. } *

