1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The move employed by Najdorf or Dragon players. Sometimes Rauzer players play this order instead of  2...Nc6  but, in general, White's sidelines against  2...Nc6  are far more challenging than the ones we'll see here. Therefore, I think it's safer to start with  2...d6  . }
3. Bb5+
{ The only serious attempt for an edge, other than  3.d4  . From the point of view of White players, the Moscow Variation entails fewer risks and is less theoretically demanding than the main lines of the Open Sicilian. }
3... Nd7
{ The most popular nowadays, perhaps due to the fact that Najdorf players prefer complicated play. According to the modern state of theory, this system is also in good shape. }
4. d4 { White is taking unnecessary risks. } 4... cxd4 { Black's best. } 5.
Qxd4
{ I don't believe in  5.Nxd4  Nf6  6.O-O  a6  7.Bd3  , but could be checked. }
5... a6 6. Be2 { The most popular move nowadays. } 6... Ngf6 7. O-O
{ The main move. } 7... e5 { Again,  7...g6  is possible. } 8. Qe3 Nc5
{ Or  8...Be7  9.c4  . } 9. Nfd2
{ Other moves allow Black to develop comfortably. For example, after  9.Nbd2  a future c4 is pointless, and  9.Nc3  Be7  10.Rd1  Bd7  leads to a Najdorf-like position where Black is fine. }
9... Be7 10. c4
{ This is what White wanted, but the knight on d2 breaks the harmony. } 10...
O-O 11. Nc3 Bd7 12. a4 Rc8
{ White would be great if he managed to transfer the d2-knight to d5. Easier said than done, though. }
