1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The move employed by Najdorf or Dragon players. Sometimes Rauzer players play this order instead of  2...Nc6  but, in general, White's sidelines against  2...Nc6  are far more challenging than the ones we'll see here. Therefore, I think it's safer to start with  2...d6  . }
3. Bb5+
{ The only serious attempt for an edge, other than  3.d4  . From the point of view of White players, the Moscow Variation entails fewer risks and is less theoretically demanding than the main lines of the Open Sicilian. }
3... Nd7
{ The most popular nowadays, perhaps due to the fact that Najdorf players prefer complicated play. According to the modern state of theory, this system is also in good shape. }
4. O-O a6 { This is perfectly fine, though not the most played. } 5. Bd3
{ A strange move whose idea is to keep the e4-protected. } 5... Ngf6
{ 5...b5  runs into  6.c4!  and Black has some issues to solve. } 6. Re1
{ The most popular, intending a Maroczy-like setup. } 6... e6
{ Again,  6...g6  is a perfectly normal plan. A sample line is  7.c3  Bg7  8.Bc2  O-O  9.d4  cxd4  10.cxd4  b5  11.Nc3  Bb7  12.a3  Rc8  with a complicated game ahead. Both sides have got decent positions out of the opening.   Black could deviate with @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1p1nppbp/p2p1np1/2p5/3PP3/2P2N2/PPB2PPP/RNBQR1K1 b - d3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qc7  , which scores well. As long as e4-e5 ideas don't work, Black should be okay. }
7. c4 { This is White's idea, although  7.c3  b5  is another option. } 7... Be7
8. Nc3 O-O 9. Bf1 b6 10. d4 { White can't try anything without this move. }
10... cxd4 11. Nxd4 Bb7 12. b3 Rc8
{ White is probably more comfortable thanks to his space advantage, but his setup is less than ideal. This position offers Black chances to take over, exactly the kind of scenario Black players are looking for when they opt for @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nd7  : a complicated game. }
13. Bb2 Qc7 14. Rc1 Qb8 { With a long struggle ahead. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
