[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 31: 2.Nf3 d6 3rd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "3.Bb5+ Nd7 4.O-O #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The move employed by Najdorf or Dragon players. Sometimes Rauzer players play this order instead of  2...Nc6  but, in general, White's sidelines against  2...Nc6  are far more challenging than the ones we'll see here. Therefore, I think it's safer to start with  2...d6  . }
3. Bb5+
{ The only serious attempt for an edge, other than  3.d4  . From the point of view of White players, the Moscow Variation entails fewer risks and is less theoretically demanding than the main lines of the Open Sicilian. }
3... Nd7
{ The most popular nowadays, perhaps due to the fact that Najdorf players prefer complicated play. According to the modern state of theory, this system is also in good shape. }
4. O-O Nf6 { I would recommend this simpler approach. } 5. Ba4
{ A recent discovery. The point is  5...a6  6.c4  transposing to  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1npppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  lines. }
5... e6
{ A simple path to equality.  5...Nxe4  6.Re1  Nef6  7.d4  offers White a very powerful initiative. }
6. Re1 Be7 7. c4 O-O
{ We have seena similar position in the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1npppp/3p4/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  system where White skipped Re1. Here he is a tempo down, in a way, because Re1 is unnecessary, and thus can't get Nc3 and d4 in. }
8. d4 { After  8.Nc3  Ne5  9.d3  Nxf3+  10.Qxf3  Nd7  , White gets nothing. }
8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 Qc7 { The most straightforward, targeting the c4-pawn. } 10.
Bb3 { The bishop is not happy here, but what to do? } 10... a6 11. Nc3 Ne5
{ Black can force a draw with a very concrete sequence.  11...b6  keeps the game alive. }
12. Qe2 Bd7 13. f4 Qb6 14. Be3 Neg4
{ And here comes a beautiful variation which obviously both sides need to know in advance. }
15. Nf5 Bd8
{ Hard to find this move on your own, but top players know their stuff. } 16.
Ne7+ Kh8 17. Bxb6 Bxb6+ 18. Kh1 Nf2+ { With a perpetual. } 19. Kg1 N2g4+ 20.
Kh1 { Of course not  21.Kf1??  Nxh2  . } 20... Nf2+
{ And draw. This line has buried the @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1nbppp/3ppn2/2p5/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQR1K1 w kq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.c4  system. }
