{ It's tempting to play this move, hoping for  4.d4  in order to transpose. }
4. Bb5
{ This is the problem for Black, and the reason 3...Nf6 isn't seen in practice all that often anymore. There is the serious danger of being crushed here in 20 moves! }
4... Qc7
{ The @@StartBracket@@relatively@@EndBracket@@ best move in the position. } 5.
O-O Nd4 { A strange and risky way of playing, but it's not that bad. } 6. Re1
{ A more solid approach. } 6... a6 7. e5
{ This was used by Vishy Anand against me in Linares 2003. } 7... Nxb5 8. exf6
Nxc3 9. fxg7 Bxg7 10. dxc3 d6
{ A very strange and unbalanced position where both sides have their trumps. Black seems to be doing alright. Objectively it's probably equal. }
