4. Bc4
{ The d5-square is greatly weakened and White immediately makes use of it. Black will be trying to exchange every piece that fights for the d5-square, be it a knight, or the light-squared bishop. If that strategy is successful, equality is usually not far away. }
4... d6 5. d3 Be7 { 5...Nf6  would be a blunder because of  6.Ng5! } 6. O-O Nf6
7. a3
{ I once played this way myself, aiming for a small advantage, but it can't be much. }
7... O-O 8. h3 a6 9. Ba2 Be6
{ Play resembles the Ruy Lopez and I think players who have some experience in that opening shouldn't have too many worries here as Black. }
