{ A very popular move, especially 20 years ago when the Sveshnikov Variation was extremely popular. It should be said that the Sveshnikov is still very popular to this day, with, for example, Magnus Carlsen using it as his main weapon in his 2018 World Championship match against Fabiano Caruana. Boris Gelfand used the same strategy in his World Championship match against Vishy Anand in 2012 and still plays the variation to this day.   3.Nc3  is considered a good way to avoid the Sveshnikov Variation, and Kasparov, Anand, Leko, and I have used this move repeatedly and with both colors! Heavy debates were taking place in this line. Of course, if you play the Classical Sicilian, the move  3.Nc3  is not very bothersome, as you can simply play  3...d6  , and White doesn't have much better than  4.d4  , transposing back into the desired variation. The same goes for the Taimanov Variation after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  4.d4  .  However, if you play the Sveshnikov Variation, you are in trouble. :@@EndBracket@@ Best Black's options are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e5  and  3...g6  , which, however, leads to a fundamentally different game, meaning your choice is mostly a matter of style. Both moves give good chances for an equal game, but while  3...e5  is a solid way to try and accomplish that,  3...g6  is a very sharp way of doing so. }
3... e5
{ A very radical way of playing, stopping d2-d4 indefinitely. Play here resembles Ruy Lopez somewhat. This move, too, has been played with both colors by Kasparov, Leko, myself, and others. While I think Black is probably equalizing in this variation, I never did mind playing it with White, as at least you get a game, and usually, a bit of pressure always remains. }
4. Bc4
{ The d5-square is greatly weakened and White immediately makes use of it. Black will be trying to exchange every piece that fights for the d5-square, be it a knight, or the light-squared bishop. If that strategy is successful, equality is usually not far away. }
4... d6 5. d3 Be7 { 5...Nf6  would be a blunder because of  6.Ng5! } 6. Ng5
{ A move that at first sight seems to blunder a piece. After some time you might realize it isn't, but actually, it is! I have some good memories of this move as it was played in my only rapid game against World Champion Mikhail Tal. I was 15, it was 1991 and I played a strong open in Moscow.  On the rest day, there was a rapid tournament in which Tal participated. At some point, we were paired and he must have looked at his opponent, some young boy, and, considering he anyway wanted simply to have a good time playing this rapid event, he probably didn't take me too seriously and went for this move. I, however, was aware of the knight jump! }
6... Bxg5 7. Qh5 { Threatening mate and the bishop on g5. } 7... Be7
{ I played this move fast and as it turns out, now both mate is prevented and the bishop is no longer attacked! }
8. Qxf7+ Kd7 9. Qxg7 Nf6 10. O-O Kc7 11. f4 Kb8
{ White has some play for the piece, but it just isn't enough and I managed to win rather quickly. A cherished memory! All in all, @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp2bppp/2np4/2p1p3/2B1P3/2NP1N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Ng5  can't be recommended. }
*

