{ This was considered a mistake in the past because it forces the exchange of Black's a-pawn for White's e-pawn. The engines have shown it not to be that clear-cut. }
9... a4 10. Nxa4 Nxe4 11. Nb5 { Threatening Be3-b6. } 11... Ra6 12. Qe2
{ White intends to play Rad1 and c2-c4 with an excellent grip of the position. This realization basically made 8...a5 disappear from tournament practice. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 32: 2...Nc6 3.c3 & 3.Nc3"]
[Black "Sicilian 3.Nc3 g6 − 6.Be3 Nf6 7.Bc4 O-O #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ In this lesson we will look at sidelines in the Sicilian with  2...Nc6  . There are certain Sicilian variations that force the second player to start with the  2...Nc6  move order. We mainly speak about the Sveshnikov after  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5  , but it also counts for the Accelerated Dragon @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...g6  , which both can't be reached properly through other move orders. As we have seen, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...g6  , White has quite a number of promising alternatives to  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  .  Another system that deserves to be mentioned is the Kalashnikov Variation which starts after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  e5  followed by  5.Nb5  d6  . As I said though, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  is mainly used at the top level to play the Sveshnikov Variation, which is an excellent opening that we will be spending a lot of time on as well − when we move to the variations with  3.d4  .  If you play the Classical Sicilian @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  d6  , or the Taimanov @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  e6  , I would rather advise you to go through the move order of playing @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  @@StartBracket@@in case of the Classical@@EndBracket@@ or  2...e6  @@StartBracket@@in case of the Taimanov@@EndBracket@@ instead, in order to avoid the difficult Rossolimo Variation: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  .  It is true that after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  , there are fewer sidelines, yet they are more dangerous compared to the sidelines after  2...d6  and  2...e6  . Having said that, Black is of course perfectly fine after both  2...Nc6  3.Bb5  and  3.Nc3  , yet they pose some problems. We will have a look at them in the next lessons. }
3. Nc3
{ A very popular move, especially 20 years ago when the Sveshnikov Variation was extremely popular. It should be said that the Sveshnikov is still very popular to this day, with, for example, Magnus Carlsen using it as his main weapon in his 2018 World Championship match against Fabiano Caruana. Boris Gelfand used the same strategy in his World Championship match against Vishy Anand in 2012 and still plays the variation to this day.   3.Nc3  is considered a good way to avoid the Sveshnikov Variation, and Kasparov, Anand, Leko, and I have used this move repeatedly and with both colors! Heavy debates were taking place in this line. Of course, if you play the Classical Sicilian, the move  3.Nc3  is not very bothersome, as you can simply play  3...d6  , and White doesn't have much better than  4.d4  , transposing back into the desired variation. The same goes for the Taimanov Variation after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  4.d4  .  However, if you play the Sveshnikov Variation, you are in trouble. :@@EndBracket@@ Best Black's options are @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e5  and  3...g6  , which, however, leads to a fundamentally different game, meaning your choice is mostly a matter of style. Both moves give good chances for an equal game, but while  3...e5  is a solid way to try and accomplish that,  3...g6  is a very sharp way of doing so. }
3... g6
{ The most challenging move for White and at the same time riskier than  3...e5  . It reminds us of the Dragon Variation, but that line is under pressure because of lines involving queenside castling by White. Yet, via this move order that is not possible and that makes it an attractive option for Black. Of course, you will need to learn a lot of theory here, as is the case with any Sicilian where the bishop  is developed to g7, but I believe it to be perfectly playable for Black. }
4. d4
{ Almost forced as  4.Bb5  Bg7  is a good version of  the Rossolimo with the knight already developed on c3. More on that in the next lesson. Other 4th moves by White also don't impress and will allow Black to gain good control over the d4-square with ...Bf8-g7 next. }
4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 Bg7 6. Be3 { The only way to fight for an advantage. } 6...
Nf6
{ Having not yet played ...d7-d6, White can now no longer manage to reach the desired setup with Qd2, f3, Bc4, and O-O-O.   It is important to start with  6...Nf6  , as after  6...d6  7.Qd2  Nf6  8.f3  , we get to the main line of the Dragon, which is not attractive from Black's perspective. We will study it later in this course. }
7. Bc4
{ Again, the only way to really challenge Black. White is still trying to build up the ideal setup connected to castling queenside. }
7... O-O 8. Bb3
{ The only way to keep the dream of castling queenside alive. We have now reached the tabiya of the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  g6  variation, and we will go through Black's options one by one. }
8... e6
{ Recently, some strong players took up this move, Dubov for instance. Placing the bishop on g7 and following it up with ...e6 somehow lacks logic for me and I don't trust this move much. It can, however, definitely be checked. }
9. O-O d5 10. exd5 exd5 11. Re1 { White is a bit better. } *

