4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 Bg7 6. Be3 { The only way to fight for an advantage. } 6...
Nf6
{ Having not yet played ...d7-d6, White can now no longer manage to reach the desired setup with Qd2, f3, Bc4, and O-O-O.   It is important to start with  6...Nf6  , as after  6...d6  7.Qd2  Nf6  8.f3  , we get to the main line of the Dragon, which is not attractive from Black's perspective. We will study it later in this course. }
7. Bc4
{ Again, the only way to really challenge Black. White is still trying to build up the ideal setup connected to castling queenside. }
7... O-O 8. Bb3
{ The only way to keep the dream of castling queenside alive. We have now reached the tabiya of the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  g6  variation, and we will go through Black's options one by one. }
8... d6
{ From all the moves we have seen so far this is obviously the most natural. }
9. f3 Bd7
{ Now, play resembles a Dragon, yet it's not! There are some nuances to consider. In the Classical Dragon, the bishop is on c4 in this position and the queen on d2. That's a significant difference in all the lines. }
10. Qd2 Nxd4 { One of those big differences compared to the Classical Dragon. }
11. Bxd4 b5
{ There were quite some discussions here some 20 years ago, but over time, it's been established that Black has a fine play. }
12. O-O-O a5 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Bxd5 Rc8
{ A lot of pieces have already been exchanged, and Black has play on the queenside. }
16. h4 { The attempt to give mate doesn't really work. } 16... h5 17. g4 Rh8
{ White simply doesn't have the resources for an all-out attack. It should also be mentioned that sometimes ...e7-e6 followed by ...a5-a4 can be a threat, trapping the bishop. }
*

