Nf6
{ Having not yet played ...d7-d6, White can now no longer manage to reach the desired setup with Qd2, f3, Bc4, and O-O-O.   It is important to start with  6...Nf6  , as after  6...d6  7.Qd2  Nf6  8.f3  , we get to the main line of the Dragon, which is not attractive from Black's perspective. We will study it later in this course. }
7. Bc4
{ Again, the only way to really challenge Black. White is still trying to build up the ideal setup connected to castling queenside. }
7... Qa5
{ This is a perfectly reasonable move as well, trying to force White to castle kingside. Of course, the queen won't prove very useful on a5 in that case, but at least White won't be able to start much of an attack with the king on g1 instead of c1. }
8. f3 { This is not possible. } 8... Qb4 9. Bb3
{ 9.Nxc6  bxc6  10.Bb3  d6  also doesn't offer White anything. } 9... Nxe4
{ The knight is hanging on d4 and in case of  10.Nxc6  Bxc3+  11.bxc3  Qxc3  12.Ke2  dxc6  , when the knight on e4 is taboo, as  13.fxe4?  would run into  13...Bg4+  . }
