{ Concluding, I think it's safe to say that @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  is sharp and very principled. It limits White's options of fighting for an advantage and the only real way of doing so is with @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1pppbp/2n2np1/8/3NP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bc4  and @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1pppbp/2n2np1/8/2BNP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QK2R w KQ - 5 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bb3  . Both @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1pppbp/2n2np1/8/2BNP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 4 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qa5  and @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1pppbp/2n2np1/8/3NP3/1BN1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QK2R b KQ - 6 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Re8  are serious sidelines that offer good chances for equality. These are also relatively fresh positions that offer room for exploration. In the main line after  8...d6  9.f3  Bd7  10.h4  , both  10...Nxd4  and  10...h5  seem to hold.  Whether you intend to play this position with Black or White, it needs heavy analysis, as one mistake could lead to an instant loss. The lines are extremely direct and sharp.  We also conclude the move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  , having analyzed all of Black's options. As we have seen, it is a very serious way of avoiding the Sveshnikov Variation.  3...Nf6  is dubious and doesn't fully equalize in my opinion. The real choice is between  3...e5  and  3...g6  , both giving excellent chances to equalize, yet in a completely different manner. After  3...e5  , Black tries to neutralize White's first move in a very slow fashion, taking play out of the position move by move, while after  3...g6  , play is risky and complicated. It requires much more theoretical knowledge. And that is the current state of affairs in 3.Nc3 against the 2...Nc6 Sicilian! }
