[White "Lesson 33: 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5"]
[Black "3...e6 with 5.d3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ And we get to what could be called nowadays, at least at the highest levels, the main line. It is definitely the most dangerous attempt for White when he tries to play without the d4 advance.One of the main reasons it is played is to avoid Sveshnikov, but we will see this in more detail in the dedicated lesson. With 3. Bb5 White fights, definitely, for an advantage in the opening but the variations are not forced, and it's actually quite difficult for Black to equalize. }
3... e6 4. Bxc6
{ An interesting alternative to the main line. The point is that Black will need time to complete the development. In addition, the c8 bishop is in danger of becoming bad. This is a strategically complex position, and this is precisely why it is more important to understand it than to memorize concrete, long lines. }
4... bxc6 5. d3
{ White is in no hurry to castle because he often, as we shall see later, pushes the h-pawn. }
5... Ne7 { With the idea of ...Ng6, followed by ...Be7 and ...f6. } 6. Qe2
{ Waiting for the knight to get to g6.   6.h4  Immediately stopping ...Ng6.  6...d6  6... h5 weakens the g5-square.  7.h5  Now 7. e5 it's not so clear.  7...e5  8.c3  As usual, when Black sets up a structure with c5-e5, White immediately plays c3-d4. }
6... d6
{ 6...d5  7.b3  isn't good for Black. If @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/p2pnppp/2p1p3/2p5/4P3/3P1N2/PPP1QPPP/RNB1K2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Ng6  then we already know ho to continue:  7.h4  h5  8.e5 }
7. e5
{ White has a slight advantage, but there is a chance that Black's bishop pair will compensate for the weakness of the doubled c-pawns. }
*

