[Black "3...e6 with 5.d3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ And we get to what could be called nowadays, at least at the highest levels, the main line. It is definitely the most dangerous attempt for White when he tries to play without the d4 advance.One of the main reasons it is played is to avoid Sveshnikov, but we will see this in more detail in the dedicated lesson. With 3. Bb5 White fights, definitely, for an advantage in the opening but the variations are not forced, and it's actually quite difficult for Black to equalize. }
3... e6 4. Bxc6
{ An interesting alternative to the main line. The point is that Black will need time to complete the development. In addition, the c8 bishop is in danger of becoming bad. This is a strategically complex position, and this is precisely why it is more important to understand it than to memorize concrete, long lines. }
4... bxc6 5. d3
{ White is in no hurry to castle because he often, as we shall see later, pushes the h-pawn. }
5... Qc7
{ A semi-waiting move, keeping playing with the ...e5 idea.  5...d5 isn't good, because the c5-pawn can become weak. Also, Black's light-squared bishop is out of the game.   If @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/p2p1ppp/2p1p3/2p5/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  then  6.e5  and again, Black has some issues with his pawn structure. The same issues arise after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/p2p1ppp/2p1p3/2p5/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d6  , when White can play  6.e5 }
6. O-O
{ If  6.Qe2  then Black can play  6...e5  and complete his development. } 6...
Ne7
{ Now Black can take advantage of the fact that White has castled to play ...Nge7, since h4 is no longer so dangerous. }
7. h4
{ Played by, among others, Fabiano Caruana against Magnus Carlsen.  7.Re1  is one of the many alternatives, but after  7...e5  8.c3  d6  9.d4  Ng6  Black is quite ok. }
7... e5 8. h5 { The latest trend in theory. } 8... d6
{ 8...Ng8  was tried, with the idea to finally get the knight on f6, but White can reply with  9.Nh2  followed by f4, with a development advantage. }
9. Nh2 h6 10. f4 exf4 11. Bxf4 g5
{ An odd-looking move, but Black has to find a way to bring the pieces into play. }
12. Bd2 Bg7 13. Bc3
{ With a difficult position to assess.The game Anand-Gelfand, Chess24 2020, continued with  13...O-O  14.Bxg7  Kxg7  15.Qd2  Be6  16.Qc3+  f6  17.Nd2  Rf7  18.Rf2  Raf8  19.Raf1  Qb6  20.Nc4  and White has the advantage. }
