1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ And we get to what could be called nowadays, at least at the highest levels, the main line. It is definitely the most dangerous attempt for White when he tries to play without the d4 advance.One of the main reasons it is played is to avoid Sveshnikov, but we will see this in more detail in the dedicated lesson. With 3. Bb5 White fights, definitely, for an advantage in the opening but the variations are not forced, and it's actually quite difficult for Black to equalize. }
3... e6 4. O-O
{ The main and most direct line. White just wants to continue with Re1, c3 and d4. And Black, so far, has not found a way to equalize. }
4... Nge7 5. c3 { The old main line. } 5... a6
{ The logical follow-up to ...Nge7. } 6. Ba4 b5 7. Bc2 Bb7 8. Re1
{ It is not easy for White to play d4, e.g.  8.d4  cxd4  9.cxd4  Nb4  and Black wins a very important bishop.   White can also try  8.Qe2  , but after  8...d5  9.e5  d4  10.Be4  Nd5  although it is not so clear, Black's position is not inferior. }
8... Rc8 { Again, Black's is playing to stop d4. } 9. a4
{ If  9.d4  cxd4  10.cxd4  Black plays  10...Nb4  , and after  11.Bb3  Black has a tactical resource that allows him to equalize,  11...Rxc1  12.Qxc1  Nd3  13.Qe3  Nxe1  14.Qxe1  Ng6 }
9... Ng6 { Or  9...b4  and Black is doing fine. } *

