{ And we get to what could be called nowadays, at least at the highest levels, the main line. It is definitely the most dangerous attempt for White when he tries to play without the d4 advance.One of the main reasons it is played is to avoid Sveshnikov, but we will see this in more detail in the dedicated lesson. With 3. Bb5 White fights, definitely, for an advantage in the opening but the variations are not forced, and it's actually quite difficult for Black to equalize. }
3... e6 4. O-O
{ The main and most direct line. White just wants to continue with Re1, c3 and d4. And Black, so far, has not found a way to equalize. }
4... Nge7 5. d4
{ One of the latest theoretical trends, and a very serious attempt to fight for an opening advantage. }
5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 a6
{ 6...Qb6  doesn't equalize.  7.Nxc6  bxc6  8.Bd3  8. Be2 is also possible.  8...Ng6  9.c4  Be7  10.Nc3  White definitely has good prospects in this line, although Black should be able to defend. One plan is to play on the queenside, with Rb1, Be3 and b4. The other is to play on the opposite side, with Be3, Qh5, f4. }
7. Be2 Nxd4
{ 7...b5  is premature because of  8.a4  and White takes the initiative on the queenside using the fact that Black has not yet finished the development. }
8. Qxd4 Nc6 9. Qd3
{ 9.Qc3  was also played, with the idea of stopping ...Bc5. } 9... Qc7 10. c4
{ And White has a space advantage. } *

