[Black "3...e6 with 5.Re1 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ And we get to what could be called nowadays, at least at the highest levels, the main line. It is definitely the most dangerous attempt for White when he tries to play without the d4 advance.One of the main reasons it is played is to avoid Sveshnikov, but we will see this in more detail in the dedicated lesson. With 3. Bb5 White fights, definitely, for an advantage in the opening but the variations are not forced, and it's actually quite difficult for Black to equalize. }
3... e6 4. O-O
{ The main and most direct line. White just wants to continue with Re1, c3 and d4. And Black, so far, has not found a way to equalize. }
4... Nge7 5. Re1 a6 6. Bf1 d5
{ Acting in the center before White has time for c3-d4. } 7. exd5 Nxd5
{ If  7...Qxd5  then  8.Na3  is quite unpleasant for Black. } 8. d4 Nf6 9. Be3
{ Carlsen won in this line against Boris Gelfand in the 2013 London Candidates Tournament; and since then, Black still struggles to find a way to fully equalize. }
9... Be7 { 9...Nd5  10.Bg5  f6  is a sad necessity for Black. } 10. c4
{ 10.dxc5  doesn't work, after  10...Qxd1  11.Rxd1  Ng4  Black takes back the pawn. }
10... O-O 11. Nc3 cxd4
{ 11...b6  was tried by Boris Gelfand, and for this reason, it deserves serious attention, since Boris is a specialist of this variation, against Praggnanandhaa in the FIDE Grand Swiss, Riga 2021. }
12. Nxd4 Nxd4
{ In case of  12...Bd7  White can push his pawns with a3-b4 but also  13.Nf3  makes sense, to prevent Black from taking on d4 and then bringing the bishop to c6. }
13. Bxd4 Bd7 14. a3 Bc6 15. b4
{ And as Carlsen's previously mentioned game shows, although Black's position looks good it is very difficult to play. }
