[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 33: 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5"]
[Black "3...g6 4.Bxc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ And we get to what could be called nowadays, at least at the highest levels, the main line. It is definitely the most dangerous attempt for White when he tries to play without the d4 advance.One of the main reasons it is played is to avoid Sveshnikov, but we will see this in more detail in the dedicated lesson. With 3. Bb5 White fights, definitely, for an advantage in the opening but the variations are not forced, and it's actually quite difficult for Black to equalize. }
3... g6
{ It is not too different from line 3...e6. Black, behind in development, must find a way to activate his pieces quickly.   3...d6  4.O-O  Bd7  5.Re1  transposes to the first lesson of this third part.   3...Nf6  is dubious.  4.Bxc6  It is difficult for Black to equalize; to do so, he should play ...e5 and ...Be6, but it is not so simple.  4...bxc6   After  4...dxc6  5.d3  Nd7  trying to get ...e5, then  6.Bf4  and White is better.  5.e5  Nd5  6.O-O  g6  Probably the best option, it transposes to one of the lines we are going to analyze in this lesson. }
4. Bxc6
{ White has just taken the bishop to b5, and suddenly changes it with the c6-knight. But don't let appearances fool you; this line is much more dangerous than it looks.This move began to gain popularity in the early 1990s, and then ...bxc6 was considered dubious. But today it is difficult to say which is the main line; both captures are considered correct by theory. }
4... dxc6 5. d3 Bg7 6. h3
{ Restricting the light-squared bishop, and preparing the maneuver Nh2-f4. Also, White waits to move his king from the center, because if Black plays ...Nf6 now, the main option becomes to castle on the queenside.   Instead, after  6.O-O  Black plays  6...Nf6  ,  intending ...Nd7 and ...e5, for instance  7.Nc3  Nd7 }
6... Nf6 7. Nc3 Nd7 8. Be3 e5 9. Qd2
{ White leaves the king in the center, keeping both options for castling. Also, Bh6 is now a threat; for example after  9...Qe7  10.Bh6  f6  11.Bxg7  Qxg7  12.Qe3  b6  13.Nd2  White's pawn structure is more flexible, which gives him a slight plus. f4 and a4-a5 are two possible continuations. }
9... h6
{ Preventing Bh6. But now Black will encounter some problems in castling. } 10.
O-O Qe7
{ The knight's maneuver ...Nf8-e6-f4 is Black's main strategical idea in this position. }
11. Nh2
{ An important theoretical position, which I tried to make work for Black, but without success. }
11... Nf8 12. f4 exf4 13. Bxf4 Ne6 14. Bg3 Nd4 15. Rae1
{ With two ideas for White. The first is to play e5-Ne4, followed by Nd6 or Nf6. The second is to play Nd1 followed by c3, taking control of the d4 square. }
*

