{ And we get to what could be called nowadays, at least at the highest levels, the main line. It is definitely the most dangerous attempt for White when he tries to play without the d4 advance.One of the main reasons it is played is to avoid Sveshnikov, but we will see this in more detail in the dedicated lesson. With 3. Bb5 White fights, definitely, for an advantage in the opening but the variations are not forced, and it's actually quite difficult for Black to equalize. }
3... g6
{ It is not too different from line 3...e6. Black, behind in development, must find a way to activate his pieces quickly.   3...d6  4.O-O  Bd7  5.Re1  transposes to the first lesson of this third part.   3...Nf6  is dubious.  4.Bxc6  It is difficult for Black to equalize; to do so, he should play ...e5 and ...Be6, but it is not so simple.  4...bxc6   After  4...dxc6  5.d3  Nd7  trying to get ...e5, then  6.Bf4  and White is better.  5.e5  Nd5  6.O-O  g6  Probably the best option, it transposes to one of the lines we are going to analyze in this lesson. }
4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 Nf6 6. Qe2 O-O
{ The engines give  6...Nh5  as the best move. I can see why; Black wants to prevent d4, nevertheless, it is a very strange move.   6...e5  7.d4  cxd4  8.cxd4  exd4  9.e5  Nd5  10.Bc4  Nde7  This line should be checked, but it seems to be good enough. }
7. d4 d5
{ 7...cxd4  is also good, for example  8.cxd4  a6  9.Bxc6  bxc6  10.Nc3  d6  11.Rd1  a5  12.b3  Nd7 }
8. e5 Ne4 9. Be3 cxd4 10. cxd4
{ White's idea is now to attack the e4-knight, for example after  10...Bd7  11.Ne1  followed by f3. }
10... f6 { Immediately attacking White's center. } 11. Nbd2 Bf5
{ And there should be no great problem for Black. } *

