6... O-O { 6...Qb6  has to be checked, it may be enough to equalize. } 7. d4 d5
8. e5 Ne4 9. Be3 { With a difficult position for Black. } 9... Qb6 10. Bxc6
{ 10.Qe2  is also playable, for example  10...cxd4  11.cxd4  Bd7  12.Ba4  and it is possible to create real problems for Black, but you have to analyze the position in depth. }
10... bxc6
{ 10...Qxc6  11.dxc5  Bg4  It is probably better for Black than the computer claims. }
11. Qc1
{ A very computer-based play, but with an obvious strategic goal, namely the g7 bishop. }
11... cxd4
{ If  11...Rb8  then  12.b3  . If @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/p3ppbp/1qp3p1/2ppP3/3Pn3/2P1BN2/PP3PPP/RNQ1R1K1 b - - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11...c4  12.Nbd2  Nxd2  13.Nxd2  Bf5  14.b3  Bd3  15.h4  with a difficult position for Black. }
12. cxd4 a5 { Preventing White from achieving a b3-Nc3 setup. } 13. Nc3
{ If  13.b3  a4 } 13... Nxc3 14. Qxc3 Bf5
{ Or  14...a4  , and it seems that Black is just in time to equalize. } *

