4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 e5 { Carlsen's choice in his match against Fabiano Caruana. }
6. Bxc6
{ 6.c3  doesn't work now that White has already lost a tempo to bring the rook on e1; after  6...Nge7  7.d4  cxd4   Or  7...exd4  8.cxd4  Nxd4  9.Nxd4  cxd4  8.cxd4  exd4  9.Bf4  a position we have already met, but with White to move, which brought the bishop to d6. Now after  9...a6  10.Bc4  d6  Black is slightly better. }
6... dxc6
{ 6...bxc6  7.c3  transposes in a previously analyzed line, with White's advantage. }
7. d3 Qe7 8. Nbd2 Nf6 9. Nc4 Nd7 10. a4 O-O
{ 10...a5  is no good without the queen on c7, since ...b6 should be played anyway and the queen is needed to protect the b-pawn. }
11. a5 Rd8
{ ...Nf8-e6 is the only plan available to Black, it is essential to play it otherwise it will be difficult to find other possible moves. }
12. Be3
{ 12.Bd2  Nf8  is ok for Black.   And  12.h4  is the engine's suggestion, with the idea  12...Nf8  13.h5  with a double-edged position. }
12... Nf8 13. h3 f6
{ Black has to protect the e5-pawn before taking the knight to e6. } 14. Qe2
Ne6 15. c3 Bd7 16. Rad1 Be8 { And Black should be able to equalize. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 33: 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5"]
[Black "3...g6 4.O-O #13"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ And we get to what could be called nowadays, at least at the highest levels, the main line. It is definitely the most dangerous attempt for White when he tries to play without the d4 advance.One of the main reasons it is played is to avoid Sveshnikov, but we will see this in more detail in the dedicated lesson. With 3. Bb5 White fights, definitely, for an advantage in the opening but the variations are not forced, and it's actually quite difficult for Black to equalize. }
3... g6
{ It is not too different from line 3...e6. Black, behind in development, must find a way to activate his pieces quickly.   3...d6  4.O-O  Bd7  5.Re1  transposes to the first lesson of this third part.   3...Nf6  is dubious.  4.Bxc6  It is difficult for Black to equalize; to do so, he should play ...e5 and ...Be6, but it is not so simple.  4...bxc6   After  4...dxc6  5.d3  Nd7  trying to get ...e5, then  6.Bf4  and White is better.  5.e5  Nd5  6.O-O  g6  Probably the best option, it transposes to one of the lines we are going to analyze in this lesson. }
4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 e5 { Carlsen's choice in his match against Fabiano Caruana. }
6. Bxc6
{ 6.c3  doesn't work now that White has already lost a tempo to bring the rook on e1; after  6...Nge7  7.d4  cxd4   Or  7...exd4  8.cxd4  Nxd4  9.Nxd4  cxd4  8.cxd4  exd4  9.Bf4  a position we have already met, but with White to move, which brought the bishop to d6. Now after  9...a6  10.Bc4  d6  Black is slightly better. }
6... dxc6
{ 6...bxc6  7.c3  transposes in a previously analyzed line, with White's advantage. }
7. d3 Qe7 8. a3 Nf6 9. b4 O-O 10. Nbd2
{ Black will continue with  10...Nd7  or  10...Be6  ,  taking out the bishop before playing ...Nd7.   10.bxc5  Qxc5  11.a4  Re8  or ...Rd8 is fine for Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 34: 2.Nf3 e6 Main lines"]
[Black "2...e6 Main lines: 4...d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ In this chapter we will analyze the mainlines of the 2...e6 Sicilian starting with the immediate  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  . This is the most critical approach for White and should be taken very seriously. }
3. d4 { Opening the center immediately. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 d6
{ This move doesn't make much sense - since it's un-forcing in nature, it offers White a pleasant choice between  5.c4  and  5.Nc3  , which transpose to other Sicilians which we aren't interested in at the moment. }
5. c4
{ The most testing way to meet this ...e6 / ...d6 setup - if Black won't fight for central space, White should. Furthermore, we can now develop our knight ideally behind the pawn on c3. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Be7 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Nc6 9. Be3
{ White has a comfortable edge in this Maroczy structure, and Black should avoid playing this way. }
