[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 34: 2.Nf3 e6 Main lines"]
[Black "2...e6 Main lines: 4...Bc5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ In this chapter we will analyze the mainlines of the 2...e6 Sicilian starting with the immediate  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  . This is the most critical approach for White and should be taken very seriously. }
3. d4 { Opening the center immediately. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Be3
{ 5.Nc3  is also playable, but in practice, 5. Be3 has become something of a refutation. }
5... d6
{ This is arguably the best way to continue for Black, but this arrangement of the bishop outside the structure is a liability. }
6. Nc3
{ Continuing normally, with the aim to castle queenside. Note there's no longer reason to push c4 since the bishop has found its way outside the pawn chain, eyeing the dark-squares. }
6... a6 7. Qd2
{ Sooner or later, the dark-squared bishops will be exchanged and the d6-pawn will be very weak. The bishop actually belongs inside the pawn chain. }
