1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ In this chapter we will analyze the mainlines of the 2...e6 Sicilian starting with the immediate  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  . This is the most critical approach for White and should be taken very seriously. }
3. d4 { Opening the center immediately. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Be3
{ 5.Nc3  is also playable, but in practice, 5. Be3 has become something of a refutation. }
5... Qb6
{ This might be a good surprise at the club level if you don't think your opponent will know how to respond and you don't feel like playing the main stuff. }
6. b4
{ 6.Na3  is also a good move, though a little strange. White wants to go Nc4 so Black's best is  6...Qa5+  7.Bd2  Qd8  8.Nb3  when White is simply better, as Black has lost a lot of time. }
6... Qxb4+
{ 6...Bxb4+  7.Nd2  Here Black will experience issues finishing development because of the loose placement of his currently developed ones. White is substantially better. }
7. c3 Qb6 8. Nd2 { White is eyeing Nc4 & Nb5 ideas. } 8... a6
{ Controlling the b5 square. } 9. Qg4
{ A deft follow-up, provoking even more dark-square weaknesses. } 9... g6 10.
Qg3 { White has a huge development lead and lots of dark squares to bite on. }
