[Black "2...e6 Main lines: 4...Qb6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ In this chapter we will analyze the mainlines of the 2...e6 Sicilian starting with the immediate  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  . This is the most critical approach for White and should be taken very seriously. }
3. d4 { Opening the center immediately. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Qb6
{ This is an offbeat but playable try for Black, going for early pressure on the g1-a7 diagonal, leading to some complications favoring White. }
5. Nc3 { Preparing Na4. } 5... Bc5 { Otherwise, there's no point to ...Qb6. }
6. Na4 Qa5+ 7. c3 { With the threat of b4. } 7... Bxd4
{ This must be played.  7...Be7  8.Nb5  and White wants to go b4 & Bf4 with a great game. }
8. Qxd4 Nf6 9. Nc5
{ The knight was vulnerable on a4, and this position has been seen many times through the 90's, and hasn't been seen much since as the following variations favor White. }
9... O-O { Probably the best try for Black. } 10. f3
{ Solidifying the position before proceeding and preparing the cozy f2 square for the queen. }
10... Nc6 11. Qf2 d5
{ White can't be allowed to simply finish development. With the bishop pair and backwards d-pawn, it's an easy advantage. }
12. Bg5 { The tactical 'refutation' of this central break. } 12... Nd7
{ Sidestepping the capture is necessary.  12...dxe4  13.Bxf6  is miserable for Black, when White recaptures on e4 next with a better structure and more active piece play. }
13. Nb3 Qc7 14. exd5
{ Establishing an IQP. Next White can castle either way and have a perfect game. White is definitely better. }
