[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 34: 2.Nf3 e6 Main lines"]
[Black "2...e6 Main lines: 4...Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ In this chapter we will analyze the mainlines of the 2...e6 Sicilian starting with the immediate  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  . This is the most critical approach for White and should be taken very seriously. }
3. d4 { Opening the center immediately. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is another option that will be useful for the White player to know how to meet. }
5. Nc3
{ Threatening e5, embarrassing the knight.  5.e5  is impossible due to  5...Qa5+  dropping the pawn with check. }
5... Bb4
{ This is a tricky old line that was supposed to be not so clear, but these days it's basically engine-refuted.  5...Nc6  is an option, which will transpose to the 2...Nc6 move order, which we've examinedhere. }
6. e5 { The critical response, deflecting the knight so we can play Qg4. } 6...
Ne4
{ This is failing concretely as in this variation as opposed to ...Nd5, the knight hangs on Qg4. }
7. Qg4 { And the tactics are favoring White. } 7... Nxc3
{ The only reasonable move, which will transpose to a position we'll see after 6...Nd5. }
8. Qxg7 Rf8
{ On any knight discovery such as  8...Nd5  we can play  9.c3  with a double attack and it's game over. }
9. a3
{ A very important move, preparing to meet any discovered attack with axb4. }
9... Nb5+ { At least winning a piece back. } 10. axb4 Nxd4 11. Bh6
{ The known refutation. } 11... Qe7 12. Bd3
{ My trainer showed me this when I was 7 years old. It's simply lost for Black, materially and positionally. }
