1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ In this chapter we will analyze the mainlines of the 2...e6 Sicilian starting with the immediate  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  . This is the most critical approach for White and should be taken very seriously. }
3. d4 { Opening the center immediately. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is another option that will be useful for the White player to know how to meet. }
5. Nc3
{ Threatening e5, embarrassing the knight.  5.e5  is impossible due to  5...Qa5+  dropping the pawn with check. }
5... Bb4
{ This is a tricky old line that was supposed to be not so clear, but these days it's basically engine-refuted.  5...Nc6  is an option, which will transpose to the 2...Nc6 move order, which we've examinedhere. }
6. e5 { The critical response, deflecting the knight so we can play Qg4. } 6...
Nd5 { Forced. } 7. Qg4
{ Maybe the strongest move, reverting to the sharp knockout lines.  7.Bd2  is also very good, and if such a simple move works, there should be no point in playing this way for Black.  7...Nxc3  8.bxc3  Be7   8...Bf8  at least stops Qg4 but simple development  9.Bd3  followed by O-O offers White great development advantage in exchange for the bad structure. White is better.  9.Qg4  hitting the g-pawn is very annoying. }
7... O-O
{ The old mainline, preparing an exchange sacrifice which was supposed to offer interesting dynamic chances. }
8. Bh6 g6 9. Nb5
{ Even stronger than taking the exchange. After  9.Bxf8  Qxf8  there is a certain compensation for Black but should still be objectively better for White. }
9... Qa5 10. O-O-O
{ The point becomes clear. If Black wants to damage our queenside, they will need to part with an important dark-square defender. }
10... Nxc3
{ 10...a6  is just too slow after a nice sequence...  11.Rxd5  exd5  12.Qh4  threatening Qf6.  12...Qd8  sad but necessary.  13.Qxb4  axb5  14.Nxd5  and Black won't survive much longer. }
11. Nxc3 Nc6 12. h4
{ Not even grabbing the exchange. This attack is simply devestating. } 12...
Bxc3 13. bxc3
{ Worst case, White can take an exchange, but more likely is checkmate. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 34: 2.Nf3 e6 Main lines"]
[Black "2...e6 Main lines: 4...Nf6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ In this chapter we will analyze the mainlines of the 2...e6 Sicilian starting with the immediate  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  . This is the most critical approach for White and should be taken very seriously. }
3. d4 { Opening the center immediately. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is another option that will be useful for the White player to know how to meet. }
5. Nc3
{ Threatening e5, embarrassing the knight.  5.e5  is impossible due to  5...Qa5+  dropping the pawn with check. }
5... d6
{ The so-called Scheveningen Defense, named after a Dutch region where it was played.   This setup has its venom and is very flexible, however this version without ...Nc6 first is in crisis nowadays.  In most Sicilians, and also in this structure, the most dangerous plans for White are connected with long castling. Short castling is mostly not critical, even if they can offer an objective edge. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack was quite revolutionary at the time, as this bold move neglects development in favor of an immediate attack. I believe this is the most dangerous weapon against this black setup. It's a very unpleasant move to meet as the kingside is the usual home of the Black king. }
6... Nc6 { Let's see what happens if Black simply develops. } 7. g5
{ Starting the attack and kicking away a key defender. } 7... Nd7 8. Be3 Be7 9.
h4 O-O 10. f4
{ This is simply a bad version of the Sicilian for Black. White's attack is much faster, and often goes h4 & g6 to break things open. }
*

