[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 34: 2.Nf3 e6 Main lines"]
[Black "2...e6 Main lines: 4...Nf6 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ In this chapter we will analyze the mainlines of the 2...e6 Sicilian starting with the immediate  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  . This is the most critical approach for White and should be taken very seriously. }
3. d4 { Opening the center immediately. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is another option that will be useful for the White player to know how to meet. }
5. Nc3
{ Threatening e5, embarrassing the knight.  5.e5  is impossible due to  5...Qa5+  dropping the pawn with check. }
5... d6
{ The so-called Scheveningen Defense, named after a Dutch region where it was played.   This setup has its venom and is very flexible, however this version without ...Nc6 first is in crisis nowadays.  In most Sicilians, and also in this structure, the most dangerous plans for White are connected with long castling. Short castling is mostly not critical, even if they can offer an objective edge. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack was quite revolutionary at the time, as this bold move neglects development in favor of an immediate attack. I believe this is the most dangerous weapon against this black setup. It's a very unpleasant move to meet as the kingside is the usual home of the Black king. }
6... e5
{ A very principled and important move to check, fighting against White's g5 idea, however I think it also fails to equalize. We obviously need to treat this setup slightly differently. }
7. Nf5
{ The most principled move for White, after which Black's position is pretty dubious. }
7... h5
{ The same idea, otherwise there's no point losing time to play e5, allowing the knight to f5. }
8. Bg5 hxg4 9. Nd5 { A very direct, aggressive way of playing. } 9... Bxf5 10.
Bxf6
{ An important intermediate move, ultimately leaving us with a great knight on d5. }
10... gxf6 11. exf5 Bh6 12. h4
{ A critical move to know if you want an advantage here. White is denying Black their desired Bg5 move, clamping on the dark-squares.  12.Rg1  is met by  12...Bg5  when the h8-rook will be very active. }
12... gxh3
{ 12...Nd7  13.Rg1  followed by Rxg4 leaves White in a dominant position on the light squares. }
13. Rxh3 { Black owes White a lot of time to escape this pin. } 13... Kf8 14.
Bg2 Nd7 15. Ke2
{ Since the bishop is blocking long castling, Ke2 seems to be a very strong move. The center is blocked so there's nothing to worry about. }
15... Rc8 16. c3 Qa5 17. a4
{ White is down a pawn, but by playing positional chess, White can continue to control the entire board, and the engines give a substantial plus to White, who will continue to slowly improve. }
