{ The so-called Scheveningen Defense, named after a Dutch region where it was played.   This setup has its venom and is very flexible, however this version without ...Nc6 first is in crisis nowadays.  In most Sicilians, and also in this structure, the most dangerous plans for White are connected with long castling. Short castling is mostly not critical, even if they can offer an objective edge. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack was quite revolutionary at the time, as this bold move neglects development in favor of an immediate attack. I believe this is the most dangerous weapon against this black setup. It's a very unpleasant move to meet as the kingside is the usual home of the Black king. }
6... e5
{ A very principled and important move to check, fighting against White's g5 idea, however I think it also fails to equalize. We obviously need to treat this setup slightly differently. }
7. Bb5+ { This is the old line. } 7... Bd7 8. Bxd7+ Qxd7 9. Nf5
{ Jumping into the natural square for the knight, which just looks very good for White, but Black has a tactical point. }
9... h5 { Undermining the knight on f5 - the point. } 10. gxh5
{ 10.g5  is not correct, and should equalize for Black at the end of this sequence.  10...Nxe4  11.Nxg7+  Bxg7  12.Nxe4  . }
10... Nxh5 11. Ng3 { Sidestepping the threat of ...Nxe5. } 11... g6 12. Nxh5
Rxh5 13. Be3
{ While this offers a decent plus for White with the juicy d5-outpost, the structure isn't great and Black has survived the worst of it. This shouldn't be considered a refutation. }
*

