[Black "2...e6 Main lines: 4...Nf6 #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ In this chapter we will analyze the mainlines of the 2...e6 Sicilian starting with the immediate  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  . This is the most critical approach for White and should be taken very seriously. }
3. d4 { Opening the center immediately. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is another option that will be useful for the White player to know how to meet. }
5. Nc3
{ Threatening e5, embarrassing the knight.  5.e5  is impossible due to  5...Qa5+  dropping the pawn with check. }
5... d6
{ The so-called Scheveningen Defense, named after a Dutch region where it was played.   This setup has its venom and is very flexible, however this version without ...Nc6 first is in crisis nowadays.  In most Sicilians, and also in this structure, the most dangerous plans for White are connected with long castling. Short castling is mostly not critical, even if they can offer an objective edge. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack was quite revolutionary at the time, as this bold move neglects development in favor of an immediate attack. I believe this is the most dangerous weapon against this black setup. It's a very unpleasant move to meet as the kingside is the usual home of the Black king. }
6... h6
{ This was always supposed to be the mainline, but White's play is very straightforward here, which is bad news for Black. }
7. h4
{ We continue our initiative, as now there's a kingside hook. This is both a strong, and fun position to play for White. }
7... Nc6
{ The main move, and necessary to neutralize White's active d4 knight. } 8. Rg1
{ We've seen it before - preparing g5! } 8... h5
{ This is the best option for Black, fighting back on the kingside. } 9. gxh5
{ The best move, not to allow the knight into the position.  9.g5  Ng4  10.Rg2  defending against ...Qb6, and preparing f3 is also good for White, but it's definitely playable for Black. }
9... Nxh5 10. Bg5
{ This position was played in Karpov-Kasparov 1985 in the first game of the match. Kasparov managed a draw, but this variation wasn't repeated. It quickly became clear that White is doing very well. }
10... Qb6 { More often Black opts for this move, counterattacking b2. } 11. Be3
Qc7
{ And at least Black has provoked White's bishop away from g5.  11...Qxb2  12.Ndb5  loses material for Black. }
12. Qd2 { Preparing long-castling. } 12... a6 13. O-O-O Bd7 14. f4
{ White has a fantastic version of typical Sicilian positions with the open g-file. Of course, the structure could be a liability in a rook endgame, but this game won't see a rook endgame. There are too many pieces on the board, so it's not such an important factor. }
14... Nf6 15. Nf3 b5
{ Black feels they need to go for counterplay.  15...O-O-O  leads to big issues on the queenside dark-squares after  16.Qf2  . }
16. Bd3
{ A simple move, asserting that White can continue development and Black can't castle. Maybe even  16.e5  is a killer - it should be analyzed. }
16... b4
{ Desparately trying to drum up something - White has too much central control to lash out anywhere else. }
17. Ne2 a5 18. Ned4 a4 19. Kb1
{ It's very easy to get crushed in the center from this kind of position. Black has no queenside attack to speak of and will be waiting for their doom. }
