[White "Lesson 34: 2.Nf3 e6 Main lines"]
[Black "2...e6 Main lines: 6.Be3 Nf6 7.f4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ In this chapter we will analyze the mainlines of the 2...e6 Sicilian starting with the immediate  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  . This is the most critical approach for White and should be taken very seriously. }
3. d4 { Opening the center immediately. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6
{ Is the main move, and my recommendation for Black. I've played this a few times against strong opposition in classical chess. I wasn't so happy with the positions I was getting, but it's playable, especially at club level.  I eventually gave it up, as I was unable to solve all problems necessary to battle it against players using the engine's ideas for the White side, but let's take a look so you can make an informed judgment whether to pursue it yourself. }
5. Nc3 d6 { The natural follow-up to 4...Nc6. } 6. Be3
{ The main move, and the move which always concerned me most when I played the Black side. }
6... Nf6
{ You can start with  6...a6  7.Qd2  Nf6  if you want, but you can't really avoid playing ...Nf6, so you might as well play it immediately. Note that Nge7 ideas aren't as logical without White playing g4. }
7. f4
{ A very serious variation. I won a very beautiful game against Topolov in a blindfold game once.  Enjoy the final position for an aesthetic appreciation of chess.  7...a6  8.Qf3  Qc7  9.O-O-O  Bd7  10.Nb3  Rc8  11.Kb1  b5  12.Bd3  Nb4  13.g4  Bc6  14.g5  Nd7  15.Qf2  g6  16.Rhf1  Bg7  17.f5  Ne5  18.Bb6  Qd7  19.Be2  Qb7  20.Na5  Qb8  21.f6  Bf8  22.a3  Nxc2  23.Kxc2  Bxe4+  24.Kb3  Ba8  25.Ba7  Qc7  26.Qb6  Qxb6  27.Bxb6  h6  28.Nxb5  Kd7  29.Bd4  Bd5+  30.Ka4  axb5+  31.Bxb5+  Bc6  32.Bxe5  Bxb5+  33.Kxb5  Rc5+  34.Kb6  Rxe5  35.Rc1  Rxa5  36.Rc7+  Kd8  37.Rfc1  Rc5  38.R1xc5  dxc5  39.Kc6  1-0 }
7... Be7
{ This is the main move, with a subtle idea of inviting the queen to the  f3  square when the knight will no longer have it as a retreat square.  7...a6  8.Qf3  followed by long-castle is how my game went with Topalov, with a very active position. This shouldn't bother you. }
8. Qf3 e5
{ Is the start of the critical variation which probably holds, but must be analyzed before venturing into. }
9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. f5 { White is trying to go g4-g5 and mate. } 10... Rb8
{ Black has to hurry with queenside counterplay. } 11. O-O-O Qa5
{ With the idea of ...Qb4. } 12. Bc4 O-O 13. Bb3 d5
{ Black is forced to go to some pretty extreme measures to stop White's kingside attack. }
14. exd5 Rxb3 15. cxb3 cxd5 16. Rxd5
{ White has no choice but to give back the exchange. } 16... Nxd5 17. Nxd5
{ The difference being in this line, Black's bishop hangs with check. } 17...
Bh4 { The best move according to the engines. } 18. f6 Qxa2
{ It's hard to say if it's enough for Black to hold, but with the help of strong engines, apparently it does. In any case, there are clearly chances for both sides in this crazy position. }
