{ For White, this is my recommended move-order if you want to play this way, even if you plan to transpose to the mainlines with f3 next. Honestly, it probably doesn't matter. }
7... Be7 { 7...Ng4  is met by  8.Bg5  with a tempo. } 8. Be2
{ This is another dangerous move-order for White.  8.f3  transposes to mymain recommendation for White which we will see. In all these cases, remember White is trying to castle long when Black will always need to worry about kingside attacks. }
8... O-O 9. O-O-O a6
{ Black should go for the typical counterplay with ... Nxd4 and ...b5. } 10. f4
Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Nd7 { An important move to avoid e5 from White. } 12. g4 b5 13.
g5 Rb8
{ Here we are in another double-edged fight with chances for both sides. Hard to say if Black is objectively fine, but we're humans. }
