[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 34: 2.Nf3 e6 Main lines"]
[Black "2...e6 Main lines: 6.Be3 Nf6 7.f3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ In this chapter we will analyze the mainlines of the 2...e6 Sicilian starting with the immediate  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  . This is the most critical approach for White and should be taken very seriously. }
3. d4 { Opening the center immediately. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6
{ Is the main move, and my recommendation for Black. I've played this a few times against strong opposition in classical chess. I wasn't so happy with the positions I was getting, but it's playable, especially at club level.  I eventually gave it up, as I was unable to solve all problems necessary to battle it against players using the engine's ideas for the White side, but let's take a look so you can make an informed judgment whether to pursue it yourself. }
5. Nc3 d6 { The natural follow-up to 4...Nc6. } 6. Be3
{ The main move, and the move which always concerned me most when I played the Black side. }
6... Nf6
{ You can start with  6...a6  7.Qd2  Nf6  if you want, but you can't really avoid playing ...Nf6, so you might as well play it immediately. Note that Nge7 ideas aren't as logical without White playing g4. }
7. f3
{ Here is the main problem this kind of Sicilian faces.  7.Bc4  Be7  8.Qe2  is another dangerous system Black must know if they want to venture into this kind of Sicilian. I won't go into it because I believe White has better, but it's one that deserves some analysis. }
7... Be7 { Finishing development. } 8. Qd2 O-O
{ 8...h5  9.O-O-O  a6  10.Kb1  is an engine-approved line, implying the king can stay in the center for a long time, but practically I don't recommend playing this way. }
9. g4
{ This is an option for White if they don't want to meet Black's ...d5 plan. }
9... d5
{ In this variation with 10. g4 instead of 9. O-O-O Black can more comfortably get away with breaking things open in the center. }
10. g5 Nh5
{ This is not an awful square for the knight, as we can always play ...g6 providing the g7 square as a pivot-point. }
11. O-O-O
{ This is another standard move after which Black can force some simplifications. }
11... Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Bxg5 13. Kb1
{ Known to be the best move, stepping out of the pin.  13.exd5  exd5  14.Nxd5  Be6  should be fine for Black. }
13... g6
{ White can always win back the pawn in the center, but it's not clear if it's enough for an advantage. }
