{ In this chapter we will analyze the mainlines of the 2...e6 Sicilian starting with the immediate  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  . This is the most critical approach for White and should be taken very seriously. }
3. d4 { Opening the center immediately. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6
{ Is the main move, and my recommendation for Black. I've played this a few times against strong opposition in classical chess. I wasn't so happy with the positions I was getting, but it's playable, especially at club level.  I eventually gave it up, as I was unable to solve all problems necessary to battle it against players using the engine's ideas for the White side, but let's take a look so you can make an informed judgment whether to pursue it yourself. }
5. Nc3 d6 { The natural follow-up to 4...Nc6. } 6. Be3
{ The main move, and the move which always concerned me most when I played the Black side. }
6... Nf6
{ You can start with  6...a6  7.Qd2  Nf6  if you want, but you can't really avoid playing ...Nf6, so you might as well play it immediately. Note that Nge7 ideas aren't as logical without White playing g4. }
7. f3
{ Here is the main problem this kind of Sicilian faces.  7.Bc4  Be7  8.Qe2  is another dangerous system Black must know if they want to venture into this kind of Sicilian. I won't go into it because I believe White has better, but it's one that deserves some analysis. }
7... Be7 { Finishing development. } 8. Qd2 O-O
{ 8...h5  9.O-O-O  a6  10.Kb1  is an engine-approved line, implying the king can stay in the center for a long time, but practically I don't recommend playing this way. }
9. O-O-O
{ This is the move you'll see more often than not, after which we will see how Black can conjure some queenside counterplay with ...a6 / ...b5. }
9... a6
{ This move is in the spirit of the Sicilian aiming for an aggressive game with counter chances on the queenside.   There were some theoretical discussions of these positions in the early 2000s when Black was getting good counterplay. But with these mighty engines, there seem to be very powerful responses to playing this way as Black which have put this system for Black a bit out of fashion. }
10. g4
{ After seeing the engine's ideas in this setup, it's hard to trust Black's chances but that doesn't mean it's not playable at most levels. We will look at the critical ideas which will give you a taste of how to handle the positions. }
10... Nxd4
{ We still go for our main idea because Black has no choice but to quickly create some play on their strong side. }
11. Bxd4 b5 12. g5
{ Seems to be the main problem for Black in this variation. } 12... Nd7
{ 12...Nh5  is not too viable as after  13.Be3  Qc7  14.Ne2  Black is compelled to fianchetto the knight. This Ne2 idea is very important to remember from the White side - helping to force through the h4-h5 idea. Black must go  14...g6  and after  15.Ng3  Ng7  White is about to crush Black with h4-h5. }
13. h4 Rb8
{ This is a typical move but it loses an important tempo in this variation. }
14. Kb1 { Always a very useful move to cover the a2 pawn. } 14... b4 15. Na4
Bb7 16. b3 { The standard response to the b4 push. } 16... Bc6 17. Nb2 a5 18.
Rg1
{ Black wants ...a4, but the rook now wants to be on a8 instead of b8, so this isn't working for Black. }
*

