[Black "Summary"]
[Result "*"]

{ Overall it seems like nowadays even the mainline of the Scheveningen systems are in crisis due to the very serious Keres Attack with g4 @@StartBracket@@especially after Black has committed to ...Nf6@@EndBracket@@. Even if Black develops in the precise way with early ...Nc6 and only then ...Nf6, simply Be3 / f3/ Qd2 / O-O-O is enough to ask Black serious questions.   Usually White's attack with g4 / g5 and ultimately g6 will come through faster than Black can organize their queenside counterplay. However, even if it's barely playable at the top level, this shouldn't stop you from trying it out from the Black side to see if you like the aggressive, double-edged positions. Chess is complicated, the Sicilian is complicated, and usually the better player wins. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 35: 2.Nf3 e6 - Paulsen"]
[Black "Paulsen 5.Nc3 b5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ This move introduces the Paulsen, a very flexible system in which Black keeps his options open.   Most of the time Black will keep the d7-pawn there for a while, which makes it difficult for White to castle queenside because, against any Nc3-Be3 system, Black will go ...Bb4 and carry out the ...d5 break.   On the other side of the coin, White is usually better developed than Black in these lines, which increases the possibility of the first player gaining an advantage. }
5. Nc3
{ This move is not very popular nowadays, but I think this is the simplest way of playing with White. }
5... b5
{ This push is the dream of all Sicilian players. This move is often very difficult to carry out. If Black manages to develop with moves like ...Nf6, ...Qc7, ...Bb7 and ...Be7, he will be fine. Obviously, White will fight against this plan. }
6. Bd3 Bb7 7. O-O { This position is critical for Black. For instance: } 7...
Qc7 8. Re1
{ The question for BLack here is how to finish the development. White has the typical Nd5 sacrifice hanging in the air. }
8... Bd6 { Preventing f4 by White, as the rook is on e1. } 9. a4
{ A very strong move here. } 9... b4 10. Nd5
{ This blow gives White a powerful attack. One possible line could follow: }
10... exd5 11. exd5+ Ne7 12. Qg4 Bxh2+ 13. Kh1 Be5 14. Nf5
{ White is better, but precision is required in order to not blow the position away. }
*

