[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 35: 2.Nf3 e6 - Paulsen"]
[Black "Paulsen 5.Nc3 d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ This move introduces the Paulsen, a very flexible system in which Black keeps his options open.   Most of the time Black will keep the d7-pawn there for a while, which makes it difficult for White to castle queenside because, against any Nc3-Be3 system, Black will go ...Bb4 and carry out the ...d5 break.   On the other side of the coin, White is usually better developed than Black in these lines, which increases the possibility of the first player gaining an advantage. }
5. Nc3
{ This move is not very popular nowadays, but I think this is the simplest way of playing with White. }
5... d6
{ This move is not so popular using the Paulsen move order, as Black players are looking to play Paulsen-type positions rather than moving to the Scheveningen. However, it is playable for Black. }
6. Bd3
{ after  6.g4  Ne7  followed by Nc6 we transpose to the previous lesson.   6.Be3  b5  is full of tricky transpositions. That's why, if you want to play the Sicilian as Black, you have to study deeply all these move orders that can lead to Najdorf, Paulsen, Taimanov, and so on. }
6... Nf6 7. Qe2
{ With the Black queen on c7, the plan Qe2 and f4 is quite dangerous for Black, but here is not. I will explain later on why. }
7... Nbd7 8. f4 { Threatening e5. } 8... Nc5 { Black is fine here. } *

