{ This move is not very popular nowadays, but I think this is the simplest way of playing with White. }
5... Qc7
{ In this system, White will most probably castle on the queenside, so Black must react to this plan. }
6. Bd3
{ After this move, Black's task of equalizing is by any means easy.   6...b5  7.O-O  will transpose to  5...b5 }
6... Nf6
{ Black was considered to be OK in this line in the past, but now  7.Qe2  seems annoying to me. }
7. Qe2 d6
{ This line was supposed to be at least playable for Black, but modern engines show that Black should be quite worried here. Let's see why. }
8. f4
{ White threatens to play e5 and, after the trade on e5, we want to put the bishop on f4 and Black's position is difficult. }
8... Nbd7 { Stopping e5. } 9. g4
{ In Keres Attack style! The idea is to push g5. White is better. Of course, this is not the only way of playing with White, but definitely is the most direct and attractive one. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 35: 2.Nf3 e6 - Paulsen"]
[Black "Paulsen 5.Bd3 Bc5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ This move introduces the Paulsen, a very flexible system in which Black keeps his options open.   Most of the time Black will keep the d7-pawn there for a while, which makes it difficult for White to castle queenside because, against any Nc3-Be3 system, Black will go ...Bb4 and carry out the ...d5 break.   On the other side of the coin, White is usually better developed than Black in these lines, which increases the possibility of the first player gaining an advantage. }
5. Bd3
{ The idea of this move is to prevent Black from playing b4. The reason is that the a4-break will be more powerful. }
5... Bc5 { A very risky move, but not too bad. } 6. Nb3 Be7
{ This move is sometimes played, but I'm afraid it's pretty dubious. } 7. O-O
d6 8. c4 Nd7 9. Nc3 Ngf6 10. f4 O-O 11. Qe2 Qc7 12. Bd2
{ White will follow with natural moves such as Rae1 and e5. Black will have a very hard time to stop this idea. }
*

