{ Again, Black must be precise if he doesn't want to be crushed on the spot. }
14... e5
{ This position is dangerous. The d5-square is weak, but not so serious yet. If you analyze the position deeply and navigate the complications, you can play this as Black, although I prefer White's space advantage, which gives him slightly better chances. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 35: 2.Nf3 e6 - Paulsen"]
[Black "Paulsen 5.Bd3 Nf6 #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ This move introduces the Paulsen, a very flexible system in which Black keeps his options open.   Most of the time Black will keep the d7-pawn there for a while, which makes it difficult for White to castle queenside because, against any Nc3-Be3 system, Black will go ...Bb4 and carry out the ...d5 break.   On the other side of the coin, White is usually better developed than Black in these lines, which increases the possibility of the first player gaining an advantage. }
5. Bd3
{ The idea of this move is to prevent Black from playing b4. The reason is that the a4-break will be more powerful. }
5... Nf6 { The main move. } 6. O-O Qc7 { Stopping e5. } 7. Qe2 d6 8. f4
{ This is a critical test of this line. Black has to prove that he is fine. }
8... g6
{ This move has been considered OK for Black for a long time, but engines found a very strong way of playing. }
9. Nc3 Bg7 10. e5 dxe5 11. Ndb5 axb5 12. Nxb5 Qe7 13. fxe5
{ Now the best way for Black to continue the game is to give te piece back. }
13... O-O 14. exf6 Bxf6 15. c3 Bd7 16. a4
{ White has a great advantage. The knight is nice on b5. } *

