1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ This move introduces the Paulsen, a very flexible system in which Black keeps his options open.   Most of the time Black will keep the d7-pawn there for a while, which makes it difficult for White to castle queenside because, against any Nc3-Be3 system, Black will go ...Bb4 and carry out the ...d5 break.   On the other side of the coin, White is usually better developed than Black in these lines, which increases the possibility of the first player gaining an advantage. }
5. c4
{ I use to play this move with White, and I have developed the theory of this move by analyzing it deeply.  Black has now a dilemma: should be played ...Qc7 or ...Bb4 after 5...Nf6? }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ My choice against Garry Kasparov in a game played in 2001. This move is playable for Black, but White can keep a slight advantage if he knows what he's doing. }
7. a3 { Slow, but necessary. This move is aimed at stopping ...Bb4 } 7... b6
{ This was the move played in the game Kasparov-Kramnik in 2001. } 8. Be3 Bb7
9. f3 Be7 10. Be2 O-O 11. Rc1 d6 12. O-O
{ 12.g4  is a move that engines like. Black has to be ready for the pawn storm. White's goal is not to mate Black's king straight away, but rather push g5 and prevent Black's ...d5-break. }
12... Nbd7 13. b4 Rfc8
{ 13...Rac8  14.Nb3  Qb8  is what I played against Garry, but I ended up being worse. }
14. Nb3 Qd8 15. Qd2 Rab8 16. Rfd1 Qf8
{ I think this is a good setup for Black. It's difficult for White to progress, although Black is a bit passive, just waiting for the opponent to strike in order to counterpunch as soon as that possibility is available. }
