[White "Lesson 36: Rublevsky System (2...e6, 4...Nc6 5.Nc3 a6)"]
[Black "Rublevsky System - 5.Nb5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nb5
{ White wants to play a hedgehog structure with the pawns on c4 and e4 against d6 and e6. White will lose some time moving his knight around but if they like this structure, it's more than a valid option. Karpov was one of the main proponents of 5.Nb5. }
5... Nf6
{ 5...d6  is the main move but Black can play  5...Nf6  if they are willing to transpose to the Sveshnikov. }
6. Bf4 { 6.N1c3  Bb4  transposes to Lesson 30: 2.Nf3 e6 3rd Move Sidelines. }
6... e5 7. Bg5 a6 { Black is not in time to play in Sveshnikov style. } 8. Bxf6
{ Black has to recapture with his g-pawn. } 8... gxf6 9. N5c3
{ Black's pawn structure is damaged and he doesn't have the typical activity, that he would normally have in the Sveshnikov, to compensate for it. }
*

