[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 36: Rublevsky System (2...e6, 4...Nc6 5.Nc3 a6)"]
[Black "Rublevsky System - 5.Nb5 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nb5
{ White wants to play a hedgehog structure with the pawns on c4 and e4 against d6 and e6. White will lose some time moving his knight around but if they like this structure, it's more than a valid option. Karpov was one of the main proponents of 5.Nb5. }
5... d6 6. c4 Nf6 7. N1c3 a6 8. Nd4
{ This is a rare move. White did manage to provoke Black into playing ...d6, which leaves the dark-squared bishop behind its pawn chain. The problem is that White invested time in achieving this and now, White's queen doesn't control the d5-square anymore. }
8... Be7 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O d5
{ Black can play ...d5 at the first given opportunity. } 11. exd5 exd5 12. cxd5
Nxd5 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Nxd5 cxd5 { Or  14...Qxd5  . } 15. Be3 Bf5
{ Black has no problems whatsoever: his IQP is compensated by his piece activity and the b2-pawn is weak as well. }
