[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 36: Rublevsky System (2...e6, 4...Nc6 5.Nc3 a6)"]
[Black "Rublevsky System - 5.Nb5 #15"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nb5
{ White wants to play a hedgehog structure with the pawns on c4 and e4 against d6 and e6. White will lose some time moving his knight around but if they like this structure, it's more than a valid option. Karpov was one of the main proponents of 5.Nb5. }
5... d6 6. c4 Nf6 7. N1c3 a6 8. Na3
{ White's queen still controls the d-file. } 8... d5
{ This was Kasparov's preparation for the World Championship match against Karpov in 1985. }
9. cxd5 exd5 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Bc4
{ This was Karpov's reaction when he first faced 8...d5 in the 12th round of the World Championship. }
11... Bg4 12. f3 Bf5 13. g4
{ This is White's only chance to fight for the advantage. Black's light-squared bishop currently controls the h3-c8 and b1-h7 diagonals, so the bishop can always drop back to d7 if needed @@StartBracket@@in case of Qa4+@@EndBracket@@. The bishop must leave one of those diagonals unattended now. }
13... Bg6 { 13...Nxg4  14.Qe2+  Kd7  15.Bf4  Bc5  is extremely unclear. } 14.
g5 Nd7 15. Qe2+ Qe7 16. Ne4
{ 8...d5 is a direct attempt at equalizing and it isn't refuted yet. } *

