1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nb5
{ White wants to play a hedgehog structure with the pawns on c4 and e4 against d6 and e6. White will lose some time moving his knight around but if they like this structure, it's more than a valid option. Karpov was one of the main proponents of 5.Nb5. }
5... d6 6. c4 Nf6 7. N1c3 a6 8. Na3
{ White's queen still controls the d-file. } 8... Be7 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O b6 11.
Be3 Bb7
{ Black has a good version of the typical hedgehog structure because White's knight is on a3 instead of d4. White needs to be extremely careful not to allow very direct counterplay, connected to ...b5 and ...d5.  We can conclude that others moves than 5.Nc3 do not pose Black any problems. }
