{ 5...Qc7 is the Taimanov Sicilian, which we will cover in Lesson 37: Taimanov except 6.Be3 and Lesson 38: Taimanov with 6.Be3, but 5...a6 doesn't have its own name.  Personally, I call it the Rublevsky system because GM Sergei Rublevsky is the greatest expert in this system. }
6. f4 Nxd4 { Black can also transpose to the Taimanov with  6...Qc7  . } 7.
Qxd4 b5 { It seems that Black is doing OK here, for example: } 8. Be3 Bb7 9.
O-O-O Rc8 10. Kb1
{ White has a significant lead in development but he has no concrete threats. }
10... Nf6 11. e5 Nd5
{ Black slowly but surely equalizes; 6.f4 is not very dangerous.   11...Ng4  is also perfectly playable. }
