[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 a6
{ 5...Qc7 is the Taimanov Sicilian, which we will cover in Lesson 37: Taimanov except 6.Be3 and Lesson 38: Taimanov with 6.Be3, but 5...a6 doesn't have its own name.  Personally, I call it the Rublevsky system because GM Sergei Rublevsky is the greatest expert in this system. }
6. g3
{ 6.g3 is one of the main lines against the Taimanov but with the queen still on d8, it lacks punch. }
6... d6 7. Bg2 Bd7 8. O-O Nf6
{ Black is in time to develop his pieces because he delayed ...Qc7. } 9. Re1
{ 9.a4  Be7  10.Nxc6  Bxc6   10...bxc6  11.a5  is pleasant for White.  11.a5  O-O  12.Be3  Nd7  13.Re1  leads to the same position. }
9... Be7 10. Nxc6 Bxc6 11. a4 O-O 12. a5 Nd7 13. Be3
{ White plans Na4, eyeing the b6-square, and b4+c4, gaining space on the queenside. }
13... Qc7 14. Na4 Rae8
{ Black found the correct plan: ...f5 with counterplay. } 15. Nb6 f5 16. exf5
Bxg2
{ Many games were played in this position and most of them ended in a draw. } *

