[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 a6
{ 5...Qc7 is the Taimanov Sicilian, which we will cover in Lesson 37: Taimanov except 6.Be3 and Lesson 38: Taimanov with 6.Be3, but 5...a6 doesn't have its own name.  Personally, I call it the Rublevsky system because GM Sergei Rublevsky is the greatest expert in this system. }
6. Be2
{ Another option for White is 6.Be2. Black must be careful to avoid a transposition to the main line theory of the Scheveningen system, which is highly theoretical. }
6... d6 7. Be3 Nf6 8. O-O Be7 9. f4 O-O 10. a4 Bd7
{ 10...Qc7  11.Kh1  transposes to the Scheveningen system and thousands of games were played from that position.   10...Bd7!  is an incredibly solid move that avoids this transposition and significantly reduces Black's workload. }
