{ Black manages to play ...d5 in one go, but White can sacrifice the e4-pawn and get enough compensation. }
9. O-O-O Qa5 { This direct attempt failed to equalize so far. } 10. Nb3 Bxc3
11. Nxa5 Bxd2+ 12. Bxd2 dxe4 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Re1
{ 14.Be2 was played in So-Ivanchuck, in Havana 2014, and the game ended in a draw. 14.Re1 is more ambitious. }
14... exf3 15. gxf3
{ This position is not so easy for Black because of his weak dark squares and White's bishop pair. }
