1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 a6
{ 5...Qc7 is the Taimanov Sicilian, which we will cover in Lesson 37: Taimanov except 6.Be3 and Lesson 38: Taimanov with 6.Be3, but 5...a6 doesn't have its own name.  Personally, I call it the Rublevsky system because GM Sergei Rublevsky is the greatest expert in this system. }
6. Be3 Nf6 { 6...Qc7  7.Qd2  transposes to the Taimanov. } 7. Qd2
{ The critical move. } 7... e5
{ If Black wants to avoid transposing to a Taimanov system, the tactical solution 7...e5 could serve him well. }
8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. f4 Ng4 10. fxe5
{ Theory is not far advanced here. White can also play  10.O-O-O  or  10.Bg1  .  So far, this position has been reached in only 1 game, Dominguez - Leitao, which ended in a draw.   From White's side, 6.Be3 is an interesting attempt at reducing your workload against the Rublevsky system, if you already play 6.Be3 against the Taimanov.  It remains to be seen whether or not Black can equalize by avoiding a direct transposition to the Taimanov. }
