[White "Lesson 36: Rublevsky System (2...e6, 4...Nc6 5.Nc3 a6)"]
[Black "Rublevsky System - 5.Nc3 a6 6.Nxc6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 a6
{ 5...Qc7 is the Taimanov Sicilian, which we will cover in Lesson 37: Taimanov except 6.Be3 and Lesson 38: Taimanov with 6.Be3, but 5...a6 doesn't have its own name.  Personally, I call it the Rublevsky system because GM Sergei Rublevsky is the greatest expert in this system. }
6. Nxc6
{ 6.a3  is not so innocent.  Black normally plays ...b5 at some point and then it's useful for White to control the b4-square, preventing ...b4 and ...Bb4.  Black's best move is  6...Qc7  , which we will consider in the Taimanov lesson. }
6... bxc6 7. Bd3
{ This is the most popular move by far. White develops his pieces harmoniously and has a slight lead in development.  White has many different tries but no clear way to get an advantage. He always has the initiative and a pleasant position, but Black remains solid.  If you are interested in playing this Sicilian with Black, please study the games of Rublevsky to understand the arising structures and middlegames. }
7... Qc7
{ Black can also start with  7...Qc7  . His idea is that after  8.O-O  Nf6  9.Re1  Bd6  White no longer has f2-f4. }
8. Qe2 Bd6 { Black can try stopping White from castling.   8...Nf6  9.e5+= } 9.
Qg4
{ This is highly unpleasant for Black. I played this against Jan Timman in Wijk aan Zee 2003 and won convincingly:   9.Qg4  Ne7  10.Qxg7  Rg8  11.Qxh7  Be5  12.Qh5  Rxg2  13.Ne2  d5  14.f4  Bd6  15.Bd2  Rb8  16.O-O-O  c5  17.e5  Qb6  18.Bc3  d4  19.exd6  dxc3  20.Qh8+  Rg8  21.Qxc3  Nd5  22.Qe5  Kd7  23.f5  Bb7  24.fxe6+  fxe6  25.Rhf1  Qxd6  26.Rf7+  Kc6  27.Qxd6+  Kxd6  28.Bh7  Rg2  29.Nf4  Rxh2  30.c4  1-0 }
