12... Qa5 13. Bg5 { The alternative,  13.Re2  , didn't impress me. } 13... Bxg5
14. Qxg5 h6 { 14...Qxa4??  15.Qd8# } 15. Qg4 c5 16. b3 Bb7 17. c4 d4
{ Black managed to activate his light-squared bishop with ...c5 and ...d4 now, but White managed to create some initiative on the kingside. }
18. h4 g6 { If Black allows h4-h5, the h8-rook can't be activated. } 19. Nb2
Rg8
{ There are still dangers to Black's position: White plans to play Be4 and Nd3 with good control over the central squares. Meanwhile, Black will have his counterplay on the queenside with ...a5-a4 and get his king to g7.   Is this position playable for Black? Frankly, only Rublevsky can answer that question. }
