[White "Lesson 37: Taimanov except 6.Be3"]
[Black "6.a3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qc7
{ The Taimanov Variation, named after the strong Grandmaster Taimanov, who even played and lost a Candidate match against Fischer but was at the same time a professional and reputed pianist. This system has much more theory than the Paulsen or the Rublevsky. Black players should work hard if they want to use it.Though a serious and solid system, I find it not very rational and somewhat confusing. Compared to other Sicilian systems, such as Najdorf, here White has a wide range of dangerous setups at his disposal, suitable for different playing styles, where Black has to fight hard for equality.The first thing to note is that  6.Ndb5  Qb8  leads nowhere. White has no follow-up and Black will play ...a6 next, forcing the knight back. }
6. a3 { If White wants to play this, he should probably start with  6.Be3  . }
6... Nf6 7. Be3
{ I decided to use this move order to show you this system, but @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/ppqp1ppp/2n1p3/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  is more accurate, as White is better after  6...Nf6  7.f4 }
7... a6 { 7...Be7  8.f4  is similar to other lines. } 8. f4 d5
{ This is not enough to equalize. Better is  8...d6  9.Qf3  but still very playable for White. }
9. e5 Ne4 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Qe2 { The e4-pawn is weak. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 37: Taimanov except 6.Be3"]
[Black "6.a3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qc7
{ The Taimanov Variation, named after the strong Grandmaster Taimanov, who even played and lost a Candidate match against Fischer but was at the same time a professional and reputed pianist. This system has much more theory than the Paulsen or the Rublevsky. Black players should work hard if they want to use it.Though a serious and solid system, I find it not very rational and somewhat confusing. Compared to other Sicilian systems, such as Najdorf, here White has a wide range of dangerous setups at his disposal, suitable for different playing styles, where Black has to fight hard for equality.The first thing to note is that  6.Ndb5  Qb8  leads nowhere. White has no follow-up and Black will play ...a6 next, forcing the knight back. }
6. a3 { If White wants to play this, he should probably start with  6.Be3  . }
6... a6 7. Be3
{ An interesting and fresh try, though a3-systems can hardly be a refutation for any Sicilian. }
7... b5
{ 7...Nf6  8.f4  Nxd4  9.Qxd4  is not a good version for Black. Usually, he shouldn't rush with ...Nf6 in these systems because White has some e5-ideas. }
8. Nxc6 { Other moves allow Black a harmonious development. } 8... dxc6
{ The most principled. We'll see similar positions with Be2 instead of a3.  Here ...b4 is not a threat, so Black practically has an extra tempo.  8...Qxc6  9.Bd3  @@StartBracket@@  9.Be2  is possible too.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/3p1ppp/p1q1p3/1p6/4P3/P1NBB3/1PP2PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Bb7  10.Qe2  Nf6  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r3kbnr/1b1p1ppp/p1q1p3/1p6/4P3/P1NBB3/1PP2PPP/R2QK2R w KQkq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.O-O  could be an alternative.  10...Nf6  11.Re1  Be7  12.Qf3  Qc7  @@EndBracket@@ }
9. Qg4 { White's best try.  9.Qf3  e5  10.Qg3  is similar. } 9... Nf6 10. Qg3
e5 { The endgame should be slightly better for White. } 11. Be2 h5
{ A very important move that secures good chances to equalize according to theory and engines. }
