{ The Taimanov Variation, named after the strong Grandmaster Taimanov, who even played and lost a Candidate match against Fischer but was at the same time a professional and reputed pianist. This system has much more theory than the Paulsen or the Rublevsky. Black players should work hard if they want to use it.Though a serious and solid system, I find it not very rational and somewhat confusing. Compared to other Sicilian systems, such as Najdorf, here White has a wide range of dangerous setups at his disposal, suitable for different playing styles, where Black has to fight hard for equality.The first thing to note is that  6.Ndb5  Qb8  leads nowhere. White has no follow-up and Black will play ...a6 next, forcing the knight back. }
6. g3
{ In general, White's g3-setups against Sicilians strike me as not very ambitious @@StartBracket@@just a way to sidestep theory and lay a game@@EndBracket@@. This is an exception. Taimanov players need to take it seriously and avoid passivity. }
6... a6 7. Bg2 Nf6
{ By far the most popular. Black has an equalizer that 'kills' the g3-variation. }
8. O-O { Now Black doesn't have time for  8...b5?  9.e5+- } 8... Nxd4 9. Qxd4
Bc5 { Black's most direct system. } 10. Bf4
{ The main move.  After  10.Qd3  both  10...d6  and  10...Ng4  are perfectly playable. }
10... d6
{ After  10...Bxd4  11.Bxc7  the endgame is bad for Black, who can barely finish development. }
11. Qd2 { Not  11.Qd3  Ng4!  and ...Ne5 with tempo. } 11... h6
{ Black wants to play ...e5 and ...Be6. The direct  11...e5  weakens the d5-square after  12.Bg5 }
12. Rad1 e5 13. Be3 { A tabiya for this system. } 13... Bb4
{ I analyzed this move while preparing this course and I can recommend it. It is sort of a new idea I'm bringing to you, still untested. I think the alternatives fall short but this could be enough to equalize, which is bad news for White players in the g3-system. White's choice is limited. }
14. Nb5 axb5 15. Qxb4 Rxa2
{ The position is very concrete. White's path is quite narrow. } 16. Qxb5+
{ Or  16.Rxd6  O-O  17.Rd2  Be6  and engines claim White is slightly better, but the b5-pawn will survive, Black's rook is active and the g2-bishop is terrible. Black should hold, in my opinion. }
16... Bd7 17. Qb4 Ra6
{ Black will castle and the d6-pawn is protected. Unless White gets something quickly, and I can't see how with that bishop on g2, this is equal. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 37: Taimanov except 6.Be3"]
[Black "6.g3 #18"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qc7
{ The Taimanov Variation, named after the strong Grandmaster Taimanov, who even played and lost a Candidate match against Fischer but was at the same time a professional and reputed pianist. This system has much more theory than the Paulsen or the Rublevsky. Black players should work hard if they want to use it.Though a serious and solid system, I find it not very rational and somewhat confusing. Compared to other Sicilian systems, such as Najdorf, here White has a wide range of dangerous setups at his disposal, suitable for different playing styles, where Black has to fight hard for equality.The first thing to note is that  6.Ndb5  Qb8  leads nowhere. White has no follow-up and Black will play ...a6 next, forcing the knight back. }
6. g3
{ In general, White's g3-setups against Sicilians strike me as not very ambitious @@StartBracket@@just a way to sidestep theory and lay a game@@EndBracket@@. This is an exception. Taimanov players need to take it seriously and avoid passivity. }
6... a6 7. Bg2 Nf6
{ By far the most popular. Black has an equalizer that 'kills' the g3-variation. }
8. O-O { Now Black doesn't have time for  8...b5?  9.e5+- } 8... Nxd4 9. Qxd4
Bc5 { Black's most direct system. } 10. Bf4
{ The main move.  After  10.Qd3  both  10...d6  and  10...Ng4  are perfectly playable. }
10... d6
{ After  10...Bxd4  11.Bxc7  the endgame is bad for Black, who can barely finish development. }
11. Qd2 { Not  11.Qd3  Ng4!  and ...Ne5 with tempo. } 11... h6
{ Black wants to play ...e5 and ...Be6. The direct  11...e5  weakens the d5-square after  12.Bg5 }
12. Rad1 e5 13. Be3 { A tabiya for this system. } 13... Bb4
{ I analyzed this move while preparing this course and I can recommend it. It is sort of a new idea I'm bringing to you, still untested. I think the alternatives fall short but this could be enough to equalize, which is bad news for White players in the g3-system. White's choice is limited. }
14. a3 Bxc3 15. Qxc3 Qxc3 16. bxc3 Be6
{ Black should let go of the d6-pawn, after  16...Ke7  White will play  17.c4  threatening c5. }
17. Rxd6 Rc8
{ Engines like White a bit but, according to my deep analysis, Black will draw this as long as he knows what he is doing.   Both this ...Bb4 and Fabiano's ...Bxe3 could very well equalize in the most straightforward way, but I understand that some players won't feel comfortable giving up a pawn to play for a draw without better prospects.   For White players, both 6.g3 and 6.Be2 are the best options to fight for an advantage. Both are positionally sound. 6.g3 has a lot less theory and can be added as a weapon against Taimanov. Objectively, 6.Be2 is stronger. }
*

