1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qc7
{ The Taimanov Variation, named after the strong Grandmaster Taimanov, who even played and lost a Candidate match against Fischer but was at the same time a professional and reputed pianist. This system has much more theory than the Paulsen or the Rublevsky. Black players should work hard if they want to use it.Though a serious and solid system, I find it not very rational and somewhat confusing. Compared to other Sicilian systems, such as Najdorf, here White has a wide range of dangerous setups at his disposal, suitable for different playing styles, where Black has to fight hard for equality.The first thing to note is that  6.Ndb5  Qb8  leads nowhere. White has no follow-up and Black will play ...a6 next, forcing the knight back. }
6. Be2
{ The second main move after  6.Be3  and formerly the main system. Together with  6.g3  it is White's positional approach, as opposed to the sharper  6.Be3  . Black needs to study it well but should equalize. }
6... a6 7. O-O Nf6 8. Be3 { The most principle move. } 8... Bb4
{ This move allows Black to stay away from the main lines. Unfortunately, it's too passive. }
9. Nxc6
{ I find this recent discovery quite unpleasant, and it's the reason why I would recommend Black players not to play this line. }
9... bxc6 { The critical move. White has two challenging replies. } 10. Qd4 c5
{ The only move that offers chances to equalize. } 11. Qc4
{ A computer move, but rather dangerous. } 11... O-O
{ The most principle move. } 12. Na4
{ After  12.Bf3  d6  13.e5  d5  Black keeps everything under control. } 12...
a5
{ I couldn't reach any clear conclusion, but I wouldn't play this with Black.   12...d5  looks logical but backfires.  13.exd5  exd5  14.Qf4  Qxf4  15.Bxf4  c4±  and White has a lot of options. }
13. Qb3 d5
{ This is probably the only move, because after  13...c4?!  14.Qxc4  Qxc4  15.Bxc4  Nxe4  Black has kept the material balance, but White has absolute control over the queenside. }
14. exd5 exd5 15. c4 Bg4 16. Bd1 { This is an engine's continuation. } 16...
dxc4 17. Qxc4 Be6 18. Qc2
{ Black should play  18...c4  and hasn't managed to equalize due to his inferior structure. I think the resulting positions after 8...Bb4 are not worth the effort: too much study to play for a draw at most. }
*

