1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qc7
{ The Taimanov Variation, named after the strong Grandmaster Taimanov, who even played and lost a Candidate match against Fischer but was at the same time a professional and reputed pianist. This system has much more theory than the Paulsen or the Rublevsky. Black players should work hard if they want to use it.Though a serious and solid system, I find it not very rational and somewhat confusing. Compared to other Sicilian systems, such as Najdorf, here White has a wide range of dangerous setups at his disposal, suitable for different playing styles, where Black has to fight hard for equality.The first thing to note is that  6.Ndb5  Qb8  leads nowhere. White has no follow-up and Black will play ...a6 next, forcing the knight back. }
6. Be2
{ The second main move after  6.Be3  and formerly the main system. Together with  6.g3  it is White's positional approach, as opposed to the sharper  6.Be3  . Black needs to study it well but should equalize. }
6... a6 7. O-O Nf6 8. Be3 { The most principle move. } 8... Be7
{ Going for the Scheveningen is best and is doing fine, according to modern theory. The alternatives are flawed. }
9. f4 d6
{ I'd advise Black players to play like this, but keep in mind it requires a lot of study. White has two main approaches. He would love to get both a4 and Qg3, but that's simply not possible. Therefore, he has to choose. }
10. a4
{ This stops ...b5 but the downside is that White is not in time to transfer his queen to g3. }
10... O-O 11. Qe1 { This is too slow. } 11... Nxd4 12. Bxd4 e5 13. fxe5
{ Black holds without problems after  13.Be3  exf4  14.Bxf4  Be6= } 13... dxe5
14. Qg3 Bc5 { The key move that justifies Black's play. } 15. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 16.
Kh1 Kh8
{ Next, Black will finish his development and thanks to his superior structure he could get the upper hand if White doesn't react quickly. }
17. Rxf6 { This leads to a forced draw but White risked becoming worse. } 17...
gxf6 18. Qh4 Rg8 19. Qxf6+ Rg7 20. Qd8+ Rg8 21. Qf6+ Rg7
{ With a perpetual. That means White gets nothing out of 11.. Qe1. } *

