{ According to theory, this is doing great, but  11...Bd7  is not easy to refute either. }
12. Bxd4 b5 { Black gets excellent counterplay chances in the long run. } 13.
a3 { Sooner or later, White has to stop ...b4. } 13... Bb7
{ This position was considered very dangerous for Black many years ago. Engines have found new resources and seem to like Black's chances to equalize. White struggles to find a plan. }
14. Rad1
{ 14.Bd3  is the old main line. After  14...Rad8  White can't make e5 work and Black is extremely solid. }
14... Rad8 { The rook's ideal spot. } 15. Bf3 Kh8
{ Engines just sit and wait. } 16. Kh1 Rd7
{ Black can double rooks on the d-file if White opens the game with e4-e5. }
17. Rd3 { This looks like a useful move, but engines are not impressed. } 17...
Rdd8
{ One of the computer's top choices. The truth is that White has to be careful not to overpress. There may be issues with the f4-pawn and none of the central breaks seems to work.   17...h6  is an interesting prophylaxis against f5.  18.f5  e5  and now we see after  19.Be3  that Black has taken the g5-square away from the bishop. It's not easy for White to create threats. }
