1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qc7
{ The Taimanov Variation, named after the strong Grandmaster Taimanov, who even played and lost a Candidate match against Fischer but was at the same time a professional and reputed pianist. This system has much more theory than the Paulsen or the Rublevsky. Black players should work hard if they want to use it.Though a serious and solid system, I find it not very rational and somewhat confusing. Compared to other Sicilian systems, such as Najdorf, here White has a wide range of dangerous setups at his disposal, suitable for different playing styles, where Black has to fight hard for equality.The first thing to note is that  6.Ndb5  Qb8  leads nowhere. White has no follow-up and Black will play ...a6 next, forcing the knight back. }
6. Be2
{ The second main move after  6.Be3  and formerly the main system. Together with  6.g3  it is White's positional approach, as opposed to the sharper  6.Be3  . Black needs to study it well but should equalize. }
6... a6 7. O-O Nf6 8. Be3 { The most principle move. } 8... Be7
{ Going for the Scheveningen is best and is doing fine, according to modern theory. The alternatives are flawed. }
9. f4 d6
{ I'd advise Black players to play like this, but keep in mind it requires a lot of study. White has two main approaches. He would love to get both a4 and Qg3, but that's simply not possible. Therefore, he has to choose. }
10. Qe1
{ The queen heads straight to g3, but then Black can get some queenside counterplay by means of ...b5. This is the most popular choice nowadays, as  10.a4  is in crisis. }
10... O-O 11. Qg3 Nxd4
{ According to theory, this is doing great, but  11...Bd7  is not easy to refute either. }
12. Bxd4 b5 { Black gets excellent counterplay chances in the long run. } 13.
a3 { Sooner or later, White has to stop ...b4. } 13... Bb7
{ This position was considered very dangerous for Black many years ago. Engines have found new resources and seem to like Black's chances to equalize. White struggles to find a plan. }
14. Kh1
{ White players have tried almost every move and this is currently the most popular choice, but Black is in good shape. }
14... Rad8
{ This is usually the best placement for this rook in this system. The key is that Black still has useful moves at his disposal and doesn't need to hurry. }
15. Rad1
{ White can also consolidate but, if he just does nothing, Black's queenside counterplay could start. Some players have tried to push b4 at some point, but that creates some weaknesses too.  Other attempts are  15.Bf3  or  15.Rae1  Rd7 }
15... Rd7 { Or  15...Bc6  16.Rfe1 } 16. Rd3
{ A seemingly sensible idea to bring the rook into a kingside attack, but that regroup is wishful thinking. }
16... Kh8 17. Re3 Ne8
{ Black intends to trade dark-squared bishops. The rook is playing an important role on d7, preventing any e5-push. Engines claim the position is 'dead equal'.  Obviously, White is more comfortable, but a different story is if White can convert this plus into something concrete in a practical game. }
*

