[White "Lesson 38: Taimanov with 6.Be3"]
[Black "6.Be3 Nf6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3
{ This lesson will be entirely devoted to Taimanov with  6.Be3  , the most dangerous line for Black and the most played at the grandmaster level. }
6... Nf6 { It is almost refuted nowadays. } 7. f4
{ After this move, trouble begins for Black. } 7... Bb4
{ After  7...d6  it will be a different Sicilian, a worse version of a Scheveningen, since the queen is already on  c7  . After  8.Qf3  ,  then O-O-O and it's just better for White.   Via a different move order, I reached this position in 2003, in a very nice blindfold game against Veselin Topalov; a memorable game for me, with my king going all the way to b6...  8.Qf3  a6  9.O-O-O  Bd7  10.Nb3  Rc8  11.Kb1  b5  12.Bd3  Nb4  13.g4  Bc6  14.g5  Nd7  15.Qf2  g6  16.Rhf1  Bg7  17.f5  Ne5  18.Bb6  Qd7  19.Be2  Qb7  20.Na5  Qb8  21.f6  Bf8  22.a3  Nxc2  23.Kxc2  Bxe4+  24.Kb3  Ba8  25.Ba7  Qc7  26.Qb6  Qxb6  27.Bxb6  h6  28.Nxb5  Kd7  29.Bd4  Bd5+  30.Ka4  axb5+  31.Bxb5+  Bc6  32.Bxe5  Bxb5+  33.Kxb5  Rc5+  34.Kb6  Rxe5  35.Rc1  Rxa5  36.Rc7+  Kd8  37.Rfc1  Rc5  38.R1xc5  dxc5  39.Kc6  1-0 }
8. Nb5 Qa5
{ If the queen moves to any other square, like for example  8...Qb8  , then after the simple  9.a3  White gets a big advantage. }
9. e5 Ne4
{ 9...Nd5  10.Bd2  Nxc3  and all three moves give White the advantage,  11.Bxc3  ,  11.bxc3  and  11.Nxc3  . }
10. Qd3
{ Also  10.Bd3  Nxc3  11.bxc3  Bxc3+  12.Kf2  is very dangerous for Black. }
10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 Be7 12. Be2
{ Or  12.g3  and it's very difficult for Black to equalize. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 38: Taimanov with 6.Be3"]
[Black "6.Be3 a6 7.Bd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3
{ This lesson will be entirely devoted to Taimanov with  6.Be3  , the most dangerous line for Black and the most played at the grandmaster level. }
6... a6 7. Bd3
{ It is an old line, which does not create any problems for Black. } 7... Nf6
{ 7...b5  8.Nxc6  dxc6  9.Qf3  is better for White. } 8. O-O Nxd4 9. Bxd4 Bc5
10. Be2
{ 10.Bxf6  gxf6  11.Qg4  looks like a fantastic Rauzer, because Black's pawn is not yet on d6 and the dar-squared bishop is much more active on c5.   10.Bxc5  Qxc5  11.Re1  d6  looks perfectly fine for Black. }
10... e5 11. Bxc5 Qxc5 12. Qd3 b5 { Just developing the bishop. } 13. b4
{ A desperate attempt to take advantage in the opening. } 13... Qxb4 14. a4 Bb7
{ But Black is in time and the position, after a series of exchanges, becomes much simpler and is pretty drawish. }
