1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3
{ This lesson will be entirely devoted to Taimanov with  6.Be3  , the most dangerous line for Black and the most played at the grandmaster level. }
6... a6 7. Bd3
{ It is an old line, which does not create any problems for Black. } 7... Nf6
{ 7...b5  8.Nxc6  dxc6  9.Qf3  is better for White. } 8. O-O b5
{ The simplest, easily equalizes.  8...Ne5  too is a playable alternative.  8...Bd6  9.Nxc6  dxc6  10.f4  e5  11.f5  b5  is another unclear line, where I am not sure White can claim an advantage. }
9. Nxc6 Qxc6 10. Qf3 { White can also try to play without a3. } 10... Bb7 11.
Bd4 Be7
{ 11...Qc7  is an interesting try, preventing Qg3 after which Black would welcome an exchange of queens, entering the endgame.  12.Bxf6  gxf6  13.Qxf6  Rg8  and Black has compensation. }
12. Qg3 b4 13. Ne2 O-O 14. c3 g6
{ And Black not only has no problem but can play for the win - a truly unsual outcome in these Taimanov lines. }
