1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3
{ This lesson will be entirely devoted to Taimanov with  6.Be3  , the most dangerous line for Black and the most played at the grandmaster level. }
6... a6 7. Qd2 { The old main line. } 7... Nf6 8. O-O-O
{ The main move. While preparing this lesson, I found a way for Black to equalize. In any case, Black has many moves at his disposal, and before introducing my novelty let us take a look at the current state of theory. }
8... Bb4 { The most popular move. } 9. f3 Ne5
{ The old main line. There are a lot of game with 9...Ne7, but I think a lot of White's moves represent a serious danger for Black, like 10.g4 or 10.Nde2 }
10. g4
{ A very straightforward attempt. It is not often played, but I could not find anything for Black.   10.Nb3  b5  11.Qe1  or  11.Kb1  seems to be playable for Black.   If  10...d5  11.Bd4 }
10... b5 11. g5 Nh5 12. Kb1 { Again, White is threatening Ncxb5. } 12... Bxc3
13. Qxc3 Qxc3 14. bxc3 Bb7
{ Black's problem is development, otherwise his position would be nice. } 15.
Nb3
{ A very strong move, pointed out by the engine. Black can't play  15...Nxf3  , otherwise after  16.Nc5  followed by Be2 he's losing a piece. }
