1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3
{ This lesson will be entirely devoted to Taimanov with  6.Be3  , the most dangerous line for Black and the most played at the grandmaster level. }
6... a6 7. Qd2 { The old main line. } 7... Nf6 8. O-O-O
{ The main move. While preparing this lesson, I found a way for Black to equalize. In any case, Black has many moves at his disposal, and before introducing my novelty let us take a look at the current state of theory. }
8... Be7
{ In my opinion, the best continuation. Practice will prove whether I am right or wrong, but I could not find any advantage for White.   8...Nxd4  9.Qxd4  Ng4  ,  attacking the e3-bishop. Now White has the strong  10.Qb6  Qc6  11.Bd4  e5  12.Be3  and after the bishop is exchanged on e3, White plays Nd5 and it's simply better. }
9. f3 { The main move. } 9... b5
{ In this line, the move order is extremely important. If  9...Nxd4  then  10.Qxd4  is strong, and e5 is a threat.   9...h5  is a typical Najdorf idea. Strategically is sound, but tactically it doesn't work.  10.Nxc6  bxc6  11.Bf4  e5  12.Bg5  d6  13.Bc4  , continuing with Bb3, protecting the king's position, f4 and White is better. }
10. g4 Nxd4
{ It is very important to take White's knight at this exact moment. } 11. Bxd4
{ 11.Qxd4  Bb7  12.g5  Nh5  followed by ...Rc8. The king in the center protects the d7-pawn, and Black organizes his counterplay very quickly. }
11... Bb7 12. Kb1
{ If  12.g5  we play  12...Nh5  and somehow, with the bishop already on b7, this position is perfectly fine for Black. }
12... O-O 13. Qf2
{ White's attack cannot be rushed, because Black has many threats, such as ...b4 or ...d5. }
13... Rac8 14. Bd3 { Protecting the c2-pawn. } 14... Bc5
{ Black has equalized. } *

