[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 39: 2.Nf3 Nc6 Kalashnikov"]
[Black "Kalashnikov: 5...a6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5
{ This move marks the Kalashnikov Variation, or the 'Accelerated Sveshnikov'. It tends to be slightly less accurate than the standard Sveshnikov as a surprise weapon or as a way to avoid some theory. The benefit of playing a slightly less sound variation is that you should be better prepared than your opponent, since fewer people play that way.  By contrast,  4...Nf6  5.Nc3  e5  is the Sveshnikov. Including ...Nf6 before committing to ...e5 does offer some advantages, as we will get into. There are some lines in the Kalashnikov which can transpose to certain lines in the Sveshnikov, but then it would be more logical for Black to start with the classical Sveshnikov move-order.   Anyway, the Kalashnikov is definitely playable, even if White retains a small plus. For this reason, in this chapter we will mostly analyze the positions from White's perspective. }
5. Nb5
{ The best move, immediately pressurizing the newly weakened dark squares before Black has a chance to play ...a6. The response is the same in the Sveshnikov once ...e5 is played. }
5... a6
{ This is a possible move that requires White to know some theory. If White knows the theory, but it does lead to some sad positions for Black. }
6. Nd6+ { Must be played - the point behind Nb5 in the first place. } 6... Bxd6
7. Qxd6
{ The queen now occupies the dark-squares, and White has a positional plus if they continue accurately. }
7... Qf6 { The best move - immediately fighting back for the dark-squares. } 8.
Qd1
{ As far as I'm concerned, this is the mainline, and most direct and is good enough to make Black think twice about playing this way with 5...a6. }
8... Qg6
{ Black has to force some complications in order not to get squeezed to death. }
9. Nc3 d5
{ Black cannot comfortably develop the knight and castle, and must take direct actions.  9...Nf6  is met by the return of the queen with  10.Qd6  when White is just much better.   9...Nge7  can be met by  10.h4  ,  harassing the queen. }
10. Nxd5
{ Starting here, White really must know how to meet ...d5 in order to retain any advantage.  10.exd5  is met by  10...Nd4  when Black has a sudden initiative.   The same is true on  10.Qxd5  Be6  . }
10... Qxe4+ 11. Be3 Nd4 12. Nc7+ Ke7
{ Forced. It cannot go anywhere on the d-file due to the deadly pin. } 13. Be2
{ I was not aware before preparing this course, but engines nowadays prefer this move. This course is comprised both of variations that demonstrate my own knowledge and experience, but I did double-check everything with modern engines to make sure my recommendations are good. Here, if Black does nothing White will either take the hanging rook and castle, so therefore play continues in a messy fashion. }
13... Qxg2
{ 13...Nxc2+  Kf1  The computers are saying this is better for White, but it's not so clear to prove. This needs to be analyzed at home, as both rooks continue to hang and it's not clear how White's h1-rook enters the game. }
14. Rf1 Qc6 { Has some merit, counterattacking on the c2 square. } 15. Bxd4
{ Simplifying into an advantageous position where the power of the 2 bishops should be felt.  15.c3  also leads to a completely insane position which needs to be analyzed further. }
15... Qxc7 16. Bc3 Be6 17. Qd2
{ If White is allowed, they will castle long next, but in any case White is a pawn down but with the bishop pair and more open lines, should retain an advantage. }
