{ This is a possible alternative which should definitely be checked by modern engines, since it's perhaps the most concrete. It could be a good choice if you're quite confident your opponent will not be aware of the engine moves. }
13... Nxc2+ 14. Kd2 Nxe3
{ Black cannot win back the exchange:  14...Nxa1  15.Bc5+  Kf6  16.Bd3  and it's clear which side is having all the fun. }
15. fxe3 Nf6 16. Qb3
{ These moves simply must be memorized, as it's so direct. } 16... Rd8+ 17. Ke1
b5 18. Nc7 { Bringing the knight back into the game. } 18... Ng4
{ Editor's Note: The rest of the variation seems critical enough to include in the rest of the trainable variation. }
19. Rd1 Rxd1+ 20. Kxd1 Nf2+
{ Black is finally able to more or less materially equalize. } 21. Kd2 Nxh1 22.
Nd5+ Kd8 23. Nc3
{ This is just one of the variations shown by the almighty engines, which shows that White does retain a slight plus as his king is slightly more safe and Black owes White some tempi. }
