[Black "Kalashnikov: 5...a6 (Alternative: 8.Qc7)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5
{ This move marks the Kalashnikov Variation, or the 'Accelerated Sveshnikov'. It tends to be slightly less accurate than the standard Sveshnikov as a surprise weapon or as a way to avoid some theory. The benefit of playing a slightly less sound variation is that you should be better prepared than your opponent, since fewer people play that way.  By contrast,  4...Nf6  5.Nc3  e5  is the Sveshnikov. Including ...Nf6 before committing to ...e5 does offer some advantages, as we will get into. There are some lines in the Kalashnikov which can transpose to certain lines in the Sveshnikov, but then it would be more logical for Black to start with the classical Sveshnikov move-order.   Anyway, the Kalashnikov is definitely playable, even if White retains a small plus. For this reason, in this chapter we will mostly analyze the positions from White's perspective. }
5. Nb5
{ The best move, immediately pressurizing the newly weakened dark squares before Black has a chance to play ...a6. The response is the same in the Sveshnikov once ...e5 is played. }
5... a6
{ This is a possible move that requires White to know some theory. If White knows the theory, but it does lead to some sad positions for Black. }
6. Nd6+ { Must be played - the point behind Nb5 in the first place. } 6... Bxd6
7. Qxd6
{ The queen now occupies the dark-squares, and White has a positional plus if they continue accurately. }
7... Qf6 { The best move - immediately fighting back for the dark-squares. } 8.
Qc7
{ Quite an interesting move if you're brave enough to risk the queen's position, but there's no way to trap it by force. Another similar response is  8.Qxf6  Nxf6  9.Nc3  Nb4  10.Kd2   10.Bd3  might give White a microscopic plus, but Kd2 is more principled, not giving up the bishops.  10...d6  11.b3  preparing Ba3  11...Be6  12.Ba3  a5  While White might be able to edge out an advantage, Black has done well to neutralize the bishops and I'm not too impressed by this for White. }
8... Nge7 9. Nc3 { Natural development. } 9... Nb4
{ The queen on c7 does bother Black enough that they must take concrete measures to free their game, leading to some forced lines. }
10. Bd3 d5
{ If they don't go for this, White will always be better, fighting against the backwards pawn. }
11. O-O d4 12. Na4 { With the big threat of Nb6. } 12... Qc6 13. Qxc6+ Nexc6
14. Nb6 Rb8 15. f4
{ This endgame is somewhat better for White. It's not clear if Black can equalize, but it's also not much for White. The b6-knight stands well, but Black will win the bishop pair back by taking on d3 eventually, and White might not have enough to win. }
