1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5
{ This move marks the Kalashnikov Variation, or the 'Accelerated Sveshnikov'. It tends to be slightly less accurate than the standard Sveshnikov as a surprise weapon or as a way to avoid some theory. The benefit of playing a slightly less sound variation is that you should be better prepared than your opponent, since fewer people play that way.  By contrast,  4...Nf6  5.Nc3  e5  is the Sveshnikov. Including ...Nf6 before committing to ...e5 does offer some advantages, as we will get into. There are some lines in the Kalashnikov which can transpose to certain lines in the Sveshnikov, but then it would be more logical for Black to start with the classical Sveshnikov move-order.   Anyway, the Kalashnikov is definitely playable, even if White retains a small plus. For this reason, in this chapter we will mostly analyze the positions from White's perspective. }
5. Nb5
{ The best move, immediately pressurizing the newly weakened dark squares before Black has a chance to play ...a6. The response is the same in the Sveshnikov once ...e5 is played. }
5... d6
{ The main move - physically blocking the d6 square by occupying it.  5...Nf6  makes no sense, as White has the pleasant choice of  6.N1c3  or even the dangerous  6.Bg5  . If they wanted to go ...Nf6 they should do it on move 4 before committing to ...e5. }
6. N1c3
{ Top players during the emergence of this system were horrified how Black could allow such a weak d5 square and get away with it, but Sveshnikov understood chess very well and showed that this was not the only factor in the position. However, this isn't the Sveshnikov proper, and White should have an advantage with precise play. }
6... a6
{ Black can start with  6...Nf6  ,  transposing to the Sveshnikov, but again, it doesn't make sense to allow White an extra option with c4 only to late play ...Nf6 anyway. }
7. Na3 b5
{ Black's original idea behind this line, delaying ...Nf6.  7...Nf6  once again probably transposes to the Sveshnikov and could be played to avoid certain lines, but perhaps this opens up an extra option for White to re-maneuver the a3-knight to a more comfortable square.  8.Nc4  b5  9.Ne3  when White has good chances for an opening plus. }
8. Nd5
{ Stepping out of the b4-fork and into the ideal outpost. In all lines, I haven't been able to find any equality for Black and White should have a comfortable game. }
8... Nf6
{ Probably the best move in the position since it puts pressure in the center. }
9. Bd3
{ This is a recent engine development that demonstrates even if White slightly delays c4, Black's predicament is quite serious. This could be an even simpler option than the immediate  9.c4  . }
9... Nxd5 { This knight can really not be tolerated on d5. } 10. exd5 Nd4
{ The natural square for the knight. } 11. O-O g6 12. c3
{ Even stronger than c4, since it comes with tempo, preparing a quick Nc2-Nb4-Nc6! }
12... Nf5 13. Nc2 { White will be far ahead of Black with their active play. }
