[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 39: 2.Nf3 Nc6 Kalashnikov"]
[Black "Kalashnikov: (Alternative: 6.c4 #3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5
{ This move marks the Kalashnikov Variation, or the 'Accelerated Sveshnikov'. It tends to be slightly less accurate than the standard Sveshnikov as a surprise weapon or as a way to avoid some theory. The benefit of playing a slightly less sound variation is that you should be better prepared than your opponent, since fewer people play that way.  By contrast,  4...Nf6  5.Nc3  e5  is the Sveshnikov. Including ...Nf6 before committing to ...e5 does offer some advantages, as we will get into. There are some lines in the Kalashnikov which can transpose to certain lines in the Sveshnikov, but then it would be more logical for Black to start with the classical Sveshnikov move-order.   Anyway, the Kalashnikov is definitely playable, even if White retains a small plus. For this reason, in this chapter we will mostly analyze the positions from White's perspective. }
5. Nb5
{ The best move, immediately pressurizing the newly weakened dark squares before Black has a chance to play ...a6. The response is the same in the Sveshnikov once ...e5 is played. }
5... d6
{ The main move - physically blocking the d6 square by occupying it.  5...Nf6  makes no sense, as White has the pleasant choice of  6.N1c3  or even the dangerous  6.Bg5  . If they wanted to go ...Nf6 they should do it on move 4 before committing to ...e5. }
6. c4
{ Sveshnikov himself discovered facing this system is not so pleasant after playing against it a lot in the 80s and 90s. While White does have a slight advantage in most lines, it's playable for Black and I myself have played it a few times, against Anand and Leko.    The only problem for White in this position is the result of c4 - the weak d4 square. Often a knight will be required to guard against a Black knight landing on d4, which limits White's play. However, White's pluses tend to outweigh their minuses. }
6... Be7 7. N1c3
{ The most logical move in the position, threatening Nd5, forcing Black's hand. }
7... a6 8. Na3 Be6 { The old-fashioned way of playing is sometimes the best. }
9. Nc2
{ White can play this way with first  9.Be2  Rc8  and only now  10.Nc2  but it makes more sense to remain flexible with the bishop since we know the knight must return to c2 eventually, and guard against ...Nd5. }
9... Rc8 { A useful move, to defend against some future Nc7+ ideas. } 10. Be2
{ The most logical move.  10.Nd5  already would allow  10...Bg5  when Black is very happy to achieve this exchange. }
10... Na5
{ This is a very direct move which aims to challenge the c4 square, but it doesn't seem to work. }
11. b3 { Defending c4. } 11... b5 12. Nd5 bxc4 13. Be3
{ Engine's top choice.  13.b4  also definitely gives White chances for an advantage but who are we to argue with the engine? }
13... Bxd5
{ 13...cxb3  cannot be played because of  14.axb3  Nxb3  15.Rxa6  when White has a big initiative, the d6-pawn is still a target, and Bb5+ coming. }
14. exd5
{ Strange as it seems, things aren't easy for Black since now the c6 square is quite weak. }
14... Nf6
{ Black still can't take on b3 since the a6-pawn hangs and White's activity is too much. }
15. b4 Nb7 16. Na3
{ Now White will win back the pawn on c4, and slowly start to enter on the kingside. }
16... a5 17. Nxc4 axb4 18. Rb1
{ At the end of the day White will win back the pawn with pressure if played accurately. }
