[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 39: 2.Nf3 Nc6 Kalashnikov"]
[Black "Summary"]
[Result "*"]

{ In conclusion, I believe the after the mainline of the Kalashnikov are reached, both the principled 9. c4 and the positional 9. Bd3 are enough for a pleasant advantage. Compare both and decide which suits your repertoire and playstyle the best. Same applies earlier on, whether you prefer 6. N1c3 or 6. c4. Both have their merits and I invite you to compare between them.  Black is always fighting for full equality which is probably not there, but White's advantage is not overwhelming. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 40: 2.Nf3 Nc6 with 5...e6 "]
[Black "5...e6: 6.Be2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is the main continuation and the most popular for Black. } 5. Nc3 e6
{ This system was always considered to be a bit dubious, and was used only as a surprise weapon. Lately though, in two main lines, the engine found some new ideas which increased its popularity and has proven it's not clear White can get an advantage by force. Hungarian GM, Richard Rapport has had good success with this variation.   For Black, you do need to know quite a lot of theory and be well-prepared; it's not an opening you can play only relying on general knowledge. One of Black's main ideas behind ...e6 is to play ...Bb4 to pressure the center. }
6. Be2 Bb4
{ A very direct move. Even if Black's position looks somewhat dangerous in a lot of lines, it should be holdable.  6...d6  or  6...Qc7  are both possible transpositions to other Sicilians, but we won't cover those here. }
7. O-O { White's main idea, sacrificing the e4 pawn. } 7... Bxc3 8. bxc3 Nxe4
{ White should have full compensation for the pawn, but probably no more than that. }
9. Bd3
{ Trying to provoke the knight to either take on c3 or to retreat with a tempo loss, after which White would have excellent chances for an advantage. }
9... d5 { A solid equalizer. } 10. Ba3
{ This is an interesting but harmless try, cutting off Black's king from castling short. }
10... Qa5 { Attacking the bishop and trying to castle. } 11. Nb5 a6 12. Nd6+
Nxd6 13. Bxd6 Qd8 { Once again, trying to castle if White will let us. } 14.
Ba3 Qa5
{ Now White's best is to force the repetition since the extra pawn is starting to count. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 40: 2.Nf3 Nc6 with 5...e6 "]
[Black "5...e6: 6.Be2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is the main continuation and the most popular for Black. } 5. Nc3 e6
{ This system was always considered to be a bit dubious, and was used only as a surprise weapon. Lately though, in two main lines, the engine found some new ideas which increased its popularity and has proven it's not clear White can get an advantage by force. Hungarian GM, Richard Rapport has had good success with this variation.   For Black, you do need to know quite a lot of theory and be well-prepared; it's not an opening you can play only relying on general knowledge. One of Black's main ideas behind ...e6 is to play ...Bb4 to pressure the center. }
6. Be2 Bb4
{ A very direct move. Even if Black's position looks somewhat dangerous in a lot of lines, it should be holdable.  6...d6  or  6...Qc7  are both possible transpositions to other Sicilians, but we won't cover those here. }
7. O-O { White's main idea, sacrificing the e4 pawn. } 7... Bxc3 8. bxc3 Nxe4
{ White should have full compensation for the pawn, but probably no more than that. }
9. Bd3
{ Trying to provoke the knight to either take on c3 or to retreat with a tempo loss, after which White would have excellent chances for an advantage. }
9... d5 { A solid equalizer. } 10. Nxc6
{ This is another option, the idea being to remove the defender of the b4 square. }
10... bxc6 11. Ba3 { Once again, stopping castling for the time being. } 11...
c5
{ The best move, giving back the pawn with a healthy structure, and the ability to castle. }
12. Bxe4 dxe4
{ White will win back the c-pawn but with a fractured structure, White cannot be better. }
