[Black "5...e6: 6.a3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is the main continuation and the most popular for Black. } 5. Nc3 e6
{ This system was always considered to be a bit dubious, and was used only as a surprise weapon. Lately though, in two main lines, the engine found some new ideas which increased its popularity and has proven it's not clear White can get an advantage by force. Hungarian GM, Richard Rapport has had good success with this variation.   For Black, you do need to know quite a lot of theory and be well-prepared; it's not an opening you can play only relying on general knowledge. One of Black's main ideas behind ...e6 is to play ...Bb4 to pressure the center. }
6. a3
{ This is played when White players want to avoid theoretical discussions after Ndb5 or Nxc5. This prevents ...Bb5 and the game will likely continue with ...d6 since the bishop now clearly belongs on e7. }
6... d6
{ A very decent way of playing since in all the transpositions with Scheveningen systems, a3 is not such a useful tempo.  6...Qc7  transposes to the Taimanov.   6...d5  is not bad. Play could continue with  7.Bb5  Bd7  8.exd5  exd5  9.O-O  Be7  10.Be3  Probably White is a bit better but not much because the a3 tempo is not so useful and Black is in time to develop, and the d5 pawn is pretty secure. }
7. Be2 Be7 8. Be3
{ Again, the a3 tempo is not doing much for White and Black has all the normal Scheveningen ideas, but this time with the a3 hook in an opposite-castling pawn race. }
