[Black "5...e6: 6.Qd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is the main continuation and the most popular for Black. } 5. Nc3 e6
{ This system was always considered to be a bit dubious, and was used only as a surprise weapon. Lately though, in two main lines, the engine found some new ideas which increased its popularity and has proven it's not clear White can get an advantage by force. Hungarian GM, Richard Rapport has had good success with this variation.   For Black, you do need to know quite a lot of theory and be well-prepared; it's not an opening you can play only relying on general knowledge. One of Black's main ideas behind ...e6 is to play ...Bb4 to pressure the center. }
6. Qd3
{ This became popular recently, trying to avoid all the mainlines which require a lot of knowledge which make it hard for White to achieve an advantage. However Black has a clear-cut equalizer here too. }
6... d5
{ Seems to equalize.  6...d6  even here in these Scheveningen structures the queen on d3 is not ideally placed, and Black can play these positions, but we have even simpler. }
7. exd5 Nb4
{ This is the idea, with the idea to recapture with a piece on d5 without being left with an IQP. }
8. Qg3
{ The only move to fight for an advantage, making it difficult for Black to develop if they recapture immediately. }
8... Bc5 9. Bb5+ { Trying to annoy the Black king before it castles. } 9... Kf8
{ A minor inconvenience, but in exchange we have very active pieces. } 10. a3
Nbxd5 { Recapturing with the piece to keep the structure in tact. } 11. Nde2
Bd7 12. Bxd7 Qxd7 13. O-O h5
{ Black will next play ...h4, ...Rh5 with enough play for an equal position. }
