[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 40: 2.Nf3 Nc6 with 5...e6 "]
[Black "5...e6: 6.Ndb5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is the main continuation and the most popular for Black. } 5. Nc3 e6
{ This system was always considered to be a bit dubious, and was used only as a surprise weapon. Lately though, in two main lines, the engine found some new ideas which increased its popularity and has proven it's not clear White can get an advantage by force. Hungarian GM, Richard Rapport has had good success with this variation.   For Black, you do need to know quite a lot of theory and be well-prepared; it's not an opening you can play only relying on general knowledge. One of Black's main ideas behind ...e6 is to play ...Bb4 to pressure the center. }
6. Ndb5 { The second-most testing way for White to play. } 6... Bb4
{ This is the independent way for Black to meet White's Ndb5 idea. This was always considered slightly dubious and not equalizing, but there are some new ideas to fight for equality. }
7. Bf4
{ This is a very serious system you need to know very well and could be a great weapon against unsuspecting opponents with the black pieces. }
7... Nxe4
{ This is the most critical try for Black.  7...O-O  8.Bc7  Qe7  9.Bd6  The best way for White to play.  9...Bxd6  10.Qxd6  Qd8  This isn't terrible for Black, but I doubt it fully equalizes.   Also after  7...e5  8.Bg5  it's not clear Black equalizes. }
8. Qf3
{ This is the most testing as the most accurate move.  8.Nc7+  Kf8  9.Qf3  is not an improvement since  9...Nxc3  is good enough for equality without the need for ...d5. }
8... d5
{ Must be played, adding more control over the d6 square as after  8...Nxc3  9.bxc3  Ba5  10.Nd6+  Black has serious problems. }
9. Nc7+ Kf8
{ The positions that start from here are very sharp and it's best if the lines are checked with an engine since the variations are so concrete. }
10. O-O-O { This is also possible, even though it looks bad. } 10... Bxc3
{ Should be preferred.  10...Nxc3  should be avoided as after  11.bxc3  Ba3+  12.Kb1  The engines prefer this position despite its aesthetic appearance because of the strength of the c4 threat, and in such a sharp position, who are we to argue with the engines? }
11. bxc3 e5
{ A solid equalizer.  11...g5  also might be enough to equalize but probably involves more risk. }
12. Nxd5 f5
{ Holding onto the strong central knight, and we're not afraid of any discoveries. }
13. Bg3 h5
{ The best move according to the engines, threatening ...h4 and ...Rh6. Very sharp and complicated but Black should not be worse. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 40: 2.Nf3 Nc6 with 5...e6 "]
[Black "5...e6: 6.Ndb5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is the main continuation and the most popular for Black. } 5. Nc3 e6
{ This system was always considered to be a bit dubious, and was used only as a surprise weapon. Lately though, in two main lines, the engine found some new ideas which increased its popularity and has proven it's not clear White can get an advantage by force. Hungarian GM, Richard Rapport has had good success with this variation.   For Black, you do need to know quite a lot of theory and be well-prepared; it's not an opening you can play only relying on general knowledge. One of Black's main ideas behind ...e6 is to play ...Bb4 to pressure the center. }
6. Ndb5 { The second-most testing way for White to play. } 6... Bb4
{ This is the independent way for Black to meet White's Ndb5 idea. This was always considered slightly dubious and not equalizing, but there are some new ideas to fight for equality. }
7. Bf4
{ This is a very serious system you need to know very well and could be a great weapon against unsuspecting opponents with the black pieces. }
7... Nxe4
{ This is the most critical try for Black.  7...O-O  8.Bc7  Qe7  9.Bd6  The best way for White to play.  9...Bxd6  10.Qxd6  Qd8  This isn't terrible for Black, but I doubt it fully equalizes.   Also after  7...e5  8.Bg5  it's not clear Black equalizes. }
8. Qf3
{ This is the most testing as the most accurate move.  8.Nc7+  Kf8  9.Qf3  is not an improvement since  9...Nxc3  is good enough for equality without the need for ...d5. }
8... d5
{ Must be played, adding more control over the d6 square as after  8...Nxc3  9.bxc3  Ba5  10.Nd6+  Black has serious problems. }
9. Nc7+ Kf8
{ The positions that start from here are very sharp and it's best if the lines are checked with an engine since the variations are so concrete. }
10. Nxa8 { The main move. } 10... e5
{ Taking the full center. Activity is vital. } 11. Bd2 { The only move. } 11...
Nd4
{ The best move, continuing our initiative.  11...Nxd2  12.Qxd5  is very risky and unnecessary. This needs to be thoroughly checked. }
12. Qd1 Qh4
{ The best move to start some direct play necessary for compensation.  12...Bg4  13.Qc1  looks nice, but this position is better for White. Once the knight falls, White will be an exchange up and apparently, there's not much of an attack. }
13. g3 Qf6 14. Nxe4 Nf3+ 15. Qxf3
{ A completely crazy move that allows White to try to fight for the win.  15.Ke2  Nd4+  16.Ke1  leads to a perpetual. }
15... Qxf3 16. Bxb4+ Kg8 17. Nd6 Qxh1 18. O-O-O Be6
{ Such a mess. White has three pieces for the queen, and the pieces are scattered, but it should nonetheless be a draw with best play. Play could continue:  19.Nc7  Qxh2  20.Nxd5  Bxd5  21.Rxd5  Qxf2  22.Rxe5   22.Rd1  h5  aiming for ...Rh6  23.Bc4  Qxg3  The engines are saying the position is equal here.  22...Qxf1+  23.Re1  Qxe1+  24.Bxe1  h5  25.Nxb7  g5  when Black organizes his counterplay with the h-pawn, and it's more or less a forced draw. }
