12... Bh5 13. Bg5
{ This is why this line used to be not playable for Black, but now the engines have come up with an active defense.  13.Kh1  d4  14.Ne2  Bg6  doesn't offer White anything. }
13... Qb6+ 14. Kh1 { The main move, not self-pinning the rook. } 14... Ne4
{ An important tactical resource - very computerish play, but it seems Black holds here. I was once preparing against Rapport to try to make this work, but nobody has found a way for White to achieve something special. }
15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Bxe4 Qxb2
{ This still looks very scary for Black fighting against the two bishops and a coming Rb1 threat, but the engines aren't impressed. }
17. Rb1 { Perhaps the scariest move to meet from a practical perspective. }
17... Qxa3 18. Rxb7 Qa6
{ A strong counterattacking and consolidating move, after which we have time to get active again. }
19. Rc7 Rac8 20. Rxc8 Rxc8 21. Re1 Bg6
{ White's initiative has come to a stop and it should be a draw. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 40: 2.Nf3 Nc6 with 5...e6 "]
[Black "5...e6: 6.Ndb5 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is the main continuation and the most popular for Black. } 5. Nc3 e6
{ This system was always considered to be a bit dubious, and was used only as a surprise weapon. Lately though, in two main lines, the engine found some new ideas which increased its popularity and has proven it's not clear White can get an advantage by force. Hungarian GM, Richard Rapport has had good success with this variation.   For Black, you do need to know quite a lot of theory and be well-prepared; it's not an opening you can play only relying on general knowledge. One of Black's main ideas behind ...e6 is to play ...Bb4 to pressure the center. }
6. Ndb5 { The second-most testing way for White to play. } 6... Bb4
{ This is the independent way for Black to meet White's Ndb5 idea. This was always considered slightly dubious and not equalizing, but there are some new ideas to fight for equality. }
7. a3
{ The main move.  7.Nd6+  is completely harmless and after  7...Ke7  8.Bf4  e5  9.Nf5+  Kf8  and Black will play ...d5 next, undermining White's centre with a great, and active game. }
7... Bxc3+
{ After this move, deflating White's positional ambitions against d6, it's quite hard for White to produce something meaningful. }
8. Nxc3 d5 9. exd5 { Appears to allow straight-forward equality. } 9... exd5
{ This must be played.  9...Nxd5  10.Bd2  O-O  11.Qh5  Nf6  12.Qh4  seems to be in White's favor with the two bishops for free. }
10. Bd3 O-O 11. O-O Bg4
{ Seems to give White major headaches in finding anything meaningful. Rapport is the specialist in this line.  11...h6  trying to prevent Bg5 is not good at all because after  12.Bf4  d4  13.Nb5  White is simply better. }
12. f3 { This move is the reason ...Bg4 was always considered to be dubious. }
12... Bh5 13. Bg5
{ This is why this line used to be not playable for Black, but now the engines have come up with an active defense.  13.Kh1  d4  14.Ne2  Bg6  doesn't offer White anything. }
13... Qb6+ 14. Kh1 { The main move, not self-pinning the rook. } 14... Ne4
{ An important tactical resource - very computerish play, but it seems Black holds here. I was once preparing against Rapport to try to make this work, but nobody has found a way for White to achieve something special. }
15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Bxe4 Qxb2
{ This still looks very scary for Black fighting against the two bishops and a coming Rb1 threat, but the engines aren't impressed. }
17. Qb1
{ Objectively this is the best move for White and was always considered to be the best way for an advantage, but similarly, the engines have shown a path to equality for Black. }
17... Qb6
{ The engine's move, giving a pawn for a reduced material endgame which is holdable. }
18. Qxb6 axb6 19. Rfb1 Bg6 { Finally neutralizing the bishop pair. } 20. Bxg6
hxg6 21. Rxb6 Rfc8
{ The position is drawish, and it's more or less a forced draw since White's queenside is so weak. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 40: 2.Nf3 Nc6 with 5...e6 "]
[Black "5...e6: (Alternative: 11...d4 #1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is the main continuation and the most popular for Black. } 5. Nc3 e6
{ This system was always considered to be a bit dubious, and was used only as a surprise weapon. Lately though, in two main lines, the engine found some new ideas which increased its popularity and has proven it's not clear White can get an advantage by force. Hungarian GM, Richard Rapport has had good success with this variation.   For Black, you do need to know quite a lot of theory and be well-prepared; it's not an opening you can play only relying on general knowledge. One of Black's main ideas behind ...e6 is to play ...Bb4 to pressure the center. }
6. Ndb5 { The second-most testing way for White to play. } 6... Bb4
{ This is the independent way for Black to meet White's Ndb5 idea. This was always considered slightly dubious and not equalizing, but there are some new ideas to fight for equality. }
7. a3
{ The main move.  7.Nd6+  is completely harmless and after  7...Ke7  8.Bf4  e5  9.Nf5+  Kf8  and Black will play ...d5 next, undermining White's centre with a great, and active game. }
7... Bxc3+
{ After this move, deflating White's positional ambitions against d6, it's quite hard for White to produce something meaningful. }
8. Nxc3 d5 9. exd5 { Appears to allow straight-forward equality. } 9... exd5
{ This must be played.  9...Nxd5  10.Bd2  O-O  11.Qh5  Nf6  12.Qh4  seems to be in White's favor with the two bishops for free. }
10. Bd3 O-O 11. O-O d4
{ I used to play this old mainline for a long time, but now it's considered just a bit worse for Black. }
12. Ne4
{ This is what Peter Leko played against me a Rapid game in Budapest 2001, but here Black equalizes. }
12... Bf5 13. Bg5
{ Otherwise there would be a lot of exchanges leading to complete equality. }
13... Bxe4 14. Bxe4 h6
{ If White manages to keep the two bishops they will be better, but they cannot manage. }
15. Bh4
{ 15.Bxf6  Qxf6  is just equal even though I managed to beat Leko from here, although it was in a time-scramble. }
15... g5 16. Bxc6 bxc6 17. Bg3 Ne4
{ It's more or less a forced draw with such reduced material. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 40: 2.Nf3 Nc6 with 5...e6 "]
[Black "5...e6: (Alternative: 11...d4 #2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is the main continuation and the most popular for Black. } 5. Nc3 e6
{ This system was always considered to be a bit dubious, and was used only as a surprise weapon. Lately though, in two main lines, the engine found some new ideas which increased its popularity and has proven it's not clear White can get an advantage by force. Hungarian GM, Richard Rapport has had good success with this variation.   For Black, you do need to know quite a lot of theory and be well-prepared; it's not an opening you can play only relying on general knowledge. One of Black's main ideas behind ...e6 is to play ...Bb4 to pressure the center. }
6. Ndb5 { The second-most testing way for White to play. } 6... Bb4
{ This is the independent way for Black to meet White's Ndb5 idea. This was always considered slightly dubious and not equalizing, but there are some new ideas to fight for equality. }
7. a3
{ The main move.  7.Nd6+  is completely harmless and after  7...Ke7  8.Bf4  e5  9.Nf5+  Kf8  and Black will play ...d5 next, undermining White's centre with a great, and active game. }
7... Bxc3+
{ After this move, deflating White's positional ambitions against d6, it's quite hard for White to produce something meaningful. }
8. Nxc3 d5 9. exd5 { Appears to allow straight-forward equality. } 9... exd5
{ This must be played.  9...Nxd5  10.Bd2  O-O  11.Qh5  Nf6  12.Qh4  seems to be in White's favor with the two bishops for free. }
10. Bd3 O-O 11. O-O d4
{ I used to play this old mainline for a long time, but now it's considered just a bit worse for Black. }
12. Ne2
{ The best move. If White can keep the two bishops on this open board, they will have an advantage. }
12... Bg4
{ My recommended move. Grischuk used to play this a lot in his youth.  12...Qd5  was the move I checked for a long time, preparing ...Bf5 and after  13.Nf4  Qd6  14.Nh5  is a very unpleasant move and White should be slightly better with annoying pressure. }
13. Re1
{ This position isn't so relevant anymore as it's slightly better for White but defendable. }
