[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 40: 2.Nf3 Nc6 with 5...e6 "]
[Black "5...e6: (Alternative: 6...d6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is the main continuation and the most popular for Black. } 5. Nc3 e6
{ This system was always considered to be a bit dubious, and was used only as a surprise weapon. Lately though, in two main lines, the engine found some new ideas which increased its popularity and has proven it's not clear White can get an advantage by force. Hungarian GM, Richard Rapport has had good success with this variation.   For Black, you do need to know quite a lot of theory and be well-prepared; it's not an opening you can play only relying on general knowledge. One of Black's main ideas behind ...e6 is to play ...Bb4 to pressure the center. }
6. Ndb5 { The second-most testing way for White to play. } 6... d6
{ This move can be played if you play the Sveshnikov with ...e5 and are comfortable in those structures. }
7. Bf4 { This transposes directly to the lines after 6. Ndb5. } 7... e5
{ 7...Ne5  8.Qd4  loses a pawn. } 8. Bg5
{ This transposes to the Sveshnikov mainline, which we've examinedhere, and is very playable for Black as we see in this course. Also note you can achieve this position with 2... e6, avoiding certain interesting variations for White such as 3. Bb5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 40: 2.Nf3 Nc6 with 5...e6 "]
[Black "5...e6: 6.Nxc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is the main continuation and the most popular for Black. } 5. Nc3 e6
{ This system was always considered to be a bit dubious, and was used only as a surprise weapon. Lately though, in two main lines, the engine found some new ideas which increased its popularity and has proven it's not clear White can get an advantage by force. Hungarian GM, Richard Rapport has had good success with this variation.   For Black, you do need to know quite a lot of theory and be well-prepared; it's not an opening you can play only relying on general knowledge. One of Black's main ideas behind ...e6 is to play ...Bb4 to pressure the center. }
6. Nxc6
{ Since as we've seen 6. Ndb5 allows Black some ways to virtually force drawn positions, this remains the mainline and leads to a key tabiya for Black. White targets the hole on d6 an Black's position is strategically precarious and one slip will give White a great position, so precision is needed. }
6... bxc6 7. e5 Nd5 8. Ne4
{ For a long time Black was in trouble here and couldn't find a good way to get an acceptable position, but once again, things are changing. Black needs to know what to do, but like all the other lines, there should be a path to equality. }
8... Qc7
{ Provoking f4,  which could be weakening. The old way of playing is  8...f5  9.exf6  Nxf6  10.Nd6+  Bxd6  11.Qxd6  Qb6  still old theory...  12.Bd3  c5  From here, if Black manages to develop the position is not so bad but after  13.Bf4  Qxb2   13...Bb7  14.O-O  is alway slightly worse due to the d6 issue.  14.O-O  Qd4  15.Rab1  Black will suffer for quite a while defending a worse position. }
9. f4 Qb6
{ The main move by far and the best move.  9...Qa5+  exists but I don't trust it.  10.Bd2   10.c3  Ba6  trying to exchange the bishops  11.Be2  still doesn't seem like enough for equality.  10...Qb6  11.Bd3  Be7  12.Qe2  with O-O next gives White a very powerful initiative if Black dare take on b2, otherwise O-O-O will be strong as well.   9...f5  also doesn't feel objectively sound enough, but it's a tricky option.  10.exf6  gxf6  11.Bd2!  offers an extremely tricky and complicated battle that really needs to be engine checked for both sides in order to be played properly. The mainline goes  11...Be7  12.Qh5+  Kd8  13.c4  Nxf4  14.Qh6  Ng6  15.O-O-O  d5  16.Bc3  a5  This position is still very difficult for both sides, but White has the initiative so you shouldn't enter this without good analysis. }
10. c4
{ 10.Bd3  and  10.a3  are also moves that you can check on your own, but much more popular and important to check is 10. c4. }
10... Bb4+
{ Play is very direct here. The king is forced to give up castling rights. }
11. Ke2 { 11.Bd2  Qe3+  will hurt. } 11... f5
{ This is the right move-order to sidestep the tactics. } 12. Nf2
{ This is the strategic alternative to  12.exf6  and is about equally playable though perhaps not as ambitious. }
12... Ba6 { Trying to start an initiative against the king. } 13. Kf3
{ Forced, and funnily enough, the king is the most active piece in White's position. }
13... Ne7 14. Be3 Bc5 15. Bxc5 Qxc5 16. Qd6
{ It's difficult for White to stabilize because if White plays a slow move like  16.b3  then  16...g5  and Black creates serious counterplay. }
16... Qb6
{ There have been many games at the top level in this position, the last probably being in Stalingrad 2022 Firouzja vs. Rapport. White has some chances for an advantage but the play is very strange and the structure is non-trivial so it must be analyzed well to understand the ideas. }
17. Be2
{ This is another possible move, favoring development and consolidating the king's position. }
17... g5
{ An interesting and good move, aiming for counterplay. Black shouldn't take on b2 as it will only help White develop the rooks.  17...c5  18.Rhd1  Rd8  is a solid way to neutralize White's central activity. }
18. fxg5 Ng6 19. h4 Qb8
{ Black is about to regain the pawn when White doesn't have the forces to maintain an initiative. }
*

