[White "Lesson 40: 2.Nf3 Nc6 with 5...e6 "]
[Black "5...e6: 6.Nxc6 (Alternative: 8...Bb7 #3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is the main continuation and the most popular for Black. } 5. Nc3 e6
{ This system was always considered to be a bit dubious, and was used only as a surprise weapon. Lately though, in two main lines, the engine found some new ideas which increased its popularity and has proven it's not clear White can get an advantage by force. Hungarian GM, Richard Rapport has had good success with this variation.   For Black, you do need to know quite a lot of theory and be well-prepared; it's not an opening you can play only relying on general knowledge. One of Black's main ideas behind ...e6 is to play ...Bb4 to pressure the center. }
6. Nxc6
{ Since as we've seen 6. Ndb5 allows Black some ways to virtually force drawn positions, this remains the mainline and leads to a key tabiya for Black. White targets the hole on d6 an Black's position is strategically precarious and one slip will give White a great position, so precision is needed. }
6... bxc6 7. e5 Nd5 8. Ne4
{ For a long time Black was in trouble here and couldn't find a good way to get an acceptable position, but once again, things are changing. Black needs to know what to do, but like all the other lines, there should be a path to equality. }
8... Bb7
{ This system is not as bad as it looks, because it works tactically somehow. I've played it myself in the past. }
9. Be2
{ Is the main problem for Black. 9.Bd3 doesn't seem to work because Black will have ...Nb4 hitting the bishop and preparing ...c5, releasing the bishop. }
9... c5
{ Practically forced.  9...Qc7  isn't good in view of  10.Nd6+  Bxd6  11.exd6  Qb6   11...Qxd6  is impossible because of  12.c4  Qb4+  13.Bd2  12.c4  and the position is very bad because Black lost time playing ...Qc7. }
10. O-O Qc7
{ White is ready to play c4 and get a very nice plus, so Black must strike at the center. }
11. Nd6+
{ Leads to a pleasant edge for White.  11.c4  Qxe5  12.cxd5  Qxe4  13.Bf3  Qb4  White has active compensation here but is still a bit dangerous for Black. }
11... Bxd6 12. exd6 Qc6 { Provoking a kingside concession. } 13. f3
{ Must be played before c4, in order to defend g2 against the queen/bishop battery. }
13... c4 { Playing it ourselves to prevent White from playing it. } 14. Qd4 O-O
15. Bxc4 Qxd6
{ Black in effect exchanges the c-pawn for the d-pawn and there have been many games here which White can try to push for an edge with the two bishops. For example, Leko beat Topalov from this position in 2002, as well as Kasparov vs. Leko when Leko managed to defend a tough position. }
