[White "Lesson 41: Sveshnikov without 7.Bg5"]
[Black "6.Ndb5 d6 7.Nd5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ In this lesson we will introduce the Sveshnikov and White's alternatives to the main line 7. Bg5. According to current theory, it is very difficult for White to prove an advantage against the Sveshnikov. It is successfully employed by numerous grandmasters - I have played it throughout my career and it is one of the main weapons of world champion Magnus Carlsen, who prepared it for his 2018 match with Fabiano Caruana - and it is one of the most popular Sicilians at any level.   After all, it is not so often that Black can play with the initiative right from the opening! }
6. Ndb5
{ Of course both  6.Nf3  and  6.Nb3  don't work because of  6...Bb4  ,  indirectly attacking e4 and preparing ...d5. }
6... d6
{ Black has tried  6...h6  but it doesn't work, for several reasons, the most immediate being  7.Nd5  . }
7. Nd5 { It is White's main alternative to  7.Bg5 } 7... Nxd5 8. exd5
{ And now Black can choose between 8...Nb8 and 8...Ne7, both of which are sound. The first is safer, positional, but gives White more opportunities to fight for an advantage. After the second, on the other hand, the game becomes sharper and it is important to know the theory move by move. }
8... Nb8 { The positional approach. } 9. c4 Be7
{ 9...a6  10.Qa4  Black is already in trouble.  10...Nd7   If  10...Bd7  11.Qa3  and Black is forced to give up the bishop;  11...Bxb5  12.cxb5  11.c5  dxc5   11...Rb8  is what I played back in 1992 in Gausdal, against GM Westerinen.  12.Nxd6+  Bxd6  13.cxd6  O-O  and even if I managed to win after slowly taking back the pawn, White is objectively better.  12.d6  axb5  13.Qxa8  Bxd6  14.Bxb5  But now Black has maybe enough compensation for the exchange. }
10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O Nd7 12. Kh1
{ A typical maneuver in these type of positions, as White will need to push his f-pawn sooner or later. }
12... a6 13. Nc3 f5
{ Black wants to continue with ...e4, ...Bf6 and ...Ne5. If White allows it, he will find himself in a worse position. }
14. f4 { If  14.f3  then after  14...Bg5  or  14...a5  Black is fine. } 14...
Bf6
{ Black often continues by taking f4, thus creating an outpost on e5 for the knight. The position is equal. }
