{ It becomes difficult for both players to win the initiative, and the game becomes more positional. }
14. Kh1
{ White can also try  14.a3  Bg5  15.b4  but Black can simply reply with ...b6, and has nothing to worry about White's play on the queenside. }
14... Bg5
{ Taking control of the dark squares. After  14...b6  15.Be3  Bg5  16.Bg1  White's king is safe, and White can start organizing his play on the queenside with b4-c5. }
15. b4 a5 { 15...b6  is ok too. } 16. a3 axb4 17. Bxg5 Qxg5 18. axb4 Rxa1 19.
Qxa1 Qe3
{ I had this position on the board back in the 1990s when I was preparing for my match with Yudasin. }
20. Be2 Nb8
{ Clearing the way for the bishop and maneuvering to attack the b4-pawn. Black is fine. }
