{ With the pawn on c4, White misses the Qc4 maneuver. If  11...Bf5  then  12.h4  is unpleasant. }
12. h4
{ The point of the White play. If, for instance,  12.Be2  then  12...Be7  and Black quickly takes the initiative. }
12... h5
{ Black needs to stop the white pawn. If  12...a6  13.h5  axb5  14.hxg6  White is better. }
13. Be2 { 13.Be3  transposes. } 13... a6 14. Nc3 Be7 15. g3
{ Black cannot castle because of the weak h5 pawn. White will proceed with Be3, taking advantage of the b6 square, if Black does not quickly come up with something. }
15... b5
{ All of a sudden, Black begins his counterplay on the other side of the board. }
16. cxb5 axb5
{ Black has at his disposal an annoying maneuver, ....Bd8-a5 or ... Bd8-b6-c5. Therefore White usually takes on b5. }
17. Nxb5 O-O 18. a4 f5
{ An extremely complicated position, requiring further analysis certainly, but one that is dynamically balanced. It can be played with both colors. }
