{ Obviously the best move in the position, White wants to get the knight closer to the d5-square, this move prevents that plan and threatens ...b4 as well. }
9. Nd5
{ So today we are going to study this move, 9.Nd5, a kind of positional system. It has been played countless times on the top level.  Now Black has to be very accurate, after listening to this course you will have good knowledge of the nuances of this system and if your opponent is not so well-prepared then you have considerable chances to get a certain advantage out of the opening. }
9... Be7
{ The only move to fight for equality, and even if Black most often equalizes on the top level, just one wrong move and White will get a significant advantage. Definitely, a rather risk-free variation for White if you know what you are doing.  For those of you who want to play this line with Black, I'll try to give a detailed analysis of the current state of theory, the best directions and certain concrete variations - that will already be enough information for you to play it with Black @@StartBracket@@if you are not in the top 10 of the world@@EndBracket@@.   9...Be6  is a mistake, you'll understand this more after watching the next lesson.  10.Bxf6  gxf6  11.c3  f5  12.exf5  Bxf5  and Black simply lost a tempo. }
10. Bxf6 Bxf6
{ In this position for many many years White would practically immediately play c3, which I believe that it's still the strongest move, trying to follow it up with Nc2. }
11. c4
{ This move started to get more and more popular sometime around the end of the 20th century, and was causing Black some problems for a while. Nevertheless, I believe that Black found a convincing way to deal with the text move.  Black tried the move 11...Nd4 for a while, sacrificing the b-pawn for some compensation, but it's not very convincing. }
11... b4 { The most logical reply. } 12. Nc2 a5
{ The problem for White in this setup is that the d4-square is terminally weakened. So the knight on c2 is tasked with defending it, trying to hold the knight on c6 for as long as possible.  White's plan ideally is to exchange the bad light-squared bishop, should he achieve that task White will end up in a strategically winning position.  Nevertheless, I must emphasize that it goes against my classical positional education to put the White pawn on c4 limiting the light-squared bishop on c1, with a potential hole on d4 I don't believe this should ever give White any advantage. }
13. g3 { The main idea in this line. } 13... O-O 14. h4
{ White's main try. A multifunctional move, firstly stopping ...Bg5, now Black has a problem to solve with his dark-squared bishop. Secondly preparing Bh3 and trying somehow to exchange the bishop.  Black didn't manage to equalize here for quite a while, but by now, people @@StartBracket@@or their engines@@EndBracket@@ finally figured out a solid and good setup against it. Actually, it is not a setup, but Black rather organizes tactical counterplay quickly and it seems to work! }
14... Be6 15. Bg2 g6
{ I like this route more than taking on d5. Black simply wants to play ...Bg7 and ...Rc8 and maybe ...f5 one day. The position is not so clear for White because the knight on c2 is still stuck and whenever you play Nce3, Black will immediately pounce with ...Nd4. }
16. Bh3
{ White is trying to pretend this is a serious move, but he is not really threatening anything. Taking on e6 will deprive White of the strong outpost on d5. }
16... Bg7 17. h5
{ The only logical continuation. White can't castle because the bishop on h3 would hang. Nevertheless, it is quite clear that White doesn't have enough resources to organize a serious attack on the black king. }
17... Rb8
{ A typical Sveshnikov move, hinting at ...b3 on an opportune moment. } 18. Qd3
Qc8 19. Bg2 Qd8
{ Hinting at ...Qg5. If I was White, I'd be in a hurry to repeat moves because it is very easy to end up in a terrible position here. }
*

