{ In this position for many many years White would practically immediately play c3, which I believe that it's still the strongest move, trying to follow it up with Nc2. }
11. c4
{ This move started to get more and more popular sometime around the end of the 20th century, and was causing Black some problems for a while. Nevertheless, I believe that Black found a convincing way to deal with the text move.  Black tried the move 11...Nd4 for a while, sacrificing the b-pawn for some compensation, but it's not very convincing. }
11... b4 { The most logical reply. } 12. Nc2 a5
{ The problem for White in this setup is that the d4-square is terminally weakened. So the knight on c2 is tasked with defending it, trying to hold the knight on c6 for as long as possible.  White's plan ideally is to exchange the bad light-squared bishop, should he achieve that task White will end up in a strategically winning position.  Nevertheless, I must emphasize that it goes against my classical positional education to put the White pawn on c4 limiting the light-squared bishop on c1, with a potential hole on d4 I don't believe this should ever give White any advantage. }
13. g3 { The main idea in this line. } 13... O-O 14. h4
{ White's main try. A multifunctional move, firstly stopping ...Bg5, now Black has a problem to solve with his dark-squared bishop. Secondly preparing Bh3 and trying somehow to exchange the bishop.  Black didn't manage to equalize here for quite a while, but by now, people @@StartBracket@@or their engines@@EndBracket@@ finally figured out a solid and good setup against it. Actually, it is not a setup, but Black rather organizes tactical counterplay quickly and it seems to work! }
