{ Obviously the best move in the position, White wants to get the knight closer to the d5-square, this move prevents that plan and threatens ...b4 as well. }
9. Nd5
{ So today we are going to study this move, 9.Nd5, a kind of positional system. It has been played countless times on the top level.  Now Black has to be very accurate, after listening to this course you will have good knowledge of the nuances of this system and if your opponent is not so well-prepared then you have considerable chances to get a certain advantage out of the opening. }
9... Be7
{ The only move to fight for equality, and even if Black most often equalizes on the top level, just one wrong move and White will get a significant advantage. Definitely, a rather risk-free variation for White if you know what you are doing.  For those of you who want to play this line with Black, I'll try to give a detailed analysis of the current state of theory, the best directions and certain concrete variations - that will already be enough information for you to play it with Black @@StartBracket@@if you are not in the top 10 of the world@@EndBracket@@.   9...Be6  is a mistake, you'll understand this more after watching the next lesson.  10.Bxf6  gxf6  11.c3  f5  12.exf5  Bxf5  and Black simply lost a tempo. }
10. Bxf6 Bxf6
{ In this position for many many years White would practically immediately play c3, which I believe that it's still the strongest move, trying to follow it up with Nc2. }
11. c3 O-O 12. Nc2 Rb8
{ This move in this order was supposed to be clear-cut equality until... } 13.
h4
{ Garry Kasparov came up with move! Practically a refutation of this move order. A very powerful move, not only because it is a strong novelty but at the time Garry really understood the core ideas behind it. It is very important for White to limit the bishop. }
13... Ne7
{ I played this move once because I vaguely recalled once that I saw in some book that h4 is a bad move and Ne7 is one of the simple ways to equalize.  But at the board I started to look at the position and somehow I couldn't understand what to do with Black.  A key difference to notice from the positions we studied previously with c4 is that the d4 square is firmly protected whereas now White simply continues with Ne3-g3 and develops a very serious attack. I don't see how to equalize this position with Black. }
14. Nxf6+ gxf6 { White is just better. } 15. Bd3
{ The strongest and approved by modern engines.  In the game against me, Garry played 15...Qh5 is also a very dangerous move, yet I managed somehow to complicate matters and get a playable position. }
15... d5 { This has to be played otherwise White will play Ne3. } 16. exd5 Qxd5
17. Ne3 Qe6 18. Qh5 f5 19. O-O-O
{ Black has a nice center and a seemingly pleasant position but his king in reality is very weak. Bc2-Bb3 is coming, g4 is also on the agenda. }
19... e4 20. Bc2 Qg6 21. Qg5
{ A very unpleasant move. If you exchange on g5 the endgame is very difficult for Black.  This is why I believe that the Rb8 move order is borderline unplayable. }
