10. Bxf6 Bxf6
{ In this position for many many years White would practically immediately play c3, which I believe that it's still the strongest move, trying to follow it up with Nc2. }
11. c3 Bg5
{ The most fashionable system nowadays, coupled with Rb8-O-O-b4.   It might be even better to start with  11...Rb8  ,  as Nxf6+ is never really a threat.  12.Nc2  Bg5  and now the point is that h4 doesn't work anymore.  13.h4  Bxh4  and there is no mate on the h-file of course. }
12. Nc2 Rb8
{ Black wants to get the same position without allowing Garry's annoying h4. }
13. a4 bxa4 14. Ncb4
{ A very serious attempt by White. Here you need to know and memorize some theory but it is only one major critical line and it seems that if you analyze it well and remember all the details there is a very good chance Black will equalize. }
14... Nxb4 15. cxb4 { All of the top players are taking with the pawn now. }
15... O-O 16. Rxa4 a5
{ If you want to equalize in a very straightforward way then this is definitely what you should do. }
17. b5 Bd7 18. Nc3 d5 19. Qxd5 Bc1 { Very unpleasant attacking the pawn on b2 }
20. b3 Bb2 21. Qd2 Bxc3 22. Qxc3 Bxb5
{ And it is only Black who can try a little bit here, but of course, it is a draw. }
*

