{ Black almost always wants to follow up f5 with d5 freeing up the g7 bishop even at the cost of a pawn sometimes. }
15. Qh5 { Now I think that Black has two ways to equalize and be fine. } 15...
d5 { The engines discovered this very direct way of handling this Qh5 system. }
16. cxd5 { Forced. } 16... Qd8
{ This is a move that a human will never find on his own. It looks strange but it's the best move in the position.   The idea behind it is if we take  16...fxe4  17.Bxe4  and now play  17...f5  , there is  18.d6  , attacking the rook on a8.   If you try to play the same idea but with  16...Qd6  instead then White has the very annoying  17.Rac1  with Rc6 coming sometimes. That's why we go 16...Qd8. }
17. f3 { This is a very dangerous move for White. } 17... f4
{ Now there is a serious issue with the queen on h5. } 18. Kh1 Rb8
{ And the rook is coming for the white queen along the 6th rank. } 19. g4
{ The only way for White to play. } 19... Rb6 20. g5 Rg6
{ Black has great compensation for the pawn. Keep in mind that the g7 bishop will eventually go to c5 probably via f8. By the way this is one of the important factors in this position is that seemingly passive bishop on g7 becomes extremely dangerous when it comes to the other diagonal. }
