{ Black is at a crossroad now, what to do with the center? } 15... d5 16. exf5
e4 17. Be2 Rd8
{ Not a lot of games here at the top level, I think Black still needs to play accurately to equalize this position. }
18. a4 { Typical idea, weakening the queenside. } 18... bxa4 19. Rxa4 Bxf5 20.
Ne3 Be6 21. Bg4
{ White needs only to watch out for d4 but so far it is not easy to achieve. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 43: Sveshnikov - The Tactical 9.Bxf6"]
[Black "Sveshnikov 9.Bxf6 gxf6 10.Nd5 Bg7 11.Bd3 Ne7 #25"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8.
Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 { We will analyze 9.Bxf6 in this lesson. } 9... gxf6
{ 9...Qxf6  doesn't make any sense as after  10.Nd5  Qd8  Black gets a worse version of the 9.Nd5 variation. }
10. Nd5
{ First of all, I would like to apologize in advance because in this lesson, there will be a lot of theory and a lot of variations. But what to do? The Sveshnikov is a very important variation and in this line, the price of a move is very high.  Quite often both sides will have to make only moves. Of course, there are general ideas: Black is trying to push ...f5 by all means and White is trying to play c2-c3 to get the knight into the game. White will usually need also to blockade the centre while trying to use the central squares to create strategic and tactical possibilities.  On the other hand, despite Black's weird pawn structure, he gets a powerful center. But frankly, all of these details won't be relevant as you will see the variations are very direct in many lines and you just need to know the theory move by move. }
10... Bg7
{ Although not the mainline, according to modern theory this is a decent way of playing. I don't see a real advantage for White here. You need to know that this variation is much more forcing than 10...f5 and Black is basically trying to make a forced draw, therefore you really need to memorize the following variations. }
11. Bd3 { The main move here in this position. } 11... Ne7
{ Since Bd3 cut the queen's access to the d5-square, this is the perfect timing to attack it with Ne7. }
12. Nxe7 Qxe7 { This is the position where play gets very direct. } 13. O-O O-O
{ It is pretty clear that sooner or later White willl try to get his knight into the game and he has two different ways to do it: c4 and c3. }
14. c3
{ As White in my opinion, I suggest you try this move c3. Even though it is out of fashion I think it is very playable. Black is okay objectively but it is less forcing and Black will have to make some accurate moves to get there. }
14... f5 { Of course. } 15. Nc2
{ Black is at a crossroad now, what to do with the center? } 15... d5 16. exf5
e4 17. Be2 Rd8
{ Not a lot of games here at the top level, I think Black still needs to play accurately to equalize this position. }
18. Bg4 Qg5 19. g3 Bxf5 20. Bxf5 Qxf5 21. a4
{ There is a very tiny tiny edge for White. Black still has to show how exactly he's making a draw. This is my recommendation for White because honestly I don't see what else. It is smart to sometime test your opponent if they know their stuff in the c4 lines but frankly if he's very well prepared the lines are pretty direct. }
*

[Event "?"]
