{ What is good about this position is that you can get it against both Bf5 and Bg7. This was causing quite some trouble for Black in the 90s as I painfully recollect now. But finally now it seems that Black has found @@StartBracket@@I can say partly thanks to my efforts@@EndBracket@@ a way to equalize against this move. }
13... Be6
{ This is another playable position that I played many times, but I prefer 13...O-O because of White's a4 idea. }
14. g3 O-O 15. Bg2 a5 16. O-O f5 { 16...Rb8 is also possible. } 17. Re1 Rb8
{ You need to study this position.  I think it is more or less equal because White has good control in the center and Black has to be very careful about this d6 pawn and the knight jumping around. The theory is not direct here; there is a lot of games and practice has shown that Black has enough counterplay to equalize the position. }
*

