{ 9...Qxf6  doesn't make any sense as after  10.Nd5  Qd8  Black gets a worse version of the 9.Nd5 variation. }
10. Nd5
{ First of all, I would like to apologize in advance because in this lesson, there will be a lot of theory and a lot of variations. But what to do? The Sveshnikov is a very important variation and in this line, the price of a move is very high.  Quite often both sides will have to make only moves. Of course, there are general ideas: Black is trying to push ...f5 by all means and White is trying to play c2-c3 to get the knight into the game. White will usually need also to blockade the centre while trying to use the central squares to create strategic and tactical possibilities.  On the other hand, despite Black's weird pawn structure, he gets a powerful center. But frankly, all of these details won't be relevant as you will see the variations are very direct in many lines and you just need to know the theory move by move. }
10... f5
{ This was my preferred choice when I was playing the Sveshnikov.  White has plenty of replies here so let's look at them one by one. }
11. Bd3 Be6 12. O-O Bxd5 { Now this move is necessary. } 13. exd5 Ne7
{ There's a lot of discussions and from time to time there are games at the top level here. There are some nuances but all in all I believe Black is holding here. }
14. Re1 Bg7 15. c3 O-O
{ Black needs to be careful here and not push e4 too quickly. } 16. Qh5
{ The idea behind my plan is to play Qh5 here. } 16... e4 17. Bf1
{ This is the most dangerous position for Black in this whole Bd3 line. Even if it is objectively okay here Black must be pretty careful. }
17... Re8 18. Nc2 Nxd5 { I think that this move is good enough. } 19. Qxf5
{ There was a game I believe here, Topalov-Mamedov, an important one that is relevant to our analysis. }
19... Re5 20. Qh3
{ White of course has certain structural advantages, but in a very typical Sveshnikov way Black manages to equalize thanks to his counterplay and active pieces. }
20... Qb6 21. Rad1 Rae8
{ Black wants to play e3 and exchange everything, so Topalov sacrificed an exchange to prevent that. }
22. Rxe4 Rxe4 23. Rxd5 R4e5
{ White of course has enough compensation for the exchange but I don't think he can really be better. This is the current state of theory of 9.Bxf6.  I tried to give you the most important and relevant information, I think you can already play it with both colours and if you want to study it further, I encourage you to explore more master games and follow the top grandmasters.  It was a long session with a lot of variations, but at least you can see that the play is very lively, which is what attracted me very much to this opening. All in all, I think Black is holding well in the Sveshnikov.  Now I feel that you know what to do in the Sveshnikov, everyone who studied this course better than most of the players in the world because I know a lot about this opening. I gave you all of the lines that I was preparing myself and I would play myself with both colours. We finished our Sveshnikov journey. }
