1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ The Dragon is the subject of this lesson. It's called the Dragon because Black's pawn structure resembles the shape of a dragon.  This system is quite interesting and popular at lower levels. As the level increases, this move becomes less and less popular, although Magnus Carlsen has played it in the past with decent results. The reason why this opening is not well-seen is that, if White is well-prepared, Black can lose on the spot if he's not careful.  I wouldn't say that the Dragon is refuted, but White has a lot of systems available, and all of them are dangerous for Black. }
6. Bc4 Bg7 7. O-O O-O
{ This system is playable and White can fight for a slight advantage. The problem of White castling kingside in these lines is that it justifies the black bishop being on g7, where it's most active than on e7 @@StartBracket@@compare the position of this bishop here with its placement in the Najdorf, Scheveningen and Classical Sicilian@@EndBracket@@. }
8. Re1 { 8.Bb3  Nc6  9.h3  probably transposes to the text move. } 8... Nc6 9.
h3 Bd7 10. Bb3
{ Trying to play a positional game, but Black shouldn't be worried about this approach. }
10... Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Bc6 { 11...b5  is fine as well. } 12. Qd3 Nd7
{ We reach a position which every Sicilian player should like playing. } *

