1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ The Dragon is the subject of this lesson. It's called the Dragon because Black's pawn structure resembles the shape of a dragon.  This system is quite interesting and popular at lower levels. As the level increases, this move becomes less and less popular, although Magnus Carlsen has played it in the past with decent results. The reason why this opening is not well-seen is that, if White is well-prepared, Black can lose on the spot if he's not careful.  I wouldn't say that the Dragon is refuted, but White has a lot of systems available, and all of them are dangerous for Black. }
6. Be3 { The best system for White against the Dragon by far. } 6... Bg7 7. Be2
Nc6 8. Qd2 { I don't think this gives anthing special for White. } 8... O-O 9.
O-O-O
{ White players could argue that having a pawn on f3 hinders the attack with h4-h5, but prevents the always annoying ...Ng4 from Black. }
9... Ng4 10. Bxg4 Bxg4 11. f3 Be6
{ An important move that should be kept in Dragon players' minds. Black has some counterplay on the queenside against the typical h-pawn push from White. Therefore, Black's light-squared bishop should be active. }
12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. Bh6 Qa5 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. h4 Rac8 16. h5 Ne5 17. hxg6 hxg6
{ Black's king will run to the center and the queenside counterplay will have a role in the game. Black is fine here. }
*

