1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ The Dragon is the subject of this lesson. It's called the Dragon because Black's pawn structure resembles the shape of a dragon.  This system is quite interesting and popular at lower levels. As the level increases, this move becomes less and less popular, although Magnus Carlsen has played it in the past with decent results. The reason why this opening is not well-seen is that, if White is well-prepared, Black can lose on the spot if he's not careful.  I wouldn't say that the Dragon is refuted, but White has a lot of systems available, and all of them are dangerous for Black. }
6. Be3 { The best system for White against the Dragon by far. } 6... Bg7 7. f3
Nc6 8. Qd2 O-O 9. g4
{ This move is dangerous, but out of fashion. The idea is to stop Black's ...d5-break. }
9... Be6 { 9...d5  10.g5 } 10. O-O-O { 10.h4  d5  is OK for Black. } 10... Nxd4
{ Luring White's queen or bishop to d4, which hinders the attack on the kingside. }
11. Bxd4 Qa5 12. a3 Rfc8 13. h4 Rab8 14. Nd5
{ After  14.h5  b5  ,  the play becomes very sharp, but engines show that the lines end in a draw. }
14... Qxd2+ 15. Rxd2 Bxd5 16. exd5
{ Karpov tried to prove that this endgame was better for White with some success, but nowadays engines hold the position for Black with the next move. }
16... b5
{ Very strong, but difficult to play OTB if it's not known because it implies sacrificing a pawn for counterplay. }
17. Bxa7
{ 17.Kb1  a5  and Black is close to break the position open with ...b4. } 17...
Ra8 18. Bd4 b4
{ Nice resource that gets the pawn back. If  19.axb4  Ra1  is mate. } *

