12... b5 { Black tries to organize counterplay. } 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Nd5
{ White is slightly better against all Black tries here. One example line could follow: }
14... Nc4 { The best try. } 15. Bxc4 bxc4 16. Ne2
{ 16.Nxf6  Qb6  17.Qc3  exf6  is holdable for Black, although White has a slight advantage. }
16... Nxd5 17. exd5 Kg8 18. Rhe1 Qb6 19. Qc3 Rb7 20. Nd4 Ba4
{ White is putting pressure on Black's position. On the other hand, Black has nice control of the b-file, but the best he can aspire is to defend a slightly inferior ending. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 44: 2.Nf3 d6 Dragon"]
[Black "Dragon 6.Be3 Main Line 9.Bc4 #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ The Dragon is the subject of this lesson. It's called the Dragon because Black's pawn structure resembles the shape of a dragon.  This system is quite interesting and popular at lower levels. As the level increases, this move becomes less and less popular, although Magnus Carlsen has played it in the past with decent results. The reason why this opening is not well-seen is that, if White is well-prepared, Black can lose on the spot if he's not careful.  I wouldn't say that the Dragon is refuted, but White has a lot of systems available, and all of them are dangerous for Black. }
6. Be3 { The best system for White against the Dragon by far. } 6... Bg7 7. f3
Nc6 8. Qd2 O-O 9. Bc4
{ The most popular move. I had a lot of fun analyzing the arising variations from White's perspective and found some interesting new ideas. Black's task is not as enjoyable - he must be precise not to get mated. }
9... Bd7 10. O-O-O { 10.Bb3  Nxd4  11.Bxd4  b5  is fine for Black. } 10... Qa5
11. Bb3 Rfc8
{ This is a big theoretical position. I wouldn't say that this line is totally refuted. It used to be the main line of the Dragon for a long time, but by now, White players have discovered two dangerous plans to pose Black problems. }
12. h4 h5 13. Kb1 Ne5 { Bringing the knight to c4. } 14. Bh6 Bxh6 15. Qxh6 Rxc3
{ A typical exchange sacrifice in the Sicilian. Black has enough counterplay here. }
*

