1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ In this lesson, before examining the Rauzer, we will examine White's alternatives to  6.Bg5  .  This setup, which can be challenged by a very few moves by White if we leave out the main line with Bg5, was one of my main weapons before I went back to playing Sveshnikov. }
6. g3
{ As usual, perhaps with the sole exceptions of Najdorf and Taimanov, the g3 system is not really dangerous for White. }
6... g6
{ Black can also play  6...e6  7.Bg2  Bd7  but in my opinion ...g6 is a more clear-cut way to play. }
7. Bg2
{ If White avoids ...Nxd4 by playing  7.Nde2  , then Black is fine after  7...Bg7  8.Bg2  O-O  9.O-O  Rb8  10.a4  a6  11.Nd5  b5 }
7... Nxd4
{ Another line is  7...Bg7  8.Nxc6  bxc6  9.e5  dxe5  10.Qxd8+  Kxd8   10.Bxc6  Bd7  11.Bxa8  Qxa8  is unclear. }
8. Qxd4 Bg7 9. O-O O-O 10. Qd3 Be6
{ 10...Nd7  with the idea ...Be6, ...Ne5-c4 is also good for Black. } 11. Nd5
Nxd5 12. exd5 Bf5 13. Qe2 b5
{ And Black has absolutely no problem. The position is equal. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 45: Classical Sicilian - Sozin"]
[Black "6.Be2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ In this lesson, before examining the Rauzer, we will examine White's alternatives to  6.Bg5  .  This setup, which can be challenged by a very few moves by White if we leave out the main line with Bg5, was one of my main weapons before I went back to playing Sveshnikov. }
6. Be2
{ You can include this line in your repertoire if you play Be2 in other variations of the Sicilian; it is not harmless; White has opportunities for an opening advantage. The following lines will be considered from Black's point of view, but are perfectly playable with both colors. }
6... e5
{ 6...e6  is rarely played.  7.Be3  Be7  transposes to a Scheveningen, a version not particularly favorable to Black, as we have already seen when White continues with  8.Qd2  and long castling.   6...g6  7.Be3  Bg7  transposes to the Dragon with Be2. }
7. Nf3
{ After  7.Nb3  Be7  8.O-O  O-O  9.Be3  the structure is that of a Najdorf in which Black has not played ...a6, so he can play  9...a5  saving a tempo.  10.a4  Nb4  followed by ...Be6 and ...d5, with a good position. }
7... h6
{ 7...Be7  might be okay too.  8.Bg5  Be6  9.O-O  O-O  10.Bxf6  Bxf6  11.Nd5  White managed to get the d5-square, but that should not be enough to gain an advantage.  11...Rc8  12.c3  Ne7  13.Nxf6+  gxf6  and Black will continue with ...d5, with an equal position. }
8. O-O Be7 9. Re1 O-O 10. h3
{ If  10.Bf1  then  10...Bg4  is strong, the bishop no longer controls d5 but the idea is to keep it on this diagonal, or transfer it to g6 to attack the e4-pawn.  11.h3  Bh5  12.Be3  Rc8  with a fine position. }
10... Be6 11. Bf1 { Preventing ...d5, since the e5-pawn will be hanging. }
11... Qa5
{ A strange queen maneuver aimed at preventing Nd5. Why strange? Because after Bd2 the queen returns to d8, thus declaring that the bishop on d2 is so bad that it justifies the lost time. And it is true. }
12. Bd2 Qd8
{ And if  13.Be3  , the bishop stands in the way of the rook, so Black can play  13...d5  since the e5-pawn is no longer hanging. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 45: Classical Sicilian - Sozin"]
[Black "6.f3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ In this lesson, before examining the Rauzer, we will examine White's alternatives to  6.Bg5  .  This setup, which can be challenged by a very few moves by White if we leave out the main line with Bg5, was one of my main weapons before I went back to playing Sveshnikov. }
6. f3 e5
{ 6...Qb6  just loses a tempo, since after  7.Be3  Black cannot take on b2. Both knights' jump on b5 are winning.   6...e6  7.Be3  transposes to the Scheveningen. As I said, those lines are dangerous, I can't see how Black can equalize.   6...g6  7.Be3  transposes to the Dragon. And since you probably don't play ...Nc6 if you want to play the Sicilian Dragon,  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2np1n2/8/3NP3/2N2P2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e5  is, by elimination, the only possible move for Black. }
7. Nb3
{ 7.Nde2  isn't good, as after  7...Be6  8.Nd5  Bxd5  9.exd5  Black has  9...Qa5+  , and after  10.Nc3  Nd4  Black is at least equal. }
7... Be7 { If  7...Be6  White can already play  8.Nd5 } 8. Be3
{ There are two ways of playing for Black that we will now investigate, one more positional and the other more direct. }
8... Be6 9. Nd5 { Logical, otherwise Black plays ...d5. } 9... O-O
{ A rarely played move, which I analyzed in depth in the making of this course and which I recommend you consider carefully.   My game against GM Chandler, played in 1994 during the German Bundesliga, continued with  9...Bxd5  10.exd5  Nb4  11.c4  forced, or White loses the d5-pawn.  11...a5  12.Qd2  b6  13.Be2  O-O  followed by ...Na6 And I am not entirely sure that Black can equalize. }
10. Be2 a5
{ A very strong move.  10...Bxd5  11.exd5  Nb4  12.c4  a5  transposes to 9... bxd5. }
11. Bb6
{ If  11.a4  Bxd5  12.exd5  Nb4  , White is forced to play  13.c4  and after  13...b6  position is completely locked, and Black is doing very well. }
11... Qd7 { With a good position. } *

