[Black "6.h3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ In this lesson, before examining the Rauzer, we will examine White's alternatives to  6.Bg5  .  This setup, which can be challenged by a very few moves by White if we leave out the main line with Bg5, was one of my main weapons before I went back to playing Sveshnikov. }
6. h3
{ This line should be considered seriously, as the game can become sharp. }
6... g6
{ After  6...e6  7.Be3  Be7  8.g4  the position resembles those we will consider in Najdorf with h3, and is playable for both colors.   6...e5  is another line that can be considered, e.g.  7.Nf3  h6  8.Bc4  Be6  9.Bb3  Be7  10.O-O  O-O  11.Re1  Rc8  12.Nd5  Bxd5  13.Bxd5  Nxd5  14.Qxd5  Nb4 }
7. Be3 Bg7 8. Qd2 O-O 9. O-O-O Nxd4
{ 9...d5  can even out but is not very dynamic, for instance  10.exd5  Nxd5  11.Nxc6  bxc6  12.Bd4  Bxd4  13.Qxd4  Qb6  14.Na4  Qc7 }
10. Bxd4 Be6
{ With a pawn on f3 instead of h3, White plays @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp2ppbp/3pbnp1/8/3BP3/2N2P1P/PPPQ2P1/2KR1B1R w - - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Kb1  and Black cannot immediately play  11...Qa5  , because after  12.Nd5  Qxd2  13.Nxe7+  Kh8  14.Rxd2  White is a pawn-up. But with a pawn on h3, Black is better off because he can take on e4. A very important difference. }
11. Kb1 Qa5 { Black is threatening ...Nxe4. } 12. a3 Rfc8
{ Black is preparing to attack with ...Rb8 and ...b5. } 13. g4 Rab8 14. g5
{ White can also try to equalize with  14.Bxf6  Bxf6  15.Nd5  giving up seeking an advantage. }
14... Nh5 15. Nd5
{ It is better for white to exchange queens as soon as possible, otherwise Black's attack is dangerous. }
15... Qxd2 16. Rxd2 { After  16.Nxe7+  Kf8  White loses the knight. } 16...
Bxd5 17. exd5 Bxd4 18. Rxd4 f6
{ Immediately opening the f-file for the rooks. } 19. Be2 fxg5
{ The position is equal. } *

