{ The theory is so vast that a whole course could be made on just 6. Bc4. I will try to guide you to the best choices, having played this position for years, especially with Black.   6.Be3  is good for Black, after  6...Ng4  7.Bg5  h6  8.Bh4  g5  9.Bg3  Bg7  10.Nb3  many moves lead to equality, e.g.  10...Be6  ,  10...h5  or the modern  10...Bxc3+  11.bxc3  Qc7 }
6... Qb6
{ 6...g6  is just bad.  7.Nxc6  bxc6  8.e5  and White is better. Also, @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2np1n2/8/2BNP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e5  isn't an option when the light-squared bishop is already on c4. After  7.Nf3  White is at least slightly better.   6...e6  7.Be3  Be7  8.Qe2  The Velimirovic Attack. I will not dwell on this system for two reasons, which are the same two reasons why it has never been in my repertoire:  1@@EndBracket@@ there is a lot of theory;  2@@EndBracket@@ it is extremely dangerous for Black.  Moreover, nowadays, this is the only move order that leads to this position and usually Black avoids it. The last word is not yet spoken, and Black does not lose by force. But to play this line one must analyze it very well. }
7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. O-O g6
{ 7. Nxc6 was played twice by Topalov against me in the 1990s. In the first game I opted for8...e6  and ended up in a bad position, mainly because of the misplaced queen on b6.  9.Qe2  Modern engines suggest 9. Bf4.  9...Nd7  to stop e5.  10.b3  Bg7  11.Bb2  O-O  12.Na4  Qc7  13.f4  and I was crushed, unable to find anything against White's strong attack. }
9. e5
{ Forced, White cannot let Black complete the development, achieving a good position, e.g.  9.Be3  Qc7  10.Qd2  Bg7   9.Qe2  Qc7  10.Bf4  Bg7  11.e5  Nh5  and Black is fine; if  11.Rfe1  ,  trying to strengthen e5, then  11...Nd7  . }
9... dxe5 10. Qe2 Qc7
{ Simpler than  10...Qd4  , the move I played in my second game against Topalov, which ended in a draw. }
11. Re1
{ If  11.f4  then  11...e4  it's the only move, but it's enough to equalize. After  12.Nxe4  Nxe4  13.Qxe4  Bg7  the pawn on f4 weakens the position, limiting the c1 bishop and exposing the king. }
11... Bg7 12. Qxe5 Qxe5 13. Rxe5 Nd5
{ A strong move, forcing matters, simplifying the position and moving closer to a draw. }
14. Bxd5 cxd5 15. Rxd5 Be6
{ Modern engines care very little about pawns, and they quickly find a clear way to equalize. }
16. Ra5 Bxc3 17. bxc3
{ And now White's extra pawn will have even less impact on the game. } 17... f6
18. Be3 Kf7 19. Bxa7 Rhc8 { With a draw. } *

