1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ In this lesson, before examining the Rauzer, we will examine White's alternatives to  6.Bg5  .  This setup, which can be challenged by a very few moves by White if we leave out the main line with Bg5, was one of my main weapons before I went back to playing Sveshnikov. }
6. Bc4
{ The theory is so vast that a whole course could be made on just 6. Bc4. I will try to guide you to the best choices, having played this position for years, especially with Black.   6.Be3  is good for Black, after  6...Ng4  7.Bg5  h6  8.Bh4  g5  9.Bg3  Bg7  10.Nb3  many moves lead to equality, e.g.  10...Be6  ,  10...h5  or the modern  10...Bxc3+  11.bxc3  Qc7 }
6... Qb6
{ 6...g6  is just bad.  7.Nxc6  bxc6  8.e5  and White is better. Also, @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2np1n2/8/2BNP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e5  isn't an option when the light-squared bishop is already on c4. After  7.Nf3  White is at least slightly better.   6...e6  7.Be3  Be7  8.Qe2  The Velimirovic Attack. I will not dwell on this system for two reasons, which are the same two reasons why it has never been in my repertoire:  1@@EndBracket@@ there is a lot of theory;  2@@EndBracket@@ it is extremely dangerous for Black.  Moreover, nowadays, this is the only move order that leads to this position and usually Black avoids it. The last word is not yet spoken, and Black does not lose by force. But to play this line one must analyze it very well. }
7. Nb3
{ The main move.  7.Be3  doesn't work because the light-squared bishop is hanging on c4.  7...Qxb2  8.Ndb5  Qb4  attacking the bishop, and White has to lose a tempo to retreat it.  9.Bd3  Qa5  10.Bd2  Qd8  11.Nd5  Nxd5  12.exd5  Ne5  and if anyone can be worse, it is White. }
7... e6 8. Bf4
{ The best move in the position.  8.Be3  Qc7  9.f4  a6  10.Bd3  b5  Since White played Bc4-d3, Black is a tempo up compared to the  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Qb6  line. }
8... Ne5 { Of course not  8...Qc7  9.Nb5 } 9. Be2
{ This idea of 8. Bf4 and 9. Be2 was introduced by Ivanchuk in our 1993 Linares game.   Good for Black is  9.Bb5+  Bd7  10.Be3  Qc7  11.Qe2  a6  12.Bxd7+  Nfxd7 }
9... Bd7
{ In my first ever Linares tournament I played  9...a6  , and after  10.Bg3  h5  the game continued  11.h3  Qc7  12.f4  Nc4  13.Bxc4  Qxc4  14.Qf3  h4  15.Bh2  Bd7  16.O-O-O  Rc8  17.Rhe1  b5  18.Qf2  Qc7  19.e5  b4  20.Rd3  dxe5  21.fxe5  bxc3  22.Rxc3  Qxc3  23.bxc3  Ba3+  24.Kd2  Nd5  25.Re4  Rxc3  26.Rg4  O-O  27.Qxh4  Rfc8  28.Nd4  Bb4  29.Ke2  Bb5+  30.Nxb5  Rxc2+  31.Kf3  axb5  32.Rxb4  Nxb4  33.Qxb4  R8c3+  0-1 Ivanchuk-Kramnik, Linares 1993. }
10. Be3 Qc7 11. Qd4
{ Preventing ...Nc4, and if Black continues with ...Rc8 then the a7-pawn is hanging. After  11.f4  Nc4  12.Bxc4  Qxc4  ...Bc6 is coming, and Black is completely fine. }
11... Be7 12. f4 Ng6 { Another option is  12...Nc6  13.Qd2  Na5 } 13. O-O-O O-O
14. f5
{ If  14.Qd2  Rfc8  followed by ...b5-b4 and Black's counterplay is really fast. }
14... Ne5 { With an unclear position. } *

