[White "Lesson 46: Classical Sicilian - Rauzer"]
[Black "Classical Sicilian - Rauzer - 6...Qb6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5
{ The Rauzer is, by far, the main system against the Classical Sicilian. Best by test! Black has to work to equalize, even though some positions are not so clear. I'd say White is always better and I'd recommend  6.Bg5  .We'll see the current state of theory and some new ideas and possible directions for both sides, and I'll tell you which lines could be recommended for Black players. }
6... Qb6
{ This is simply not working. Also,  6...Qa5  is very rare and unsound. It can only be tried at bullet chess where maybe White has premoved  7.Qd2  . After  7.Bb5±  Bd7  8.Nb3  Qd8  Black is losing too many tempi.  9.Qe2  White is much better but also  9.Bxf6  gxf6  10.Qh5  ,though not a usual square for the queen, is strong. }
7. Be3
{ This is a killer. Notice the contrast with the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2np1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bc4  Qb6  line shownhere. Now, there's no loose bishop. }
7... Ng4 8. Nd5 Nxe3 9. fxe3 Qd8 { An admission of failure. } 10. Nb5
{ And the fork on c7 is unstoppable. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 46: Classical Sicilian - Rauzer"]
[Black "Classical Sicilian - Rauzer - 6...g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5
{ The Rauzer is, by far, the main system against the Classical Sicilian. Best by test! Black has to work to equalize, even though some positions are not so clear. I'd say White is always better and I'd recommend  6.Bg5  .We'll see the current state of theory and some new ideas and possible directions for both sides, and I'll tell you which lines could be recommended for Black players. }
6... g6 { Played quite successfully by Dubov. } 7. Bxf6 exf6
{ I don't believe Black can reasonably equalize here. } 8. Bb5 Bd7 9. Qd2 Bg7
10. O-O-O O-O 11. Nb3 { The most direct approach, hitting d6. } 11... Qb6 12.
Qxd6 Be6 13. Qc5
{ I think this settles the issue. I checked this line when preparing the course and can't find anything for Black. }
13... Bh6+ 14. Kb1 Bxb3 15. Qxb6 Bxa2+
{ Or  15...Bxc2+  16.Kxc2  axb6  17.Rd7  with a huge advantage for White. } 16.
Nxa2 axb6 17. Bc4
{ Or  17.c3  . Black has a collection of pawn weaknesses and has to fight for a draw. In my view, this variation puts the line  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2np1n2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...g6  into question. Maybe Dubov has some ideas, or maybe he's just bluffing when he plays it on rapid chess. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 46: Classical Sicilian - Rauzer"]
[Black "Classical Sicilian - Rauzer - 6...e6 7.Qd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5
{ The Rauzer is, by far, the main system against the Classical Sicilian. Best by test! Black has to work to equalize, even though some positions are not so clear. I'd say White is always better and I'd recommend  6.Bg5  .We'll see the current state of theory and some new ideas and possible directions for both sides, and I'll tell you which lines could be recommended for Black players. }
6... e6 7. Qd3
{ This is recently becoming popular and has some venom. It leads, as many Rauzer lines, to unclear sharp positions. White's idea is  7...a6  8.Nxc6  bxc6  9.O-O-O  Be7  10.Qg3  . As we've seen in previous lessons, in some Sicilian systems the queen is very strong on g3. Here it puts pressure on g7 and d6. }
7... Bd7
{ Another idea is  7...Be7  8.O-O-O  O-O  9.f4  or  9.h4  . It's not clear if the presence of the queen on  d3  rather than  d2  benefits White or not, or if Black can exploit it in any way.This 7.Qd3 system needs more practical tests. In any case,  7...Bd7  is my recommendation to Black players. }
8. Ndb5
{ The most challenging.  8.O-O-O  a6  is something we'll examine with the queen on d2. In that case, it's the best option for Black. Here it is even better: the queen is misplaced.  9.f3  doesn't make sense so White should go for  9.f4  but Black can probably play  9...h6  10.Bh4  g5  11.fxg5  Ng4  and get a better version thanthis variation with the white queen on d2. }
8... Nb4
{ A tactical resource to save the pawn, only possible with the white queen on d3. }
9. Qd2 a6
{ White can't take on d6 because of ...Nxc2+ at the end of the line. } 10. Bxf6
gxf6 11. Nd4 h5
{ With a good version of typical Rauzer positions - White has wasted many tempi with his knight and queen. }
*

