{ This leads by force to an inferior endgame for Black to defend, which is especially sad considering he has played a Sicilian, not a solid opening such as Caro-Kann or Petroff. }
11... dxe5 12. Qxe5 Qb6 13. Be3 Ng4
{ Things would be even worse if Black didn't have this. } 14. Bxb6 Nxe5 15. Bc7
Ng4 16. Bg3
{ Black is just worse and has to defend an inferior endgame. He still needs to finish his development, whereas White enjoys full development and the d-file. A possible continuation is  16...f5  17.Be2  stopping ...f4. }
