{ Now the bishop can't retreat with  11.Be3  due to  11...Ng4  and  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2bpp1/3ppn1p/6B1/3QP2P/2N5/PPP2PP1/2KR1B1R w - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Bd2  is odd. }
11. e5
{ This leads by force to an inferior endgame for Black to defend, which is especially sad considering he has played a Sicilian, not a solid opening such as Caro-Kann or Petroff. }
11... hxg5 { This leads to another inferior endgame. } 12. exd6 Qxd6
{ Black has to go for the queen trade to avoid being checkmated on the h-file. }
13. Qxd6 Bxd6 14. Rxd6 gxh4 15. Rxh4
{ White has some pleasant initiative and Black is only fighting for a draw. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 46: Classical Sicilian - Rauzer"]
[Black "Classical Sicilian - Rauzer - 6...e6 7.Qd2 Be7 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5
{ The Rauzer is, by far, the main system against the Classical Sicilian. Best by test! Black has to work to equalize, even though some positions are not so clear. I'd say White is always better and I'd recommend  6.Bg5  .We'll see the current state of theory and some new ideas and possible directions for both sides, and I'll tell you which lines could be recommended for Black players. }
6... e6 7. Qd2
{ Black doesn't have many options here, and I won't stop at any possibility. I'll just cover the most important lines, focusing on the variations and plans I consider most principled. Note Black can't play  7...Bd7  here  @@StartBracket@@which wasmy recommendation against 7.Qd3@@EndBracket@@ due to  8.Ndb5  and the d6-pawn falls.   Also,  7...h6  is not viable. After  8.Bxf6  the recapture  8...gxf6  is forced and Black has wasted a tempo with the h-pawn, whereas  8...Qxf6  runs into  9.Ndb5  Qd8  10.O-O-O  .   7...Qb6  is possible and White has a choice between  8.Nb3  and the ending after  8.O-O-O  followed by the massive trade on d4, which is very unpleasant for Black. }
7... Be7
{ This used to be my favorite move in the 90s, before I switched to  7...a6  . Those were simpler times without deep computer analysis. I have a very strong idea to challenge this line. I'd almost say it is a refutation. }
8. O-O-O O-O
{ I started out by playing this, but then I got concerned about  9.Nb3  , a move I faced against Ivanchuk in a crazy game in Monaco. That is a serious line, as it is the main move  9.f4  Nxd4  10.Qxd4  Qa5  . I don't trust this as a Black player. I feel White always has different ways to pose problems. }
9. h4
{ On the other hand,  9.f4  involves a lot of memorizing @@StartBracket@@Black has many possible replies@@EndBracket@@ and I believe  9.h4  is a clear-cut way to obtain an advantage. }
9... h6
{ The critical test. Actually, it's quite hard to find a move for Black. We have seenhere that trading on d4 leads to very sad endgames. }
10. Nxc6
{ Again, retreating the bishop was not an option. Black would love to trade it for his knight after  10.Be3  Ng4  . Fortunately for White, there's a tactical solution to get an advantage. }
10... bxc6 11. e5 dxe5
{ 11...hxg5  12.exd6  is a worse version ofthis line because Black's queenside structure has been damaged. }
12. Bxh6 { A recent discovery made by engines. } 12... Qxd2+
{ This leads to another very sad endgame. } 13. Bxd2 Rd8 14. Re1 Bc5 15. f3
{ White's advantage might not be huge, but his structure is much better and that secures some long-term risk-free pressure. No Sicilian Rauzer player would like to play this endgame with the black pieces. }
*

