[White "Lesson 46: Classical Sicilian - Rauzer"]
[Black "Classical Sicilian - Rauzer - 6...e6 7.Qd2 a6 8.O-O-O h6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5
{ The Rauzer is, by far, the main system against the Classical Sicilian. Best by test! Black has to work to equalize, even though some positions are not so clear. I'd say White is always better and I'd recommend  6.Bg5  .We'll see the current state of theory and some new ideas and possible directions for both sides, and I'll tell you which lines could be recommended for Black players. }
6... e6 7. Qd2
{ Black doesn't have many options here, and I won't stop at any possibility. I'll just cover the most important lines, focusing on the variations and plans I consider most principled. Note Black can't play  7...Bd7  here  @@StartBracket@@which wasmy recommendation against 7.Qd3@@EndBracket@@ due to  8.Ndb5  and the d6-pawn falls.   Also,  7...h6  is not viable. After  8.Bxf6  the recapture  8...gxf6  is forced and Black has wasted a tempo with the h-pawn, whereas  8...Qxf6  runs into  9.Ndb5  Qd8  10.O-O-O  .   7...Qb6  is possible and White has a choice between  8.Nb3  and the ending after  8.O-O-O  followed by the massive trade on d4, which is very unpleasant for Black. }
7... a6 { This is what I'd recommend nowadays. } 8. O-O-O
{ Now  8...Bd7  is the most popular system and, in my opinion, the most interesting line for Black, but I'll show it via the  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2np1n2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bd7  7.Qd2  e6  8.O-O-O  move order. }
8... h6
{ My pet line in the 90s. I won some nice games against Ivanchuk or Hübner. Sadly, White has several ways to get an edge. }
9. Nxc6
{ Also unpleasant is  9.Be3  Be7  and here Kasparov, among others, have played  10.f4  , but I'm always more inclined to play  10.f3  systems.  10...Nxd4  11.Bxd4  b5  and Black struggles to equalize. I've played this with both colors. However, the text is the move that made me stop playing this line. I consider it a refutation. }
9... bxc6 10. Bf4 d5 11. Qe3
{ As seen in other positions, the queen wants to go to g3. } 11... Bb4
{ After  11...Be7  12.Be2  O-O  13.h4  Black has reasons for concern. White has ideas like g4-g5 or Rh3-Rg3. }
12. Be2 { 12.a3  Ba5  is not a problem. } 12... Qa5
{ This has a forcing refutation. } 13. Be5 Bxc3 14. Bxc3 Qxa2 15. Bd3
{ This is killing. Computers give +2 to White. } 15... dxe4 16. Qg3 exd3 17.
Qxg7
{ Black's position is terrible, even if engines manage not to lose directly. }
