[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 46: Classical Sicilian - Rauzer"]
[Black "Classical Sicilian - Rauzer - 6...e6 7.Qd2 a6 8.O-O-O h6 9.Bxf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5
{ The Rauzer is, by far, the main system against the Classical Sicilian. Best by test! Black has to work to equalize, even though some positions are not so clear. I'd say White is always better and I'd recommend  6.Bg5  .We'll see the current state of theory and some new ideas and possible directions for both sides, and I'll tell you which lines could be recommended for Black players. }
6... e6 7. Qd2
{ Black doesn't have many options here, and I won't stop at any possibility. I'll just cover the most important lines, focusing on the variations and plans I consider most principled. Note Black can't play  7...Bd7  here  @@StartBracket@@which wasmy recommendation against 7.Qd3@@EndBracket@@ due to  8.Ndb5  and the d6-pawn falls.   Also,  7...h6  is not viable. After  8.Bxf6  the recapture  8...gxf6  is forced and Black has wasted a tempo with the h-pawn, whereas  8...Qxf6  runs into  9.Ndb5  Qd8  10.O-O-O  .   7...Qb6  is possible and White has a choice between  8.Nb3  and the ending after  8.O-O-O  followed by the massive trade on d4, which is very unpleasant for Black. }
7... a6 { This is what I'd recommend nowadays. } 8. O-O-O
{ Now  8...Bd7  is the most popular system and, in my opinion, the most interesting line for Black, but I'll show it via the  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2np1n2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bd7  7.Qd2  e6  8.O-O-O  move order. }
8... Be7
{ As we'll see, this is a clever move order. I like White's prospects, but I admit it is playable with the black pieces. }
9. Bxf6 { The critical test. } 9... gxf6
{ Black doesn't get enough compensation after  9...Bxf6  . } 10. f4
{ A very complex structure that requires some deep knowledge from both players. The fact that the bishop is already on e7 changes everything. Here there are no ...h5 and ...Bh6 ideas, so White doesn't mind an early trade on f6 without a previous ...h6. }
10... Bd7 11. Kb1 { Thematic. } 11... Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Qc7 13. f5
{ White's standard plan. Note that any ...exf5 or ...e5 willl eventually run into Nd5. }
13... Qc5 14. Qd2
{ Black's main problem is that he can't touch his central pawn structure. The e6-pawn has to cover the d5-square and White will build up some pressure. It's not easy to activate the bishop pair. In general, Black is doomed to passivity.   A possible continuation could be  14...O-O-O  15.Be2  intending Bh5 and forcing  15...h5  . Then Bf3 and Ne2-Nf4 is a typical regroup. The position is full of subtleties and Black struggles to equalize, though his position has some potential. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 46: Classical Sicilian - Rauzer"]
[Black "Classical Sicilian - Rauzer - 6...e6 7.Qd2 a6 8.O-O-O h6 9.f4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5
{ The Rauzer is, by far, the main system against the Classical Sicilian. Best by test! Black has to work to equalize, even though some positions are not so clear. I'd say White is always better and I'd recommend  6.Bg5  .We'll see the current state of theory and some new ideas and possible directions for both sides, and I'll tell you which lines could be recommended for Black players. }
6... e6 7. Qd2
{ Black doesn't have many options here, and I won't stop at any possibility. I'll just cover the most important lines, focusing on the variations and plans I consider most principled. Note Black can't play  7...Bd7  here  @@StartBracket@@which wasmy recommendation against 7.Qd3@@EndBracket@@ due to  8.Ndb5  and the d6-pawn falls.   Also,  7...h6  is not viable. After  8.Bxf6  the recapture  8...gxf6  is forced and Black has wasted a tempo with the h-pawn, whereas  8...Qxf6  runs into  9.Ndb5  Qd8  10.O-O-O  .   7...Qb6  is possible and White has a choice between  8.Nb3  and the ending after  8.O-O-O  followed by the massive trade on d4, which is very unpleasant for Black. }
7... a6 { This is what I'd recommend nowadays. } 8. O-O-O
{ Now  8...Bd7  is the most popular system and, in my opinion, the most interesting line for Black, but I'll show it via the  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2np1n2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bd7  7.Qd2  e6  8.O-O-O  move order. }
8... Be7
{ As we'll see, this is a clever move order. I like White's prospects, but I admit it is playable with the black pieces. }
9. f4
{ 9.f3  Nxd4  10.Qxd4  b5  might be a better version for Black than the main lines where Black's bishop is already on d7, which are not so bad for Black already. }
9... Nxd4
{ 9...Bd7  leads to the main lines, where I consider f3-systems stronger than f4-lines for White. Black can thus transpose to the main lines having skipped the most dangerous setup for White. }
10. Qxd4 b5
{ This used to be very popular. Many top players employed this systems. Eventually, I dropped it and dropped the whole Rauzer. Too much suffering. }
11. Bxf6
{ The strongest, but  11.Be2  Bb7  12.Bf3  is another interesting way of playing. }
11... gxf6 { Forced.  11...Bxf6  12.e5  dxe5  13.Qe4  is killing. } 12. f5
{ This can pose real problems. Instead,  12.e5  d5  leads to terrible complications but Black can navigate them quite well. }
12... Qc7
{ Better than  12...Qa5  13.Kb1  b4  14.Ne2  when White has better prospects after  14...e5  15.Qd2  with ideas like Ng3-Nh5 or a bind on the d5-square. }
13. Be2 Qc5 14. Qxc5
{ This secures a more comfortable ending.  14.Rhf1  can be tried. } 14... dxc5
15. fxe6 { Black can hold with accurate defense. } 15... fxe6
{ Covering the d5-square. } 16. Bh5+ Kf8 17. e5 f5 18. g4
{ Engines hold but Black is at most fighting for a draw. } *

