7. Qd2
{ Here,  7.Qd3  is met by  7...Rc8  and  8.O-O-O  doesn't work so well due to  8...Qa5  threatening ...Nb4 and forcing  9.Bxf6  gxf6=  .A better try is  @@StartFEN@@2rqkb1r/pp1bpppp/2np1n2/6B1/3NP3/2NQ4/PPP2PPP/R3KB1R w KQk - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nb3  a6  9.O-O-O  e6  but nothing that should worry Black.   Anyway, asseen under the traditional move order, I believe Black is fine after  7.Qd3  e6  . }
7... Rc8
{ The best order to play this line. Black can start with  7...Nxd4  8.Qxd4  Qa5  but first, according to theory  9.f4  is better for White, and also the simple  9.Bd2  Rc8  10.f3  transposes, though  10.Bd3  might be even stronger here, preparing against ...Qc5. }
8. f3
{ 8.f4  is good, as usual, but I won't delve into it. I wouldn't recommend this system to Black players and I'm more inclined towards f3-setups with White. Let's keep things simple. }
8... Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Qa5 10. Bd2 { 10.h4!?  is also pleasant for White. } 10... a6
{ Black's idea is to offer a queen trade on c5 and defend an inferior endgame. }
11. Bd3 { An alternative plan worth checking. } 11... Qc5 12. Qxc5 Rxc5 13. b4
{ White's idea is this queenside expansion. } 13... Rc8 14. a4 g6 15. b5
{ Exploiting Black's lack of development. } *

