{ Here,  7.Qd3  is met by  7...Rc8  and  8.O-O-O  doesn't work so well due to  8...Qa5  threatening ...Nb4 and forcing  9.Bxf6  gxf6=  .A better try is  @@StartFEN@@2rqkb1r/pp1bpppp/2np1n2/6B1/3NP3/2NQ4/PPP2PPP/R3KB1R w KQk - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nb3  a6  9.O-O-O  e6  but nothing that should worry Black.   Anyway, asseen under the traditional move order, I believe Black is fine after  7.Qd3  e6  . }
7... a6
{ The only sensible approach, in my opinion, is ...a6 and ...e6. Remember that  7...e6?  is just bad due to  8.Ndb5  . }
8. O-O-O
{ Now  8.Bxf6  gxf6  9.O-O-O  is not the same, as Black hasn't played ...h6 and that changes everything. Not only that saves a tempo, but ...Bh6 is possible in some lines. Both  9...Rc8  or  9...Nxd4  10.Qxd4  Rc8  are fine.   8.f4  e6  transposes to main lines because White has nothing better than  9.O-O-O  . }
8... e6
{ Of course, the most usual move order to reach this position is @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2np1n2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  7.Qd2  a6  8.O-O-O  Bd7  . Here White has two main setups. }
9. f4
{ This may be more dangerous and ambitious, but it also allows Black more counterplay. Many lines are rather direct and complicated. }
9... Be7 { I find this perfectly playable as well. } 10. Nf3
{ The main move. Some players go for  10.Nb3  b5  11.Bxf6  gxf6  12.Kb1  Qb6  but the knight looks better placed on f3 than on b3. }
10... b5 11. Bxf6
{ Again, Black's setup holds tactically. White can't win immediately by pushing  11.e5  due to  11...b4  12.exf6  bxc3  13.Qxc3  gxf6  . We've seen before how Black's counterstrike didn't work with the inclusion of ...h6 Bh4. Here White needs to retreat his bishop.I won't extend myself on the theory, but the position is dynamically balanced. Black's king is stuck in the center, so his rooks are not connected. However, he can play actively on the queenside. }
11... gxf6 12. Kb1 Qb6
{ This is the tabiya of this system. Black intends to play ...b4 and it's important that White can't stop it by playing  13.a3  . This would be premature before Black commits to long castle, because it would only create a hook for Black's queenside attack. }
13. Bd3 { A not-so-direct approach which shouldn't worry Black players. } 13...
b4
{ A standard and already familiar reaction. Black wants to close the center with ...e5 but needs to kick the white knight away from d5 first. }
14. Ne2 h5
{ Artemiev has played  14...a5  15.f5  a4  16.Nf4  Qc5  . Engines claim White has a small plus, but I would rather play this position as Black. There's enough counterplay to keep the balance and Black's king is safer than White's. }
15. f5 { Or  15.Ng3  h4  . } 15... e5 { The e2-knight is out of play. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 46: Classical Sicilian - Rauzer"]
[Black "Classical Sicilian - Rauzer - Main Line 9.f4 Be7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5
{ The Rauzer is, by far, the main system against the Classical Sicilian. Best by test! Black has to work to equalize, even though some positions are not so clear. I'd say White is always better and I'd recommend  6.Bg5  .We'll see the current state of theory and some new ideas and possible directions for both sides, and I'll tell you which lines could be recommended for Black players. }
6... Bd7
{ Lately, this move order has been employed to reach the main lines, when in the past the usual order was  6...e6  7.Qd2  a6  8.O-O-O  Bd7  . One point could be to avoid sidelines like  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2np1n2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  7.Qd3  . }
7. Qd2
{ Here,  7.Qd3  is met by  7...Rc8  and  8.O-O-O  doesn't work so well due to  8...Qa5  threatening ...Nb4 and forcing  9.Bxf6  gxf6=  .A better try is  @@StartFEN@@2rqkb1r/pp1bpppp/2np1n2/6B1/3NP3/2NQ4/PPP2PPP/R3KB1R w KQk - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nb3  a6  9.O-O-O  e6  but nothing that should worry Black.   Anyway, asseen under the traditional move order, I believe Black is fine after  7.Qd3  e6  . }
7... a6
{ The only sensible approach, in my opinion, is ...a6 and ...e6. Remember that  7...e6?  is just bad due to  8.Ndb5  . }
8. O-O-O
{ Now  8.Bxf6  gxf6  9.O-O-O  is not the same, as Black hasn't played ...h6 and that changes everything. Not only that saves a tempo, but ...Bh6 is possible in some lines. Both  9...Rc8  or  9...Nxd4  10.Qxd4  Rc8  are fine.   8.f4  e6  transposes to main lines because White has nothing better than  9.O-O-O  . }
8... e6
{ Of course, the most usual move order to reach this position is @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2np1n2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  7.Qd2  a6  8.O-O-O  Bd7  . Here White has two main setups. }
9. f4
{ This may be more dangerous and ambitious, but it also allows Black more counterplay. Many lines are rather direct and complicated. }
9... Be7 { I find this perfectly playable as well. } 10. Nf3
{ The main move. Some players go for  10.Nb3  b5  11.Bxf6  gxf6  12.Kb1  Qb6  but the knight looks better placed on f3 than on b3. }
10... b5 11. Bxf6
{ Again, Black's setup holds tactically. White can't win immediately by pushing  11.e5  due to  11...b4  12.exf6  bxc3  13.Qxc3  gxf6  . We've seen before how Black's counterstrike didn't work with the inclusion of ...h6 Bh4. Here White needs to retreat his bishop.I won't extend myself on the theory, but the position is dynamically balanced. Black's king is stuck in the center, so his rooks are not connected. However, he can play actively on the queenside. }
11... gxf6 12. Kb1 Qb6
{ This is the tabiya of this system. Black intends to play ...b4 and it's important that White can't stop it by playing  13.a3  . This would be premature before Black commits to long castle, because it would only create a hook for Black's queenside attack. }
13. f5
{ The most challenging plan, which at some point put Black's system into question. White will put pressure on e6 by means of g3-Bh3. }
13... O-O-O
{ 13...b4  is weak now:  14.fxe6  fxe6  15.Ne2  and White piles up on the e6-pawn. }
14. g3
{ White has tried many different plans, but this is the most convincing. In any case, any player wishing to employ this system with Black should carefully study other games and ideas. }
14... Kb8 15. fxe6 fxe6 16. Bh3 Na5
{ A new idea that seems to hold and changed the assessment of the whole system. The old theory went  16...Bc8  17.Qe1  Prophylaxis against a quick ...b4 and ...d5.  17...Rhe8  18.Ne2  followed by Rf1 and Nf4, with pressure on the e6-pawn. Black is passive, though it may not be serious. }
17. Nd4
{ White piles up on e6. Trying to stop ...Nc4 by means of  17.b3  is met by  17...b4  18.Ne2  Nb7  . A very nice maneuver. The knight will land on c5, protecting e6 and supporting Black's queenside actions. }
17... b4 18. Nce2 e5
{ This looks ugly, but Black is fine. White's pieces can't take advantage of the holes. }
19. Bxd7 Rxd7 20. Nf5 Nc4 { ...Rc8 is coming next. } 21. Qd5 Rc8 22. Nc1 a5
{ White's f5-knight is great, but Black has plenty of counterplay on the queenside. All in all, Black has enough resources to hold his own in the f4-lines of the Rauzer and can even choose among different systems. }
*

