{ The most accurate. After the immediate  11...b5  12.g4  engines show a big edge for White. Black needs to push his queenside pawns, but also to stop White from getting his ideal g4-h4 pawn formation. }
12. g4
{ This is dangerous. Instead,  12.h4  h6  13.Be3  h5  is an important resource to stop g4. Now Black can go on with his own queenside play.  Note that  @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/1pqbbpp1/p2ppn1p/6B1/3QP2P/2N2P2/PPP3P1/1K1R1B1R w kq - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Bxf6  is not good here. Both the pawn sac  13...Bxf6  and the 'ugly'  13...gxf6  offer Black good prospects. }
12... h5
{ This has to be played. White can't be allowed to push his pawns uncontested.  12...b5  is careless:  13.Be3  O-O  14.g5  Nh5  15.Qd2  Rac8  16.Ne2  or  16.Bh3  and White's attack is faster. One familiar idea is Ne2-Ng3 to challenge Black's knight. }
13. gxh5 { The only logical reply. There are top level games with this. } 13...
Nxh5 { But not  13...Rxh5?  14.h4±  . } 14. Rg1
{ Black's point is  14.Bxe7  Kxe7  . Of course, nobody played like this before engines showed the way. }
14... Bxg5
{ In a rapid game Grischuk-Firouzja, the young Iranian made the instructive mistake  14...Qc5  intending to trade queens, but  15.Qd2  was Sasha's winning prep.  15...Qxg1  loses to  16.Bxe7+-  . }
15. Rxg5 O-O-O { This is how engines play and try to hold Black's position. }
16. Qb4
{ This deserves some research. Instead,  16.Qxd6  Qxd6  17.Rxd6  Bc6  offers Black enough play for the pawn. White's kingside is full of weaknesses. }
16... Bc6 17. a4 { Setting up some potential Nb5 ideas. } 17... Nf4
{ Black's best. } 18. Rxg7 Rxh2
{ Black may very well hold this. Typically in the Rauzer, Black needs to make some accurate @@StartBracket@@only!@@EndBracket@@ moves and if he survives that phase, everything will be fine. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 46: Classical Sicilian - Rauzer"]
[Black "Classical Sicilian - Rauzer - Main Line 9.f3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5
{ The Rauzer is, by far, the main system against the Classical Sicilian. Best by test! Black has to work to equalize, even though some positions are not so clear. I'd say White is always better and I'd recommend  6.Bg5  .We'll see the current state of theory and some new ideas and possible directions for both sides, and I'll tell you which lines could be recommended for Black players. }
6... Bd7
{ Lately, this move order has been employed to reach the main lines, when in the past the usual order was  6...e6  7.Qd2  a6  8.O-O-O  Bd7  . One point could be to avoid sidelines like  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2np1n2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  7.Qd3  . }
7. Qd2
{ Here,  7.Qd3  is met by  7...Rc8  and  8.O-O-O  doesn't work so well due to  8...Qa5  threatening ...Nb4 and forcing  9.Bxf6  gxf6=  .A better try is  @@StartFEN@@2rqkb1r/pp1bpppp/2np1n2/6B1/3NP3/2NQ4/PPP2PPP/R3KB1R w KQk - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nb3  a6  9.O-O-O  e6  but nothing that should worry Black.   Anyway, asseen under the traditional move order, I believe Black is fine after  7.Qd3  e6  . }
7... a6
{ The only sensible approach, in my opinion, is ...a6 and ...e6. Remember that  7...e6?  is just bad due to  8.Ndb5  . }
8. O-O-O
{ Now  8.Bxf6  gxf6  9.O-O-O  is not the same, as Black hasn't played ...h6 and that changes everything. Not only that saves a tempo, but ...Bh6 is possible in some lines. Both  9...Rc8  or  9...Nxd4  10.Qxd4  Rc8  are fine.   8.f4  e6  transposes to main lines because White has nothing better than  9.O-O-O  . }
8... e6
{ Of course, the most usual move order to reach this position is @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2np1n2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  7.Qd2  a6  8.O-O-O  Bd7  . Here White has two main setups. }
9. f3
{ My personal preference. This system is more positional and I'd recommend it because it is objectively stronger and it also makes Black's task more difficult.White's plan is simple: push his kingside pawns while keeping the e4-pawn protected to take the sting out of Black's ... b5-...b4 idea.To be honest, this system convinced me to stay away from the ... e6-...a6 Rauzer lines as Black. Kasparov beat me in a model rapid game in Mainz and that left an impression. }
9... Nxd4
{ Black would do better in trading knights on his terms to disrupt White's setup.  9...b5  10.Nxc6  Bxc6  11.Kb1  Be7  12.h4  illustrates White's simple but effective attacking plan. }
10. Qxd4 Be7 11. Kb1 Qc7
{ The most accurate. After the immediate  11...b5  12.g4  engines show a big edge for White. Black needs to push his queenside pawns, but also to stop White from getting his ideal g4-h4 pawn formation. }
12. Qd2 { This is an interesting approach for White, without forcing matters. }
12... b5 13. h4 { The right push. Here  13.g4  runs into  13...h5  . } 13... h6
14. Be3 h5 { An important resource for Black we've already seen. } 15. Ne2
{ A typical regroup. My impression is that White has an easier game. It's hard to play this position with Black. Castling into a kingside attack doesn't look attractive. }
15... a5 16. Bg5 b4 { Anyway, it's not so easy for White to create threats. }
17. Rc1
{ Sometimes White opens up the queenside taking advantage of the lack of coordination in Black's camp with his king stuck in the center. }
17... Qb7 18. Nf4 Rc8 19. Be2
{ A complicated position where I would definitely pick White, even though it is playable for Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 46: Classical Sicilian - Rauzer"]
[Black "Classical Sicilian - Rauzer - Conclusion"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5
{ All in all, I firmly believe @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1p1b1ppp/p1nppn2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPPQ1PPP/2KR1B1R w kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.f3  is the best practical choice for White players. It offers an easier game where Black struggles to find counterplay.   In contrast, the @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1p1b1ppp/p1nppn2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPPQ1PPP/2KR1B1R w kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.f4  system demands a bigger effort and you may end up studying it for a whole month without finding a way to get an advantage. In general, White can pose problems in the Rauzer.   For Black players I can recommend exploring the ...a6 +...Bd7 system and the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2nppn2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPPQ1PPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...a6  8.O-O-O  Be7  move order.Rauzer is complicated for both sides and can offer winning chances for Black as well, especially in the double-edged positions with Bxf6 gxf6, but it is important to study games and understand the plans and ideas. The player with a better understanding will prevail. }
*

