[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 47: Najdorf - 6th Move Sidelines"]
[Black "Najdorf - 6.h4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. h4
{ This move was quite fashionable a few years ago and many strong players gave it a try. }
6... e5
{ In the 80s and 90s, Kasparov was the main proponent of the Najdorf and he greatly contributed to the development of its opening theory. He normally prefered ...e7-e6, the Scheveningen setup.  Over time, Black players, including Kasparov himself, started liking ...e5 better. The weakening of the d5-square is not something White can easily exploit. }
7. Nb3 Be7 8. Bg5 { This is the only way to justify having played h4. } 8...
Be6 9. Bxf6
{ After ...Be6, White normally takes on f6 right away as Black would otherwise play ...Nbd7 and recapture on f6 with the knight.   After  9.Qd2  Nbd7  followed by ...h6, h4 and Bg5 didn't make sense. }
9... Bxf6 10. g3 Be7 { Preparing ...Nd7. } 11. Bh3
{ After  11.Nd5  Nd7  , the knight on b3 is misplaced - it's 4 moves away from the d5-square. }
11... O-O 12. Bxe6 fxe6 13. Qg4 Rf6
{ Black protects the e6-pawn without problems. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 47: Najdorf - 6th Move Sidelines"]
[Black "Najdorf - 6.h4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. h4
{ This move was quite fashionable a few years ago and many strong players gave it a try. }
6... e5
{ In the 80s and 90s, Kasparov was the main proponent of the Najdorf and he greatly contributed to the development of its opening theory. He normally prefered ...e7-e6, the Scheveningen setup.  Over time, Black players, including Kasparov himself, started liking ...e5 better. The weakening of the d5-square is not something White can easily exploit. }
7. Nb3 Be6
{ This is more ambitious than 7...Be7.   Black wants to meet  8.Bg5  with  8...Nbd7  . }
8. f4 g6
{ This is a difficult move to find over the board, but Black shouldn't fear the endgame after  9.fxe5  dxe5  10.Qxd8+  Kxd8=  . }
9. Be2 Nc6 10. g4
{ After  10.h5  Be7  11.hxg6  fxg6=+  , Black is the one who will benefit from the opening of the f-file. }
10... h6
{ This move leads to a strategically complex position. Black intends to meet  11.g5  with  11...hxg5  12.fxg5  Nh5=+  , with a solid blockade on the light squares. }
11. f5 gxf5 12. gxf5 Bxb3 13. axb3 Qb6
{ White is strategically better because he controls the center and has the bishop pair but at the same time, his king is in the middle and it's difficult for him to finish development. This is playable for Black, of course, but 10...exf4 is an easier solution. }
*

