[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. h4
{ This move was quite fashionable a few years ago and many strong players gave it a try. }
6... e5
{ In the 80s and 90s, Kasparov was the main proponent of the Najdorf and he greatly contributed to the development of its opening theory. He normally prefered ...e7-e6, the Scheveningen setup.  Over time, Black players, including Kasparov himself, started liking ...e5 better. The weakening of the d5-square is not something White can easily exploit. }
7. Nb3 Be6
{ This is more ambitious than 7...Be7.   Black wants to meet  8.Bg5  with  8...Nbd7  . }
8. f4 g6
{ This is a difficult move to find over the board, but Black shouldn't fear the endgame after  9.fxe5  dxe5  10.Qxd8+  Kxd8=  . }
9. Be2 Nc6 10. g4
{ After  10.h5  Be7  11.hxg6  fxg6=+  , Black is the one who will benefit from the opening of the f-file. }
10... exf4 11. g5 { 11.Bxf4  d5= } 11... f3
{ This is a vital resource. White would be somewhat better after  11...Nd7  12.Bxf4  when Black doesn't have  12...Nde5  . }
12. Bxf3 Nd7
{ The position is very double-edged and Black will have winning chances too - exactly what a Najdorf player wants!   In conclusion, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.h4  e5  7.Nb3  Be7  is a solid equalizer for Black but  7...Be6  is more interesting if Black wants to play a more complicated game. }
