[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 47: Najdorf - 6th Move Sidelines"]
[Black "Najdorf - 6.a3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. a3
{ On the top level, fighting for an opening advantage against the Najdorf is really difficult: it requires outstanding preparation and White has to take risks. Therefore they try to surprise their opponents in the opening with moves like 6.a3 and they would only play such a variation in 1 or 2 games. Carlsen also tried it with White. }
6... e5 7. Nf5
{ It's quite clear that White doesn't gain an advantage here but at least the play will be original. }
7... d5 8. Bg5 d4 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. Nd5 Qc6
{ After  10...Qd8  , as Wojtaszek played against Carlsen, it's unclear if Black can equalize and White scored well in practice. Their game went  11.Qg4  Bxf5  12.Qxf5  Bd6  13.h4  Nc6  14.Bc4  b5  15.Bb3  Ne7  16.Qg4  O-O  17.Rh3  Nxd5  18.Bxd5  Ra7  19.Rg3  Qf6  20.a4  Bb4+  21.Kf1  bxa4  22.Rxa4  a5  23.Ra1  Rc7  24.Bb3  Ra8  25.Kg1  Bf8  26.Qh5  g6  27.Qg4  Ra6  28.h5  Qf4  29.Qe2  Qf6  30.Qb5  Qc6  31.Qxe5  Re7  32.Qf4  a4  33.Bd5  Qc7  34.Qd2  Qb6  35.Ra2  Rc7  36.Rf3  Qb4  37.Qe2  Rb6  38.hxg6  hxg6  39.g3  Kg7  40.Kg2  Rd7  41.Qd1  Rf6  42.Rxf6  Kxf6  43.c3  dxc3  44.Rxa4  1-0 Carlsen @@StartBracket@@2840@@EndBracket@@ - Wojtaszek  @@StartBracket@@2750@@EndBracket@@, Wijk aan Zee 2017. }
11. c4 g6 12. Nxd4 exd4 13. Qxd4 f6
{ This position was reached on the high-level multiple times and Black scores well. White's only trump is the d5-knight but Black can quite easily play around it or exchange it. }
*

