[White "Lesson 47: Najdorf - 6th Move Sidelines"]
[Black "Najdorf - 6.Nb3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Nb3
{ 6.Nb3 makes some sense, anticipating ...e5. } 6... e6 7. a4 Nc6
{ 7...b6  8.g4  could be unpleasant for Black. } 8. Be2 { 8.a5  d5= } 8... b6
{ Black has a great Scheveningen because normally, he needs ...Bd7 to protect the c6-knight. In this case, White only helped us by voluntarily removing his knight from d4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 47: Najdorf - 6th Move Sidelines"]
[Black "Najdorf - 6.Nb3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Nb3
{ 6.Nb3 makes some sense, anticipating ...e5. } 6... e6 7. g4
{ The only critical move. On the top level, Svidler and Wei Yi seem to like this position from White's side and Caruana, Nakamura and Anand have also tried it. }
7... b5 8. a3 { 8.g5  b4   8...Nfd7  is also possible  9.gxf6  bxc3= } 8... Bb7
9. Qe2 Be7 10. g5 Nfd7 11. h4 Nc6
{ With counterplay. If White castles queenside, there is ...Ne5-c4 and against kingside castling, he can try to play ...h6.  I would already prefer Black since he managed to develop his pieces so harmoniously whereas White still has to justify his somewhat unnatural setup.  Unsurprisingly, 6.Nb3 is no threat to the Najdorf. }
*

