[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 47: Najdorf - 6th Move Sidelines"]
[Black "Najdorf - 6.f4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. f4 e5
{ 6...Nbd7  7.Be2  g6  is quite complicated but after 6...e5, I don't see the slightest problem for Black. }
7. Nf3 Nbd7 { There is no g2-g4 now. } 8. a4
{ Both 8... Be7 and 8...Qc7 are playable for Black. 8...Be7 is by far the main move but I quite like 8...Qc7, which is more complex. }
8... Be7 9. Bd3 O-O 10. O-O Nc5
{ 10...exf4  11.Bxf4  Qb6+  12.Kh1  Qb2∞  is by no means refuted yet so if you're feeling adventurous, you can take the pawn on b2! }
11. Kh1
{ 11.Qe1  Re8  12.Kh1  allows  12...d5=  with very good play for Black. } 11...
exf4
{ 11...d5  12.Nxe5   12.fxe5  Nfxe4=  Ncxe4  13.Be3  is playable for both sides. }
12. Bxf4 Bg4 13. Qe1 Rc8 14. h3 Bh5 15. Nh4 Bg6
{ The bishop looks somewhat strange on g6 but Black has good pressure on the e4-pawn, which is arguably weaker than the d6-pawn. Black can take on d3 at any given moment.  Black has many ways of equalizing and the positions are somewhat dry, which is why I prefer 8...Qc7 over 8...Be7. }
