1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. f4 e5
{ 6...Nbd7  7.Be2  g6  is quite complicated but after 6...e5, I don't see the slightest problem for Black. }
7. Nf3 Nbd7 { There is no g2-g4 now. } 8. a4
{ Both 8... Be7 and 8...Qc7 are playable for Black. 8...Be7 is by far the main move but I quite like 8...Qc7, which is more complex. }
8... Qc7 { This move prevents Bc4. } 9. Bd3 Be7 10. O-O
{ 10.a5  O-O  11.O-O  Nc5  transposes to the text move. } 10... O-O
{ Black plans ...Nc5, ...Bd7 and ... Re8. This way of playing is not so popular for Black but frankly, I don't see anything wrong with it. }
11. Kh1 { 11.a5  Nc5∞ } 11... Nc5 12. Qe1 Re8 { Black is preparing ...d5. } 13.
Be3 { 13.fxe5  dxe5  14.Qg3  Be6!=+ } 13... exf4 14. Bxf4 Bd7
{ White could potentially start a kingside attack but Black has good pressure against the e4-pawn. 8...Qc7 is a very simple and reliable solution for Black. }
