1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. a4
{ This is an interesting move for White and it has been played by Carlsen, Firouzja, Anand, Giri and other top players. White is always in full control and Black must be accurate to equalize. }
6... e5
{ 6...e6  7.Be2  transposes to the Classical Scheveningen system @@StartBracket@@with O-O for White@@EndBracket@@, which is a respected system and more importantly, not all Najdorf players are willing or able to play the Scheveningen with Black. }
7. Nf3 Be7 8. Bg5 Be6
{ As we have seen before, Black wants to play ...Nbd7 and ...h6 so that he can recapture on f6 with the knight. In other words, ...Be6 practically forces White to take on f6.   After  8...Nbd7  9.Bc4  , the bishop is strong on the a2-g8 diagonal and White has some plus. }
9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Nd5 Nd7 11. Bc4 Rc8
{ If White manages to stabilise his position, with b3 and O-O, he could be somewhat better: he controls the d5-square and the bishop is well placed on the a2-g8 diagonal. It's difficult for White to avoid simplifications, though. }
12. b3 O-O 13. O-O Rc5
{ Black prepares ...b5, fighting for control over the dark squares. } 14. Qd3
Qc8
{ This is an important move. Black still wants to play ...b5, when after cxb5 axb5 Bxb5, the c2-pawn will be hanging. ...Qd8 also makes room for ...Bd8. }
15. Nd2 Bxd5 16. Bxd5 Nb6
{ The position is dead equal and I find this solution, 12...O-O followed by 14...Qc8!, much more convincing than 12...Nb6. }
