1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Qd3
{ 6.Qd3 is clearly better than 6.Qe2 and 6.Qf3. It became quite fashionable lately, Carlsen and Van Foreest played it too, and it's a fresh approach.  Still, I strongly doubt White can objectively fight for an advantage with 6.Qd3. Black has a wide range of options. }
6... e5 { 6...e5 is not so great. } 7. Nf5 d5
{ This is the standard reaction to Nf5 but it doesn't work with the white queen on d3. }
8. Nxd5 Nxd5 9. exd5
{ The f5-knight is protected so Black simply blundered a pawn. } *

