[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 48: Najdorf 6.Bd3, 6.g3 & 6.Be2"]
[Black "Najdorf: 6.Bd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf requires a lot of concrete theory in most lines White can choose. This also applies to White. White must be aware of many forced lines Black can initiate in order to hope to emerge with an advantage, and indeed not lose themselves.   The point of this move is to control the b5 square and later support the ...b5 push, thematic to Black's queenside counterplay. It also acts as something of a waiting move. }
6. Bd3
{ This started to be a frequent guest in tournament play at the top level, and Black has a wide choice of perfectly playable options against this choice. One benefit of choosing this for White is that you can most often just get a game since theory isn't as developed. }
6... e5
{ Maybe objectively the best move which offers Black a reliable position.  6...e6  is good if you enjoy the Scheveningen structures and after  7.f4  Qc7  there is a lot of theory involved in this line, which can be reached after many move orders. }
7. Nde2 Be7 { Simply developing. } 8. O-O O-O 9. f4
{ Looks ambitious, but doesn't really lead anywhere. } 9... b5
{ Black just ignores this f-pawn and continues with their queenside play. } 10.
Ng3 Nbd7
{ The engine's preference.  10...Nc6  is also fine.  11.h3  exf4  12.Bxf4  Ne5  is a typical Sicilian position - equal but double-edged. }
11. Nf5 Re8 { Making space for the bishop to play a defensive role. } 12. Qf3
Bf8 13. Qg3 g6
{ This is a very principled line which seems to stop White's initiative. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 48: Najdorf 6.Bd3, 6.g3 & 6.Be2"]
[Black "Najdorf: 6.Bd3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf requires a lot of concrete theory in most lines White can choose. This also applies to White. White must be aware of many forced lines Black can initiate in order to hope to emerge with an advantage, and indeed not lose themselves.   The point of this move is to control the b5 square and later support the ...b5 push, thematic to Black's queenside counterplay. It also acts as something of a waiting move. }
6. Bd3
{ This started to be a frequent guest in tournament play at the top level, and Black has a wide choice of perfectly playable options against this choice. One benefit of choosing this for White is that you can most often just get a game since theory isn't as developed. }
6... e5
{ Maybe objectively the best move which offers Black a reliable position.  6...e6  is good if you enjoy the Scheveningen structures and after  7.f4  Qc7  there is a lot of theory involved in this line, which can be reached after many move orders. }
7. Nde2 Be7 { Simply developing. } 8. O-O O-O 9. Ng3
{ Probably the best try for an advantage. } 9... Be6 { Logical development. }
10. Nd5
{ 10.f4  White wants to play f5 here, so we take.  10...exf4  11.Bxf4  Nbd7  Here it's pretty equal without the need for a queenside attack with ...b5. }
10... Nxd5
{ 10...Bxd5  is a popular choice where there were many games continuing  11.exd5  g6  12.Bh6  Re8  13.c4  Nbd7  14.Rc1  including Nakamura-MVL, Anand-Keymer and Nepomniachtchi-Wojtaszek. White has the two bishops and with f4 potential, there is some attacking potential. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 48: Najdorf 6.Bd3, 6.g3 & 6.Be2"]
[Black "Najdorf: 6.Bd3 (Alternative: 6...g6 #1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf requires a lot of concrete theory in most lines White can choose. This also applies to White. White must be aware of many forced lines Black can initiate in order to hope to emerge with an advantage, and indeed not lose themselves.   The point of this move is to control the b5 square and later support the ...b5 push, thematic to Black's queenside counterplay. It also acts as something of a waiting move. }
6. Bd3
{ This started to be a frequent guest in tournament play at the top level, and Black has a wide choice of perfectly playable options against this choice. One benefit of choosing this for White is that you can most often just get a game since theory isn't as developed. }
6... g6
{ This is another playable setup for Black if you want to play for a win in a complicated, sharp position. }
7. f3
{ The most flexible and critical option.  7.Be3  perhaps preparing long-castling.  7...Ng4  8.Bg5  h6  9.Bh4  Bg7  10.Be2  g5  11.Bg3  the best move, and all of a sudden it's a well-known theoretical position I will cover in the next lesson, generally considered reliable for Black.   7.O-O  Bg7  Should be nothing for White since the bishop on d3 is not so good, and these variations in the dragon where White castles short are not too dangerous. }
7... Qb6
{ This seems to be doing quite well. I'm not threatening the knight because of Bb5+ but the idea is to prevent the dark-squared bishop from developing by pressurizing b2. }
8. a3
{ This is a very serious move, after which White wants to play Be3 and Black can't take on b2 because of Na4. }
8... Nbd7
{ An important move, otherwise Black might just be worse.  8...Nc6  9.Be3  Qxb2  10.Na4  is not a fun scenario for Black. }
9. Be3
{ Following through with the plan, but now the knight is somewhat pinned. }
9... e5 { Seems to tactically work out for Black. } 10. Nf5 Nc5 11. b4 gxf5
{ Engines assess this as complex equality. Very sharp and unclear but it seems like a very interesting way to play for Black. }
*

