[White "Lesson 48: Najdorf 6.Bd3, 6.g3 & 6.Be2"]
[Black "Najdorf: 6.Bd3 (Alternative: 6...g6 #2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf requires a lot of concrete theory in most lines White can choose. This also applies to White. White must be aware of many forced lines Black can initiate in order to hope to emerge with an advantage, and indeed not lose themselves.   The point of this move is to control the b5 square and later support the ...b5 push, thematic to Black's queenside counterplay. It also acts as something of a waiting move. }
6. Bd3
{ This started to be a frequent guest in tournament play at the top level, and Black has a wide choice of perfectly playable options against this choice. One benefit of choosing this for White is that you can most often just get a game since theory isn't as developed. }
6... g6
{ This is another playable setup for Black if you want to play for a win in a complicated, sharp position. }
7. f3
{ The most flexible and critical option.  7.Be3  perhaps preparing long-castling.  7...Ng4  8.Bg5  h6  9.Bh4  Bg7  10.Be2  g5  11.Bg3  the best move, and all of a sudden it's a well-known theoretical position I will cover in the next lesson, generally considered reliable for Black.   7.O-O  Bg7  Should be nothing for White since the bishop on d3 is not so good, and these variations in the dragon where White castles short are not too dangerous. }
7... Qb6
{ This seems to be doing quite well. I'm not threatening the knight because of Bb5+ but the idea is to prevent the dark-squared bishop from developing by pressurizing b2. }
8. Nb3
{ A tamer idea that should again lead to complex position with chances for both sides. }
8... Bg7 9. Bg5 { The engine's choice. } 9... Be6 10. Qd2 Nc6
{ Aiming to long-castle. } 11. O-O-O Rc8
{ Bringing the rook to the open file. } 12. Kb1 O-O 13. h4 h5
{ Clamping down on the kingside.  13...Ne5  might also work since after  14.h5  Nxh5  there seems to be no clear mate, and if Black can defend, they shouldn't be worse. }
14. g4 Ne5
{ This seems dynamically equal as Black has their chances with the f-pawn hanging and a potential exchange sacrifice on tap. }
