[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 48: Najdorf 6.Bd3, 6.g3 & 6.Be2"]
[Black "Najdorf: 6.Bd3 (Alternative: 6...Nc6 #2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf requires a lot of concrete theory in most lines White can choose. This also applies to White. White must be aware of many forced lines Black can initiate in order to hope to emerge with an advantage, and indeed not lose themselves.   The point of this move is to control the b5 square and later support the ...b5 push, thematic to Black's queenside counterplay. It also acts as something of a waiting move. }
6. Bd3
{ This started to be a frequent guest in tournament play at the top level, and Black has a wide choice of perfectly playable options against this choice. One benefit of choosing this for White is that you can most often just get a game since theory isn't as developed. }
6... Nc6
{ A very playable option that isn't very popular, but I'm not sure why. } 7.
Nxc6 { The more critical try in this variation. } 7... bxc6 8. b3
{ This is White's point, hoping to have an unrivaled bishop on the long diagonal. White has tried this recently since the engines give White a small plus for some reason. }
8... g6 { Black simply neutralizes the bishop and has a fine game. } 9. Bb2 Bg7
10. Qd2
{ 10.Na4  would be a good move if not for  10...Qa5+  11.Bc3  Qg5  when Black is doing fine with the active queen. }
10... Nd7
{ An important idea, activating the bishop and pinning White's knight. } 11.
Na4
{ White has nothing better than to alleviate the pin immediately.  11.h4  h5  stays solid for Black. }
11... Bxb2 12. Nxb2 Nc5 13. h4 h5
{ I don't understand why this should be better for White. It seems like an equal position with some play left, but Black is solid. The king should probably stay in the center for now since castling can be dangerous. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 48: Najdorf 6.Bd3, 6.g3 & 6.Be2"]
[Black "Najdorf: 6.g3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf requires a lot of concrete theory in most lines White can choose. This also applies to White. White must be aware of many forced lines Black can initiate in order to hope to emerge with an advantage, and indeed not lose themselves.   The point of this move is to control the b5 square and later support the ...b5 push, thematic to Black's queenside counterplay. It also acts as something of a waiting move. }
6. g3
{ This is no exception to the general rule that mostly the g3 systems are harmless, but it's definitely playable. There's some theory but it's not so forcing. It leads to a more positional game. }
6... e5
{ The best move, leading to strategically complex play.  6...g6  might not fully equalize after  7.Bg2  Bg7  8.h3  O-O  9.O-O  Nc6  10.Be3  Rb8  11.Nd5  where there have been some games of Carlsen, and it's a very reliable system for White with h3 / Be3. White has a pleasant position which is slightly better for White. }
7. Nf3
{ This is played sometimes, but a little strange, with the idea of Nh4-f5. But we're not too worried. }
7... Be7 { Aiming to castle quickly as there's no pawn-storm coming. } 8. Nh4
O-O
{ 8...g6  9.Nge2  is a clever positional trap for White to maneuver the knight to e3, with a permanent hold on d5. }
9. Bg2 g6
{ 9...Bg4  is also quite playable when after  10.Bf3  Bxf3  11.Qxf3  Nc6  12.Nf5  Nd4  13.Nxd4  exd4  14.Ne2  the position is equal. }
10. O-O Be6 { Typical play. } 11. a4
{ 11.Bh6  Re8  is no big deal, especially with the ...Ng4 threat. } 11... Nbd7
{ Here it's not so clear what the knight is doing on h4, so this tends to buy Black some time to drum up their own play. }
12. Nf3 { A sad retreat. } 12... Rc8
{ Black's weakened kingside position probably isn't worth two tempi and Black is fine. }
*

