[White "Lesson 48: Najdorf 6.Bd3, 6.g3 & 6.Be2"]
[Black "Najdorf: 6.g3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf requires a lot of concrete theory in most lines White can choose. This also applies to White. White must be aware of many forced lines Black can initiate in order to hope to emerge with an advantage, and indeed not lose themselves.   The point of this move is to control the b5 square and later support the ...b5 push, thematic to Black's queenside counterplay. It also acts as something of a waiting move. }
6. g3
{ This is no exception to the general rule that mostly the g3 systems are harmless, but it's definitely playable. There's some theory but it's not so forcing. It leads to a more positional game. }
6... e5
{ The best move, leading to strategically complex play.  6...g6  might not fully equalize after  7.Bg2  Bg7  8.h3  O-O  9.O-O  Nc6  10.Be3  Rb8  11.Nd5  where there have been some games of Carlsen, and it's a very reliable system for White with h3 / Be3. White has a pleasant position which is slightly better for White. }
7. Nb3
{ The main move and most natural square for the knight for now, even though myself I prefer Nde2. }
7... Be7 { Trying to castle. } 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O
{ 9.a4  Nc6  and the knight will head comfortably to b4. } 9... Be6
{ This is the most stable, natural option. } 10. Re1 { A typical move. } 10...
Qc7
