{ This is the most stable, natural option. } 10. Re1 { A typical move. } 10...
Qc7
{ When preparing this lesson, I thought ...b5 would be the most accurate way to directly equalize, but I think this is an even better move-order - staying flexible.  10...b5  is premature and dubious after  11.a4  b4  12.Nd5  Nxd5  13.exd5  Bf5  14.a5  exposes the b4 pawn as a weakness. }
11. a4 { White plays against Black's ...b5 idea. } 11... Rc8
{ The new idea I found, waiting with my knight on b8.  11...Nc6  is less accurate on account of  12.Nd5  Bxd5  13.exd5  when the knight cannot make use of b4 in view of c3. }
12. Nd2 Nc6
{ This is my idea - when the knight starts its route to e3, we can jump in ourselves. }
13. Nf1 Nb4
{ Or even  13...Nd4  . Black now has great control over the d5 square, and in order to remove our knight, he must move his own. }
