[Black "Najdorf: 6.g3 (Alternative: 9...b5 #1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf requires a lot of concrete theory in most lines White can choose. This also applies to White. White must be aware of many forced lines Black can initiate in order to hope to emerge with an advantage, and indeed not lose themselves.   The point of this move is to control the b5 square and later support the ...b5 push, thematic to Black's queenside counterplay. It also acts as something of a waiting move. }
6. g3
{ This is no exception to the general rule that mostly the g3 systems are harmless, but it's definitely playable. There's some theory but it's not so forcing. It leads to a more positional game. }
6... e5
{ The best move, leading to strategically complex play.  6...g6  might not fully equalize after  7.Bg2  Bg7  8.h3  O-O  9.O-O  Nc6  10.Be3  Rb8  11.Nd5  where there have been some games of Carlsen, and it's a very reliable system for White with h3 / Be3. White has a pleasant position which is slightly better for White. }
7. Nde2 { I played this myself against Giri in London in a classical game. }
7... Be7
{ 7...Be6  A new setup at the time of our game.  8.Bg2  h5  Threatening h4.  9.Bg5  Nbd7  10.Qd2  Be7  In general is another fine setup. There are many ways to handle this g3 setup, but you do sort of have to be careful to avoid getting slowly outplayed. }
8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O
{ 9.a4  Nc6  Here the b4 square is very tasty for the black knight. Often White waits for Black to play ...Nbd7 before playing a4. }
9... b5 10. a4
{ This move-order isn't quite right since after some simplifications, Black's structure is quite solid. }
10... b4 { Controlling the c3 square, which is annoying for White. } 11. Nd5
Nxd5 12. Qxd5 Ra7
{ a4 ...b4 is in Black's favor and White now has as many weaknesses as Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 48: Najdorf 6.Bd3, 6.g3 & 6.Be2"]
[Black "Najdorf: 6.g3 (Alternative: 9...b5 #2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf requires a lot of concrete theory in most lines White can choose. This also applies to White. White must be aware of many forced lines Black can initiate in order to hope to emerge with an advantage, and indeed not lose themselves.   The point of this move is to control the b5 square and later support the ...b5 push, thematic to Black's queenside counterplay. It also acts as something of a waiting move. }
6. g3
{ This is no exception to the general rule that mostly the g3 systems are harmless, but it's definitely playable. There's some theory but it's not so forcing. It leads to a more positional game. }
6... e5
{ The best move, leading to strategically complex play.  6...g6  might not fully equalize after  7.Bg2  Bg7  8.h3  O-O  9.O-O  Nc6  10.Be3  Rb8  11.Nd5  where there have been some games of Carlsen, and it's a very reliable system for White with h3 / Be3. White has a pleasant position which is slightly better for White. }
7. Nde2 { I played this myself against Giri in London in a classical game. }
7... Be7
{ 7...Be6  A new setup at the time of our game.  8.Bg2  h5  Threatening h4.  9.Bg5  Nbd7  10.Qd2  Be7  In general is another fine setup. There are many ways to handle this g3 setup, but you do sort of have to be careful to avoid getting slowly outplayed. }
8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O
{ 9.a4  Nc6  Here the b4 square is very tasty for the black knight. Often White waits for Black to play ...Nbd7 before playing a4. }
9... b5 10. Nd5 { The usual way to press. is to meet ...b5 with Nd5. } 10...
Nbd7
{ I tried to prove an advantage for White after this move, but could not. Engines agree that it's equal from here on out.  10...Nxd5  11.Qxd5  Ra7  12.Be3  Be6  13.Qd2  Maybe at the end of the day Black equalizes, but White has some ideas with f4, a4 and Black needs to prove equality. }
11. Nec3 Nxd5
{ Initiating some central exchanges, and Black is well-suited to continue to develop around, and put pressure on White's center. }
12. Nxd5 Nf6 13. Nxf6+
{ If White doesn't take, Black will simply continue with ...Bb7 and continue pressurizing the center, eventually ...d5 will become possible. }
13... Bxf6 14. Be3 Be6
{ Nominally White may be better because of the d6 pawn but with such reduced material, and the fact that Black can easily protect d6 offers White very little. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 48: Najdorf 6.Bd3, 6.g3 & 6.Be2"]
[Black "Najdorf: 6.g3 (Alternative: 9...b5 #3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf requires a lot of concrete theory in most lines White can choose. This also applies to White. White must be aware of many forced lines Black can initiate in order to hope to emerge with an advantage, and indeed not lose themselves.   The point of this move is to control the b5 square and later support the ...b5 push, thematic to Black's queenside counterplay. It also acts as something of a waiting move. }
6. g3
{ This is no exception to the general rule that mostly the g3 systems are harmless, but it's definitely playable. There's some theory but it's not so forcing. It leads to a more positional game. }
6... e5
{ The best move, leading to strategically complex play.  6...g6  might not fully equalize after  7.Bg2  Bg7  8.h3  O-O  9.O-O  Nc6  10.Be3  Rb8  11.Nd5  where there have been some games of Carlsen, and it's a very reliable system for White with h3 / Be3. White has a pleasant position which is slightly better for White. }
7. Nb3
{ The main move and most natural square for the knight for now, even though myself I prefer Nde2. }
7... Be7 { Trying to castle. } 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O
{ 9.a4  Nc6  and the knight will head comfortably to b4. } 9... b5
{ This leads to a position where there have been many games, tempting the knight into d5 with some exchanges. }
10. Nd5 Nxd5 11. Qxd5 Ra7
{ Black has good chances to equalize, but it's not so trivial. White has small pressure in the center and positional players would enjoy this grind. }
