[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 48: Najdorf 6.Bd3, 6.g3 & 6.Be2"]
[Black "Najdorf: 6.g3 (Alternative: 6...e6 #1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf requires a lot of concrete theory in most lines White can choose. This also applies to White. White must be aware of many forced lines Black can initiate in order to hope to emerge with an advantage, and indeed not lose themselves.   The point of this move is to control the b5 square and later support the ...b5 push, thematic to Black's queenside counterplay. It also acts as something of a waiting move. }
6. g3
{ This is no exception to the general rule that mostly the g3 systems are harmless, but it's definitely playable. There's some theory but it's not so forcing. It leads to a more positional game. }
6... e6
{ Going into the Scheveningen structures is also, once again, very playable. }
7. Bg2 Qc7
{ 7...Be7  is a little bit risky because White can go for the quick g4 idea.  8.Be3  O-O   8...Qc7  could possibly be an improvement to keep the king in the center and wait and see what White does, to meet g4 with ...h6 or ...Nc6.  9.g4  Nc6  10.g5  Nd7  11.h4  This position is not easy for Black. }
8. Be3 { Another natural choice. } 8... Nc6
{ A conservative choice, stopping g4.  8...b5  9.e5  Bb7  The engines say this is also working tactically. }
9. f4 Be7 10. Qe2 Nxd4
{ Here Black can initiate a known classical sequence which stabilizes for Black. }
11. Bxd4 e5
{ Acheiving central control with tempo, and White won't have a kingside attack anymore. }
12. Be3 b5 { Black is fine here. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 48: Najdorf 6.Bd3, 6.g3 & 6.Be2"]
[Black "Najdorf: 6.g3 (Alternative: 6...e6 #2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf requires a lot of concrete theory in most lines White can choose. This also applies to White. White must be aware of many forced lines Black can initiate in order to hope to emerge with an advantage, and indeed not lose themselves.   The point of this move is to control the b5 square and later support the ...b5 push, thematic to Black's queenside counterplay. It also acts as something of a waiting move. }
6. g3
{ This is no exception to the general rule that mostly the g3 systems are harmless, but it's definitely playable. There's some theory but it's not so forcing. It leads to a more positional game. }
6... e6
{ Going into the Scheveningen structures is also, once again, very playable. }
7. Bg2 Qc7
{ 7...Be7  is a little bit risky because White can go for the quick g4 idea.  8.Be3  O-O   8...Qc7  could possibly be an improvement to keep the king in the center and wait and see what White does, to meet g4 with ...h6 or ...Nc6.  9.g4  Nc6  10.g5  Nd7  11.h4  This position is not easy for Black. }
8. g4
{ The most ambitious try, dissuading Black from castling.  8...Be7  9.a4  Nc6  10.Be3  O-O  Castling is safer than with White's bishop on e2. This time, we have Ne5-c4 ideas. }
8... h6
{ Making White extend further in order to gain more space. We no longer plan to castle kingside. }
9. h4 Nc6 10. g5
{ White has nothing better than to continue gaining space, but it's not clear this will benefit White. }
10... hxg5 11. hxg5 Rxh1+
{ Exchanging the rooks benefits Black, with less White attacking forces on the kingside. }
12. Bxh1 Nd7 13. g6
{ Must be the challenging move, hitting Black's light-squares.  13.f4  Nxd4  14.Qxd4  b5  leads to an unusual position - normally there are rooks on the h-file, but the absence of the rooks are in Black's favor, who has all his typical queenside counterplay.   13.Be3  Nce5  seems to be very unclear and complicated, but also  13...g6  must be ok for Black. }
13... Nxd4 { Removing one attacker of those weakened light squares. } 14. gxf7+
Kxf7 15. Qxd4 Be7 { Threatening ...Bf6 with mass exchanges. } 16. Qd1
{ Sidestepping ... Bf6. } 16... Nf6 17. Be3 Bd7
{ Sometimes ...Rh8 is coming, ...Bc6 and White's keep is not so safe either. Black should be fine. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 48: Najdorf 6.Bd3, 6.g3 & 6.Be2"]
[Black "Najdorf: 6.Be2 e5 7.Nf5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf requires a lot of concrete theory in most lines White can choose. This also applies to White. White must be aware of many forced lines Black can initiate in order to hope to emerge with an advantage, and indeed not lose themselves.   The point of this move is to control the b5 square and later support the ...b5 push, thematic to Black's queenside counterplay. It also acts as something of a waiting move. }
6. Be2
{ This is the main and most critical response to the Najdorf if White wants to play a more constrained, positional game. From here, the bishop is most active, eyeing both sides of the board, and White maintains flexibility with the kingside pawns. This was the main line before Kasparov started to show how to meet it with Black.   Garry's way of playing all Sicilians was amazing, nobody can compete with him, and if you want to understand how to play from either side, you should study his games. I have played both sides of this system with both colors numerous times and I'll share that knowledge with you now. }
6... e5
{ My recommended move. I've tried lots of different things for White here but didn't manage to achieve an advantage. You can even win games with this move, since it's so double-edged.  6...g6  is not a good move because after  7.Be3  is a simple way to get an advantage.  7...Bg7  8.Qd2  b5  9.Bf3  e5  Even though this setup with Be2 isn't ideal for White, it should still be better. }
7. Nf5
{ This is not a serious try as it allows us to transform the central structure to our advantage. }
7... d5
{ Intending pushing ahead with ...d4 when we will never need to worry about the backwards d-pawn in these lines. }
8. Bg5 d4 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 { 9...gxf6  10.Nb1  is also good for Black. } 10. Nd5
Qd8 { The most stable square for the queen. } 11. c4 g6 12. Ng3 Nc6
{ I would rather take Black in this position, with a strong center and ...h5 ideas. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 48: Najdorf 6.Bd3, 6.g3 & 6.Be2"]
[Black "Najdorf: 6.Be2 e5 7.Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf requires a lot of concrete theory in most lines White can choose. This also applies to White. White must be aware of many forced lines Black can initiate in order to hope to emerge with an advantage, and indeed not lose themselves.   The point of this move is to control the b5 square and later support the ...b5 push, thematic to Black's queenside counterplay. It also acts as something of a waiting move. }
6. Be2
{ This is the main and most critical response to the Najdorf if White wants to play a more constrained, positional game. From here, the bishop is most active, eyeing both sides of the board, and White maintains flexibility with the kingside pawns. This was the main line before Kasparov started to show how to meet it with Black.   Garry's way of playing all Sicilians was amazing, nobody can compete with him, and if you want to understand how to play from either side, you should study his games. I have played both sides of this system with both colors numerous times and I'll share that knowledge with you now. }
6... e5
{ My recommended move. I've tried lots of different things for White here but didn't manage to achieve an advantage. You can even win games with this move, since it's so double-edged.  6...g6  is not a good move because after  7.Be3  is a simple way to get an advantage.  7...Bg7  8.Qd2  b5  9.Bf3  e5  Even though this setup with Be2 isn't ideal for White, it should still be better. }
7. Nf3
{ Lately this retreat has become more popular, intending to eventually reroute the knight to the ideal e3 square. }
7... Be7
{ This is simple enough.  7...Be6  8.Ng5  shows another merit of the knight being on f3. }
8. Bg5
{ The whole point - aiming to exchange the bishop for the knight to increase White's control of d5. }
8... Be6
{ Should be preferred, not fearing Bxf6, and it's not clear where our knight is going yet.  8...Nbd7  is a popular try at the top level, and play typically continues  9.a4  Qc7  10.Nd2  on the way to e3.  10...h6  11.Bh4  g5  12.Bg3  Nc5  with a playable position for Black, but I think we have simpler. }
9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Qd2
{ Preparing castling with pressure on d6.  10.Nd5  is less accurate because after  10...Nd7  11.O-O  Rc8  Black doesn't have to use a tempo on ...Be7. }
10... O-O 11. O-O Be7
{ Simply defending.  11...Qc7  is another move-order that should transpose.  12.Nd5   12.Rfd1  anyway we go  12...Be7  12...Bxd5  13.Qxd5  This is a strategically dangerous position for Black because if a White piece stabilizes on d5, White is always better, but tactically they cannot manage. For example, once the knight leaves f3, Bg5 becomes possible.  13...Nd7  14.c3  Be7  15.Nd2  b5  The knight will come to b6 and Black has plenty of active play around the center. }
12. Nd5 Nd7 13. Rfd1
{ This doesn't cause much concern as we can comfortably simplify in the center. }
13... Bxd5 14. Qxd5 Qb6
{ Black finishes development and it's not clear how White should continue to add pressure. }
15. Qb3 Qxb3 16. axb3 Nf6
{ This gives Black a healthy position with the possibility of ...d5. } *

