[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 48: Najdorf 6.Bd3, 6.g3 & 6.Be2"]
[Black "Najdorf: 6.Be2 e5 7.Nb3 Be7 8.g4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf requires a lot of concrete theory in most lines White can choose. This also applies to White. White must be aware of many forced lines Black can initiate in order to hope to emerge with an advantage, and indeed not lose themselves.   The point of this move is to control the b5 square and later support the ...b5 push, thematic to Black's queenside counterplay. It also acts as something of a waiting move. }
6. Be2
{ This is the main and most critical response to the Najdorf if White wants to play a more constrained, positional game. From here, the bishop is most active, eyeing both sides of the board, and White maintains flexibility with the kingside pawns. This was the main line before Kasparov started to show how to meet it with Black.   Garry's way of playing all Sicilians was amazing, nobody can compete with him, and if you want to understand how to play from either side, you should study his games. I have played both sides of this system with both colors numerous times and I'll share that knowledge with you now. }
6... e5
{ My recommended move. I've tried lots of different things for White here but didn't manage to achieve an advantage. You can even win games with this move, since it's so double-edged.  6...g6  is not a good move because after  7.Be3  is a simple way to get an advantage.  7...Bg7  8.Qd2  b5  9.Bf3  e5  Even though this setup with Be2 isn't ideal for White, it should still be better. }
7. Nb3 { The main move, keeping the most tension. } 7... Be7
{ 7...Be6  is inaccurate since  8.f4  exf4  9.Bxf4  is a very unpleasant position for Black; White saved a tempo by taking on f4 immediately before developing the bishop. }
8. g4
{ This would make a lot of sense if they manage to get g5 through, but it won't work. }
8... h6
{ Once again, slowing White's kingside play and preparing to open the h-file if they ever push g5. }
9. h4 Be6 10. Be3 Nbd7
{ 10...d5  exchanging everything offers White a small plus at the end.  11.exd5  Nxd5  12.Nxd5  Bxd5  13.Bf3  Bxf3  14.Qxf3  Nc6  and maybe Black is alright, but  10...Nbd7  is more patient. }
11. Rg1 Nh7
{ Adding even more control over g5, when the engine actually suggests Rh1 could be best for White. }
*

