{ My recommended move. I've tried lots of different things for White here but didn't manage to achieve an advantage. You can even win games with this move, since it's so double-edged.  6...g6  is not a good move because after  7.Be3  is a simple way to get an advantage.  7...Bg7  8.Qd2  b5  9.Bf3  e5  Even though this setup with Be2 isn't ideal for White, it should still be better. }
7. Nb3 { The main move, keeping the most tension. } 7... Be7
{ 7...Be6  is inaccurate since  8.f4  exf4  9.Bxf4  is a very unpleasant position for Black; White saved a tempo by taking on f4 immediately before developing the bishop. }
8. Bg5
{ I believe I played this first at the top level, which is rather popular nowadays because White is struggling to find anything else. }
8... Be6
{ The best move, with straightforward development.  8...Nbd7  used to be the answer, but after  9.a4  the situation is not so clear for Black.  9...h6   9...Qc7  10.a5  clamps down on the weak  10...b6  square.   9...b6  10.Bc4  was my game against Gelfand 2003 in Rapid Chess when Black was suffering.  10.Be3  b6  Black has an extra tempo with ...h6 but this setup isn't the best against classical play which we will see later in this lesson. }
9. Bxf6 { White's idea. } 9... Bxf6 10. Qd3 Qc7
{ The most useful move, defensively and actively.  10...Nc6  is logical with direct play, but after  11.O-O-O  Nd4  12.Nxd4  exd4  13.Nd5  Bxd5  14.exd5  White should have some advantage in the form of a more active bishop.   10...O-O  is also a possible way of playing.  11.O-O-O  Qb6   12.Qxd6  Qxf2  is a bit dangerous and tricky to play.  12.Rhf1  Nc6  13.Kb1  Rfd8  and Black is probably ok, but the position remains complex. }
11. Rd1
{ This is a commital move as it rules out long-castling and shouldn't offer much as Black can simply defend the pawn. }
11... Be7 12. Nd5 Bxd5 { A knight cannot be tolerated on d5. } 13. Qxd5 Nd7
{ It's not easy at all for White to manage getting a piece to d5. } 14. O-O Nf6
15. Qd3 O-O { Now Black can aim for ...Rfe8 / ...d5 with an equal game. } 16.
c4 b5
{ Black is very comfortable now since anytime White captures on b5, it activates our a-rook. Our bishop will also one day reroute to the nice b6-square. }
*

