{ Very normal play, getting active while waiting for White to prove something. }
12. Rfd1 Qc7
{ Another cagey 'waiting' move. Note these positions tend to be better versions for White with the queen on d2, not d3.  12...Nb6  now White has  13.Nd2  and White keeps the game going and Black doesn't get to equalize on the spot.   The engines also approve of  12...Ng4  which is a bit strange but after  13.Bxg4  Bxg4  14.f3  Be6  Black is in time to meet  15.Nd5  with  15...Bxd5  and Black is fine. }
13. a5 Rfd8 { Ding's move against me. } 14. Bf3 Nc5
{ 14...h6  would lead to a normal, playable position which I had expected in the Ding game, but he found a better way to equalize which he had prepared beforehand. }
15. Nxc5 dxc5 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. exd5 f5
{ A very important, active move and Black equalizes by a single tempo. } 18.
Qb3 { A scary tactical threat, but Black has it under control. } 18... Bf7
{ After  19.d6  ,  mass trades were initiated and I ended up blundering a rook and losing with a misclick. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 48: Najdorf 6.Bd3, 6.g3 & 6.Be2"]
[Black "Najdorf: 6.Be2 e5 7.Nb3 Be7 8.O-O #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf requires a lot of concrete theory in most lines White can choose. This also applies to White. White must be aware of many forced lines Black can initiate in order to hope to emerge with an advantage, and indeed not lose themselves.   The point of this move is to control the b5 square and later support the ...b5 push, thematic to Black's queenside counterplay. It also acts as something of a waiting move. }
6. Be2
{ This is the main and most critical response to the Najdorf if White wants to play a more constrained, positional game. From here, the bishop is most active, eyeing both sides of the board, and White maintains flexibility with the kingside pawns. This was the main line before Kasparov started to show how to meet it with Black.   Garry's way of playing all Sicilians was amazing, nobody can compete with him, and if you want to understand how to play from either side, you should study his games. I have played both sides of this system with both colors numerous times and I'll share that knowledge with you now. }
6... e5
{ My recommended move. I've tried lots of different things for White here but didn't manage to achieve an advantage. You can even win games with this move, since it's so double-edged.  6...g6  is not a good move because after  7.Be3  is a simple way to get an advantage.  7...Bg7  8.Qd2  b5  9.Bf3  e5  Even though this setup with Be2 isn't ideal for White, it should still be better. }
7. Nb3 { The main move, keeping the most tension. } 7... Be7
{ 7...Be6  is inaccurate since  8.f4  exf4  9.Bxf4  is a very unpleasant position for Black; White saved a tempo by taking on f4 immediately before developing the bishop. }
8. O-O
{ Waiting for Black to commit to ...Be6.  8.f4  can now be met by  8...b5  when f5 is not a threat. }
8... O-O { 8...Be6  is too early again in view of  9.f4  . } 9. Be3
{ By process of elimination, Be3 is the only reasonable move. } 9... Be6 10.
Qd2 { The main move, trying to add more heavy piece influence on the d-file. }
10... Nbd7
{ The normal square for the knight, making the ...b5 push more attractive.  10...b5  is premature since after  11.a4  b4  12.Nd5  There are no guarantees Black will equalize here, and it's a bit unpleasant. }
11. a4
{ A simple necessity.  11.Rfd1  is possible but allows  11...b5  which probably is enough for equality.  11...Rc8  is another option that definitely prepares ...b5, so 12. a4 will be forced sooner or later. }
11... Nb6
{ Pretty much equalizes by force.  11...Rc8  is a move played by Geller and Karpov for example when after something like  12.a5  Qc7  13.Rfd1  it's much more difficult to prepare ...b6 or ...b5 because the pawn on a6 is always hanging. In these positions, White wants to maneuver a knight to the potent c4 square and while these positions are interesting and playable, it's not near as straightforward as ...Nb6. }
12. Rfd1 { This is too slow, and allows Black more queenside activity. } 12...
Rc8 { Intending to go ...Nc4 and recapture with the rook this time. } 13. Bg5
Nc4
{ Black's main idea, a pawn sacrifice leading to a very healthy, active endgame for Black. }
14. Bxc4 Rxc4 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Qxd6 Qxd6 17. Rxd6 Be7 18. Rb6
{ Practically forced since it can be Black playing for a win if ...Bb4 is allowed. }
18... Rb8 19. Rd1 h5
{ Whtie cannot improve because the rook on c4 is very powerful and Black has the bishop pair. It should end in a draw. }
*

