{ Lately, this move seems to be equalizing with this idea of ...Nxd4 and ...Bc6.  10...Qc7  The start of this classical position where you can record an entire course on this position only, so I won't go too in-depth. Kasparov and Anand have both played this with both colors, for example. According to theory, Black should hold.  11.Kh1  Re8  12.Qe1  or  12.Bd3  ,  12.Bg1  or  12.Bf3  can be played. The 24th game in the 1985 World Championship match where Garry became World Champion is the most famous example. }
11. Nb3
{ This was always considered to be a problem for Black because White, preparing kingside aggressions. }
11... Na5
{ Trying to relieve some pressure.  11...b6  was sometimes played when after  12.Bf3  Qc7  13.g4  White gets his kingside play going.  13...Bc8  losing a tempo.  14.g5  Nd7  15.Bg2  Re8  16.Rf3  looks very scary for Black. They're not mating by force, but White has good practical chances and is a better version of the Karpov-Kasparov game from 1985. }
12. e5
{ The logical way to take advantage of the black knight abandoning the center. }
12... Ne8
{ This looks passive for Black but since this system was played by a number of prominent players, nobody has shown a way to prove they can take advantage of the temporarily misplaced knight. }
13. Nxa5 Qxa5 14. Ne4 Qc7 { Simply defending d6 and pressurizing e5. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 48: Najdorf 6.Bd3, 6.g3 & 6.Be2"]
[Black "Najdorf: 6.Be2 (Alternative: 6...e6 #4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf requires a lot of concrete theory in most lines White can choose. This also applies to White. White must be aware of many forced lines Black can initiate in order to hope to emerge with an advantage, and indeed not lose themselves.   The point of this move is to control the b5 square and later support the ...b5 push, thematic to Black's queenside counterplay. It also acts as something of a waiting move. }
6. Be2
{ This is the main and most critical response to the Najdorf if White wants to play a more constrained, positional game. From here, the bishop is most active, eyeing both sides of the board, and White maintains flexibility with the kingside pawns. This was the main line before Kasparov started to show how to meet it with Black.   Garry's way of playing all Sicilians was amazing, nobody can compete with him, and if you want to understand how to play from either side, you should study his games. I have played both sides of this system with both colors numerous times and I'll share that knowledge with you now. }
6... e6
{ Karpov was trying to play in a classical fashion and develop and castle short next. Black has more problems after this move, and Black must know lots of theory to make this playable. It might equalize with precise play, but it's riskier. }
7. Be3
{ I believe this is the second most critical system, which prepares long-castling and stays flexible with the f-pawn. }
7... Qc7
{ The usual move, staying flexible and avoiding concrete continuations for the moment. It also has the merit of protecting the bishop if it ever lands on b7.  7...b5  is premature as after  8.Bf3  e5  is forced when Black has lost important tempi.   7...Nc6  8.f4  with the idea of Qd2 and O-O-O next as we've already covered can be quite dangerous for Black.   8.Qd2  preparing long-castle would allow this  8...Bd7  idea, quickly preparing ...b5. }
8. Qd2
{ The normal move.  8.a4  is another try, aiming to transpose to the classical Sicilians after ...Nc6 but here Black is in time with  8...b6  9.Bf3  Bb7  when the bishop is protected and there is no e5 tactic.   8.f4  is met by the immediate b5 and Black is fine. }
8... b5 { Whenever it's tactically justified, Black should go ...b5. } 9. a3
Bb7 10. f3 Nbd7
{ Now the most logical square for the knight, where it can quickly jump to any number of squares. }
11. O-O-O Rc8 12. Kb1 h5
{ There's a transposition to this line in another critical setup for White we will analyze with the bishop not yet developed on e2, but still it often goes to e2 anyway so this is definitely playable. This position is a bit easier to play for White because Black's king will be stuck in the center for some time, but it's not such a big deal. }
