6. Be2
{ This is the main and most critical response to the Najdorf if White wants to play a more constrained, positional game. From here, the bishop is most active, eyeing both sides of the board, and White maintains flexibility with the kingside pawns. This was the main line before Kasparov started to show how to meet it with Black.   Garry's way of playing all Sicilians was amazing, nobody can compete with him, and if you want to understand how to play from either side, you should study his games. I have played both sides of this system with both colors numerous times and I'll share that knowledge with you now. }
6... e6
{ Karpov was trying to play in a classical fashion and develop and castle short next. Black has more problems after this move, and Black must know lots of theory to make this playable. It might equalize with precise play, but it's riskier. }
7. f4
{ This is a very serious move you need to reckon with if you want to play these Scheveningen structures. }
7... Qc7
{ Again, my recommendation in order to remain flexible with the other pieces.  7...b5  8.e5  leads to an advantage for White.   and on  7...Nc6  White has the same idea of  8.Qd2  with O-O-O next with a dangerous position.   Lastly,  7...Be7  with quick castling doesn't impress in view of  8.Be3  O-O   8...Qc7  9.g4  9.g4  d5  10.e5  Nfd7  11.g5  which also looks very dangerous for Black. It's some kind of French structure where White has some initiative. }
8. Bf3 { An interesting move, but not so terrible for Black. } 8... Nc6 9. Be3
Be7 10. g4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 e5
{ An important move, keeping White's bishop on f3 passive. } 12. Qd1 exf4 13.
Bxf4 Be6
{ The engines give White a small plus, but I don't see it. This should just be equal. }
