{ Karpov was trying to play in a classical fashion and develop and castle short next. Black has more problems after this move, and Black must know lots of theory to make this playable. It might equalize with precise play, but it's riskier. }
7. f4
{ This is a very serious move you need to reckon with if you want to play these Scheveningen structures. }
7... Qc7
{ Again, my recommendation in order to remain flexible with the other pieces.  7...b5  8.e5  leads to an advantage for White.   and on  7...Nc6  White has the same idea of  8.Qd2  with O-O-O next with a dangerous position.   Lastly,  7...Be7  with quick castling doesn't impress in view of  8.Be3  O-O   8...Qc7  9.g4  9.g4  d5  10.e5  Nfd7  11.g5  which also looks very dangerous for Black. It's some kind of French structure where White has some initiative. }
8. g4
{ The most critical option.  9.Be3  would allow  9...b5  9.Bf3  Bb7  when we're in time with developing the bishop when it's protected. }
8... h6
{ If White wants g5 it will open Black's rook. From here there is no clear way for White to get an advantage, but they have many tries.  8...b5  would be ideal, but after  9.g5  b4  10.Ncb5  axb5  11.gxf6  White stands well.   8...Nc6  is also tempting but after  9.g5  Nd7  10.Be3  these positions are always favoring White. We should slow down White's kingside play. }
9. g5
{ A strange way of playing, insisting on opening the kingside which might not be fully justified but will appeal to those who want to steer the position into forcing waters quickly. }
9... hxg5 { Opening our rook. } 10. fxg5 Nfd7 11. h4
{ 11.g6  Ne5  is solid for Black. } 11... Ne5 12. Bf4
{ The position might be more pleasant for White and can be considered a serious try. Ultimately we shouldn't prefer this variation over the more straightforward 6...e5. }
