[Black "Najdorf: 6.Be2 (Alternative: 6...e6 #7)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf requires a lot of concrete theory in most lines White can choose. This also applies to White. White must be aware of many forced lines Black can initiate in order to hope to emerge with an advantage, and indeed not lose themselves.   The point of this move is to control the b5 square and later support the ...b5 push, thematic to Black's queenside counterplay. It also acts as something of a waiting move. }
6. Be2
{ This is the main and most critical response to the Najdorf if White wants to play a more constrained, positional game. From here, the bishop is most active, eyeing both sides of the board, and White maintains flexibility with the kingside pawns. This was the main line before Kasparov started to show how to meet it with Black.   Garry's way of playing all Sicilians was amazing, nobody can compete with him, and if you want to understand how to play from either side, you should study his games. I have played both sides of this system with both colors numerous times and I'll share that knowledge with you now. }
6... e6
{ Karpov was trying to play in a classical fashion and develop and castle short next. Black has more problems after this move, and Black must know lots of theory to make this playable. It might equalize with precise play, but it's riskier. }
7. f4
{ This is a very serious move you need to reckon with if you want to play these Scheveningen structures. }
7... Qc7
{ Again, my recommendation in order to remain flexible with the other pieces.  7...b5  8.e5  leads to an advantage for White.   and on  7...Nc6  White has the same idea of  8.Qd2  with O-O-O next with a dangerous position.   Lastly,  7...Be7  with quick castling doesn't impress in view of  8.Be3  O-O   8...Qc7  9.g4  9.g4  d5  10.e5  Nfd7  11.g5  which also looks very dangerous for Black. It's some kind of French structure where White has some initiative. }
8. g4
{ The most critical option.  9.Be3  would allow  9...b5  9.Bf3  Bb7  when we're in time with developing the bishop when it's protected. }
8... h6
{ If White wants g5 it will open Black's rook. From here there is no clear way for White to get an advantage, but they have many tries.  8...b5  would be ideal, but after  9.g5  b4  10.Ncb5  axb5  11.gxf6  White stands well.   8...Nc6  is also tempting but after  9.g5  Nd7  10.Be3  these positions are always favoring White. We should slow down White's kingside play. }
9. Be3 b5 10. a3
{ Followed by Bf3 and h4 and I'm not completely sure Black can clearly equalize here, but it's a very complex, double-edged fight. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 48: Najdorf 6.Bd3, 6.g3 & 6.Be2"]
[Black "Najdorf: 6.Be2 - Conclusion"]
[Result "*"]

{ In conclusion, with all of these slower, positional systems against the Najdorf, Black seems to be having a good game after ...e5 in Sveshnikov style structures. The g3 system isn't so scary since the bishop tends to be misplaced there, and similarly after Bd3, the bishop is less flexible, and offers White less chance to create a bind on d5.   In all of these systems, Black is aiming for simple development with eventual queenside expansion with typical moves such as ...Be7 / O-O / ...Be6 / ...Nbd7 / ...Rc8 and ...b5. Of course there are subtleties to which moves are good at which moments, and it pays to know how to meet White's typical ideas such as f4 and Nd5, but play tends to be quite simple.   That being said, although play is simple, the positions remain complicated which should favor the Najdorf player. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 49: Najdorf 6.Bc4 & 6.h3"]
[Black "Fischer-Sozin Attack 6.Bc4 e6 7.O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ We are going to check now a couple of systems that are pretty aggressive, especially if we compare them with the previous lessons where White played positional variations mostly. Now, I will discuss two systems that are very double-edged, which shouldn't come as a surprise as we are talking about the Najdorf.  As usual, I believe Black is doing fine in more than one way, while White will try to be as aggressive as possible. However, it might suit your style if you prefer sharp play with White, while Black will need to be very well prepared and very well aware of various move orders, as timing is essential in the Najdorf. }
6. Bc4
{ A very tricky system, full of traps and tactical motifs, when Black might end up just lost rather fast if unaware of the ideas and the exact move orders. The 6.Bc4 system was very popular back in the day, but now it has almost disappeared from top-level tournament practice due to the presence of computers that handle extremely well those direct positions.  It may look like a very aggressive opening for White, which is true to some extent in view of the fast development and active pieces, but Black is also very solid. If White doesn't obtain the initiative fast, the positions might even end up lost for White with the bishop on b3. The plan f4-f5 is often employed in this system, to activate the bishop on b3 once Black played ...e7-e6, otherwise, the white bishop will be a spectator.  According to the current state of the theory @@StartBracket@@so many games have been played at the top-level that we can trust the general consensus@@EndBracket@@, Black has good play here, with chances to even fight for advantage sometimes, as White's game plan is also risky. However, if you are well prepared and know all the ins and outs of this system, you can surely employ it with White, which could turn out as a deadly weapon in faster time controls, for instance. Nonetheless, objectively, Black is fine. }
6... e6
{ A rather forced reaction, as the ...e5 structures are not ideal against the well-placed bishop on c4. }
7. O-O
{ The good thing about this move is that it avoids  7...Nbd7  , which would run into  8.Bxe6+-  . }
7... Be7
{ 7...Nc6  is also a normal developing reaction, but the best Black can do is the text move. Also, Black can already play  7...b5  , and after  8.Bb3  , we transpose to the line we are going to study. }
8. Bb3 O-O
{ Once again,  8...b5  is not yet  needed @@StartBracket@@it would give White some additional Qf3-g3 ideas@@EndBracket@@, but it can be played as well and just transpose to the main line. }
9. f4 Nc6
{ This is at least playable for White given a position we are going to see in a minute, which is the reason why 9...Nc6 is no longer popular. }
10. Be3 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 b5 12. e5
{ Play is very concrete, as White has to hurry to avoid getting worse with the bishop on b3. }
12... dxe5 13. fxe5 Nd7
{ The main line.  13...Ne8  is a rare move but played by Kasparov once and, perhaps, it is not too bad. }
14. Ne4 Bb7 15. Nd6 Bxd6 16. exd6 Qg5 17. Qe2
{ This was played in the Short-Kasparov match in 1993 too. Both sides have their trumps in this seemingly equal position: the passed pawn on d6 is blocked, White has the bishop pair, but the one on b3 is a bit out of play, while Black has a very powerful bishop on b7 − the game is extremely complicated, but at least White has some chances for an advantage. }
*

