[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 49: Najdorf 6.Bc4 & 6.h3"]
[Black "Fischer-Sozin Attack 6.Bc4 e6 7.Bb3 b5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ We are going to check now a couple of systems that are pretty aggressive, especially if we compare them with the previous lessons where White played positional variations mostly. Now, I will discuss two systems that are very double-edged, which shouldn't come as a surprise as we are talking about the Najdorf.  As usual, I believe Black is doing fine in more than one way, while White will try to be as aggressive as possible. However, it might suit your style if you prefer sharp play with White, while Black will need to be very well prepared and very well aware of various move orders, as timing is essential in the Najdorf. }
6. Bc4
{ A very tricky system, full of traps and tactical motifs, when Black might end up just lost rather fast if unaware of the ideas and the exact move orders. The 6.Bc4 system was very popular back in the day, but now it has almost disappeared from top-level tournament practice due to the presence of computers that handle extremely well those direct positions.  It may look like a very aggressive opening for White, which is true to some extent in view of the fast development and active pieces, but Black is also very solid. If White doesn't obtain the initiative fast, the positions might even end up lost for White with the bishop on b3. The plan f4-f5 is often employed in this system, to activate the bishop on b3 once Black played ...e7-e6, otherwise, the white bishop will be a spectator.  According to the current state of the theory @@StartBracket@@so many games have been played at the top-level that we can trust the general consensus@@EndBracket@@, Black has good play here, with chances to even fight for advantage sometimes, as White's game plan is also risky. However, if you are well prepared and know all the ins and outs of this system, you can surely employ it with White, which could turn out as a deadly weapon in faster time controls, for instance. Nonetheless, objectively, Black is fine. }
6... e6
{ A rather forced reaction, as the ...e5 structures are not ideal against the well-placed bishop on c4. }
7. Bb3
{ This unnecessary-looking move is actually played most of the time. The idea is to postpone castling so that after  7...Be7  , White has  8.g4  . This may not be dramatic, but I wouldn't recommend it for Black. }
7... b5 { By far the most popular continuation. } 8. Be3
{ White is still trying to play with O-O-O, which I also did a couple of times in faster time controls via a different move order: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p2ppn2/8/2BNP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Be3  b5  8.Bb3  . I don't believe in this system, but I wanted something sharp that is less explored. }
8... Be7 9. a3 { A useful move since ...b4 is always on the agenda. } 9... O-O
10. f3 Bb7
{ In case of  10...Bd7  , White can play a quick  11.g4  , but still, after  11...Nc6  , the position continues to be unclear. }
11. g4 Nc6 12. g5 Nd7
{ Without @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/4bppp/p2ppn2/1p6/3NP3/PBN1BP2/1PP3PP/R2QK2R b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Bd7  on the board,  the knight has the d7-square available for the knight and is probably better already. }
