{ Visually, it looks like White has got something working: attack, developed pieces, activity, while Black's knights are parked on the 8th rank. However, White has the same problem as always in the 6.Bc4 system: the bishop on b3. }
13. f4 { The most principled move. } 13... Nc6
{ It is always a question of tempi in this system, but as I mentioned often, time is in Black's favor, meaning that 6.Bc4 against the Najdorf is not so dangerous. }
14. f5
{ One of White's options, played by Mamedyarov against Gelfand in the Candidates Tournament, Kazan 2011 − a beautiful game that is worth checking! By the way, I strongly advise studying Gelfand's games in the Najdorf, as he played this opening his whole life and handled it very well. }
14... Nxd4 15. Rxd4 Kh8
{ Visually, the position can look misleading. It may appear as if White is better, but in reality, that is not the case. }
16. Be3 Nf6
{ As mentioned many times, if White doesn't have an immediate course of action, the position can quickly turn into Black's favor, who has the simple plan of ...a5-a4.   For illustrative purposes, this is how the game Mamedyarov-Gelfand continued:  17.Qh3  d5  18.e5  Qxe5  19.Rh4  Rfc8  20.Kh1  Rxc3  21.bxc3  Qxc3  22.Rd4  a5  23.Rd3  Qc6  24.c3  a4  25.Bc2  e5  26.Bg5  b4  27.Qh4  bxc3  28.Rh3  Kg8  29.Re1  e4  30.g4  Kf8  31.Be3  Qc4  32.g5  Bxf5  33.gxf6  Bxf6  34.Qh5  Bg6  35.Qg4  Qxa2  36.Bb1  Qc4  37.Qg2  a3  38.Ba2  Qc6  39.Rg3  Rb8  0-1. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 49: Najdorf 6.Bc4 & 6.h3"]
[Black "Fischer-Sozin Attack 6.Bc4 e6 7.Bb3 b5 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ We are going to check now a couple of systems that are pretty aggressive, especially if we compare them with the previous lessons where White played positional variations mostly. Now, I will discuss two systems that are very double-edged, which shouldn't come as a surprise as we are talking about the Najdorf.  As usual, I believe Black is doing fine in more than one way, while White will try to be as aggressive as possible. However, it might suit your style if you prefer sharp play with White, while Black will need to be very well prepared and very well aware of various move orders, as timing is essential in the Najdorf. }
6. Bc4
{ A very tricky system, full of traps and tactical motifs, when Black might end up just lost rather fast if unaware of the ideas and the exact move orders. The 6.Bc4 system was very popular back in the day, but now it has almost disappeared from top-level tournament practice due to the presence of computers that handle extremely well those direct positions.  It may look like a very aggressive opening for White, which is true to some extent in view of the fast development and active pieces, but Black is also very solid. If White doesn't obtain the initiative fast, the positions might even end up lost for White with the bishop on b3. The plan f4-f5 is often employed in this system, to activate the bishop on b3 once Black played ...e7-e6, otherwise, the white bishop will be a spectator.  According to the current state of the theory @@StartBracket@@so many games have been played at the top-level that we can trust the general consensus@@EndBracket@@, Black has good play here, with chances to even fight for advantage sometimes, as White's game plan is also risky. However, if you are well prepared and know all the ins and outs of this system, you can surely employ it with White, which could turn out as a deadly weapon in faster time controls, for instance. Nonetheless, objectively, Black is fine. }
6... e6
{ A rather forced reaction, as the ...e5 structures are not ideal against the well-placed bishop on c4. }
7. Bb3
{ This unnecessary-looking move is actually played most of the time. The idea is to postpone castling so that after  7...Be7  , White has  8.g4  . This may not be dramatic, but I wouldn't recommend it for Black. }
7... b5 { By far the most popular continuation. } 8. O-O Be7
{ 8...Nbd7  is again hit by  9.Bxe6  , which is not recommended.  Generally, Black either plays ...Nbd7-c5 or ...b5, when it is not advisable to develop the knight to d7 anymore. }
9. Qf3
{ As explained before, White has to act fast. If Black finishes development, the position will be in Black's favor. }
9... Qc7
{ Many strong players go for this line, including Boris Gelfand, and it is the most popular variation, with a lot of theory. Since so many hours have been spent on this system at the top level and with so many games played, we can be pretty sure that Black is all right and the conclusions correct as well. }
10. Qg3 O-O 11. Bh6 Ne8 12. Rad1 Bd7
{ Visually, it looks like White has got something working: attack, developed pieces, activity, while Black's knights are parked on the 8th rank. However, White has the same problem as always in the 6.Bc4 system: the bishop on b3. }
13. f4 { The most principled move. } 13... Nc6
{ It is always a question of tempi in this system, but as I mentioned often, time is in Black's favor, meaning that 6.Bc4 against the Najdorf is not so dangerous. }
14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. f5 Kh8
{ This is an important line and must be known with both colors, but after ...Kh8, Black is perfectly fine. }
16. f6 gxh6 17. fxe7 Qxe7
{ The position is more or less equal, as I don't see any reason why White would be any better. Of course, the king is a bit weak on h8, but in return, Black has an extra pawn, while the bishop on b3 is still suffering. }
18. Qf2
{ There was a game Kasimdzhanov-Gelfand, Tashkent 2014, that went like this, and finally led to a logical draw. }
18... Ng7 19. Qb6 Rfc8
{ I would rather take Black here. Had the b3-bishop been on d3, that would have been a completely different picture. As is, I don't like the bishop on b3 at all. One day ...a5-a4 will come and White will get a headache because of the light-squared bishop. }
*

