{ This unnecessary-looking move is actually played most of the time. The idea is to postpone castling so that after  7...Be7  , White has  8.g4  . This may not be dramatic, but I wouldn't recommend it for Black. }
7... Nbd7
{ A very good system, and perhaps even simpler than  7...b5  . I tried to find a problem for Black in this line while preparing this lesson but to no avail. White has tried many moves in this position, but none is really dangerous. }
8. f4 Nc5
{ Many games have been played here. In the '90s, Kasparov, Short, Topalov played this line, but at that time, the engines were quite weak and White would get the initiative now and then. Nowadays, the computer is laughing at White's attack and Black is even better in many variations. }
9. e5
{ I wouldn't say this is a critical continuation, as it doesn't present any danger for Black, but at least White is not worse. }
9... Nfd7
{ Not allowing Bf4 as it is the case in the  9...dxe5  variation, played by Kasparov against Short in their match:  10.fxe5  Nfd7  11.Bf4  . This position is also unclear and complicated, but it could potentially be dangerous for Black. Kasparov himself was also in trouble at some point. }
10. exd6 Nf6 11. Qf3 Bxd6 12. Be3 { White is trying to get some advantage. }
12... O-O 13. O-O-O Nxb3+ 14. axb3 Qc7 15. Kb1 Re8
{ One of the possible moves, supporting ...e5. The position is equal. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 49: Najdorf 6.Bc4 & 6.h3"]
[Black "Najdorf 6.h3 g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ We are going to check now a couple of systems that are pretty aggressive, especially if we compare them with the previous lessons where White played positional variations mostly. Now, I will discuss two systems that are very double-edged, which shouldn't come as a surprise as we are talking about the Najdorf.  As usual, I believe Black is doing fine in more than one way, while White will try to be as aggressive as possible. However, it might suit your style if you prefer sharp play with White, while Black will need to be very well prepared and very well aware of various move orders, as timing is essential in the Najdorf. }
6. h3
{ A modest-looking move, but in reality, it is quite a serious try and rather popular. You might wonder why isn't this move part of the previous lesson where we discussed positional play... The idea behind it is, in fact, very aggressive: g4 is played in almost every line followed by castling queenside, with very dangerous positions.   Now, Black has the usual dilemma: should  6...e6  or rather  6...e5  appear on the board? In fact, how about  6...b5  and  6...g6  @@StartBracket@@I wouldn't recommend them though@@EndBracket@@, which are also played often?  6...Nc6  is possible, but it doesn't combine well  with ...a6. }
6... g6
{ This might be playable, but, in my opinion, it doesn't fully equalize. } 7.
g3
{ The simplest and also played by Magnus Carlsen. White transposes to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.g3  variation, where Black goes  6...g6  @@StartBracket@@you can check it in one of the previous lessons − White will have to play h3 at some point anyway, to secure Be3@@EndBracket@@.   Instead of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pp1p/p2p1np1/8/3NP3/2N4P/PPP2PP1/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.g3  , White can also opt for  7.Be3  Bg7  8.Qd2  , where there is a lot of theory and not so easy for Black to counter it, or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pp1p/p2p1np1/8/3NP3/2N4P/PPP2PP1/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.g4  Bg7  8.Bg2  , when Black's task is also not trivial. }
7... Bg7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O Nc6 10. Be3
{ As mentioned before, I am not sure Black has enough to equalize here. Carlsen and Grischuk played this line as well, amongst others, and I must say I don't like Black's position. }
10... Rb8 11. Nd5
{ I would be very happy to play this with White, especially since we are talking about the Najdorf, where it is very difficult to get a plus out of the opening. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 49: Najdorf 6.Bc4 & 6.h3"]
[Black "Najdorf 6.h3 e6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ We are going to check now a couple of systems that are pretty aggressive, especially if we compare them with the previous lessons where White played positional variations mostly. Now, I will discuss two systems that are very double-edged, which shouldn't come as a surprise as we are talking about the Najdorf.  As usual, I believe Black is doing fine in more than one way, while White will try to be as aggressive as possible. However, it might suit your style if you prefer sharp play with White, while Black will need to be very well prepared and very well aware of various move orders, as timing is essential in the Najdorf. }
6. h3
{ A modest-looking move, but in reality, it is quite a serious try and rather popular. You might wonder why isn't this move part of the previous lesson where we discussed positional play... The idea behind it is, in fact, very aggressive: g4 is played in almost every line followed by castling queenside, with very dangerous positions.   Now, Black has the usual dilemma: should  6...e6  or rather  6...e5  appear on the board? In fact, how about  6...b5  and  6...g6  @@StartBracket@@I wouldn't recommend them though@@EndBracket@@, which are also played often?  6...Nc6  is possible, but it doesn't combine well  with ...a6. }
6... e6
{ This is also a reasonable continuation. It is not bullet-proof, as White has a couple of tries, but I think that Black has enough counter chances. It just depends on what type of structure you prefer. If you are inspired by the Scheveningen structures and Kasparov's games, then ...e6 is surely an option.  It is, of course, not working against every single line that White could play @@StartBracket@@for instance, the 6.Be3 variation is not so easy to face@@EndBracket@@, but here it works perfectly fine. The move orders are important though, as always. All in all, it is playable with both colors, but  6...e5  poses White more difficulties in showing something concrete, otherwise Black is totally fine. }
7. g4 b5 8. Bg2 Bb7 9. O-O
{ This can be dangerous for Black and, as just shown before,  9...b4  10.Nd5  brings bad news. }
9... Be7
{ We have to check this briefly, in order to be aware of White's typical ideas in these positions. }
10. e5 Bxg2 11. exf6 Bxf1 12. fxe7 Qxe7 13. Qxf1 { White is just winning. } *

