1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ We are going to check now a couple of systems that are pretty aggressive, especially if we compare them with the previous lessons where White played positional variations mostly. Now, I will discuss two systems that are very double-edged, which shouldn't come as a surprise as we are talking about the Najdorf.  As usual, I believe Black is doing fine in more than one way, while White will try to be as aggressive as possible. However, it might suit your style if you prefer sharp play with White, while Black will need to be very well prepared and very well aware of various move orders, as timing is essential in the Najdorf. }
6. h3
{ A modest-looking move, but in reality, it is quite a serious try and rather popular. You might wonder why isn't this move part of the previous lesson where we discussed positional play... The idea behind it is, in fact, very aggressive: g4 is played in almost every line followed by castling queenside, with very dangerous positions.   Now, Black has the usual dilemma: should  6...e6  or rather  6...e5  appear on the board? In fact, how about  6...b5  and  6...g6  @@StartBracket@@I wouldn't recommend them though@@EndBracket@@, which are also played often?  6...Nc6  is possible, but it doesn't combine well  with ...a6. }
6... b5
{ It is unnecessary to go for this dubious line when  6...e6  or  6...e5  are perfectly fine instead. }
7. a4 { First of all, White can immediately target b5 with this move. } 7... b4
8. Nd5 e6 { Black's best reaction. } 9. Nxf6+ Qxf6 10. Bd3
{ White can play in a very positional manner now that the black queen is oddly placed on f6. A possible way to develop is O-O, Be3, Qd2, Nf3, or start attacking the queenside at some point with Bd2, c3... White is slightly better and has a very comfortable position, which is enough reason to avoid @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N4P/PPP2PP1/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...b5  in the first place. }
