[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ We are going to check now a couple of systems that are pretty aggressive, especially if we compare them with the previous lessons where White played positional variations mostly. Now, I will discuss two systems that are very double-edged, which shouldn't come as a surprise as we are talking about the Najdorf.  As usual, I believe Black is doing fine in more than one way, while White will try to be as aggressive as possible. However, it might suit your style if you prefer sharp play with White, while Black will need to be very well prepared and very well aware of various move orders, as timing is essential in the Najdorf. }
6. h3
{ A modest-looking move, but in reality, it is quite a serious try and rather popular. You might wonder why isn't this move part of the previous lesson where we discussed positional play... The idea behind it is, in fact, very aggressive: g4 is played in almost every line followed by castling queenside, with very dangerous positions.   Now, Black has the usual dilemma: should  6...e6  or rather  6...e5  appear on the board? In fact, how about  6...b5  and  6...g6  @@StartBracket@@I wouldn't recommend them though@@EndBracket@@, which are also played often?  6...Nc6  is possible, but it doesn't combine well  with ...a6. }
6... e5 { By far the most popular and challenging move. } 7. Nb3
{ White has the pawn on h3 instead of f3, which is the subject of our last lesson in the Najdorf. The difference is that here, White will try to push f4. }
7... Be6
{ The main move, although it runs into f4-f5, but it does prevent White's plans with  8.g4  since that would be well met by  8...d5  . }
8. f4
{ The typical Najdorf tango: when Black develops the bishop to e7, White can throw in g4, while when the light-squared bishop is coming to e6, White tries to get in f4-f5. In this position, taking on f4 is not well timed as White's bishop didn't lose a tempo with Be3. }
8... g6
{ The main move, defending against f4-f5 and preparing to develop the bishop on the long diagonal.   8...Nc6  9.f5  Bxb3  10.axb3  is a little bit worse than with Be3 and ...Be7 included, but still may be playable.  10...d5  11.exd5  Nd4  − this variation should be checked. Maybe Black doesn't fully equalize, but it is not too bad either. The engine gives a small plus for White, however, that doesn't say much for such complex positions. }
9. Be2 Nbd7
{ This is how Maxime Vachier-Lagrave played against Wesley So a couple of times. }
10. O-O Rc8 { Putting ...Rxc3 on the menu in the future. } 11. Be3 Be7 12. f5
{ The engines give  12.Qe1  as a possible move. There are various tries for both sides along the way and analyzing everything in detail would be outside the scope of this course. It is just another complicated position that can be played with both colors if it suits your style.  If you have the impression that you understand the lines and you like this type of dynamic play, then go for it. Otherwise, wiser would be to switch to something else, as here, it is not possible to analyze it all to the smallest details and a clear-cut evaluation.  The position is too dynamic and murky, which makes your skills more important than the engine's assessment of these lines. Whether it is +0.2 or 0.00... who cares?! There are a lot of pieces on the board and very rich play, hence the computer's opinion is less relevant. }
12... gxf5 13. exf5 Bc4
{ This is how the game between Wesley So and Maxime Vachier-Lagrave continued when the engines assess the position as equal. }
*

