[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 49: Najdorf 6.Bc4 & 6.h3"]
[Black "Najdorf 6.Bc4 & 6.h3 - Conclusion"]
[Result "*"]

{ ♟ Fischer-Sozin Attack   To conclude: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bc4  is not as aggressive and dangerous as it looks. In fact, this system is in deep crisis for White, not in the sense that White cannot equalize, but Black's play is safe and simple. Of course, some moves and typical ideas must be known in advance in order to play accurately, but at the moment, White is unable to create anything tangible.  ♟ 6.h3 Najdorf   As White, if you like to have control over the game, then perhaps @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p2p1n2/4p3/3NP3/2N4P/PPP2PP1/R1BQKB1R w KQkq e6 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nde2  is your move since in  7.Nb3  , the positions are very sharp. Whether you choose @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N4P/PPP2PP1/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  or  6...e5  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.h3  is a very complicated line, which started to develop more and more, compared with the main moves  6.Be3  and  6.Bg5  , which we will check in a moment.  In  6.h3  , which is a rather young line, there is more room to explore, leading to very interesting and complicated flights. For Black, there is nothing to worry about, as play is a typical Najdorf one. Just take your time to digest all the data @@StartBracket@@sorry for the long lecture, but I want you to understand the nuances@@EndBracket@@. This is not the Petroff Defense, just one wrong move order and Black can get in serious trouble. Or being unaware of a strategic aspect can cost you the game.  As in all the Najdorf, Black has resources, and  6.h3  is surely not a refutation of this opening. We will move on now to the systems with  6.Bg5  and  6.Be3  , which are very big, but I will try my best to offer you the most valuable information, as Black must have a good answer against those two systems. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 50: Najdorf 6.Bg5"]
[Black "Najdorf 6.Bg5: 6...Nbd7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5
{ One of the sharpest and most dangerous systems in the Najdorf. I have some bad news for Black players: you'll need to learn tons of variations and memorize quite a few lines, fixing the exact move order in your mind, to get a good position out of the opening.White is playing for quick development and attack: any inaccuracy in Black's play may lead to losing the game right out of the opening. Having said that, the good news is that Black is doing well.For White players, the bad news is that Black has different options to obtain a fine position, so he gets to choose the direction of the game, which forces White players to study a lot.The bright side is that 6.Bg5 offers high chances of crushing your opponent at an early stage, especially an unprepared one.On the top level, things are rather straightforward: the player with a stronger engine and a better memory will prevail. This is a very exciting system for both sides at the club level.As usual, we'll explore the most critical lines and the most important ideas for White and Black players. For example, we won't stop at lines where White castles short since that goes against the spirit of 6.Bg5. }
6... Nbd7
{ A very playable though risky system many strong players have adopted, especially when they want to sidestep the lines where White has a forced draw at his disposal. In contrast with most of the other lines, here Black doesn't have to choose between getting trapped in a forced draw or playing something suboptimal and risk falling into a worse position. Here, Black can play for a win. }
7. Bc4
{ A dangerous extra option for White, made possible by Black's chosen move order. }
7... h6 { Black gets the bishop pair but loses important tempi. } 8. Bxf6 Nxf6
9. Qe2 { This position is rather dangerous for Black. } 9... e6
{ This has to be played sooner or later. } 10. O-O-O
{ White can quickly launch an attack with f4-f5 and Black lacks an adequate reaction. }
*

