[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5
{ One of the sharpest and most dangerous systems in the Najdorf. I have some bad news for Black players: you'll need to learn tons of variations and memorize quite a few lines, fixing the exact move order in your mind, to get a good position out of the opening.White is playing for quick development and attack: any inaccuracy in Black's play may lead to losing the game right out of the opening. Having said that, the good news is that Black is doing well.For White players, the bad news is that Black has different options to obtain a fine position, so he gets to choose the direction of the game, which forces White players to study a lot.The bright side is that 6.Bg5 offers high chances of crushing your opponent at an early stage, especially an unprepared one.On the top level, things are rather straightforward: the player with a stronger engine and a better memory will prevail. This is a very exciting system for both sides at the club level.As usual, we'll explore the most critical lines and the most important ideas for White and Black players. For example, we won't stop at lines where White castles short since that goes against the spirit of 6.Bg5. }
6... Nbd7
{ A very playable though risky system many strong players have adopted, especially when they want to sidestep the lines where White has a forced draw at his disposal. In contrast with most of the other lines, here Black doesn't have to choose between getting trapped in a forced draw or playing something suboptimal and risk falling into a worse position. Here, Black can play for a win. }
7. Qe2
{ The most popular choice, especially among White players who employ this move against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  7.f4  Nbd7  . However, Black has ways to avoid transpositions. }
7... h6 8. Bh4 { The main move. } 8... g6 9. f4
{ The most challenging. Alternatively, White can go for a slow game with  9.O-O-O  e5  10.Nb3  Be7  , but Black is happy to sidestep forcing lines and keep the game alive. }
9... e5 10. fxe5 dxe5 11. O-O-O Qc7 { But not  11...exd4  12.e5  . } 12. Nb3 b5
{ White has a huge development lead and the d5-square is weak, but things are not so clear. For example, after the direct  13.Nd5  Nxd5  14.exd5  Bd6  I'm not sure which side I would pick. }
13. Rxd7 { A very interesting sacrifice. } 13... Nxd7 14. Nd5 Qb8
{ Or  14...Qd6  15.Na5  . } 15. Na5
{ This is very sharp. Engines can be a great help in these lines but also spoil the fun. Very deep analysis shows this is finally a draw, but it is definitely a good try for White players if you think your opponent doesn't know it so well. }
