1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5
{ One of the sharpest and most dangerous systems in the Najdorf. I have some bad news for Black players: you'll need to learn tons of variations and memorize quite a few lines, fixing the exact move order in your mind, to get a good position out of the opening.White is playing for quick development and attack: any inaccuracy in Black's play may lead to losing the game right out of the opening. Having said that, the good news is that Black is doing well.For White players, the bad news is that Black has different options to obtain a fine position, so he gets to choose the direction of the game, which forces White players to study a lot.The bright side is that 6.Bg5 offers high chances of crushing your opponent at an early stage, especially an unprepared one.On the top level, things are rather straightforward: the player with a stronger engine and a better memory will prevail. This is a very exciting system for both sides at the club level.As usual, we'll explore the most critical lines and the most important ideas for White and Black players. For example, we won't stop at lines where White castles short since that goes against the spirit of 6.Bg5. }
6... e6 { By far, the main move. } 7. f4
{ The main tabiya of the variation. Black has a lot of moves here, but some are dubious after being refuted by engines. I'd say  7...Nbd7  and  7...Be7  are the soundest and most human options, whereas  7...Qb6  is taken over by engines and there, memory weighs more than chess skills. }
7... Qb6
{ There's some overlap with  7...h6  8.Bh4  Qb6  . This line is nowadays more suitable for professional players than amateurs. I wouldn't recommend it because there's not much play: it's mostly about memorizing powerful engine lines.Anyway, White players should know how to fight it and some people may want to add it to their repertoire as Black. I won't pretend to cover all the lines because of their complexity. An engine will be more useful than me to help you navigate this system. Keep in mind that if you miss or forget one move, or if your opponent's engine is stronger than yours, you're toast.I'll add that  7...Qb6  is a perfectly sound system and, actually, the reason why I didn't play 6.Bg5 against the Najdorf. I struggled to find an advantage and didn't want to enter a memory contest with my opponent, but rather play some chess.Maxime Vachier-Lagrave is a big specialist in Najdorf @@StartBracket@@I encourage you to study his games@@EndBracket@@ and a regular player of this system... and too often he loses because he mixes up move orders and subtleties. Memory matters! }
8. a3
{ This is not as dangerous as after  7...h6  8.Bh4  Qb6  because there's no Bf2. }
8... Nbd7
{ 8...Nc6  9.Nb3  Be7  10.Qf3  is interesting, but I consider the text to be more precise. }
9. f5
{ White can play  9.Bh4!?  intending Bf2. Instead,  9.Qd2  is not working:  9...Qxb2  10.Nb3  Nc5!  saving the queen. This resource is available thanks to White's a3. }
9... exf5 { The simplest. } 10. exf5
{ Forced, as  10.Nxf5  Qxb2  11.Na4  Qe5  is clearly a dream for Black's queen. }
10... Be7
{ Black is fine. White can't castle queenside and the best is probably  11.Bc4  and O-O now. }
