[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 50: Najdorf 6.Bg5"]
[Black "Najdorf 6.Bg5: 7...Be7 8.Qf3 - 10.Bd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5
{ One of the sharpest and most dangerous systems in the Najdorf. I have some bad news for Black players: you'll need to learn tons of variations and memorize quite a few lines, fixing the exact move order in your mind, to get a good position out of the opening.White is playing for quick development and attack: any inaccuracy in Black's play may lead to losing the game right out of the opening. Having said that, the good news is that Black is doing well.For White players, the bad news is that Black has different options to obtain a fine position, so he gets to choose the direction of the game, which forces White players to study a lot.The bright side is that 6.Bg5 offers high chances of crushing your opponent at an early stage, especially an unprepared one.On the top level, things are rather straightforward: the player with a stronger engine and a better memory will prevail. This is a very exciting system for both sides at the club level.As usual, we'll explore the most critical lines and the most important ideas for White and Black players. For example, we won't stop at lines where White castles short since that goes against the spirit of 6.Bg5. }
6... e6 { By far, the main move. } 7. f4
{ The main tabiya of the variation. Black has a lot of moves here, but some are dubious after being refuted by engines. I'd say  7...Nbd7  and  7...Be7  are the soundest and most human options, whereas  7...Qb6  is taken over by engines and there, memory weighs more than chess skills. }
7... Be7
{ Compared to  7...Nbd7  , here White only has one challenging setup. } 8. Qf3
{ The only reasonable move. As I said, going for short castle is harmless. }
8... Qc7 { Black wants to play ...Nbd7, ...b5 and ...Bb7. } 9. O-O-O Nbd7
{ White is at a crossroads. Both paths are complicated and play is pretty direct. White can't afford to play a slow game and let Black complete his development as intended. Therefore,  10.Kb1?  would be a mistake due to  10...b5  and if  11.e5  Bb7  White has lost an important tempo. }
10. Bd3 b5 11. Rhe1
{ White just completes his development and tries to start some central action. }
11... Bb7
{ Again  12.Kb1  is too slow:  12...Qb6  is a thematic reply, forcing the knight to retreat.  13.Nb3  b4  Black launches his counterattack.  14.Ne2  a5  15.Nd2  a4  and Black is better. That doesn't mean that White is going to be checkmated right now, but he has no central breaks, lacks coordination, and Black has excellent play. }
12. Nd5 Nxd5 { The alternative if you don't like sacrifices. } 13. exd5 Bxg5
{ This is good enough. } 14. fxg5 Ne5 15. Qh3 Bxd5
{ The main line continues  16.g6  but White can equalize at most. } *

