14. Rg1 { White's most promising continuation. } 14... b4
{ The thematic counterstrike. } 15. Nce2 e5
{ Now  15...Bb7  runs into an improved version ofthis line because now Black can't take twice on f6. He can try  16.f6  Bd8  but he's unlikely to survive. }
16. f6 { White's only reasonable try. } 16... exd4
{ This works well now for Black. } 17. fxe7 Re8 18. Nxd4 Ne5
{ If you want to play this variation, this is where your analysis starts :-@@EndBracket@@ White has some initiative with moves like  19.Qf4  @@StartBracket@@Giri-Grischuk@@EndBracket@@ or  19.Qb3  , but Black holds with accurate defense.All in all,  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p2ppn2/6B1/3NPP2/2N5/PPP3PP/R2QKB1R b KQkq f3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Be7  is very direct, but Black should hold even against White's most promising try,  @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/1pqnbppp/p2ppn2/6B1/3NPP2/2N2Q2/PPP3PP/2KR1B1R w kq - 5 10@@EndFEN@@  10.g4  and then  @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/2qnbppp/p2pp3/1p3PP1/3NP3/2N2Q2/PPP4P/2KR1B1R w - - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Rg1  .Anyway, White can certainly go for this knowing that it offers some initiative and his opponent will need a very deep preparation to survive with a draw. }
