{ The most popular line and something I would certainly recommend to Black players. The game is usually not so forcing and definitely more interesting, even though inevitably you will need to memorize some lines. Still, it's more human and more chess than other systems covered in this chapter. As usual,  8.Qd2  h6  is not how White plays in the 6.Bg5 Najdorf. }
8. Qe2 { The most dangerous try according to the current state of theory. }
8... Qc7 9. O-O-O b5
{ The same type of play we've seen throughout this chapter, but here the lines are not so forcing. }
10. a3 { Prophylaxis against Black's standard ...b4 push. } 10... Be7
{ Black's best. } 11. g4
{ Not a lot of good ideas are available. In contrast with the Qf3 setups, here White can challenge any ...Bb7 with Bg2, but there are no Bxb5 tactics. }
11... h6
{ Black has to play this move sooner or later and I believe this is the accurate move order. }
12. Bh4
{ Now Black has two plans. This is a very rich position, full of possibilities, and it's hard to reach a clear verdict. }
12... Bb7 13. Bg2 Qc4
{ A solid move. White has nothing better than trading queens.  13...Rc8  14.Be1  is an interesting alternative, intending ...Nb6 and ...Nc4. }
14. Qxc4 bxc4 15. h3
{ As usual, engines claim a slight plus for White, but the position is very rich. }
15... Nc5 16. Rhe1 { Protecting the e4-pawn and intending to push f5. } 16...
Rc8 17. f5 Rc7
{ The engine's suggestion, probably some prophylaxis against e5. Maybe White has a tiny plus, but nothing serious.In conclusion, both @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p2ppn2/6B1/3NPP2/2N5/PPP3PP/R2QKB1R b KQkq f3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nbd7  and  7...Be7  are in good shape. Of course, you need to know! Well, now you know :-@@EndBracket@@White has only one reasonable setup against  7...Be7  , but it is quite promising. On the other hand, Black shouldn't worry against White's two possible plans after  7...Nbd7  . Then,  8.Qf3  is more or less neutralized, whereas  8.Qe2  leads to incredibly rich play. }
