[White "Lesson 50: Najdorf 6.Bg5"]
[Black "Najdorf 6.Bg5 - Conclusion"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5
{ All in all,  6.Bg5  is not that dangerous, objectively speaking. Black has different good systems, mainly  6...e6  7.f4  Qb6  ,  7...Be7  or  7...Nbd7  . All of them are holdable. Let's not forget  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nbd7  , maybe not as principled as the big three but still very playable. Definitely, Black has a choice.On the other hand, Black is walking a narrow path, which makes 6.Bg5 a very dangerous weapon at a non-professional level, where the depth of the analysis and preparation is not as serious as among the elite.Also, those who won't buy this course won't acquire all that knowledge, which will enable you to crush them after their first slip :-@@EndBracket@@ }
