[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 51: English Attack 6.Be3 & 6.f3"]
[Black "English Attack 6.Be3 e5 7.Nb3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ Welcome back! Your diligence is impressive given the amount of data you had to digest, but good news: today we are going to finish the Najdorf, hopefully. And the subject of this lesson is a variation that is considered one of the most dangerous weapons against the Najdorf − we are going to study the English Attack, which is the most popular variation at the top level.  We will check both  6.Be3  and  6.f3  , which, essentially, lead to the same system, but there are some nuances, however. Most of the time, White has both moves in the repertoire since after playing  6.f3  , it is hard to avoid continuing with Be3 against both of Black's systems:  6...e6  or  6...e5  . If White starts with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  , that yields additional options not only for White but for Black too. }
6. Be3
{ Let's start with  6.Be3  and see the theory where White is not playing f3, and then we  move on to  6.f3  , when we will discuss all the main lines. After both @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  and  6...e5  , White has a number of interesting options, especially against  6...e6  , this system  without f3 could prove even more dangerous. }
6... e5
{ Lately, the strong players are trying to play  6...e5  against most lines in the Najdorf, which could be a matter of fashion, but also the engines incline towards  the ...e5 setups.  Also, if against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.f3  you play  6...e5  , it is very logical to answer @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  in a similar fashion. In this section, we will check  the lines without f3, which I believe don't give Black many headaches. }
7. Nb3 { The main move, but I don't think Black has any issues. } 7... Be6 8.
f4
{ Perhaps the only independent continuation, otherwise, the position will transpose to other systems, for instance, after  8.Be2  , we reach the same position as in @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be2  e5  7.Nb3  , which we've studied already.   8.h3  is a possible move and you can check the lesson on @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.h3  e5  7.Nb3  , while @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/1p3ppp/p2pbn2/4p3/4P3/1NN1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.f3  followed by Qd2 and long castle will also lead to transpositions we are going to consider later. }
8... exf4 9. Bxf4 Nc6 10. Nd4
{ This could have been interesting, hadn't it been for Black's strong reply. Also, after  10.Qd2  , Black equalizes easily with  10...d5  . }
10... Qb6 11. Nxe6 fxe6
{ Black is doing very well. White can maybe still equalize, but no more than that since castling is now a difficult task. }
