{ Lately, the strong players are trying to play  6...e5  against most lines in the Najdorf, which could be a matter of fashion, but also the engines incline towards  the ...e5 setups.  Also, if against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.f3  you play  6...e5  , it is very logical to answer @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  in a similar fashion. In this section, we will check  the lines without f3, which I believe don't give Black many headaches. }
7. Nf3
{ Instead of playing all the concrete lines, White has the option of going for slow, positional play. This won't yield a big advantage, of course, but it is always a good idea to play accurately as Black since this is the type of Sicilian that resembles Petroff. If you get a worse position, you will suffer for the rest of the game and defend passively. I would recommend this variation for White, at least from time to time since Black's task is not trivial. }
7... Qc7
{ Stopping Bc4 ideas, but I am not sure Black is equalizing in this line, which is why I would recommend  7...Be7  instead. }
8. a4
{ White can also start with  8.Be2  because  8...b5  doesn't work here @@StartBracket@@Black should go for  8...Be7  , when White can still answer with  9.a4  , with better play@@EndBracket@@. @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/2q2ppp/p2p1n2/1p2p3/4P3/2N1BN2/PPP1BPPP/R2QK2R w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.a4  b4  10.Nd5  Nxd5  11.Qxd5  Bb7  12.Qb3  and White is considerably better. }
8... Be7 9. a5 { It is a bit early to put the pawn on a5. } 9... O-O 10. Be2
Nc6
{ Targeting the pawn on a5, but the engines give the strange-looking  10...Bd8  as well, the point being that after  11.Bb6  , Black  has a nice square on e7 for the queen. After a further ...Nc6, Black will probably equalize already. }
11. Bb6 Qb8 12. Nd5 { A principled move. } 12... Be6 13. Nc7 Nxe4
{ The exchange sacrifice works pretty well here since Black has good compensation with the knight on e4, good hold in the center, and ...d5 and ...f5 incoming. This is why @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/1pq1bppp/p2p1n2/4p3/P3P3/2N1BN2/1PP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Be2  is stronger, in my opinion. }
