{ If White stabilizes here with Ne3, Rd2, Rd1, Black can suffer in the long run. }
16... f5
{ An important resource that brings Black a typical Sveshnikov counterplay. }
17. exf5 Bxf5 18. Ne3 Bg6 19. Nc4 { Pressing the pawn on d6. } 19... Bh5 20.
Nxd6 Rf4
{ Defending against Qc4+, and an illustration that Black can start playing for an advantage if White goes too far. }
