{ 10...h6  is a logical move,  preventing Bg5 ideas, but now Black allows White to reach the f5-square after  11.Nh4  . I won in a similar fashion a Rapid game against Veselin Topalov in 2003. }
11. Qe2 Na5
{ 11...Rc8  12.Rfd1  Qc7  is also very solid for Black, but the text move is more direct and also has the stamp of approval by both Gelfand and Karjakin. }
12. Rfd1
{ Of course, if  12.Bxe6  fxe6  , White has nothing in this structure given the knight that is  misplaced on f3 @@StartBracket@@unless it wins by force the pawn on e6@@EndBracket@@. }
12... Nxb3 13. axb3 { The classical and healthier-looking approach. } 13... Qc7
{ White will always have a problem with the c2-pawn after a rook will land on c8 and the c3-knight will be tied up. Obviously, White would be happy if  13...h6  appears on the board in view of  14.Nxe5  . }
14. Bg5 { Otherwise, after ...h6, Black will be at least equal. } 14... Nh5
{ The most clear-cut equality. After  14...Rac8  15.Bxf6  Bxf6  16.Ne1  , White is planning to bring the 2nd knight to  d5  via  d3  and  b4  , with a playable position. }
15. Nxe5 { 15.Bxe7  Qxe7  is harmless. } 15... Bxg5
{ We are following the game Kamsky-Gelfand, Candidates Tournament, Kazan 2011, which was won by Boris Gelfand. }
16. Qxh5 Bf6 17. Nf3 Bxc3 18. bxc3 Qxc3 19. Nd4 Rae8
{ And it is quite clear that the game should end in a draw. } *

