[White "Lesson 51: English Attack 6.Be3 & 6.f3"]
[Black "English Attack 6.Be3 e5 7.Nf3 Be7 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ Welcome back! Your diligence is impressive given the amount of data you had to digest, but good news: today we are going to finish the Najdorf, hopefully. And the subject of this lesson is a variation that is considered one of the most dangerous weapons against the Najdorf − we are going to study the English Attack, which is the most popular variation at the top level.  We will check both  6.Be3  and  6.f3  , which, essentially, lead to the same system, but there are some nuances, however. Most of the time, White has both moves in the repertoire since after playing  6.f3  , it is hard to avoid continuing with Be3 against both of Black's systems:  6...e6  or  6...e5  . If White starts with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  , that yields additional options not only for White but for Black too. }
6. Be3
{ Let's start with  6.Be3  and see the theory where White is not playing f3, and then we  move on to  6.f3  , when we will discuss all the main lines. After both @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  and  6...e5  , White has a number of interesting options, especially against  6...e6  , this system  without f3 could prove even more dangerous. }
6... e5
{ Lately, the strong players are trying to play  6...e5  against most lines in the Najdorf, which could be a matter of fashion, but also the engines incline towards  the ...e5 setups.  Also, if against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.f3  you play  6...e5  , it is very logical to answer @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  in a similar fashion. In this section, we will check  the lines without f3, which I believe don't give Black many headaches. }
7. Nf3
{ Instead of playing all the concrete lines, White has the option of going for slow, positional play. This won't yield a big advantage, of course, but it is always a good idea to play accurately as Black since this is the type of Sicilian that resembles Petroff. If you get a worse position, you will suffer for the rest of the game and defend passively. I would recommend this variation for White, at least from time to time since Black's task is not trivial. }
7... Be7
{ The most popular move, at least at the GM level, and also my recommendation. }
8. Bc4
{ White has now this square available for the bishop, which is a bit unpleasant but not too dramatic either. }
8... O-O
{ Just don't hurry with  8...b5  9.Bd5  Nxd5  10.Qxd5  ,  as suddenly the rook on a8 is in jeopardy. }
9. O-O Be6
{ Sometimes Black starts with  9...Nc6  , but after  10.Qe2  , we will have similar positions to the ones from the main line. }
10. Bb3 Nc6
{ 10...h6  is a logical move,  preventing Bg5 ideas, but now Black allows White to reach the f5-square after  11.Nh4  . I won in a similar fashion a Rapid game against Veselin Topalov in 2003. }
11. Qe2 Na5
{ 11...Rc8  12.Rfd1  Qc7  is also very solid for Black, but the text move is more direct and also has the stamp of approval by both Gelfand and Karjakin. }
12. Rfd1
{ Of course, if  12.Bxe6  fxe6  , White has nothing in this structure given the knight that is  misplaced on f3 @@StartBracket@@unless it wins by force the pawn on e6@@EndBracket@@. }
12... Nxb3 13. cxb3
{ Played by Carlsen in Rapid, which may look a bit odd, but it does make some sense, as White will no longer have an issue with the c2-pawn, while  13...Qc7  will run into  14.Rac1  .  Also, the Nf3-e1-c2-b4 maneuver became available, but it is still a long way though. }
13... Qe8
{ Correctly played by Karjakin in a Rapid game against Carlsen, which he also won. }
14. Ne1 Ng4
{ I don't know if after  14...h6  15.Nc2  Rc8  , White has anything special.  Even if White brings the knight to b4 and d5, Black can play ...Nxd5, and continue with ...Bd8 at some point, then ...f5, and it is not much for White. Karjakin chose to play more aggressively though. }
15. Nc2 f5
{ Black created counterplay and slowly but surely won in Carlsen-Karjakin. This is also what Gelfand is playing against the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p2p1n2/4p3/3NP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq e6 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nf3  variation, who is an expert in the Najdorf and also a good analyst. We can surely trust him, as mentioned several times already, especially if we speak about classical games. However, it is not completely poisonless and can be tried with White as well. }
*

