ous tries. }
7. a3
{ Another annoying move to face as Black. It may look a bit weird and slow but it is quite new and interesting actually. The strong engines pointed it out and it does make a lot of sense, even though some people may laugh seeing it on the board.   7.Be2  is also possible. You should check out the lesson about @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be2  e6  ,  when the most dangerous plans are not connected with O-O but more with  7.Be3  and f4 ideas, when it is not so easy for Black to equalize. Therefore, this is an interesting try for White, in case Black  plays @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  . Perhaps you remember that starting with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be2  allows Black to answer with  6...e5  , which is a good continuation for Black. }
7... b5 { White's point of 7.a3 is revealed in this variation. } 8. g4
{ Now,  8...e5  9.Nf5  is just bad for Black. } 8... Bb7 9. Bg2
