1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ Welcome back! Your diligence is impressive given the amount of data you had to digest, but good news: today we are going to finish the Najdorf, hopefully. And the subject of this lesson is a variation that is considered one of the most dangerous weapons against the Najdorf − we are going to study the English Attack, which is the most popular variation at the top level.  We will check both  6.Be3  and  6.f3  , which, essentially, lead to the same system, but there are some nuances, however. Most of the time, White has both moves in the repertoire since after playing  6.f3  , it is hard to avoid continuing with Be3 against both of Black's systems:  6...e6  or  6...e5  . If White starts with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  , that yields additional options not only for White but for Black too. }
6. Be3
{ Let's start with  6.Be3  and see the theory where White is not playing f3, and then we  move on to  6.f3  , when we will discuss all the main lines. After both @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  and  6...e5  , White has a number of interesting options, especially against  6...e6  , this system  without f3 could prove even more dangerous. }
6... e6
{ A rare guest in tournament practice nowadays − end of the '90s, beginning of this century, this move was more popular, and then slowly but surely the attention started to shift towards  6...e5  . Garry Kasparov was an advocate of  the ...e6 structures back in the day, and he played this type of Scheveningen with very good results.  That doesn't mean his solutions correspond to the objective evaluations of these positions, but the whole point of the Najdorf, and the whole Sicilian in general, is that even if White is better on paper, the game is so complicated that all three results are on the cards. By comparison, in the Ruy Lopez or Petroff, if White is slightly better, that means Black will just have to defend for the rest of the game and maybe you will manage to avoid losing.  In the Sicilian, you can be objectively worse according to the engine, and still win your game since the positions are very sharp. Kasparov had a very good feel in those dynamic positions and I remember Linares 1999 when he was winning every game with Black in the Sicilian, crushing everybody. I think I was one of the few who held a draw against him with White, but maybe that has to do with my opening choice: 1.d4. :@@EndBracket@@  Kasparov won with Black against Anand, Svidler, and Ivanchuk... all getting crushed in the Najdorf. Nowadays,  6...e6  became less fashionable, not because it is a bad choice but both  6...e5  and  6...Ng4  give White difficulties getting an advantage out of the opening.  6...e6  on the other hand, hands White a few additional options. Even if against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.f3  you are playing the  6...e6  system, against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  I would advise you to think twice because, on top of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p2ppn2/8/3NP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.f3  , White has quite a number of dangerous tries. }
7. a3
{ Another annoying move to face as Black. It may look a bit weird and slow but it is quite new and interesting actually. The strong engines pointed it out and it does make a lot of sense, even though some people may laugh seeing it on the board.   7.Be2  is also possible. You should check out the lesson about @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be2  e6  ,  when the most dangerous plans are not connected with O-O but more with  7.Be3  and f4 ideas, when it is not so easy for Black to equalize. Therefore, this is an interesting try for White, in case Black  plays @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  . Perhaps you remember that starting with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be2  allows Black to answer with  6...e5  , which is a good continuation for Black. }
7... Nc6
{ Maybe a better try, but here too, White has options:  8.Be2  or  8.f4  . } 8.
Be2 Be7 9. Qd2 Bd7
{ Transposing to a position in the Sicilian that is quite dangerous for Black. Here though, it is less harmful as White lost a bit of time to include a3, but this move can also be useful often. Let's see an example. }
10. O-O-O b5 11. Kb1
{ White slowed down Black's counterplay on the queenside, while f4 and g4 are on the cards, with a complicated game, but not completely harmless for Black. }
*

