ous tries. }
7. g4
{ This is an annoying move for Black to face, leading to very direct play in the style of Keres Attack. Since I am not sure whether giving a perpetual check to make a draw in a very forced line suits your taste, perhaps it is better to choose differently on move 6 with Black.   7.Be2  is another possibility. You should check out the lesson about @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be2  e6  ,  when the most dangerous plans are not connected with O-O but more with  7.Be3  and f4 ideas, when it is not so easy for Black to equalize. Therefore, this is an interesting try for White, in case Black  plays @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  . Perhaps you remember that starting with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be2  allows Black to answer with  6...e5  , which is a good continuation for Black. }
7... d5
{ Sadly, this move doesn't equalize and White has two ways to be slightly better:  8.g5  and  8.exd5  . }
8. g5
