8... g6 { The main line, when the fun starts. } 9. g5 gxf5 10. exf5 d5 11. Qf3
{ This position is so difficult to analyze, even for computers, that I am not sure there is a final verdict for this position. Playing it with Black, however, requires very diligent work and move-by-move memorization in many variations.  It is too hard to play this over the board for Black since White's play is much easier: just attack. With such a king in the center on e8, even with two pieces down, White is simply going for mate and you have to be an extremely good tactician and calculator, to survive. }
11... d4
{ Black has to play the only moves, otherwise the position collapses. } 12.
O-O-O Nbd7 13. Bd2
{ The main move. Additionally, White has  13.Bxd4  and  13.Bc4  as well, making this position a very exciting and interesting one, but maybe for analysis purposes rather than choosing to play it in classical games @@StartBracket@@unless you are extremely well prepared with Black@@EndBracket@@.  Shirov won many games with White here, which is not surprising given the positions suit his style like a glove. The final evaluations say that Black can hold a draw, but reaching there in such complicated and long lines scares off many players and it is the reason why they stay away from @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  . }
13... dxc3 14. Bxc3 Bg7 15. Rg1
{ This is how the beautiful game Polgar-Anand @@StartBracket@@Dos Hermanas 1999@@EndBracket@@ went, when White proved this line is quite a problem for Black.   You can have a look at the rest of the game, as I am sure you won't regret it:  15...O-O  16.gxf6  Qxf6  17.Qe3  Kh8  18.f4  Qb6  19.Qg3  Qh6  20.Rd6  f6  21.Bd2  e4  22.Bc4  b5  23.Be6  Ra7  24.Rc6  a5  25.Be3  Rb7  26.Bd5  Rb8  27.Rc7  b4  28.b3  Rb5  29.Bc6  Rxf5  30.Rxc8  Rxc8  31.Bxd7  Rcc5  32.Bxf5  Rxf5  33.Rd1  Kg8  34.Qg2  1-0. }
