[White "Lesson 51: English Attack 6.Be3 & 6.f3"]
[Black "English Attack 6.Be3 Ng4 − 8.Bh4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ Welcome back! Your diligence is impressive given the amount of data you had to digest, but good news: today we are going to finish the Najdorf, hopefully. And the subject of this lesson is a variation that is considered one of the most dangerous weapons against the Najdorf − we are going to study the English Attack, which is the most popular variation at the top level.  We will check both  6.Be3  and  6.f3  , which, essentially, lead to the same system, but there are some nuances, however. Most of the time, White has both moves in the repertoire since after playing  6.f3  , it is hard to avoid continuing with Be3 against both of Black's systems:  6...e6  or  6...e5  . If White starts with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  , that yields additional options not only for White but for Black too. }
6. Be3
{ Let's start with  6.Be3  and see the theory where White is not playing f3, and then we  move on to  6.f3  , when we will discuss all the main lines. After both @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  and  6...e5  , White has a number of interesting options, especially against  6...e6  , this system  without f3 could prove even more dangerous. }
6... Ng4
{ Nonetheless, Black also gets an additional option with this move, which was developed by Kasparov, and currently, Black is doing well in this line. White is unable to pose any serious problems and at the top level,  6...Ng4  is very annoying to face. Of course, it's not very easy to equalize either, White has a number of tries, but it is a very serious option for Black. }
7. Bg5
{ On a side note, I see often players who want to go for the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  system, but when they have to deal with  6...Ng4  , often play  7.Bc1  here, and after  7...Nf6  , which is considered the best move, they switch back to  8.f3  positions or another system altogether. }
7... h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Bg3 Bg7
{ Kasparov developed this system, where White tried many moves here. } 10. Be2
h5 { In many lines, ...h4 is a threat and White must address it. } 11. Bxg4
{ In the past, this was the main move. } 11... hxg4
{ 11...Bxg4  12.f3  Bd7  was preferred by Kasparov and he won a few nice games in this line. However, he also lost some, for instance against Anand in a Rapid game in 1998. But since the text move sterilizes this variation, Kasparov also switched to  taking on g4 with the pawn, and he played that against Shirov in Wijk aan Zee 1999. }
12. O-O Nc6 13. Nf5 { Otherwise, White will just be worse. } 13... Bxc3 14.
bxc3 f6 15. Qxg4 Qa5
{ White is a pawn up, but due to the doubled pawns on the c-file and the limited bishop on g3, Black is doing fine also thanks to the nice control over the e5-square. The position should be about equal. }
*

