7... h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Bg3 Bg7
{ Kasparov developed this system, where White tried many moves here. } 10. Be2
h5 { In many lines, ...h4 is a threat and White must address it. } 11. h4
{ This is, perhaps, White's best chance and also played at the top level. For example, MVL played it with both colors. }
11... gxh4 { You can also start with  11...Nc6  12.Nb3  and  now take on h4. }
12. Bxh4 Nc6 13. Nb3
{ Black's king is in the center, and the pawn on h5 is a bit weak, but the pieces are very active, especially the knight on g4, and that compensates for the weaknesses in Black's position. }
13... Be6
{ Computers claim that  13...Bxc3+  is also perfectly playable. Following  14.bxc3  Rg8  15.Qd2  Be6  , Black may be just fine, but I would still prefer @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1p2ppb1/p1np4/7p/4P1nB/1NN5/PPP1BPP1/R2QK2R b KQkq - 2 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Be6  . }
14. Qd2 Rc8
{ Black also gets an attack in case White castles long, for instance with ...Nb4, so both sides must be careful. }
15. f3 Bh6 16. Bg5 Bxg5 17. Qxg5 Nf6
{ There were many games here, for instance, MVL-Mamedyarov or Svidler-Gelfand, and Black has enough counterplay − the king seems to be safe on e8. }
