{ On a side note, I see often players who want to go for the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  system, but when they have to deal with  6...Ng4  , often play  7.Bc1  here, and after  7...Nf6  , which is considered the best move, they switch back to  8.f3  positions or another system altogether. }
7... h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Bg3 Bg7
{ Kasparov developed this system, where White tried many moves here. } 10. h3
Nf6 { The old move, which is not refuted at all. } 11. Bc4 Qb6
{ There was an interesting Kasparov-Polgar game in this position, Wijk aan Zee 2000, which was won by Kasparov. }
12. O-O { If  12.Nb3  Nc6  13.Qe2  Ne5  . } 12... O-O 13. Nde2 Qxb2
{ Garry sacrificed a pawn, which is a rather unclear decision. Judit accepted the offer, leading to very unclear play, but  13...Nbd7  followed  by ...Ne5 or ... Nc5 is perfectly playable as well. }
14. Bb3 Qa3
{ The game continued with  15.f4  and a very complicated fight ensued.  15...Nc6  16.Kh1  Be6  17.Qd3  Rac8  18.fxg5  hxg5  19.Nd5  Rfe8  20.Rad1  Nb4  21.Qf3  Nbxd5  22.exd5  Bd7  23.c3  a5  24.Qd3  a4  25.Bc2  Qc5  26.Rxf6  exf6  27.Qh7+  Kf8  28.Nd4  Re5  29.Bxe5  fxe5  30.Ne6+  Bxe6  31.dxe6  Rc7  32.Bxa4  d5  33.Qf5  Qc4  34.Bd7  Qf4  35.Qb1  fxe6  36.Bxe6  Ke7  37.Bxd5  Rd7  38.c4  Qe3  39.Qh7  Kd8  40.Rb1  Qf4  41.Be6  Re7  42.Bg4  Rf7  43.Qd3+  Qd4  44.Qg6  1-0. }
