{ Welcome back! Your diligence is impressive given the amount of data you had to digest, but good news: today we are going to finish the Najdorf, hopefully. And the subject of this lesson is a variation that is considered one of the most dangerous weapons against the Najdorf − we are going to study the English Attack, which is the most popular variation at the top level.  We will check both  6.Be3  and  6.f3  , which, essentially, lead to the same system, but there are some nuances, however. Most of the time, White has both moves in the repertoire since after playing  6.f3  , it is hard to avoid continuing with Be3 against both of Black's systems:  6...e6  or  6...e5  . If White starts with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  , that yields additional options not only for White but for Black too. }
6. f3
{ Lately, the players start with  6.f3  , in order to eliminate the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Ng4  option. }
6... Qb6
{ This move had its share of short popularity. The idea of having a compact and manageable repertoire against the English Attack sounds perfect @@StartBracket@@against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  , Black can answer  6...Ng4  , while @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.f3  would be met by the not-so theoretically heavy  6...Qb6  @@EndBracket@@, but sadly,  6...Qb6  is pretty bad for Black. }
7. g4 Nc6 8. Nb3 e6 9. g5 Nd7 10. Qe2
{ As it often happens when the pawn is on g5, Black's position will get under pressure. }
10... Qc7 11. Be3 b5 12. O-O-O Nb6
{ Black is already in trouble, even if, visually, it looks like some counterplay can be found with ...Nc4. }
13. Qf2 Rb8 14. Kb1
{ 30-40 years ago, this line was considered decent enough for Black, but that is no longer the case. Besides, White can already take aggressive measures by playing  14.f4  instead. }
14... Na4 15. Ne2 Ne5 16. Bc1
{ The +1.5 engine's evaluation should be enough proof that Black has no meaningful attack. In other words, we have no other choice as Black but to study the main lines with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N2P2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e5  or  6...e6  since  6...Qb6  is plain bad. }
