1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ Welcome back! Your diligence is impressive given the amount of data you had to digest, but good news: today we are going to finish the Najdorf, hopefully. And the subject of this lesson is a variation that is considered one of the most dangerous weapons against the Najdorf − we are going to study the English Attack, which is the most popular variation at the top level.  We will check both  6.Be3  and  6.f3  , which, essentially, lead to the same system, but there are some nuances, however. Most of the time, White has both moves in the repertoire since after playing  6.f3  , it is hard to avoid continuing with Be3 against both of Black's systems:  6...e6  or  6...e5  . If White starts with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  , that yields additional options not only for White but for Black too. }
6. f3
{ Lately, the players start with  6.f3  , in order to eliminate the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Ng4  option. }
6... e6
{ Black has two options here:  6...e6  or  6...e5  since anything else would lead to better Dragon or Rauzer positions for White. I believe  6...e5  is the most direct and challenging option, while after  6...e6  , it is not so easy to equalize, but the positions are very complicated. }
7. Be3 h5
{ Lately, Black is going for this move, stopping  g4  , which is quite a revolutionary decision since, back in the day, it was considered that castling kingside will no longer be possible while having the king in the center is not ideal either. Nowadays, ...h5 became the main move, but the question for both @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.f3  e6  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.f3  e5  ,  is when exactly should ...h5 be played?  Warning: there are many nuances and move orders, which are difficult for me too. I tried to be as structured as possible, in order to explain the differences for a wide range of players, and I believe this course can be very useful for amateurs, club players, and GMs alike. Don't get flustered if you will get the feeling that you've got lost and cannot follow, it is simply very difficult. Just return to the generous information you have in this course, play more Rapid and Blitz games to get accustomed to the positions, and slowly you will get to understand all these move orders.  From this lesson alone, I expect a mess in your head due to all the nuances and details. But it is important to know the forced variations, and understand the general patterns and the precise move orders since alone, just looking at the online games or computer suggestions, is extremely hard. I will do my very best, however, to eliminate any confusion!  In this position, it looks a bit desperate to throw in ...h5 already, but quite a few players are not worried about that. }
8. Qd2
{ This is another option for White when again, the pawn on h5 is not so well placed, while  8.a4  has also been played by Fabiano Caruana. Let's just quickly reach the position I would like to explain further: }
8... Nbd7 9. O-O-O b5 10. a3 Bb7 11. Kb1 Rc8
{ The tabiya in this line, but the question remains: how exactly should Black reach it? }
