[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 51: English Attack 6.Be3 & 6.f3"]
[Black "English Attack 6.f3 e6 7.Be3 b5 8.Qd2 Nbd7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ Welcome back! Your diligence is impressive given the amount of data you had to digest, but good news: today we are going to finish the Najdorf, hopefully. And the subject of this lesson is a variation that is considered one of the most dangerous weapons against the Najdorf − we are going to study the English Attack, which is the most popular variation at the top level.  We will check both  6.Be3  and  6.f3  , which, essentially, lead to the same system, but there are some nuances, however. Most of the time, White has both moves in the repertoire since after playing  6.f3  , it is hard to avoid continuing with Be3 against both of Black's systems:  6...e6  or  6...e5  . If White starts with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  , that yields additional options not only for White but for Black too. }
6. f3
{ Lately, the players start with  6.f3  , in order to eliminate the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Ng4  option. }
6... e6
{ Black has two options here:  6...e6  or  6...e5  since anything else would lead to better Dragon or Rauzer positions for White. I believe  6...e5  is the most direct and challenging option, while after  6...e6  , it is not so easy to equalize, but the positions are very complicated. }
7. Be3 b5
{ Now, White has a variety of moves to choose from, each of them containing its own venom and nuances. }
8. Qd2
{ The most natural move and, perhaps, the most dangerous too, as getting the ...h5 system in becomes more difficult compared to, for example,  8.a3  where  8...h5  is an option for Black. }
8... Nbd7
{ Practically, the only move. Playing  8...b4  now is not leading anywhere, as White hasn't weakened  the structure with g4, and Black will simply be worse. }
9. g4
{ A very principled move and I hope I am still making sense and that you are still able to follow, but since this system is pretty much about move orders, we have to try and digest them. }
9... h6
{ 9...Bb7  would run into  10.g5  when even though the engines hold with  10...Nh5  for the moment, the position is better for White. }
10. a3
{ Again, a very important move. It is very difficult to make sense of it all, so please hang on! If  10.O-O-O  instead, Black has  10...b4  11.Na4  Ne5  , which is the novelty Topalov introduced in our game from Wijk aan Zee, where White is suffering. }
10... Bb7 11. O-O-O Rc8
{ I couldn't find a refutation for Black's play, but nobody seems to like entering this line with Black as, usually, having the pawns on g2 and h5 is preferred. }
12. h4 d5
{ A very dangerous position for Black, which can be played only if you analyzed it from A to Z, as playing only moves over the board is not advisable. }
13. Rg1 { White is trying to get g5 in, but  13.Be2  is also possible. } 13...
dxe4 14. g5 hxg5 15. hxg5 Nd5 { Black is playing only moves. } 16. Nxd5
{ After  16.Nxe4  g6  , Black gets counterplay  with ...b4 and maybe it is holdable even with the eternal king in the center. }
16... Bxd5 17. fxe4
{ Morozevich played  17.g6  against Nakamura in Thessaloniki 2013, but after  17...f5  , Black is probably holding. }
17... Bxe4 18. Bg2
{ The engine gives +0.5 for White here, whatever that means, but it is clear that you have to analyze this position until draw with Black. }
18... Rh4 { Already this move is quite difficult. } 19. Kb1 Bg6 20. Ka1
{ I wouldn't go into such dangerous territories with Black. } *

