{ Lately, the players start with  6.f3  , in order to eliminate the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Ng4  option. }
6... e6
{ Black has two options here:  6...e6  or  6...e5  since anything else would lead to better Dragon or Rauzer positions for White. I believe  6...e5  is the most direct and challenging option, while after  6...e6  , it is not so easy to equalize, but the positions are very complicated. }
7. Be3 b5
{ Now, White has a variety of moves to choose from, each of them containing its own venom and nuances. }
8. g4
{ Back in my days when Kasparov was playing these lines,  8.g4  was considered to be the most accurate move. It's quite funny that in the past we all went for this @@StartBracket@@myself, Kasparov, Topalov, Anand, virtually everyone@@EndBracket@@, and now I don't see why would White start with  8.g4  . In case White prefers to continue without inserting  8.a3  , then  8.Qd2  is a better move order. }
8... h6
{ White wants to force this move since  8...Nbd7  is not possible due to  9.g5  . }
9. Qd2 b4
{ This is Topalov's very strong idea, which brings Black equality in the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/5ppp/p2ppn2/1p6/3NP3/2N1BP2/PPP3PP/R2QKB1R w KQkq b6 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.g4  variation. Sadly, he played this novelty against me in Wijk aan Zee 2005, when I lost a very sharp game where preparation is essential. }
10. Nce2 e5 { I believe Black is just fine here. } 11. Nb3
{ I tried for a while to make the piece sacrifice work for White after  11.O-O-O  exd4  12.Nxd4  , but it seems that Black is better. }
11... a5
{ 11...Nc6  12.Ng3  Be6  can also be played, but the text move is more accurate. }
12. Ng3 a4 13. Nc1 d5
{ Kind of a weird play, pushing all the pawns forward instead of developing the pieces, but chess is a complicated game, and if it works it works @@StartBracket@@White made a lot of unnecessary moves with the knights as well@@EndBracket@@. }
*

