1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ Welcome back! Your diligence is impressive given the amount of data you had to digest, but good news: today we are going to finish the Najdorf, hopefully. And the subject of this lesson is a variation that is considered one of the most dangerous weapons against the Najdorf − we are going to study the English Attack, which is the most popular variation at the top level.  We will check both  6.Be3  and  6.f3  , which, essentially, lead to the same system, but there are some nuances, however. Most of the time, White has both moves in the repertoire since after playing  6.f3  , it is hard to avoid continuing with Be3 against both of Black's systems:  6...e6  or  6...e5  . If White starts with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  , that yields additional options not only for White but for Black too. }
6. f3
{ Lately, the players start with  6.f3  , in order to eliminate the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Ng4  option. }
6... e6
{ Black has two options here:  6...e6  or  6...e5  since anything else would lead to better Dragon or Rauzer positions for White. I believe  6...e5  is the most direct and challenging option, while after  6...e6  , it is not so easy to equalize, but the positions are very complicated. }
7. Be3 b5
{ Now, White has a variety of moves to choose from, each of them containing its own venom and nuances. }
8. a3
{ Lately, this move started being fashionable, but it allows @@StartBracket@@and Black should take this opportunity@@EndBracket@@  8...h5  . }
8... h5 9. Qd2 Bb7 10. O-O-O Nbd7 11. Kb1
{ Magnus Carlsen played like this twice against Maxime Vachier-Lagrave. } 11...
Be7
{ Black can play both the text move or  11...Rc8  . Here, we reached a status quo: Black doesn't have a clear plan, but the same goes for White. A very subtle play will start. }
12. Rg1
{ A useful move, preparing to open the g-file at an appropriate moment. } 12...
Rc8 13. Be2
{ Another useful move, as  13...O-O  is too dangerous, while after  13...d5  , Black gets good chances to be crushed. }
13... Nb6
{ Instead, the engine gives the strange move  13...g6  here, while Svidler went for  13...Qc7  against Carlsen in a Rapid game in 2020. Following  14.Bg5  Qb6  , Black managed to get a draw, not without some weird-looking moves. }
14. Qe1
{ A very subtle position that you should analyze and play a lot, to understand what is going on. For instance, the engines suggest the funny-looking ...Kf8-g8, while the rook on h8 will make sure the king is not getting mated. The position is very difficult and I believe it is easier to play it with White, but once we dig deeper, I am not sure White is any better. Objectively, it should be about equal. }
14... Nfd7 { Played by MVL against Magnus in London 2019. } 15. h3
{ The engine's suggestion. } 15... h4 16. g4
{ Now, the importance of having the rook on g1 becomes visible. } 16... g5 17.
Rf1
{ White is slightly better, but definitely, this system is playable for Black. The pawn on @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/5ppp/p2ppn2/1p6/3NP3/P1N1BP2/1PP3PP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...h5  is much better than it looks.  The serious question is how to get the ...h5 on the board, as Black can also opt for the line with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/5ppp/p2ppn2/1p6/3NP3/P1N1BP2/1PP3PP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bb7  and the ...Nb8-d7-b6 and ...Nfd7 setup. }
