[Black "Summary"]
[Result "*"]

{ ♟English Attack 6.Be3   I believe that @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  is well met by  6...Ng4  and I would recommend starting with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.f3  for White @@StartBracket@@or playing the less explored @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p4/8/3NP1n1/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bc1  variation and prove to the chess world that  the h-pawn should remain on h7 in the Najdorf@@EndBracket@@ since I don't see what to do against 6...Ng4. The reason for that is not because the game will end in a draw, but Black has too active play for my taste, so better avoid it if you want a playable position with White.  ♟English Attack 6.f3 e6   To me, the main issue is the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/5ppp/p2ppn2/1p6/3NP3/2N1BP2/PPP3PP/R2QKB1R w KQkq b6 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qd2  move order and after  8...Nbd7  9.g4  . If Black finds something here, then @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N2P2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  is definitely playable. We had a difficult journey in this system, with many weird move orders and complicated setups, but I hope you have a solid base now and that you can choose and discern between all the subtle nuances.  Of course, you can choose to play  6...e6  with Black, but the bottom line: it is not a bullet-proof system − White is posing problems. This is the reason why  6...e5  became the more popular move, limiting White's choices and widening Black's options. After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.f3  , the most reliable response is  6...e5  , which is the subject of our final lesson. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lesson 52: Najdorf 6.f3 e5"]
[Black "Najdorf 6.f3 e5: 7.Nb3 Be6 8.Be3 h5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. f3 e5
{ I decided to make a separate lesson on the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.f3  e5  Najdorf because the positions that arise here are very important theoretically and are very complicated to understand.  Besides, there are a lot of move order tricks that are useful to know in order not to be lost on them. }
7. Nb3
{ 7.Nde2?!  Be6  g4  h6  and Black is ready for ...d5. This is not recommended for White. }
7... Be6
{ 7...Be7  is an option too, but Black will have to play ...Be6 anyway soon. }
8. Be3
{ Now Black has three possible responses. Let's have a look at them one by one. }
8... h5
{ This move introduces a system on its own that is quite popular in the elite. I recommend you to play it with Black. Objectively, White is slightly better, but the positions are immensely complex and rich and there's not a lot of theory to memorize.  White has three options now: }
9. Qd2 Nbd7 10. O-O-O
{ A logical -and dangerous- plan for Black, who cannot castle short so easily due to the fact that the move ...h5 was made. However, Black often castles short anyway, which means that it's not so dramatic for the second player. }
10... Rc8 11. Kb1 Be7
{ Move order-wise, this is a better move to start. If Black plays  11...b5  , the position after  12.Nd5  Bxd5  13.exd5  Nb6  14.Qa5  Nbxd5  15.Bf2  is very dangerous, as the pawn structure is weakened and White has a nice advantage in development. Black is in trouble here. }
12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. exd5 Bf5
{ Compared to the line where Black played 11...b5 instead of 11...Be7, the knight meneuver Na5-Nc6 is not possible. }
14. Bd3 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 Bg5
{ An important move, trading the dark-squared bishops. This position is fine with Black despite of having the pawn on h5 instead of h7. }
*

