[Black "Najdorf 6.f3 e5: 8...Be7 #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. f3 e5
{ I decided to make a separate lesson on the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.f3  e5  Najdorf because the positions that arise here are very important theoretically and are very complicated to understand.  Besides, there are a lot of move order tricks that are useful to know in order not to be lost on them. }
7. Nb3
{ 7.Nde2?!  Be6  g4  h6  and Black is ready for ...d5. This is not recommended for White. }
7... Be6
{ 7...Be7  is an option too, but Black will have to play ...Be6 anyway soon. }
8. Be3
{ Now Black has three possible responses. Let's have a look at them one by one. }
8... Be7
{ This is the main position of the  6.f3  e5  complex. I recommend Black not to try to trick White using weird move orders, as they are not totally sound and White can take advantage of them. }
9. Qd2 O-O
{ 9...d5  doesn't work here because of  10.exd5  and White is better. } 10.
O-O-O
{ 10.Nd5  is harmless. After  10...Nxd5  11.exd5  Bf5  the position is equal. }
10... Nbd7 11. g4 b5
{ We reach an important position in these  6.f3  e5  Najdorf lines. } 12. g5
Nh5
{ This move is less principled than the main one  12...b4  , but the modern theory proves that Black holds. THe only problem that playing this move has is that you have to have a good memory and know the lines move by move due to the direct nature of the game. }
13. h4
{ A very strange move to my understanding, as Black's g-pawn is still on g7. }
13... Ng3 { After  13...Rc8  Black is fine, too. } 14. Rg1 Nxf1 15. Rgxf1 a5
{ Black has a very dangerous attack on the queenside. ...a4 and ...b4 will come with tempo. }
