1. e4 c5
{ I propose you a game to illustrate my concept. I'll show you some positions and you can stop the video, think about them, and then start it again and check the answers. All of them will be based on the content you'll learn in this course.When you play chess at a non-professional level, very often your opponents will have a somewhat limited repertoire. Finding a hole in his preparation and taking him to unfamiliar territory, will lead you to a big success, in the opening and in the game. Therefore, it's important to know some lines not because you're going to play them regularly but to move-order your opponent and get the upper hand.Let's see some examples! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Bonus: Move Order Quest"]
[Black "Quest 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ Here's your first quest. Of course, you can play  2.h4  and your opponent will be out of book, but I want you to play serious lines and go for an opening advantage. }
2. Nf3
{ 2.c3  If you try the Alapin, you see your opponent always plays  2...d5  This is a very sound system.  3.exd5  Qxd5  4.d4  Nf6  5.Nf3  e6  Your opponent has more experience and knowledge with this than you. }
2... Nc6 { Your opponent's favorite move order. } 3. c3
{ With this move order, you'll manage to get your opponent out of his repertoire.   3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5  6.Ndb5  d6  This is the standard move order for the Sveshnikov, where your opponent also has more experience than you. }
3... d5
{ One of the main moves.  3...Nf6  would be the other option.  4.e5  Nd5  5.Bc4  This is a good system for Black, though White has some interesting attempts. However, it's a system your opponent doesn't usually play. }
4. exd5 Qxd5
{ Now the knight is already on c6. As I will explain in the course, this system is not good for Black. I don't think he can reach equality. }
5. d4
{ And you have reach a position you could predict and study in advance, taking your opponent by surprise and making him uncomfortable. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Bonus: Move Order Quest"]
[Black "Quest 2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ Same exercise. Let's see what your opponent wants to play and how to challenge his repertoire. }
2. Nf3
{ 2.c3  Nf6  3.e5  Nd5  4.Nf3  Nc6  This is a good system for Black. Your opponent knows it very well and plays it successfully, so it's his only line against the Alapin. }
2... e6
{ Your opponent's main weapon is the Paulsen System, and this is the only move order to get it. How can we get him out of his comfort zone? }
3. c3
{ Again, we trick our opponent with this move order and force him to start thinking on move 3.   Instead,  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  a6  leads to the Paulsen Sicilian, where your opponent also has more experience and knowledge than you. }
3... Nf6 4. e5 Nd5 5. d4
{ This is not so easy for Black and, very importantly, your opponent can't go for his favorite system with ...Nc6 because he has already played ...e6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Bonus: Move Order Quest"]
[Black "Quest 3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 { This time we have the black pieces. } 2. Nf3
{ Now your main repertoire is  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nc6  5.Nc3  Qc7  and your opponent's favorite system is  6.g3  , quite a dangerous weapon against the Taimanov. In fact, your opponent has a compact repertoire and favors g3-systems with short castle against different Sicilians.Now, which one should we choose to take advantage of that? }
2... d6
{ Heading to a Dragon, where White's g3 and short castle are harmless. } 3. d4
cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ The Dragon is the best Sicilian against a player who likes g3-setups and short castle. As we'll see in the course, White can only fight for advantage by playing long castle. Otherwise, Black is safe.   Instead,  5...a6  6.g3  is still a serious system against the Najdorf. }
6. g3 Bg7 7. Bg2 O-O { Black plays his regular Dragon setup and will be fine. }
8. O-O Nc6 { We'll see this position in the course. } 9. Nde2
{ White's main move. } 9... Rb8
{ I would probably already take Black in this position. The position is equal and you have solved all your opening problems thanks to your global understanding of the Sicilian. }
*

[Event "?"]
