[White "Bonus: Move Order Quest"]
[Black "Quest 4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. g3 a6 7. Bg2
{ Again this position, and you want to get a Scheveningen setup: ...Nf6, ...Be7, ...d6, ...Bd7. Black has good prospects if he can get this but what is the most accurate move order? }
7... d6
{ 7...Nf6?!  This move order is less precise. Let's see why:  8.O-O  d6  9.Re1  Black is not in time to get the ideal setup because tactics work in White's favor.  9...Be7  10.Nxc6  bxc6  11.e5  dxe5  12.Rxe5  12...O-O  We'll discuss this position in the course, but White enjoys a comfortable edge thanks to the damage done to Black's structure. Worse is  12...Qxe5  13.Bxc6+  Bd7  14.Bxa8  and White wins a pawn.     @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/1pq2ppp/p1nppn2/8/3NP3/2N3P1/PPP2PBP/R1BQR1K1 b kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Bd7  10.Nxc6  bxc6  I'll explain in the course that this doesn't fit well with ...Bd7. The bishop belongs on b7.  10...Bxc6  is the logical follow-up to ...Bd7, but here it fails tactically.  11.Nd5!  Bxd5  12.exd5  e5  13.a4!  The structure resembles a Najdorf, but in a fantastic version for White. }
8. O-O Bd7 9. Re1 { According to theory, the most dangerous move. } 9... Be7
{ Again, delaying ...Nf6. The point is that Nd5 ideas don't work now. } 10.
Nxc6 Bxc6 { Next, we'll play ...Nf6.  11.Nd5  exd5  is safe for Black. } *

